<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>David Brower: &quotFor Earth's Sake&quot</TITLE>

</HEAD>



<BODY>

<BODY BGCOLOR="F5CCB0">



<H1><CITE>For Earth's Sake: The Life and Times of David Brower</CITE></H1>

<H2>Volume 1 of David R. Brower's autobiography</H2>

<H3><I>A Peregrine Smith Book, published in 1990 by Gibbs Smith Publisher</I></H3>

<H3>556 pp., hardcover, $24.95</H3>

<H3>ISBN: 0-87905-013-6</H3>



<BLOCKQUOTE>&quotWhatever you can do,<BR>or dream you can do, begin it.<BR>

Boldness has genius,<BR>

power, and magic in it &quot<BR>

- Goethe</BLOCKQUOTE>



Theodore Roosevelt said he would rather wear out than rust out;  David Brower is doing 

neither.  Now in his late seventies, he reminds one of the most potent environmental 

activists of our time.<P>



Over the past fifty years, Brower was a leader in the campaigns to save the Grand Canyon, 

six national parks and seashores, and the national wilderness system.  But while he can also 

count scores of successes, he still grieves over the loss of Glen Canyon on the Colorado 

River, and his lack of foresight which could have saved it from the dam waters which now 

cover it.<P>



In <STRONG>For Earth's Sake</STRONG>, David Brower tells about the beginnings that awakened 

his young spirit to the challenge of the natural world, especially the steep parts.  He 

introduces his friends who challenged him most, including those who assisted his ouster as 

the Sierra Club's first executive director.  Among those who adjusted his thinking are Ansel 

Adams, Rachel Carson, William O. Douglas, and Loren Eiseley.  Selecting his favorite and 

little-known accounts of early struggles, reappraising them, augmenting them with humor and 

stories both poignant and revealing, Brower tells about one man's commitment to saving the 

earth.<P>



To protect the beauty of the planet and the splendor of its life and wild places, Brower's 

message to us all is Peace On and With the Earth!<P>



<HR>



<BLOCKQUOTE>&quotNothing I have heard from anybody else has so affected my thinking so 

deeply as what I heard from David Brower.. In a complex, technological world, it is 

astonishing that one man could make as much difference as he has made and is still 

making.&quot<BR>

- Charles Kuralt</BLOCKQUOTE>



<BLOCKQUOTE>&quot[Brower is] the most effective conservation activist in the world today.&quot<BR>

- John Oakes, of the <CITE>New York Times</CITE></BLOCKQUOTE>



<BLOCKQUOTE>&quotDave Brower is a good man to have on your side in a fight.&quot<BR>

- <A HREF="../journal/stegner.html">Wallace Stegner</A></BLOCKQUOTE>



<HR>



<IMG SRC="books.gif"

 ALIGN=RIGHT

 WIDTH=98 HEIGHT=79>



<H2>Other David Brower books</H2>



<UL>

<LI>Work in Progress: book 2 of David Brower's 

autobiography.<P>

<LI><A HREF="brow3.html">Let the Mountains Talk, Let the Rivers Run</A>: David 

Brower's newest book.

</UL>



<HR>


