<TITLE>MAP's history and goals</TITLE>

<H1>MAP's history and goals</H1>

<H2>By A. Quarto, MAP Director</H2>

Since its inception in April, 1992, the Mangrove Action Project has addressed
key issues surrounding the rapid loss of mangrove forests.  MAP has grown into
an effective, pro-active international campaign, combining vital information
and contact exchange with effective lobbying pressures via action alerts and
published articles.   Our determined efforts are now paying off, as our network
has expanded into 40 nations, including nearly 300 non-governmental
organizations (NGOs).  <P>

Its work to protect threatened mangrove forests has involved MAP in human
rights issues and local community organizing.  We have seen many excellent
examples of local community involvement in sustainable mangrove management.  In
Thailand, the Yad Fon Association,  has worked with great success in 17 coastal
communities. Community managed mangrove forests have been established in many
small  villages, offering a very positive model for surrounding communities to
follow.  Reforestation and conservation efforts have proven themselves in
increased fish yields and enhanced livelihoods for participating communities.
MAP's imperatives are to promote and protect mangrove forest ecosystems and to
support the rights of local peoples for sustainable resource management.  
Uncontrolled shrimp aquaculture expansion quickly became a key focus, when we
realized that vast tracts of mangrove forests were being permanently lost to
install shrimp ponds in many nations around the world. For four years, we have
worked to prove that this industry is unsustainable and massively destructive
in its present mode of operation. It adversely affects mangrove forests,
fisheries, wildlife, other natural coastal resources, and coastal communities. 
<P>

I am clarifying MAP's role  for two reasons:

<OL>

<LI> There are many recent new members to MAP's network, as well as
environmental groups who have recently taken up the mangrove issue, who may not
be familiar with MAP's history and goals.<P>

<LI> Over the past  year, a powerful  outcry against the shrimp farming
industry, driven by coalitions in Asia, India, and Ecuador, has begun to call
for a world boycott of farmed shrimp.  MAP is in a unique position to help
coordinate  international campaigns through its existing network.

</OL>

Through its network and information exchange, MAP will increase public
awareness towards halting this boom/bust enterprise from further unsustainable
expansion. It will collaborate with  groups in the North to ensure that unified
campaigns develop which look to Southern NGOs for direction.  We will continue
to work at the policy and research level to ensure that corrective measures are
applied, so that future developments which impact mangrove forests and other
coastal resources are ecologically sustainable and socially just.<P>

<BR>

