<TITLE>MAP: To Boycott Or Not To Boycott,  That Is The Question!</TITLE>

<H1>To Boycott Or Not To Boycott,  That Is The Question!</H1>

</H2>By A. Quarto</H2>

Over the years, MAP has held off on a boycott, believing that such action would
be premature in the Northern shrimp consuming nations, until a broader-based
consumer awareness existed.  Also, we have hoped for a solution driven
campaign, such as promoting an "eco" certified shrimp product.<P>

Another important reason  is that MAP looks for the directive for a boycott  to
come from our coalition, particularly those in the impacted nations.   Thus, we
have been waiting for our Southern Hemisphere network members to coalesce such
a directive and actively guide us in a unified strategy.   Some of our Southern
NGO associates have now begun promoting boycott campaigns targeted at their own
country's farmed shrimp exports.

<UL>

<LI>Ecuador: A boycott campaign was initiated by Accion Ecologica  last March,
calling for a ban on consumption of Ecuadorian farmed shrimp.<P>

<LI>India:  The Orissa Krushak Mahasangh, PREPARE, and the recently formed
Peoples Alliance Against Shrimp Industry (PAASI),   have all recently called
for a worldwide boycott.<P>

<LI>Honduras: CODDEFFAGOLF, based in Honduras, which works with over 140
fishing communities around the Gulf of Fonseca, has just announced their
support for a shrimp boycott.

</UL>

Other recent international actions:

<UL>

<LI>The International Network Against Unsustainable Aquaculture (INUA): A newly
formed group based out of  Malaysia, is working with many international NGOs,
and is developing a campaign with Northern groups to boycott farmed shrimp in
the near future.<P>

<LI>Greenpeace International:  Greenpeace is considering initiating a shrimp aquaculture
campaign next year.<P>

<LI>United States:  A variety of U.S. groups have begun or expanded their
activities relating to mangroves and shrimp.  The Sea Turtle Restoration
Project, <A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">STRP</A>, recently launched a "Turtle Safe Shrimp Campaign", targeting
trawler caught shrimp.   STRP mainly encourages trawler use of Turtle Excluder
Devices (TEDs) to protect sea turtles. STRP  thus promotes a "safe shrimp"
alternative for the commercial market.  Also, the Natural Resources Defense
Council, and the Environmental Defense Fund  have both dedicated staff to
research  the shrimp aquaculture industry.<P>

<LI>Canada:  Sierra Club Canada has asked that MAP help them launch an
international consumer awareness campaign that could lead to a boycott.<P>

<LI>Europe:  Sweden has already launched a boycott of aquaculture shrimp. 
Calls for a boycott     have also arisen in Switzerland during the past year.

</UL>

Since MAP is at the forefront of mangrove forest issues,  it must form a clear
position at this crucial period.  Our efforts to publicize the issues are
succeeding, spurring other groups to call for stronger action.  However, we
must ensure that those Southern member NGOs most affected by such a boycott are
supportive before we act on your behalf.<P>

<H2>We really need comments</H2>

We really need comments from our associates regarding your information and
views on the boycott question!
Are you aware of past successes, or failures,
with boycott campaigns?<P>

Can you, or your organization, participate in a
consumer campaign by sending MAP regular updates and facts?<P>

Please provide MAP
with a position paper, and any supporting documentation.  Send it to our <A HREF="mailto:mangrove@earthisland.org,mangroveap@aol.com">email</A>
or postal address.  Vandana Shiva, India representative for Third World Network
and the Director of PAASI, is currently facilitating coordination with Asian
members; MAP comments may also be sent to her.<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="map.html#toc"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif"></A>Go to MAP's<A HREF="map.html#toc"> table of contents</A>.<P>

