<TITLE>MAP: Boycott Review: Get Ready For The Long Haul</TITLE>

<H1>Boycott Review: Get Ready For The Long Haul</H1>

<H2>K. Cissna and E. Johnson, MAP Staff</H2>

To boycott or not to boycott may be the question, but where do we go from
there?  Many a boycott has come and gone in the United States, most creating
less than a ripple, a few creating dramatic changes over time.  In order to
execute a boycott in the U.S., we must know several things:<OL>

<LI>In what sense have past political or legal efforts  failed, such that we
may believe that a boycott is justified?<P>

<LI>What do we want to achieve?<P>

<LI>What will our targets be?<P>

<LI>What strategies will be used?<P>

<LI>What are the guidelines and solutions that we will offer?

</OL>

Below we offer a few very brief sketches of boycotts in the U.S., looking at
what made them succeed, or fail:

<H2>Greenpeace Boycott of Icelandic Fish</H2>

Greenpeace initiated a boycott of Icelandic white fish to force the country to
comply with the IWC and stop whaling.  GP went after major restaurant chains,
with high-profile public images.  It was successful in getting Shoney's a large
chain in the U.S. South, to stop buying Icelandic fish.<P>

<B>Result:</B> Shortly after this large contract was canceled, the Icelandic
government  agreed to comply with the International Whaling Commission in
regard to its whaling practices.<P>

<B>Analysis:</B>  Iceland was singled out, among other nations that also sell white
fish; thus, the restaurant chains were not being asked to eliminate a product,
but simply to buy elsewhere.  Iceland was particularly vulnerable, because its
economy is dominated by fish exports,  which are its main export revenue
source.  The whaling issue was well developed in public awareness in the United
States.  After the contract was canceled with Shoney's, Iceland was clearly
afraid that other buyers would follow suit, and this fear brought the
government to the bargaining table. Also, the campaign relied upon working with
an established international commission, the IWC, which exerted political
pressure on Iceland to comply with the  <I>international policies  previously
established</I> by the IWC.

<H2>RAN Boycott of Rainforest Beef</H2>

Rainforest Action Network (RAN) launched a national boycott against Burger King
to force the restaurant chain to stop buying beef raised in destroyed tropical
rainforests. The  boycott included a massive direct mailing campaign, full page
advertisements in major national newspapers, and hundreds of protests in front
of high-traffic restaurants, often near university campuses.  The dynamic and
creative protests were carried out mainly by "RAGs",  local groups of
Rainforest Action Network activists, in more than 50 cities across the U.S.  
In addition, activists showed up at business promotional events, board
meetings, and media conferences, in a "dogged pursuit" of the corporate giant.<P>

<B>Result:</B> Public response was strong.  Many restaurants saw a measurable decline
in the lunch customers, and media attention grew increasingly negative.  
Restaurant managers began complaining to corporate headquarters.  Burger King
announced that its restaurants would no longer serve "rainforest beef".<P>

<B>Analysis:</B>   In addition to expending considerable resources, this boycott
targeted a corporation with a very high consumer profile, therefore very
vulnerable to criticism.   According to Mike Roselle, board member of RAN, "the
threat to their good name was more important than saving a few cents on cheap
beef".   Rainforest Action Network has  had limited success with its ongoing
Mitsubishi boycott.   Mitsubishi does not rely as heavily upon a public image
as a restaurant chain.   Yet, in both cases, RAN  inititated dialogue with the
targeted corporations from the outset of its campaign, and has continued to
offer to talk about differences and proposed solutions.   Lastly, the beef
boycott occured at the same time that the public diet was beginning to shift
away from its love affair with beef because it was linked to heart disease and
other health problems for the consumer.

<H2>Boycott of General Electric & Nestle</H2>

A boycott of General Electric was initiated by INFACT in 1984, and ended in
1993, to protest the corporation's nuclear defense contracts.  The boycott
focused on getting large medical facilities and hardware stores to stop buying
GE products. Greenpeace and other groups also urged citizens to boycott GE.  A
centerpiece of the campaign was a video, "Deadly Deception", which won an
Academy Award for best short documentary.<P>

<B>Result:</B>   In 1993, GE sold all its shares in nuclear defense contracts.<P>

<B>Analysis:</B>  "A long and tortuous struggle", the INFACT boycott never had the
public impact of "rainforest beef".  Yet, their strategy of developing allies
among major buyers of GE products was more successful and less costly than a
major national public outreach.  What really put the boycott over the edge was
the tremendous success of the short documentary.  Upon receiving the academy
award, the video's producers said "boycott GE" on national television, and
shortly thereafter, GE announced its decision.<P>

INFACT calls its boycott of <I>Nestle</I> Corp. for selling infant formula
banned in the U.S. to African nations,  a "pseudo-success".  In response to a
very public citizen oriented campaign, which was widely covered by the media,
Nestle told the public it would stop.  INFACT accordingly dropped its boycott. 
However,  in practice, the corporation continued this and other unethical
practices in the Third World.  Now, there is another watchdog group hounding
Nestle's heels.



<H2>Earth Island's "Dolphin Safe Tuna" and "Turtle Safe Shrimp"</H2>

The <A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">Sea Turtle Restoration Project</A>'s (STRP)
"Turtle-Safe Shrimp" campaign has similarities to  the dramatic "<A
HREF="../immp/immp.html">Dolphin-Safe Tuna</A>" campaign.  This campaign
obtained industry co-partners who agreed to abide by new rules.  The businesses
who did not change were boycotted, while those who did were rewarded with
public promotion.  Both campaigns rely upon their own certification process to
identify eco-friendly enterprises.<P>

<B>Result:</B> The dolphin safe tuna campaign, while having various problems,
has still been one of the most successful boycotts in the environmental
movement. At this point, the Turtle-Safe Shrimp campaign looks a  little more
problematic, but still very promising.<P>

<B>Analysis:</B>  One immediate reason  for success is that the U.S. public has
a great affection for dolphins.   The <A
HREF="../immp/immp.html">Dolphin-Safe</A> success was built on a simple
campaign design:  the tuna industry has only a few major
processors/distributors (Starkist, Bumblebee, etc.), whose public image is
carefully nurtured.  The market process for trawled shrimp, on the other hand,
is a maze of entry points, distributors, and buyers.  Shrimp  are much more
difficult  to track, identify , and certify, than tuna.   Another  problem with
STRP's shrimp campaign is that the current demand for  the turtle-safe product
is much higher than the available supply.    Several fine restaurants in the
San Francisco area are now lining up for turtle-safe shrimp, but only one
trawling outfit has completed its certification with <A
HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">STRP</A>.  The campaign began its consumer
campaign strategies before it was able to fully develop its certification
program with the shrimp trawling industry.  However, an  increase in
participating businesses is expected soon.

<H2>Conclusion</H2>

These examples indicate that successful boycotts must focus on targets which
are susceptible to public opinion, and which are also vulnerable economically,
such as Iceland's dependence on its fish exports.   A boycott is a blunt
instrument, relying on rapid public response.  Thus, it  must get across a 
fairly simple idea, if it is meant for mainstream public consumption.  The
early and continual use of dialogue with industries and government agencies, in
order to articulate and achieve clear goals, is important.  Rewarding
cooperative participants, while boycotting others, can bring powerful allies
and  pro-active solutions to campaigns.<P>

In most cases, a boycott is by no means an overnight reality, but rather a
commitment that may take many years.  Some successful boycotts have followed
well developed public awareness programs, but on review, this hasn't been
necessary in all cases.   Exclusively "boycott" campaigns have generally fallen
out of popularity with an increasingly cynical public in the U.S.    Yet,
sometimes the function of a boycott is more political than economic: the threat
of a boycott alone can bring governments, industries, and institutions to the
bargaining table.<P>

Any time a Northern group effects a boycott on a product from a developing
country, there are issues of discrimination, economic stability, and national
sovereignty.   Some MAP members have refused to support a boycott in the past
because it would create a negative backlash on their ability to work within
their nations.   If we are able to find a sustainable shrimp product to
endorse, will other members think it worthwhile to promote  producers from one
or two nations and punish the rest?<P>

We apologize that all the examples above are from the U.S.  They are meant as a
starting point, to raise some brainstorming questions.  We hope that
inernational MAP members will let us know your views and strategies.  MAP aims
hold a meeting in the U.S. in 1996, to facilitate Northern groups' coordination
 on shrimp/mangrove campaigns, and to present direction from the South.

<BR>

<A HREF="map.html#toc"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif"></A>Go to MAP's<A HREF="map.html#toc"> table of contents</A>.<P>

<HR>


