<TITLE>MAP Regional Updates</TITLE>

<H1>Regional Updates</H1>

<H2>Africa</H2>

<H3>Urgent Alert: Shrimp Industry Vying for African Coasts--Cheap Labor,
Unpolluted Waters Are Enticements</H3>

"During the remainder of this decade the absolute gap between the average
salary of people in Africa and those in Asia will continue to grow. As a
partial result, Asian aquaculture entrepreneurs will find it increasingly
commercially attractive to develop aquaculture production units in Africa,
using a favorable physical environment, African labor, Asian technology and
capital from Asia or elsewhere..." (<I>The State Of World Fisheries And
Aquaculture</I>, FAO Fisheries Department Report, Rome, 1995, pg. 38)<P>

<H3>Message about Africa from MAP Director Alfredo Quarto</H3>

From the first days of MAP's formation, we have been aware of the rapid spread
of the shrimp aquaculture industry to new and relatively unspoiled shores. When
Taiwan's huge shrimp industry began deteriorating in the mid-1980s, due to
pollution and disease problems, astute industry investors began planting their
shrimp ventures along the coasts of unsuspecting neighboring nations. In the
early nineties, Thai shrimp entrepreneurs began to seek inroads into India,
Cambodia, Mexico, and other countries. And, in just a few years, India began
facing the same coastal pollution and habitat loss problems as Thailand.
Seemingly overnight, entire coastal villages have been displaced, left without
drinking water, or denied access to traditional fishing and food gathering
areas.<P>

As stated in the above mentioned FAO report, African nations may soon witness
the newest waves of shrimp farms aligning their rows of brackish water ponds
along coastlines. MAP urges our African members to help us sound the alarm
against unsustainable expansion of shrimp aquaculture. The same temptations of
tremendous profits, and increases in export earnings, which attracted other
nations, are bound to distract African government officials from the problems
associated with the industry.<P>

MAP encourages members to support African efforts at public outreach and
education As in Thailand, India, Ecuador, and elsewhere, far more than mangrove
forests are at stake here. The entire natural resource base along coastal
regions will be negatively affected, including the likely irreparable
disruption and displacement of countless coastal communities by a relatively
short-lived business venture.<P>

Please join us in this latest battle to protect mangrove forest ecosystems and
those coastal communities which depend on these invaluable resources. At
present, MAP has just a few members from Kenya, Ghana, Tanzania, and Senegal.
Pass the newsletter along, or let us know of individuals, NGOs, or institutions
in Africa who may wish to join MAP.

<HR>

<H2>Asia</H2>

<H3>Burma - Thai-Burmese Joint Fisheries Venture </H3>

"Burma's Department of Fisheries and Thailand's NGO Asian Fishery Industries
Co. have formed a joint venture to fish and process marine product, produce
fishmeal and raise prawns. The department holds 40% of Myanma Narong Fishery
Industries, with a registered capital of 120 million Kyats (Burmese currency)."
(from the <I>Bangkok Post</I>, 20-June-95) Thai shrimp industry investors have
been courting other nations for international business partnerships aimed at
shrimp farming.<P>

The Thai companies entice Burma and other governments with promises of huge
returns on initial investments, neglecting to accurately relate the downside of
shrimp aquaculture. In fact, in many instances, Thai industry reps have
misstated that pollution and disease problems are well under control in
Thailand.<P>

<H3>Thailand- The MIDAS REPORT-Disease, Sustainability Problems</H3>

This year an important World Bank funded study on the sustainability of
Thailand's shrimp aquaculture industry was released. The report also contains a
critical analysis of Thailand's $30 million program for mangrove replanting.
Commissioned by the Thai government, the private consulting firm MIDAS
undertook an intensive analysis of the shrimp industry. Its unabashed report is
extremely important in that it draws some key conclusions. Following are some
excerpts from this report:

<BLOCKQUOTE>"Until now shrimp aquaculture has not been sustainable anywhere in
Southeast Asia. A four year project by the Institute of Aquaculture of the
University of Stirling has concluded:<P>

'An analysis of the development the intensive shrimp farming industry in
southeast Asia...has highlighted the historical unsustainability of the
industry....the unsustainable nature of the Thai intensive shrimp industry has
resulted in decreasing pond production, increased crop and farm failure...and
environmental and socio-economic degradation.."(pg. 49, <I>MIDAS Report</I>,
1995)<P>

"Of the total shrimp pond area it is estimated that more than 31,000 rai is in
encroached mangrove forest. The relevant government agencies seem to have had
no success in preventing clearing of protected forests. Mangroves are still
being encroached...This loss of extensive mangrove areas represents a
significant deterioration in the quality of the coastal environment....On the
basis of the above evidence it would be unrealistic to expect that in the short to mid-term small-scale aquaculture
will be operated in anything other than a deteriorating or degraded coastal
environment..." (<I>Ibid</I>, pgs. 53 and 54)</BLOCKQUOTE>

The report also concludes that Thailand's mangrove reforestation efforts are an
expensive failure, prone from the beginning to bad planning due to lack of
insight among government officials involved in the program This important
conclusive study is verified by other studies, which combined confirm that
Thailand's ride on the crest of the great wave of shrimp industry profit may
soon come to an abrupt end, as was the case in Taiwan just a decade before.

<BLOCKQUOTE> "...The shrimp farming industry in Thailand is reaching, if not
exceeding, its geographical boundary and ecological carrying capacity. The
concept and reality of 'limits to growth' is a hard fact which must be
recognized by all parties concerned..." ( from "Progression of Intensive Marine
Shrimp Culture in Thailand", by C. Kwei Lin, pg. 22, of Shrimp Farming Industry
In Thailand,1995).</BLOCKQUOTE>

Note: Portions, or complete copies of any referenced public documents are
available from MAP. We ask for reimbursement of copying costs, for those who
are able to do so.

<HR>

<H2>India</H2>

<H3>Paradeep Convention and Save The Coast Movement</H3>

On October 15th, The Save the Coast Movement organized a large convention at
Paradeep Port, in Orissa, India. Around 5,000 coastal fishers and farmers
attended. MAP Director Alfredo Quarto attended as the guest speaker. The
convention was organized by the Indian NGO, Orissa Krushak Mahasangh.<P>

Paradeep Convention was dedicated to the two fishers who were shot to death at
Adhuan village on January 13, 1995, while peacefully protesting against shrimp
farming in their area. Representative fisher groups from throughout Orissa
attended, as well as visiting groups from neighboring coastal states. Many
speakers took the podium that day, and there were many emotionally charged
speeches. The Paradeep Convention represented a milestone in the fledgling Save
The Coast Movement.<P>

After only four years of intensive shrimp farm expansion along India's coasts,
the industry has destroyed vast stretches of once productive mangrove forests,
and has contaminated both land and water resources, creating tremendous
hardships for traditional coastal dwellers. Shrimp industry hired thugs have
tried to suppress the growing sentiments of popular resistance. These so-called
"prawn mafias" were responsible for many terrorist-style actions against
peaceful protests, including beatings, shootings, and arson.<P>

A more unified grassroots resistance was required in India. The Paradeep
Convention represented such a step taken along the long road to political and
social democracy. The following excerpt is taken from the Declaration of the
Paradeep Convention:

<BLOCKQUOTE> "This convention of the coastal people under the banner of Save
The Coast Movement, particularly of agriculturists, agriculture labourers and
fishermen community, resolves to carry on a determined struggle against
indiscriminate proliferation of brackish water prawn culture and urges upon the
people to mobilize themselves and strengthen the organizational base at
grassroots level to defeat the nexus between prawn entrepreneurs,
administrators and politicians....<P>

" The convention further calls upon the affluent countries to boycott prawn
import for consumption, which is nothing but the blood, sweat and livelihood of
the common people of the Third World countries..."</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>India Supreme Court Decision Pending</H3>

India's Supreme Court will, or may already have made a precedent setting
decision on extensive measures to greatly restrict shrimp farming along the
coasts of India. Among the nearly 14 pages of proposed guidelines, there are
requirements that no shrimp farms be built in natural mangrove areas, in
ecologically sensitive wetlands, or on productive agricultural lands. Also,
access to the sea must not be restricted by the shrimp ponds and waters from
underground aquifers cannot be used in the aquaculture process.<P>

The Indian recommended measures would go far in restricting this otherwise
runaway industry. However, a strong lobbying effort by the powerful shrimp
investors may succeed in blocking this timely move. Supreme Court action, if
taken, will set a very positive example for other nations beset with similar
issues. Already, the temporary injunction against further shrimp aquaculture
expansion in three coastal states has caused a stir.<P>

M. C. Mehta is the courageous lawyer pushing for legal reform of the shrimp
industry. The press calls him "India's Green Warrior" because of his successful
and undaunting record battling environmental issues of significance in India's
Supreme Court. Mehta has won several precedent setting cases in the past,
including cleaning up pollution affecting the Ganges River, and cleaning up the
polluted air corroding the famous Taj Majal.<P>

Since Mehta became involved in the shrimp aquaculture case, he has received
several death threats via the mail and telephone, but he is determined to carry
on his important work. He states that any laws passed will need popular support
to ensure their enforcement. Even with the temporary injunction against further
shrimp farm developments, there have been several incidents of non-compliance.
These infractions have been opposed by local coastal residents. In a personal
interview Mehta described the remarkable courage of those Indian fishers and
farmers who have risked their lives in their continued non-violent resistance
to the shrimp farm 'mafias". Some have physically placed themselves in front of
the bulldozers to stop the illegal building of new ponds.<P>

As he has done many times in the past, Mehta has taken on this case pro-bono.
MAP is assisting his important efforts by supplying him with needed documents
and contacts to help further substantiate his case in the Court.

<H3>Sri Lanka - Massive Popular Outreach</H3>

There is a growing popular movement in Sri Lanka to curb the expansionary
appetite of commercial shrimp farming ventures. A massive poster and leafleting
campaign recently passed out around 35,000 leaflets in the southern province.
The outreach was organized because the government had issued permits to
establish shrimp culture on 3,000 additional acres of coastal lands in the
vicinity of important fishing lagoons and fragile wetlands areas in the south.
Of the estimated 8,000 total acres of mangrove forested lands found in Sri
Lanka in 1982, only a small fraction still exists in the northwestern province.
Much of the regions' mangrove forests were lost to shrimp ponds. According to a
report received from the Environmental Foundation Limited in Sri Lanka, "There
are about 10,000 acres of legal and illegal prawn culture areas, and now their
productivity has gone down due to the pollution and other environmental
problems as well as the bacteria diseases. Now they are looking for alternative
lands from southern province.<P>

"... we are trying to stop their effort and.. have big support from the public
in that area..." (from an e-mail message sent by Hemantha, Senior Environmental
Scientist for EFL)

<HR>

<H2>Latin America</H2>

<H3>Mexico - World Bank Loan Proposal Postponed For Further Study</H3>

The World Bank's proposed $50 million or more loan to develop Mexico's
aquaculture industry has again been postponed. The Bank is permitting a longer
review process to take place via the NGOs involved in the process. MAP is
providing relevant documents and information on the issues of aquaculture and
coastal resources internationally to help broaden the analysis.

<H3>Ecuador - Smoke and Mirrors: Ecological Reserve, and Shrimp Farms Too</H3>

<H4>K. Cissna, Latin America Coordinator</H4>

MAP visited Ecuador in November to
investigate NGO and government efforts to resolve the mangrove crisis. Accion
Ecologica's call for a boycott last March had produced some action towards a
long hoped for ecological reserve in the northern province of Esmeraldas.
Unfortunately, the final product, announced by the government in October, is a
grave disappointment to most of the NGOs working on the coast. While the entire
region of Cayapas-Mataje has been declared an "ecological reserve", the zone
has actually been classified in different potential uses, leaving most of the
total land area "exempt" from the more stringent ecological prohibitions. The
actual protected area includes the fringe of mangroves along coastlines and
river mouth estuaries, and a buffer of between 50 to 100 meters between
mangrove trees and other vegetation.<P>

Some interesting progress has been made in setting up zone committees which
include the NGOs, industry, affected coastal people, and government agencies,
to help increase enforcement of the laws and resolve conflicts among user
groups. However, while these committees have been somewhat effective in the
south, to the north in Esmeraldas, coastal people feel betrayed and ruined by
the current situation. Essentially, the reserve is worse than no reserve,
because it provides a premise for shrimp farming expansion in the north.<P>

In Muisne, Esmeraldas province, over 90% of the mangroves have been destroyed
since 1986, even while a series of laws protected the mangroves on paper. The
local NGO is cynical of the government's commitment to, and capability of,
keeping aquaculturists within the newly prescribed perameters in the province. Coastal
fishers and NGO leaders have taken it upon themselve to physically, at their
own expense, bring forestry officials to sites of illegal mangrove cuts so that
they will be forced to do their jobs and arrest the transgressors. Villagers
have stood in front of bulldozers on occasion, paralyzing pond construction.<P>

Meanwhile, villages further north, who are most likely to be affected by new
developments, have become much better organized over the past year. The crisis
situation has brought various environmental groups into the fray; local groups
are trying to activate their impoverished members into a unified campaign to
demand a halt to further shrimp farming expansion in the northern "gem" of
mangrove forest ecosystem.<P>

What is striking about the Ecuadorian situation is the lack of facts. We were
surprised to repeatedly find that technical studies do not exist which would
analyze the impacts of developments, capacity of the land area, extent and
causes of fisheries declines, and various other environmental and social costs.
Although satellite photo analysis of geographic changes is supposed to be
completed every other year, some documents utilize satellite data from 1989, or
1991, as their most current information. Both environmental groups and the
government are thus working in the dark, even while drafting laws and
declarations which will have a profound impact on Ecuador's future, and the
immediate survival of coastal peoples.<P>

<B>"Clown" Study Pushes Aquaculture Agenda:</B> Two rushed studies have been
completed in the past year, for the purpose of establishing the ecological
reserve. However, while both studies were inadequate, there they part company.
The first was produced by a technical institute, EcoCiencia, which bid and won
a government contract to do the reserve study. EcoCiencia took 45 days to
investigate the area, travelling by canoe and outboard boats to reach
inaccessible areas.<P>

When EcoCiencia's results came out, the National Aquaculture Chamber was
displeased. The Chamber paid another private team to produce a second study to
counter the first. This study, utilizing a technical team from Petroleum
Services of Ecuador, Inc. (SERPET) and led by a Dr. Roger Fay, of Texas A & M
University, was accomplished after just 9 days in the area in question.
According to the Quito-based IUCN South America Wetlands Director, Tarcicio
Granizo, the report is a "clown study", which blatantly pushes the agenda of
the Chamber at great environmental and social cost. When EcoCiencia examined
the findings of the Dr. Carlos Valle, the biologist hired by SERPET, it found
that in many instances, Dr. Valle's reccomendations were ignored in the final
study. Among the Chamber study's claims:

<UL>

<LI>"mangroves are...of a low diversity"<P>

<LI>"the ecosystem of the mangrove is exremely resistent, with a great capacity
to support contamination...(it) is not fragile..."<P>

<LI>"The direct nutrition from the mangrove trees to aquatic organisms is
restricted."<P>

<LI>"The mangrove ecosystem generally does not contain species in danger of
extinction; there are some exceptions, but not in Ecuador...it is not a unique
habitat for permanent or migratory species"<P>

<LI>"It is not an attractive scene aesthetically such as one would find in
coral reefs"<P>

</UL>

Meanwhile, Dr. Valle concluded that, " the area offers an opportunity to see
one of the best and most exuberant examples of mangroves existing in the
Eastern Pacific...a high diversity of animal species, especially native birds
and 19 migratory species, and various species in danger of extinction,
including the coastal crocodile, tigrillo, and others"<P>

Dr. Fay's vision of ecoturism for the zone:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"The focus of tourism is provided by the introduction of large scale shrimp
cultivation...this signifies that the shrimp farms would be open and available
for tours."</BLOCKQUOTE>

EcoCiencia claims Dr. Fay's "simplistic and reductionist vision of the
mangrove" allows him to define the mangrove as the "gathering of plant
communities along the borders of tropical coasts". This definition permeates
the study's conclusions, which fail to address many ecological services
provided by mangroves, including its holistic role as a point of union,
interacting with sea, coastal land, ground waters, and atmosphere.<P>

Although the second study was paid for and commissioned by the very industry
which has an obvious agenda to promote shrimp culture development of the area,
its conclusions are forming the "scientific" basis for government policy in
Ecuador.<P>

Copies of the report summaries, and the commentaries of Dr. Fay and EcoCiencia,
are available from MAP. <I>We strongly encourage MAP's members, particularly
academic advisers, to take some time to read through these documents, and send
your comments to Ecuador.</I> To request your copies and Ecuadorian addresses,
please call/write MAP, or <A HREF="mailto:kacissna@aol.com">email Kate Cissna</A> .

<HR>

<H2>United States</H2>

<H3>Florida Everglades Supporters Seek a Two Cent Sugar Tax</H3>

By Bob Riley

According to local citizens, sugar farming has severely damaged and polluted
the entire ecosystem of the Florida Everglades, an irreplaceable mangrove
habitat . Local NGOs and business leaders ask that letters be sent to Senators
Leahy, Graham, Lugar and Specter, who sit on the commitment overseeing the
sugar tax. Below is a sample message:<P>

"I am writing to solicit your support for the Everglades restoration and the
proposed two cent tax on sugar. It is reasonable that those who use natural
resources for economic gain, and adversely impact the surrounding environment,
should help to bear the economic costs of sustaining that environment. Saving
the Everglades and other south Florida natural areas is crucial to the entire
region's economic health, according to the Commission on a Sustainable
Florida." (Mr. Riley is a resident of Melbourne Beach, Florida.)<P>

The Senators' email addresses are: <A HREF="mailto:leahy@leahy.senate.gov">leahy@leahy.senate.gov</A>,<BR>

<A HREF="mailto:bob_graham@graham.senate.gov">bob_graham@graham.senate.gov</A>,<BR>

<A HREF="mailto:lugar@iquest.net">lugar@iquest.net</A>,<BR>

<A HREF="mailto:senator_specter@specter.senate.gov">senator_specter@specter.senate.gov</A><P>

Postal Address: The Honorable _______<BR>
United States Senate<BR>
Washington D.C.
20510.

<HR>

<H2>Conferences</H2>

<H3>Vietnam</H3>

From January 8-12, 1996, MAP will be represented at the
upcoming UNESCO conference ECOTONE V, which will be held in Ho Chi Minh City.
The theme of this conference, <I>"Community Participation in Conservation,
Sustainable Use and Rehabilitation of Mangroves in Southeast Asia,</I>" is
particularly relevant to MAP's work promoting community managed mangrove
forests.<P>

<H3>Bangladesh</H3>

An important international conference held from Nov. 9-11
1995, was organized by Nijera Kori, a Bangadeshi NGO, which addressed
international shrimp aquaculture expansion. This conference aimed to develop
strategies and a stronger regional network for Asian groups. Those wishing to
contact Nijera Kori to find out more about the conference or its papers can do
so at: P.O. Box 5015, New Market, Dhaka-1205, Bangladesh.

<H3>Legal and Regulatory Workgroup</H3>

The International Law Institute is
planning a working group meeting, set for early next year, in Bangkok. The
meeting will address legal issues, and attempt to set up an international
framework of legal guidelines aiming to ensure sustainable aquaculture
practices.

