<H1>MAP's mission statement</H1>

<TITLE>MAP's mission statement</TITLE>

<H2>MAP objectives</H2>

The Mangrove Action Project (MAP), a project of
Earth Island Institute, is addressing the serious problems associated with
prawn aquaculture. MAP is a growing international coalition consisting of
environmental, human rights and community-based groups.  MAP coalition members
include organizations based both in threatened, and in industrialized nations,
where the cultured prawns are mainly consumed.  MAP is actively involved in
raising public awareness about these important issues.<P>

The Mangrove Action Project has three main objectives:<P>

<UL>

<LI>To raise worldwide public awareness about the mangrove forests and
related issues.<P>

<LI>To help protect and restore the world's remaining mangrove forest areas.<P>

<LI>To protect and promote the rights of indigenous coastal peoples, including
fishers and farmers, especially in relation to indigenous people retaining
their rights to sustainably manage their own coastal resources.<P> </UL>


Mangrove Ecosystems Provide:<P>

<UL><LI>Sheltered nursery and spawning grounds for much of the world's costal
marine life.<P>

<LI>Vast quantities of forest detritus, ensureing rich nutrients for sea
life.<P>

<LI>Needed protection of shorelines from erosion by waves and storm action. The
bracing roots of the mangroves protect sea grasses and coral reefs from
otherwise devastating siltation.<P>

<LI>Essential habitat for many varietites fo endangered species - rare birds,
<A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">sea turtles</A>, manatees, and <A
HREF="../immp/immp.html">dolphins</A>.<P>

<LI> Natural resrouces for traditional costal fishers and farmers who depend on
a healthy mangrove ecosystem for their cultures and livelihoods.<P>

</UL> Mangrove forests are found in both the tropical and sub-tropical regions
of the world.  The widest range of mangrove species exists in tropical
Southeast Asia. Three species are found along Florida's coast.  It has been
estimated that there are over 40 million acres or about 16 million hectares of
mangrove forests remaining in three regions of the world.<P>

<UL><LI>Asia contains about 46% of the world's mangrove forests. (Indonesia has
the largest are of mangrove forests in the world with an estmated 12.2 million
acres, or about 4.9 million hectares.)<P>

<LI>The Americas have around 35%.<P>

<LI>Africa has nearly 17%.<P> </UL> <H2>All for the Sake of Prawns and
Profit</H2> Modern industrial development now threatens the world's remaining
mangroves. The greatest threat to mangroves is the aquaculture industry -
especially shrimp or prawn aquaculture.<P>

Costal pollution from other industries is also an increasing threat.<BR> The
charcoal industry regulary harvests large tracts of mangroves.<BR> Tourism
development often results in mangrove destruction.<P>

<H2>A Billion Dollar Nightmare</H2> Millions of coastal fishers and farmers are
also adversely affected by prawn farming. The prawn aquaculture industry often
clears vast areas of mangrove forests and coastal farmlands for the
construction of large artificial ponds. Huge quantities of prawns are raised
within these shallow, brackish water ponds.  (Approximately 80% are produced in
the Eastern Hemisphere.)<P>

The so-called "prawn fever" is a relatively new malady.  Yet it is rapidly
spreading along the world's mangrove-forested coast, leaving pollution and ruin
in its wake.  Prawn awuaculture has become a multi-billion dollar industry
financed by multi-national corporations and wealthy investors.<P>

Mangrove forests are being destroyed at an alarming rate to make way for theis
burgeoning export industry.  Often, on those same lands once rich with
mangroves, the profitable, but destructive, prawn farms are closed in just a
few years.  Insurmountable pollution problems eventually plague the ponds
themselves.<P>

Yet, big business investors, undaunted by the inevitable decline in proawn
production, simply reopen business elsewhere, always looking for new, as yet
unspoilt grounds to begin again.<P>

This scenario of destruction has visited the coasts of Taiwan, China,
Bangladesh, The Philippines, <A HREF="../gsc/thai.html">Thailand</A>,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Ecuador, Columbia, and many other countries.  And now, the
prawn industry is establishing footholds in Vietnam, Cambodia, Burma, Iran,
Yemen, Mexico, and other parts of Asia, Latin America and Africa.<P>

Each year total prawn production increases. Record years follow record years.
In 1992, nearly 700,000 metric tons of prawns were aqua-culturally produced
worldwide.  Presently, Japan and the U.S. are the world's top importers of
prawn products.<P>

<H2>The problem with prawn aquaculture</H2> Serious problems with prawn
aquaculture include:<P>

<UL><LI> Destruction of the world's remainging mangrove forests.<P>

<LI>Loss of invaluable wildlife habitat, thus further threatening endangered
species and bio-diversity.<P>

<LI>Serious declines in world's tropical coastal fisheries.<P>

<LI> Poisoning both coastal waters and adjacent farmlands with dangerous
additives and antibiotics found in prawn feeds resulting in further serious
declines in food productivity contributing to food shortages for indigenous
peoples.<P>

<LI>Salinization and pollution of nearby ground waters, including drinking
water.<P>

<LI>Reduction in available protein for local communities becomign nealy 90% of
aquaculture raised prawns are exported.<P>

<LI>Deaths, injuries and property damage associated with denuded coastlines
where natural protective buffer zones once provided by the mangroves were
removed to make way for encroaching prawn farms.<P>

<LI>Massive problems of coastal destabilization, including heavy erosion and
siltation resulting in loss of both sea grasses and coral reefs.<P>

<LI>Activation of the acid-sulfate in the soils.<P>

</UL>

<H2>What you can do:</H2>

MAP is the leading effort to end the worldwide destruction of mangrove forests
caused by unsustainable prawn farming.  We need your help in spreading the
word. Write a letter to:<P>

Mr. Lewis Preston<BR> World Bank President<BR> 1818 H St. NW<BR> Washington, DC
20433 <P>

and ask him to more closely monitor World Bank funding to ensure that
ecologically and socially destructive projects such as prawn aquaculture are
not funded in the future.<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="map.html#toc"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif"></A>Go to MAP's<A HREF="map.html#toc"> table of contents</A>.<P>

