<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Green Hope on Black Mesa</TITLE>

<H1>Green Hope on Black Mesa</H1>

<H2>by Tracey Silberman</H2>

Arizona -- Violent drops of rain splashed red desert dust onto Highway 264 just outside of
Hotevilla, one of the last <A HREF="../slfp/status.html">Hopi</A> settlements to reject modern utilities. As I turned north toward the
historic homeland of the Dine (Navajo) people, my headlights caught a storm-soaked billboard
rising out of the sagebrush. It read: "RELOCATION IS GENOCIDE."<P>

For more than 20 years, the Dine of northern Arizona's Black Mesa region have
been fighting eviction from their traditional homelands. In 1974, the US
Congress arbitrarily redefined the high <A
HREF="desert.html">desert</A> region of Black Mesa (including Big
Mountain, a Dine sacred site) as land belonging to the Hopi tribe. All Dine
living in the area were told to relocate. Only nine Dine families remain on the
disputed land.<P>

The Dine and Hopi had lived in harmony for centuries, but the relocation order severed this traditional
relationship. The Peabody Coal Company, with a large mine in nearby Kayenta, has long coveted the
coal and uranium that lie beneath native land. The Navajo tribal government favors resource
extraction because it provides income. Unfortunately, the benefits of this "community
empowerment" strategy do not outweigh the disruption of the community, and the health and
environmental hazards caused by mining.<P>

A slurry pipeline that runs from Peabody's Kayenta mine
to Bull Head City, Nevada, uses two-to-three million gallons of Navajo Aquifer water daily. As a
result, the whole Dinnebito Watershed ecosystem is drying up, causing a loss of vegetation and
increasing erosion. At present rates of usage, water resources are expected to run dry in 15 years.<P>

Most of the Dine who accepted the relocation offer had to give up their traditional way of life.
Culturally displaced, they were forced off the land and thrust into the cash economy. Meanwhile,
expanding mining operations have disrupted the landscape, leaving behind shadeless, shelterless
grasslands, inhospitable to traditional Navajo sheepgrazing. Sheep do not eat snakeweed, a
sun-tolerant exotic weed that has invaded the mining-damaged land, choking out native plants and
grasses. Mining operations have destroyed sacred sites (disrupting the practice of religious
ceremonies), eradicated rare medicinal plants, destroyed critical wildlife habitat, and exacerbated
air pollution and groundwater contamination.<P>

<H3>Coal vs. Culture</H3>

Several independent groups have formed to deal with the environmental problems on these
embattled native lands, the most prominent being the Big Mountain Support Group, Dine Alliance,
Dine CARE (Citizens Against Ruining the Environment) and the Black Mesa Permaculture Project
(BMPP).<P>

The Dine Alliance was originally formed to battle for religious freedom, insisting on
access to traditional Dine sacred sites on the disputed land. "First we fought physically and now we
fight paper wars. We have no economy and our only money is through [making] crafts, and many
times there is no time for that," says Dine Alliance's Louise Benally.<P>

The Dine Alliance has evolved
into a lobbying group that is challenging mining operations that threaten Dine land and health. As
Benally, the main force behind Dine Alliance, angrily insists, "We are human beings who are being
denied our land. We drink the water and breathe the air, and we do not agree with living in a
contaminated environment."<P>

Because there are virtually no governmental regulations for mining on
reservation lands, Dine mineworkers are routinely subjected to unhealthy working conditions and
toxic pollutants. According to the Dine Alliance, the last time anyone used Office of Surface Mining
(OSM) regulations to challenge Peabody's activities was in 1968.<P>

After 40 years of Bureau of
Indian Affairs (BIA) oversight, many Dine have begun to lose their cultural identity. In a culture
that is so tied to the land, without land there can be no culture. "The Creator made all things for a
purpose. He made the Hopi to plant corn and me to graze sheep," says Dine farmer William Begay.
Reflecting on the success of his new cornfield and the loss of his sheep-ranching way of life, he
jokes, "Maybe I'm becoming a Hopi."<P>

<H3>Resist and Restore</H3>

The Black Mesa Permaculture Project was established in 1991 to heal the Earth and revive Navajo
culture through the principles of permaculture -- land restoration, revegetation, erosion control
and water-table replenishment. BMPP teaches local families how to restore damaged soils and
enhance self-sufficiency through the creation of productive, sustainable, land-based systems that
provide food, energy and shelter. Permaculture (a conjunction of "permanent" and "agriculture")
was developed in Tasmania in 1974 by Australian Bill Mollison, who was determined to put the
"culture" back in agriculture.<P>

One of permaculture's guiding principles -- the concept that
everything is connected to everything else -- echoes a basic tenet of Indigenous philosophy.
Permaculture's interdependent, non-hierarchical nature not only mirrors healthy ecosystems, it
also parallels Dine society's mutual, non-hierarchical sharing of information, cooperation and
support.<P>

Traditional Dine teachings say that by using the land and offering respect, the land in turn
will take care of you. When the spirit dies, it returns to the land. In permaculture, everything is
recycled. The system is said to work if it manages to sustain itself. BMPP believes that
permaculture's goals of self-sufficiency and sustainability can play a major role in advancing
sovereignty and self-determination in a culturally sensitive way.<P>

Permaculture is helping to draw
Dine kids back to the land. Justin Willy, an elementary science teacher at the Little Singer School
in Winslow and one of BMPP's instructors, helps children remember where they came from by
integrating permaculture principles with traditional teaching and language in his classes. Like Dine
culture, permaculture works with the elements and the seasons, Willy explains. All sustainable
systems and cultures, he says, work with nature, not against it.<P>

Willy firmly believes in education
and environmental restoration to ensure the survival of his people. He teaches his students that,
"the more we care for the land, the more the land will care for us."<P>

Each year, BMPP hosts a public
permaculture course. Non-natives pay $250 for the two-week workshop, which enables BMPP to
offer the course free to Indigenous people. This year's course was attended by 18 participants,
including several Dine from other parts of the reservation, members of Nevada's Shoshone Western
Defense Project and members of the Yaqui and Paiute nations.<P>

The workshop began in late May at the
Begay home in Black Mesa. Classes were held in the Begay's hogan, a traditional eight-sided,
mud-roofed, log dwelling. Work parties soon moved into the surrounding area armed with picks and
shovels. Through three days of rain and a week of relentless heat, the diverse group of volunteers
labored with local residents to construct compost piles, cisterns and swales (soil structures built
on a contour to catch runoff) at several homesites. Since permaculture stresses the use of locally
available materials, workers built compost bins from chicken wire, and reinforced cisterns with
plywood and rocks. The only item purchased was a galvanized gutter used to channel rainwater from
a rooftop to a cistern.<P>

Ironically, while Peabody is allowed to tear open the land and poison the air,
Bureau of Land Management laws state that reservation residents may not change, build on, or
"improve" the land in any way. Of course, that was exactly what we were doing -- building swales
and gabions (dam-like rock structures that catch silt) to channel and conserve the moisture,
constructing gardens and improving the soil by providing moisture and nutrients.<P>

During the ten days of the workshop, BIA agents drove through the property three times, twice stopping at the
Begay's house. Usually the residents of the house just kept their heads down and would not
acknowledge the intrusion.<P>

One day, while collecting wood near the family's home, we were pulled
over and brusquely questioned by the Hopi Tribal Police. After informing us that we needed a permit
to cut wood and that the Begay family was supposed to tell the police if they were having guests, the
officer let us go. He could have given us a $200 fine and confiscated the wood.<P>

It is through this type of intimidation that the tribal governments and the BIA hope to force the few remaining Dine to
leave. But these Dine are not going to give up. They stay because they have a true connection to the
Earth. The Big Mountain groups' persistence has shown other Navajos that their only hope to
survive on these lands lies with restoration.<P>

Louise Benally is optimistic for the future of Black
Mesa. "We have felt help and inspiration from the environmental movement. In the last few years,
this has made our voice stronger. Previously environmental issues did not cross cultural issues.
But with Mount Graham and Yucca Mountain and Black Mesa -- seeing sacred sites environmentally
degraded -- we have been able to work together on these issues."<P>

Around the campfire on the last
night of the workshop, voices echoed under a warm, star-filled sky. "We claim the sacred
mountains and the two rivers connecting them as sovereign land. We don't recognize the old white
man's law. The tribal government has oppressed us to support them, but now the tribal government
wants to meet with us. We will show them that we can make change. We can change things if we start
right where we are. It can be done, we can have control."<P>

<HR>

