<H1>The Sacred Land Film Series -- a detailed description</H1>
<TITLE>The Sacred Land Film Series -- a detailed description</TITLE>

Australian Aborigines. Tibetan pilgrims. Indians of the <A HREF="../journal/mclibel.html">Brazilian</A> rainforest
and the American Southwest. Around the globe, indigenous people sing the same
songs. They sing of sacred land -- those special places where countless
generations of women and men have sought and experienced the profound mystery
of life on Earth -- where human beings have traditionally learned the values of
awareness and responsibility, humility and respect.<P>

But indigenous people sing also of loss and strife and grief, because the
demand for raw materials and energy resources in industrial,
technologically-advanced nations is pushing the machines of destruction deeper
and deeper into the last wild places on the planet. Everywhere, sacred lands
are under siege. Australia's aboriginal people confront uranium mining,
Brazil's Yanomami fight dams and deforestation, A HREF="../journal/blmesa.html">Hopis</A> and Navajos protest coal
slurrylines that destroy precious springs, and Tibetans face destruction of
their temples and natural sacred sites.<P>

Hundreds of indigenous cultures have perished in recent centuries as a result
of modern industrial society's rapid expansion. With the vanishing people went
ancient knowledge of their homeland, their ecological heritage, their sacred
places. In recent years, the survivors have begun to organize and speak out.
Today, as we face a global environmental crisis, what these indigenous people
have to say about the appropriate relationship between humankind and the
natural world holds valuable lessons and may be essential to the survival of
all human life on the planet. But what do we know of their stories and beliefs,
their dreams and struggles? What do we know of sacred land, the ethics that
protect it, and the songs that celebrate it? <P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>White fingers press the keys of a small field computer. A woman's
voice asks "We're at the southern edge, aren't we?" "Yes," responds a male
voice. An orbiting satellite beams a signal back to the computer, registering
latitude and longitude, which are recorded on a map. "Using a mining company's
tools to register a sacred site, ironic isn't it?" says the anthropologist to
the Aborigine. Gazing out over a dry swamp in central Australia, Engineer Jack,
the site's traditional custodian, tells the story of how two weary ancestral
snakes took refuge here during the Dreamtime creation era and were revived by
porridge made from the seeds of a tree in the center of the swamp. Clacking two
stones together he sings a song. "The ceremony given to us by those ancestors
is performed here every year," says Engineer Jack to the anthropologist with
whom he is working on a land claim in an attempt to stop the local mining town
from drilling into the swamp for water. The waterhole is on a "songline"
connecting it to other important sites in the Walbiri people's territory,
places which were also visited by the ancestral snakes and which are now
important sources of food and medicine, and are initiation sites for the young.
"What I want to know," says the Aboriginal elder, "is how white man can claim
that he can own the land and the water, own the spirit in
nature."</BLOCKQUOTE>

Sacred places in the natural world have been known to every culture from
ancient times to the present. Peoples of India, Egypt, Tibet, North and South
America and the British Isles historically based their civilizations on an
understanding of their relationship to the forests and streams around them, the
mountains and stars above them. While the experience of sacred land is often a
personal one, cultures throughout history have designated specific places as
sacred because of recurring human experience at these sites. Certain places
associated with fertility, healing, clairvoyance, prophetic dreams, ancestral
burials, important historical events or supernatural phenomena have come to be
respected, protected and utilized for the beneficial results experienced there.
These are the sacred places of the planet, where human beings experience
transcendence of the physical plane and discover an ever-deepening relationship
to themselves, to the Earth, to other species, to the life force.<P>

Mythologist Joseph Campbell observed that all mythic heroes seek a place of
peace and rest -- the center. From that center, from that peace, flows
enlightened action. Historian Mircea Eliade showed that religious cultures
throughout time have been founded on an <I>axis mundi</I>, the center of the
universe, which takes many shapes -- a cosmic mountain, an old cedar tree or a
village plaza -- and which connects communities to the transcendent and insures
communication with the spirit world. To connect with the unseen force behind
life, and to maintain health and harmony, these indigenous cultures and mythic
heroes have based their actions on the insight that the human body comes from
the Earth, is the Earth. Collectively, this wisdom teaches that we are the
consciousness of the Earth and that certain places have the power to reveal
these truths and remind humanity of this responsibility. But European
civilization long ago severed those bonds with the land and for centuries has
evolved an increasingly mechanized, urbanized lifestyle that mines the Earth
for its bounty and exports a utilitarian world view to other cultures. In
religion, science and language we have become secularized and detached. We have
lost our center.<P>

Many people within Western culture are struggling to make intimate contact with
the natural world, to recover ceremony and rediscover a sense of the sacred.
Yet few among us seem to know how to talk about these things, let alone how to
pursue this quest for meaning. Thinkers like Aldo Leopold, Rachel Carson, Carl
Jung and Joseph Campbell initiated the search for a new frontier linking
psychological and ecological health.<P>

And today, a growing number of people are seeking solutions to the
environmental crisis by restoring personal and cultural connections to the
Earth, to the unconscious, to the elusive dimension we call the sacred. One
aspect of this search is to explore how we in  technological society lost our
connection to the land; another is to understand how earth-based people are
fighting to preserve theirs. <P>

The films will explore the difference between <I>natural</I> sacred sites and
<I>man-made</I> sites of worship -- a forest where silence is needed for a
vision quest in contrast to a church's inner sanctum, a waterfall where spirits
dwell in contrast to a shrine honoring a saint, a rock formation marking the
birth place of a mythic hero in contrast to a house where George Washington
slept, the San Francisco Peaks in contrast to Jerusalem. Natural sacred sites
are rarely regarded as legitimate places of worship and are generally not
valued as sources of inspiration by members of urban-based cultures.
Consequently, they are not protected by legal systems which otherwise provide
protections for the freedom to worship. On the contrary, sacred sites in nature
are often regarded as cultural artifacts or commercial commodities to be
developed for tourism or exploited for television advertisements. And
indigenous people are rarely portrayed in film as <I>real people</I> -- they
are cultural curiosities in the minds of most Euro-Americans. Indigenous people
must be allowed to tell <I>their own story</I> if people from urban, industrial
societies are going to be open to their wisdom, to care about their survival,
and to understand the meaning and support the protection of natural sacred
sites.<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Bill Tallbull, a Northern Cheyenne Professor from Lame Deer College
in Montana, stood on a sandstone cliff at Mesa Verde National Park. Looking out
over a deep canyon full of pinon and juniper, he said, "The reason white people
don't understand our sacred places is that their religion is a
<I>commemorative</I> religion that celebrates people and historical events,
while our religion is a <I>living religion</I> based on ceremonies of renewal. Our
life goal is to maintain spiritual harmony, to appease and affirm the spirit
life of a place -- hence our tie to the land. We see and feel God
<I>everywhere</I>. 
We cannot allow a sacred place to become dormant or to be defiled. It is too
dangerous. We are the stewards."  "So how do you protect such a place?" I
asked. "We have a hell of a teaching job to do," he replied.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

The <B>Sacred Land</B> films will probe the relationship between culture and
land, explore the root causes of the violence being done to the Earth by industrial
civilization, and highlight the words and world views of earth-based peoples
from around the world. We believe that one way out of the current
environmental/spiritual crisis is to re-establish 
an understanding and a sense of sacred land within Western culture. Honoring
sacred places, ours and others', may be the only way we can repair our tattered
ties to the land. <P>

More about the The Sacred Land Film Project:<P>

