<H1>The Premise of the Sacred Land Film Project</H1>
<TITLE>The Premise of the Sacred Land Film Project</TITLE>

by Christopher McLeod, Project Director<P>

Fifteen years immersion in environmental issues has convinced me that the
ecological crisis is, at its root, a spiritual crisis that stems from a culture
that is disconnected from nature and the spiritual forces of the natural world.
This disconnection long ago led to an imbalanced emphasis on material values.
Spending a lot of time among the Hopi, Navajo, Wintu, Tibetan, Australian
aboriginal and other indigenous people around the world -- attending
ceremonies, listening to stories, walking to places in the landscape that hold
great cultural and historic significance -- questions took shape in my
Euro-American mind. Why do we have no sacred sites? What is the cost of this
absence in our culture in terms of the health of individuals, of the culture,
of the planet? Why have we no language to discuss experiences at sacred sites?
How might we re-discover these places and remember the practices that are
appropriate to them? I came to the viewpoint, through my Native American
friends' experiences and way of seeing the world, that cultural disintegration
is the direct result of disconnection from the land, and that sacred sites are
at the heart of, and are inextricably linked to, the very practices and beliefs
that nurture connection to the earth that sustains us.<P>

These experiences have inspired the Sacred Land Film Project.<P>

I feel deeply that we need stories -- stories of ceremony, stories of elders,
stories of struggles to protect sacred sites. These stories can be told
powerfully on film, with visual images of the sites and heartfelt words spoken
by the traditional caretakers of the powerful natural sanctuaries that exist
throughout all of the world.<P>

To understand the meaning and importance of sacred sites, we also need experience, <I> authentic </I> experience. Many people have already had transformative experiences at places like Machu Pichu or Chaco Canyon, where a sacred site is marked by a shrine. Others have had these life-changing experiences in the wild -- in a canyon, on a mountaintop, in the ocean, in our own backyards. Indigenous people are willing to teach and guide us as we seek these experiences, but the process should not be taken lightly. This is not a New Age fad. There are rules. There is etiquette. There are cultural secrets. Powerful forces are at work at the heart of sacred places.<P>

I recently showed Florence Jones three hours of film footage. We watched her singing
in trance, praying to Panther Spring on Mt. Shasta, and blessing native people
at a healing ceremony atop Universe Rock on Cold Springs Mountain -- images
that capture spiritual connection to place and illustrate how a trained healer
works with the powers of the natural world. After seeing the footage, Florence
said: "I want to show this video to the Forest Service to show them how
important these sites are to my people." <P>

Our sense of urgency grows with the ongoing need to interview elders before
they pass away. Also, the 1994 national elections manifested a new and
potent threat to sacred sites: the "wise-use"/private property rights movement.
Mt. Shasta may be the first victim. Florence Jones recently won an important victory
and it has already been undone. The Department of the Interior in
March 1994, recognized Mt. Shasta -- in its entirety -- as a national historic
site due to its "spiritual significance" to Native Californians. Ten days after
the November 1994 elections, however, this historic decision was reversed under
intense pressure from local property owners. A proposed ski resort once again
threatens Florence's sacred spring, and the implications for native land rights
are ominous. This story will be at the heart of our first film on Mt. Shasta
and Florence Jones.<P>

This is an important moment to be producing documentary films that can capture
these stories as they unfold. It is clear that now is the time to get some of
these urgent stories out to the public. Our current plan is to complete a film
on Florence Jones and Mt. Shasta as we work with the Hopi and move towards a
second piece on the Four Corners area. Then, with two films in distribution, we
will be in a good position to raise production funds for our larger vision: a
continuing series on the meaning of sacred land to cultures around the world.
<P>

As the current social and legislative climate moves America toward
privatization of public lands, many of us feel a deeply renewed commitment to
take concrete action that will eventually help bring about real ecological
change in our society. Media is a vital tool for educating the general public
and influencing people in positions of power. With so much of the media
concentrated in a shrinking number of hands and progressive government support
for documentary filmmaking on the verge of being eliminated, independent media
have never been so important or so difficult to produce. Independent voices can
help focus on the real issues that underlie the frustration and search for
meaning that in all likelihood cannot be addressed in the mainstream media. To
accomplish this ambitious and challenging project we must work together with,
and gain the support of, like-minded funders -- people who see the
environmental crisis as a spiritual crisis. We hope you will join us in this
effort.<P>

We have some wonderful and important footage and are ready to continue filming.
Your support at this critical time in the project's evolution would be
enormously helpful. Our production budget for these first two film segments is
$300,000.<P>

Tax-deductible contributions are welcome, and may be made out to Earth Island
Institute/SLFP and sent to P.O. Box C-151, La Honda CA 94020 or to Earth Island
Institute, 300 Broadway, Suite 28, San Francisco, CA 94133. <P>

For further information contact: Christopher (Toby) McLeod, Earth Image Films,
P.O. Box C-151, La Honda, CA 94020 USA (e-mail: eif@igc.apc.org)<P>

Thank you very much for your interest and your support!<P>

More about the The Sacred Land Film Project:<P>

