<H1>SLFP Project Status</H1>
<TITLE>SLFP Project Status</TITLE>

The Sacred Land Film Project is currently producing the first two in a series
of films on the meaning of sacred land to a variety of cultures around the
world. Our first film focuses on Mt. Shasta, in northern California, and
Florence Jones, an 87-year-old  medicine woman who may be the last in a long lineage of healers from the Wintu tribe. The second film focuses on the Four Corners area
of the American Southwest, homeland of the A HREF="../journal/blmesa.html">Hopi</A> and Navajo, a region described by Hopi spokesman Thomas Banyacya as "a sacred chamber" which the Hopi
protect through prayer and ceremony.<P>

A little project history: Our original plan was to produce a four-part series that would tell stories of sacred sites and indigenous cultures around the world.
Project Director Christopher "Toby" McLeod made a five-month, round-the-world research trip in 1991-2 to develop this global film series. His experiences on that research trip are detailed in the winter 1993-4 issue of <A HREF="../journal/journal.html">Earth
Island Journal</A>.<P>

After spending two years (1992-3) fundraising we decided that coming up with $2.5 million for a film series that is both political and spiritual would take a long time, especially in the current
economic and political climate. We elected to begin production close to home --
at Mt. Shasta and in Hopi country -- with several elders who are caretakers of
sacred sites and whose knowledge and wisdom, we feel, simply must be preserved
and shared.<P>

And so, after two years of research and development, 1994 marked the start of
production of the Sacred Land Film Series.<P>

In August 1994, we filmed four days of ceremonies in northern California,
working with Wintu medicine woman Florence Jones. It was an
incredible experience and we were able to capture scenes that we once thought
we might never be able to film. We filmed a sunset fire ceremony with Mt. Shasta rising on the western horizon, a healing ceremony at Panther Spring on Mt. Shasta and another healing ceremony at Universe Rock. We also filmed a four-hour meeting between Florence and the local district ranger of the U.S. Forest Service, in which Florence stated her strong opposition to a ski resort that is proposed for the slopes of Mt. Shasta and which would desecrate Panther Spring. It was an auspicious beginning to the production phase of the film series. Our experience at Mt. Shasta is described in detail in the winter 1994-5 issue of <A HREF="../journal/journal.html">Earth
Island Journal</A>.<P>

In 1995, we continued our work with Florence Jones and 86 year-old Hopi
spokesman Thomas Banyacya, filming key scenes that will make up the heart of
the first two films in the Sacred Land Film Series. <P>

In August 1995, we confronted one of the central questions of the film series:
Is the destruction of sacred sites intentional or does it occur out of ignorance?
In the spring of 1995, a major California timber company cut down several important trees in a sacred grove that serves as a Wintu men's prayer and fasting site. Florence Jones had previously journeyed to the site with the forester from the company to point out its boundaries. The area was marked off with ribbons to
identify it as a cultural site and each tree was painted with the word "NO." A
week later, chainsaw-wielding loggers entered the site and cut down three big
Douglas Fir trees. Our film trip up the mountain with Florence and three
employees of the logging company, along with Florence's attorney Patricia
Cummings, after the trees were cut down, is described in the film project's 1995 Annual Report. <P>

In November 1995, we found ourselves on the edge of the Hopi mesas,
interviewing Thomas Banyacya about the spiritual center his people have
inhabited and cared for through prayer for thousands of years. In the camera's
view over Thomas' shoulder was a simple but distinctive mesa, the place from
which the spirits of the deceased depart from this world. Thomas told the story
of the Spanish occupation of Hopi land in the 17th century. Hopi religion was
suppressed and their ceremonies were stopped. "There was no rain," said Thomas.
"Famine began to spread. It could destroy the whole earth like a flood. We had
to stop it. All Pueblos rose up one day and got rid of the churches and the
priests. We began singing and dancing and the rain started coming again. So,
this Four Corners area is very important."<P>

In 1996, we will continue our film work with Florence and Thomas, documenting their struggles to protect sacred sites and their efforts to explain the importance of these spiritual places to those who will listen.  <P> 

After several years of
careful preparation, we are now gathering the wealth of material from which
good films are made. And we are excited about narrowing the focus of the project from the four-part global series to these two initial films. We believe that two films on specific sacred sites and the elders who love and protect them will be a good start to the larger, global film series. We will soon have two finished films in distribution. They will be invaluable in fundraising, and the material from them can easily be edited into the larger series.<P>

More about the The Sacred Land Film Project:<P>

<UL>

<LI><A HREF="sacredla.html">Introduction</A><P>

<LI><A HREF="detail.html">The Sacred Land Film Series -- a detailed description</A><P>

<LI><A HREF="premise.html">The Premise of the Sacred Land Film Project</A><P>

</UL>


