<TITLE>STRP: First Dolphin-Safe Tuna, now Sea Turtle-Safe Shrimp?</TITLE>

<H2>First Dolphin-Safe Tuna, now Sea Turtle-Safe Shrimp?</H2>

<H3>ASPCA, The Fund For Animals, The Humane Society of the United States Join Earth Island Institute in Turtle-Safe(TM) Shrimp Eco-labeling Campaign<P>

Mutilated Sea Turtles Wash Ashore on Texas Beaches</H3>

San Francisco -- Citing the federal government's apparent inability to end the drowning deaths of thousands of endangered sea turtles every year in US waters, a coalition of over 45 environmental and animal protection organizations and concerned businesses has launched a consumer-powered campaign to end the slaughter. The Turtle-Safe(TM) Shrimp Program works with responsible shrimp fishers who use fishing gear which allows sea turtles to escape from shrimp nets. <P>

"From its inception in 1866 the ASPCA has been, and will continue to be, committed to protecting endangered sea turtles," said Jamie Cotel Altman of the ASPCA."Turtle Excluder Devices, or TEDs, are inexpensive devices which, when sewn into shrimp nets, serve as an easy means of escape for sea turtles. Use of TEDs is mandated by federal law."<P>

Despite such laws, in 1995 over 2,000 sea turtles washed up dead on US beaches. These high numbers support the widely-held belief that many US shrimpers, particularly in the Gulf of Mexico, are disabling their TEDs because they fear a reduced catch. Yet when used properly, TEDs can actually increase the overall shrimp catch and lower operating costs.<P>

"Shrimpers who properly and consistently use TEDs, and sign contracts with Earth Island Institute agreeing to participate in a monitoring program, are certified as Turtle-Safe," explained Todd Steiner, Director of the Sea Turtle Restoration Project of Earth Island Institute. "They are permitted to use our Turtle-Safe logo on their shrimp, and display signs on their boats. For our part, we help increase demand through our ever-growing activist network, and by publicizing the campaign and the product."<P>

Over 100 sea turtles have stranded since shrimp season opened, only a few weeks ago. Many of these turtles have had their flippers and/or heads cut off. Some have even been shot. One Kemp's ridley sea turtle had been shot twice and had a rope tied around one flipper; presumably the rope had been tied to a weight in hopes of "sinking the evidence." The Kemp's ridley is one of the most endangered animals on earth.<P>

"The addition of large national organizations with millions of members, such as the ASPCA, The Fund for Animals and The Humane Society of the United States, will enable us to reach millions of US citizens with our message: Don't eat shrimp unless it's Turtle-Safe," added Carole Allen of Help Endangered Animals - Ridley Turtles (HEART), a Houston, Texas-based organization which has spearheaded the coalition-building effort. "Shrimpers who refuse to save sea turtles need to feel the economic pressure millions of caring consumers can wield."<P>

"Shrimp fishing is one of the most wasteful fisheries in the world," said Dr. John W. Grandy of The Humane Society of the United States. "In addition to drowning thousands of sea turtles every year, shrimp nets capture and kill ten pounds of non-target species for every pound of shrimp caught. TEDs reduce this "by-catch" by up to 60%. They reduce impacts to sea turtles and to the entire marine environment."<P>

"The National Marine Fisheries Service has proven itself unwilling to take meaningful action to save these gentle creatures from extinction," said Cleveland Amory, best-selling author and president of The Fund for Animals. "We will use the power of the pocketbook to bring about change and protect this endangered species. Scientists agree: we need some areas of the Gulf to be closed to shrimp fishing, and we need to limit the number of shrimp boats in the fleet. It's out of control."<P>

"We did it for the dolphins," pointed out Steiner, referring to Earth Island's successful campaign to end the drowning of dolphins in tuna nets by convincing shoppers to boycott tuna. "We can do it for the sea turtles. Georgia shrimpers who are participating in this campaign provided over one million pounds of Turtle-Safe shrimp to the marketplace in our pilot project phase last year. We invite Texas shrimpers to get on board."<P>

<H2>Visuals Available</H2>
Video footage (VHS and 3/4") of sea turtles, TEDs, and Georgia shrimpers.<P>

Color slides of live and stranded sea turtles (including mutilated turtles).<P>

Graphics of the Turtle-Safe logo and TEDs.


<H2>Contacts</H2>

