<TITLE>STRP: New Study Shows 60,000 Sea Turtles Caught Each Year in Central
American Shrimp Nets</TITLE>

<H2>New Study Shows 60,000 Sea Turtles Caught Each Year in Central
American Shrimp Nets</H2>

More than sixty thousand sea turtles a year are captured by the approximately
350 vessels that make up the shrimp fleets of the seven Central American
nations, according to a new study by STRP Central American Director Randall
Arauz Vargas. The report was presented to the 16th Annual Sea Turtle
Conference, held in February, 1996 at Hilton Head Island, South Carolina. <P>

Most turtles captured are olive ridleys, with lesser numbers of greens,
hawksbills and leatherbacks.  The vast majority are caught off Central
America's Pacific coast.  Only 500 sea turtles are caught off these countries'
Caribbean coasts each year.  Ironically, these nations (under pressure from the
US government) have all passed laws requiring TED use only on their Caribbean
fleets, allowing the continued drowning of tens of thousands of turtles on the
Pacific side each year.<P>

Previous estimates of the numbers of sea turtles captured in shrimp nets
worldwide have been "guesses" at best.  The US is the only nation that has
conducted in-depth studies.  Estimates for other countries have been based on
the assumption that sea turtle capture rates per ton of shrimp caught are
similar to such rates for the US.

"Randall has pulled together the best available data from Central America and
we now have a much better understanding of the magnitude of the problem.  It is
obvious we need international implementation of TEDs to help save the turtles,"
said Jack Woody, one of STRP's scientific advisors.  <P>

The report is available from STRP by sending a SASE (52 cents).

<H3>Estimate Of Sea Turtles Captured by Central American Shrimp Fleets</H3>

<TABLE BORDER CELLPADDING=5>

<TR><TH ALIGN=LEFT>Country</TH><TH ALIGN=RIGHT># of vessels</TH><TH ALIGN=RIGHT>Turtles per year</TH></TR>
<TR><TD>Belize (Caribbean)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>10</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>87</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Guatemala (Pacific)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>58</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><I>10,000</I></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>El Salvador (Pacific)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>70</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>21,280</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Honduras (Caribbean)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>89</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>287</TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Nicaragua (Caribbean)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>40</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><I>140</I></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Nicaragua (Pacific)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>21</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT><I>8,000</I></TD></TR>
<TR><TD>Costa Rica (Pacific)</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>55</TD><TD ALIGN=RIGHT>20,762</TD></TR>
<Tr><TH ALIGN=LEFT>Total Caribbean</Th><Th ALIGN=RIGHT>139</Th><Th ALIGN=RIGHT>514</Th></Tr>
