<H1>Turtle-Safe Shrimp Makes Waves</H1>

<TITLE>STRP: Turtle-Safe Shrimp Makes Waves</TITLE>

Turtle-Safe&#174; shrimp has made the leap from the boat deck to the
marketplace, landing in restaurants and markets on both US coasts.<P>

The Turtle-Safe campaign takes a new market-oriented approach to the old
problem of sea turtles drowning in shrimp nets.  Shrimp caught by fishermen who
join the program carry a Turtle-Safe seal on the package.  The seal lets
consumers know which shrimp was caught using fishing gear that allows turtles
to escape.<P>

Publicity, including a full-page advertisement (run in the New York Times in
July 1995), a brochure, and a television public service announcement, informs
consumers about the sea turtle/shrimp interaction and how consumer demand can
make a difference.  Fishermen who use turtle excluder devices (TEDs) receive
recognition for their efforts.  For the first time, there's a way to tell their
shrimp from other shrimp and encouragement for others to follow their
example.<P>

The program started with forward-looking fishermen from Georgia.  One from
South Carolina has also joined the program.  Georgia fishermen were pioneers in
turtle protection, developing the first excluders to keep out jellyfish and
horseshoe crabs as early as the late 1960s.

The first boxes of fresh Turtle-Safe shrimp were shipped last fall, a peak time
for Georgia white shrimp, to distributors in San Francisco, Boston, and Denver.
 In addition the Organic Farming Research Foundation (OFRF) served Turtle-Safe
shrimp at events at the landmark Claremont Hotel in Oakland, CA, and at One
Market in San Francisco.<P>

OFRF, California Certified Organic Farmers (CCOF), and the Rainforest
Alliance's Smart Wood Program, have generously offered support and advice that
helped get Turtle-Safe shrimp on menus and in stores.  The CCOF program was
created and is managed by the farmers themselves.  A first step in that
direction for the Turtle-Safe program is the Turtle-Safe Advisory Board. 
Fishermen, dock owners, and OFRF's executive director Bob Scowcroft are among
the board members.<P>

Turtle-Safe shrimp is in the pilot program stage. You can help get more
Turtle-Safe shrimp on the market by asking for it at restaurants and
supermarkets.  This lets them and, in turn, their suppliers know that their
customers want only shrimp caught while protecting sea turtles.  <P>


<HR>
<H2>Other Stories</H2>

Giant Legal <A HREF="0396victory.html">Victory for Sea Turtles</A>! 70
Nations must adopt sea turtle conservation measures or face shrimp embargo on
May 1st.<P>

New Study Shows <A HREF="0396newstudy.html">60,000 Sea Turtles Caught Each
Year in Central American</A> Shrimp Nets<P>

<A HREF="0396whshrmp.html">Where Can I Buy Turtle-Safe Shrimp?</A><P>

<A HREF="0396gulfc.html">Gulf Crisis Worsens</A>- Top Scientists join in
our lawsuit to save critically endangered Sea Turtles. <P>

<A HREF="0396lackfaith.html">Scientists declare</A> lack of faith in the
National Marine Fisheries Service<P>


<A HREF="0396saveesa.html">Save the Endangered Species Act!</A><P>

