<TITLE>STRP: Gulf Crisis Worsens</TITLE>

<H1>Gulf Crisis Worsens</H1>

<H2>Top Scientists join in our lawsuit to save critically endangered Sea
Turtles.</H2>

Sea turtles continued to strand (wash up dead) on US beaches in record numbers
in 1995 (see chart), a continuation of the problem that re-surfaced in 1994.
Two separate Endangered Species Act lawsuits have been filed against the
National Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS), in an attempt to force NMFS to take
effective action on this crisis. <P>

All parties agree that the major source of mortality is from shrimp fishing,
although there is significant disagreement over the precise cause.  Is the
problem primarily caused by "cheaters" dismantling TEDs while fishing?  Is it
"pulse-fishing" (turtles being caught multiple times with insufficient recovery
time between captures)?  Is it an increase in turtle populations, so there are
more to kill?  Or could it be the unmentionable: TEDs are not as effective as
believed?<P>

<H2>Government Response Inadequate</H2>

In a biological opinion issued November 14, 1994, required under the Endangered
Species Act, NMFS wrote, "the continued long-term operation of the shrimp
fishery in the nearshore waters of the southeastern United States is likely to
jeopardize the continued existence of the highly endangered Kemp's ridley sea
turtle."  In order to issue an incidental take exception which would allow
shrimp fishing to continue, NMFS had to put in place a "reasonable and prudent
alternative" that would "ensure no jeopardy" to the Kemp's ridley sea turtle.
That alternative became known as the "Emergency Response Plan" (ERP).  The ERP
included weekly monitoring of sea turtle mortality, and temporary 30-day
increases in enforcement when strandings exceeded historical averages for two
consecutive weeks.  <P>

<B>In 1994, 2,149 sea turtles stranded, including at least 565 Kemp's ridleys.
In 1995, with the government's ERP in full operation, 2,175 turtles stranded,
including at least 373 Kemp's ridleys.</B><P>

The Kemp's ridley is one of the most endangered animals on earth.  Less than
1000 breeding females remain, all nesting on one beach.<P>

<H2>Conservation Groups Sue To Force Action</H2>

A lawsuit was filed by Earth Island Institute, Carole Allen, founder and Chair
of HEART (Help Endangered Animals - Ridley Turtles), and The Humane Society of
the US.  The suit charges that the ERP is inadequate to solve this chronic
problem, and calls for major reform, including closing critical Kemp's ridley
habitat in the Gulf of Mexico to shrimp fishing.  Of critical importance were
the biological opinions provided by three prominent sea turtle scientists in
support of this lawsuit (see sidebar).  <P>

Another lawsuit, filed by the Center for Marine Conservation (CMC), is
attempting to compel the government to enforce the ERP, which it felt the
government was not doing.<P>

These most recent lawsuits follow years of NMFS foot-dragging over
implementation and enforcement of TEDs.  CMC has published an excellent account
of this controversy, entitled "Delay and Denial: A Political History of Sea
Turtles and Shrimp Fishing."  It seems that every time the environmental
community sues or threatens to sue, NMFS comes up with a "new plan."  This
solves their legal problem, since federal judges usually take a "wait and see
attitude" to see if the new plan will work.  This is where we find ourselves
today as we await yet another "new rule", promised in November 1995, but tied
up in bureaucratic delay.<P>

Did the ERP plan fail because it was not adequately enforced, or because it was
a bad plan to begin with?  With the 1996 shrimping season opening in a month or
so, this is hardly the point.  The preliminary stranding figures for 1995
already exceed the record numbers of 1994.  Strong and decisive action is
needed to ensure that 1996 isn't another disastrous year for endangered sea
turtles.<P>

<H2>Area Closures Needed to Protect Kemp's Ridley</H2>

The Earth Island/HEART/HSUS lawsuit calls for an injunction to prohibit
shrimping in times and areas where sea turtles are known to occur in high
numbers, until the government can ensure that shrimping activities will not
jeopardize the continued existence of the endangered sea turtles.  These areas
include nearshore waters in parts of Texas and Louisiana, but are only a small
part of the range of the shrimp fishing fleets of the Gulf.<P>

"NMFS' plan has failed miserably.  The Kemp's ridley turtle is one of the most
endangered species in the world, and the government agency responsible for its
protection continues to concoct half-hearted schemes, such as the so-called
'Emergency Response Plan,' which appear to be designed more to protect the
shrimp industry than the endangered sea turtles," said STRP Director Todd
Steiner.  He continued, "We will not stand idly by while a species that
outlived the dinosaur disappears from earth right before our eyes.  It's
criminal and unforgivable." <P>

<H2>Shrimp Industry in Denial</H2>

The turtles that have washed up dead represent only a fraction of those
actually killed.  Many die and never wash ashore, and some that wash ashore are
never found.  Some turtles are being maliciously mutilated, either to send a
message of non-compliance or in hope that cut-up turtles will sink or become
shark food, thus destroying the evidence of mortality.  Turtles ripped from
their shells, decapitated turtles and turtles with flippers missing and metal
bars tied to them have washed up on our shores from Texas to South Carolina.<P>

Shrimp fishers in the Gulf have been quick to blame their economic woes on
turtle-saving regulations issued under the Endangered Species Act.
Environmentalists counter that the shrimp fishery in the Gulf is not
sustainable.  The number of vessels fishing  for shrimp in the Gulf has
increased 250 percent since the 1950s, yet the amount of shrimp harvested has
not increased significantly (from approximately 90 million pounds to 128
million pounds).  <P>

Meanwhile, the vessels and the amount of nets being pulled have gotten bigger,
the cost of operating the vessels has gone up dramatically, and US shrimpers
have to compete with cheap imported farm-raised shrimp.  The numbers of vessels
shrimping in the Gulf must go down if shrimpers are going to have a chance of
surviving economically.  Unfortunately, more and bigger shrimp vessels are
still being built at the present time.<P>

Environmentalists blame NMFS for failing to adequately regulate the fisheries
or protect endangered sea turtles.  Steiner said, "The facts are clear. The
shrimpers are overfishing the resource, the fishery is overcapitalized and NMFS
is doing nothing to limit entry. This is a disaster occurring right before our
eyes -- what is happening to the turtles is only a symptom of what's happening
to the marine environment.  Turtles, shrimpers and the ecosystem are all the
losers."<P>


