<TITLE>Scientists declare Lack of faith in the National Marine Fisheries
Service</TITLE>

<H2>Scientists declare Lack of faith in the National Marine Fisheries
Service</H2>

In their supporting declarations to our lawsuit, these top sea turtle
scientists clearly state their lack of faith in the National Marine Fisheries
Service, and the need for immediate action to halt the sea turtle crisis in US
waters.<P>

<H3>Dr. Pam Plotkin<BR>
Former NMFS Acting National Sea Turtle Coordinator</H3>


"In my professional opinion, the ERP (Emergency Response Plan) is unlikely to
protect sea turtles... My best professional judgement, based on the
inadequacies in the ERP and the importance of the nearshore habitat, is that
the nearshore waters of the Northwestern Gulf of Mexico should be immediately
closed to shrimping."<P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Dr. Peter Pritchard<BR>
Co-author of the definitive National Academy of Sciences
report "Decline of the Sea Turtles"</H3>

"Given the high continuing levels of sea turtle strandings described above, the
Plan is a failure and cannot be relied upon to reduce sea turtle mortalities to
an acceptable level.... based on my thirty years experience, an immediate
moratorium in nearshore Texas waters is necessary to insure the continued
existence of the Kemp's ridley."<P>

</BLOCKQUOTE>

<H3>Jack Woody<BR>
Former Sea Turtle Coordinator, US Fish and Wildlife
Service</H3>

"Unless the cause of this loss is promptly addressed and halted in 1995 (which
the government's plan is unable to accomplish), the species' survival remains
in grave jeopardy.  A number of actions, implemented properly, could greatly
curtail the further loss of turtles for this and future seasons.  To begin
with, there must be some seasonal trawling closures in defined areas [along the
Gulf Coast]."

</BLOCKQUOTE>



