<TITLE>STRP: Save the Endangered Species Act</TITLE>

<H1>Save the Endangered Species Act!</H1>

When Congress passed the Endangered Species Act in 1973, it gave the US one of
the strongest pieces of environmental legislation in the world.  The ESA not
only mandated federal agencies to identify and list species at risk, but also
to write and implement recovery plans.<P>

The ESA has been strengthened three times since then: in 1978, 1982 and 1988. 
But now in 1996, with ecosystems unravelling under an onslaught of industrial
exploitation, the ESA itself is in danger of extinction.  With the ESA up for
reauthorization, the so-called "Wise Use" (Unwise Abuse) Movement and its
friends in the 104th Congress have been on the offensive, depicting the ESA as
unwieldy, expensive and outmoded.  They would like to see the ESA eliminated or
drastically weakened in order to allow industrial activity (including shrimp
fishing) to proceed unimpeded, no matter what the impact to endangered species
and their habitats. <P>

A number of "wise-use" bills have been offered up by anti-ESA politicians. 
Fortunately, the public supports protecting endangered species, and largely
sees past the hype to the real intent of bills which would "amend" the ESA. 
<P>

The Young/Pombo bill (HR 2275), which passed the House Resources Committee in
October 1995, is a severe piece of legislation.  Its provisions would
specifically harm sea turtles and other endangered and threatened marine
species.  <P>

Under the Young/Pombo bill, shrimp fishermen would be exempted from using
Turtle Excluder Devices (TEDs), if the shrimpers make donations to conservation
programs for sea turtles, such as the protection of nesting beaches.  TEDs have
proven to be 97% effective in saving sea turtles when properly used; the
removal of TED requirements would drastically hurt sea turtles.  There is
little point in protecting nesting beaches while allowing turtles to drown by
the thousands at sea.<P>

HR2275 would also lift the ban on importation of wildlife and wildlife products
governed by the Convention on International Trade of Endangered Species
(CITES).  <P>

Other unpopular extremist bills, such as those authored by Kempthorne (R-ID)
and Gorton (R-WA) would severely damage the country's efforts to protect
endangered wildlife and plants, including the six species of sea turtles
currently listed as "endangered" or "threatened" under the ESA. <P>

Last fall Congress placed a moratorium on new listings of threatened or
endangered species, by eliminating the funding necessary for the US Fish and
Wildlife Service to undertake such listings.  This means many species at risk
are not getting the protection they need.  This will actually <B>increase</B> the
ultimate cost of recovery; while debate drags on the situation for imperilled
species can only worsen.<P>

The fact that this is an election year may push the ESA reauthorization issue
into 1997.   In the meantime, wildlife advocates must pressure their
representatives to oppose attempts to weaken the ESA, and let them know there
is public support for <B>stronger</B> endangered species legislation.


<HR>
