<TITLE>Save India's Bhitar Kanika: Critical olive ridley sea turtle nesting
beach</TITLE>

<H2>Save India's Bhitar Kanika: Critical olive ridley sea turtle nesting
beach</H2>

In our last newsletter we filled you in on the precarious status of the Bhitar
Kanika Wildlife Sanctuary on the Bay of Bengal in Orissa, India.  This
international treasure, 415 miles square, is the worlds most important nesting
beach for the olive ridley sea turtle.  Bhitar Kanika also contains the
second-largest contiguous mangrove forest in India, provides critical habitat
for the endangered estuarine crocodile, and is home to over 80,000 wading
birds.<P>

Construction of a commercial fishing port adjacent to Bhitar Kanika threatens
the ecological integrity of the area.  The port would include 500 shrimp
trawlers, a processing plant and shrimp farming operations.  Intensive shrimp
trawling would quickly diminish local fisheries, while shrimp farming would
deforest and pollute the ecosystem.  The terrible effects of shrimp trawling on
sea turtles are well-known.<P>

Last year, in response to international pressure, the Chief Minister of Orissa
State voiced his support for making Bhitar Kanika a National Park, and
potentially a United Nations Biosphere Reserve.  Unfortunately, the Chief
Minister lost his seat in the last election, and the new Chief Minister has
been slow to support protection for Bhitar Kanika.<P>

<H3>Please Take Action!</H3>

The fight is far from over!  We must continue to put international pressure on
the Indian government.  Please send letters or postcards to the Indian
officials below, expressing your desire that Bhitar Kanika be protected.<P>

Chief Minister of Orissa<BR> Government of Orissa<BR> Bhubaneshwar, Orissa,
INDIA<P>

Prime Minister<BR> P.V. Narashimha Rao<BR> Rashtrapati Bhavan<BR> New Delhi
110011, INDIA<P>

We also have petitions available, and a Bhitar Kanika comic book! <A
HREF="mailto:sea turtle@igc.apc.orgs">Contact STRP</A> at 415-488-0370 to
receive copies.


