<TITLE>STRP: Sea turtle products for sale at Vietnam Airport</TITLE>

<H1>Sea turtle products for sale at Vietnam Airport</H1>

The Sea Turtle Restoration Project has recently received reports and photo
documentation of sea turtle products being sold in the duty-free section of
Vietnam's Ho Chi Minh City airport.  These products, made from endangered
hawksbill sea turtles, include eyeglass frames, cigarette holders, hair pins,
fans, necklaces and whole stuffed turtles.<P>

Vietnam has recently joined the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species of Wild Fauna and Flora (CITES).  Sea turtle products are available for
sale throughout Vietnam, but as a new CITES member Vietnam agreed to ban
<B>international</B> trade in these products.  Selling sea turtle products to people
<B>after</B> they have passed through customs on their way out of Vietnam violates the
spirit, and potentially the letter, of the CITES ban.<P>

This is just one example of a global problem: the sale of endangered species
products in airports around the world.  Our concerns have been brought to the
attention of Dr. Sue Lieberman of the US Fish and Wildlife Service' Office of
Management Authority, who will be discussing the matter with CITES authorities
when she meets with them next.<P>

STRP is working with other concerned groups to bring an end to this heinous
practice.  We will take every step possible to see that these products are
removed from the duty-free shop, and to end all trade in endangered sea
turtles.

<H3>You Can Help!</H3>

Please write to the Vietnamese government and ask them to end their trade in
endangered sea turtles.  Write to:<P>

CITES Management Authority<BR> Ministry of Forestry<BR> 123 Lo Duc<BR> Hanoi,
Vietnam<BR> fax 844-252-542


<HR>
