<H1>Turtle-Safe Shrimp News</H1>

<TITLE>STRP: Turtle-Safe Shrimp News</TITLE>

Turtle-Safe shrimp has made the leap from the boat deck to the marketplace,
landing in restaurants and markets on both U.S. coasts.<P>

The Turtle-Safe campaign takes a new market-oriented approach to the old
problem of sea turtles drowning in shrimp nets. In the first years after the
U.S. government required shrimp fishermen to use turtle excluder devices about
1990, many environmentalists and fishermen alike thought the turtles were safe.
The past two years proved them wrong. More than 4,000 washed up on U.S. shores.
 Based on pre-TEDs U.S. figures, the Sea Turtle Restoration Project estimates
shrimp nets are fatal to 155,000 each year in other countries.<P>

Shrimp caught by fishermen who join the program carry a Turtle-Safe seal on the
package. The seal lets consumers know which shrimp was caught using fishing
gear that allows turtles to escape.<P>

Publicity, like the New York Times ad that ran in July, a brochure, and a
television public service announcement, informs consumers about the sea
turtle-shrimp interaction and how their demand can influence the outcome.
Fishermen who use turtle excluder devices (TEDs) receive recognition for their
efforts. For the first time, there's a way to tell their shrimp from other
shrimp and encouragement for others to follow their example.<P>

The program started with forward-looking fishermen from Georgia. Georgia
fishermen were pioneers in turtle protection, developing the first excluders to
keep out jellyfish and horseshoe crabs as early as the late 1960s.

The first boxes of fresh Turtle-Safe shrimp were shipped last fall, a peak time
for Georgia white shrimp, to distributors in San Francisco, Boston, and Denver.
Bread & Circus stores in Boston, owned by Whole Foods Market, were among stores
that carried the shrimp. The Organic Farming Research Foundation (OFRF) served
Turtle-Safe at two events, one at the landmark Claremont Hotel in Oakland,
Calif., and the other at One Market in San Francisco.<P>

OFRF, California Certified Organic Farmers, and the Rainforest Alliance's Smart
Wood Program, have generously offered support and advice that helped get
Turtle-Safe shrimp on menus and in stores. The California program was created
and is managed by the farmers themselves. A first step in that direction for
the Turtle-Safe program is the Turtle-Safe Advisory Board. Fishermen, dock
owners, and OFRF's executive director Bob Scowcroft are among the board
members.<P>

Turtle-Safe shrimp is in the pilot program stage and the shrimp is in short
supply. You can help get more on the market by asking for Turtle-Safe shrimp.
Even though the winter months are the off-season for Georgia shrimp, just
asking for Turtle-Safe creates demand. It lets restaurants, supermarkets, and,
in turn, their suppliers know that their customers want only shrimp caught
while protecting sea turtles.<P>

<HR>


