<TITLE>Beyond the 'Scenic By-Ways'</TITLE>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Beyond the 'Scenic By-Ways'</H2><P>


The Southern Rockies, world-renowned for their scenic beauty and outstanding recreational opportunities, are in trouble.  Decades of impact from resource extraction such as logging, road-building, mining and grazing, has left a legacy of damage that poses serious threats to the region's ability to sustain wildlife and wild habitat.  While some pristine pockets of untouched wilderness remain, the fact is that just over the ridge from that spectacular view are clearcuts, badly-eroding roads, polluted streams and trampled vegetation.  The intact pieces that are left are insufficient to sustain the biological integrity of the region.  While the damage is extensive,  much of it can and must be healed if we are to prevent further deterioration of habitat quality, and the decline of numerous species of animal and plant life.

<P>


 Comprehensive watershed management offers the best chance of protecting, restoring and enhancing the region's watershed resources .  All concerned and affected parties must be brought together in a coordinated effort to develop and apply a long-term, sustainable strategy for watershed management which will address the problems of environmental degradation, habitat fragmentation, loss of biodiversity, declining local economies and quality of life.
<P>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>Healing the Damage</H2><P>

Restoring damaged ecosystems requires the coordinated efforts of a diverse group of people.  Local community members must team up with indiginous leaders, scientific experts and environmental activists to determine the needs of the land, and the most appropriate method of healing the damage.  The Southern Rockies Restoration Project is working to establish Watershed Councils in each of the regions watersheds, and to give them the tools necessary to plan and carry out effective restoration projects.<P>
<BR>
<P ALIGN=CENTER><BLOCKQUOTE><CENTER><!-- Link Tag --><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="srrp.html">Back to SRRP home page</A></A> | <!-- Link Tag --><!--A HREF="region.html">The Southern Rockies Ecoregion</A></CENTER>
