<IMG SRC="carl-sml.gif"><P> <TITLE>A Message from Earth Island Institute's
President</TITLE> <H1>A Message from Earth Island Institute's President</H1>

Both challenges and accomplishments marked the year 1994.  Every day the media
carried stories about the changing atmosphere, loss of habitat, and threats to
biological and cultural diversity.  But as
Earth Island's President,  I can look back with pride on the work that our
staff, volunteers, and members have done to make the planet healthier and more
accommodating for all life.<P>

The principles of social justice must be at the heart of efforts to protect our
planet.  Our vision must offer a real alternative to seeing the tropical
rainforest as either a private laboratory for multinational pharmaceutical
companies or an inviolate preserve, ignoring the needs of indigenous
populations.  We must avoid the misuse of environmental issues as a way of
rationalizing the economic status quo.  We cannot manipulate terms so that the
legitimate need for population control becomes a code word for racism.<P>

Alienation from the source of our abundance and well-being - the natural
environment - is a greatly disturbing trend.  The loss of this contact with
living and growing things, even rudimentary knowledge of where food and water
come from, presents serious consequences that we have no way of measuring.<P>

The alarming results of the national elections in November 1994 and the
escalating attacks on our environment and on the disenfranchised remind us that
we must never become complacent.  In 1995, Earth Island continues to be a place
where environmental leadership is cultivated and where the struggles for
ecological consciousness and social justice draw nourishment.  Thank you for
your support.<P>

Carl Anthony, President<P>


<HR>


