<html>







<head>



<title>GSC Background and Organization</title>



</head>







<body>







<H2>Background and History of the Global Service Corps Organization</H2>







<br>







Rick Lathrop<br>



Executive Director<p>







The idea behind Global Service Corps (GSC) began evolving in 



1992 during my mid-career graduate studies.  Prior to that time I had gained 



experience as a high school teacher, a print advertising account 



representative, a non profit administrator, and an adult holistic educater and 



leadership trainer.  My graduate studies were part of the Human and 



Organization Development Ph.D. program at The Fielding Institute in Santa 



Barbara, California.  At Fielding I became interested in global studies, 



particularly in the area of sustainable development, and discovered that there 



were few educational programs available for adults to gain first-hand 



experience in the field of international development.  With the assistance of 



a small start-up grant from Fielding, I began the development of a program of 



short-term, "mini Peace Corps" types of experiences to provide Fielding students 



and others international grass roots exposure to global issues.  The concept 



soon expanded to include participation of adults from all walks of life 



interested in this kind of experience.  I began developing the GSC program 



part time while continuing my studies, finished my Masters degree 



in Organization Development in August of 1994, and have since been working full time 



on this endeavor.<p>







In 1993, GSC developed a working relationship with Global 



Routes, an organization which had been providing international community 



service summer programs for high school and college students for about ten 



years.  The two principals of Global Routes are friends of mine and they 



offered to assist me with the development of Global Service Corps by providing 



their non profit status along with their administrative expertise and 



international contacts.  Acting as the nominal adult division of Global Routes, 



GSC began to establish volunteer service programs for adults, 



with an emphasis on village-based sustainable development.  The first project 



trip took place in December of 1993 in Costa Rica, when 7 volunteers spent two 



weeks volunteering at the Monteverde Cloud Forest Preserve and the Curu 



Biological Reserve.  The GSC program expanded to Kenya in 1994, with projects 



relating to small scale food production utilizing biointensive gardening, and 



community based health care education.  In 1995, a project was established in 



Thailand with a present emphasis on teaching English and community service. 



During this time, GSC also began providing <A HREF="long.html">longer term service opportunities</A>



for adult volunteers.<p>







In August of 1995, GSC took another step in its development by 



becoming a project of <A HREF="../index.html">Earth Island Institute</A> (EII) in San Francisco.  EII was 



founded in 1982 by David Brower, first Executive Director of the Sierra Club, 



and founder of Friends of the Earth.  EII supports over 30 environmentally 



related projects ranging from <A HREF="../baikal/baikal.html">Baikal Watch</A> 



(protection of the Baikal Lake in Russia) to the <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">International Marine Mammal Project</A> (dolphin and whale protection including the "Free Willy" 



project), and the Urban Habitat Program 



(support for socially-just and ecologically-sustainable urban communities).  



GSC is now benefiting from the support of the Earth Island network services 



which include assistance in project administration, accounting, promotion, 



fund development and computer services.  The relationship established with 



Earth Island Institute acknowledges the inherent connection between sustainable 



development and environmental concerns. This relationship is providing connection 



to other environmentally oriented social action endeavors. The increasing availability 



and applicability of electronic communications is opening doors for at-distance volunteering 



and connections which has great potential. GSC has recently initiated a quarterly newsletter 



in both <A HREF="print.html">print</A> and <A HREF="updt.html">electronic</A> 



editions.<p>







Over the course of the development of GSC, the organization has benefitted from 



the all-volunteer efforts of various staff members.  Volunteers have assisted 



GSC with office administration, research, project coordination, in-country 



logistics, accounting, promotion, electronic communications and general 



support. One of the major reasons for the initiation of this organization was 



to provide opportunities for adults to become more actively involved in 



addressing our many global issues.  GSC will continue to emphasize volunteer 



participation as opportunities become increasingly available.<p>







GSC is now embarking on its first fund development campaign in 



order to establish a paid staff, to increase support of project development, 



and to establish an efficient vehicle to notify potential volunteers of this 



program.  It is our hope that GSC can expand its provision of 



international service opportunities to greater numbers of interested adult 



volunteers in the U.S. and other developed countries.  At the same time, we 



continue to strengthen our connections with our host communities.  We welcome your participation in 



the development of this program.  See <A HREF="invol.html">How you can be involved</A> and 



<A HREF="reg.html">How to register for trips</A>.



<p>







<br>







