<html>







<head>



<title>FRONT PAGE ARTICLE</title>



</head>







<h2><center>New Partners in Collaboration</center></h2>







<body>







<br>







Global Service Corps is pleased to announce the initiation of collaborative ventures with two new 



institutional partners, both of whom share with Global Service Corps the values of appropriate international 



sustainable development, collaboration, volunteer service, and experiential education.<p>







Presidio World College (PWC) is a new educational institution emerging at The Presidio of San Francisco, 



a 1,480 acre U.S. National Park being developed as a "global center for exchanging ideas on critical 



environmental and social challenges."  The mission of Presidio World College is to prepare men and women 



to find sensible, practical ways to achieve social and economic development while restoring and sustaining 



our environmental commons, and to see the goal of sustainable development in global terms, across the 



real differences that exist among various nations and cultures. PWC will offer degree and non-degree 



programs in Sustainable Development Studies, which emphasizes the common ground between economics 



and the environment, internationally and cross-culturally.  These programs will include a Bachelor of Arts 



Degree, a Master of Arts Degree (in collaboration with GSC institutional partner, The Fielding Institute), and 



a Sustainable Later-Life Design program for "second-stage learners,"  men and women in transition in their 



forties, fifties, and beyond.<p>







All three of these programs will include experiential education components where students will live and 



study in a culture very different from his or her own while being involved in a sustainable development 



project.   The study will include both academic and practical work including language and cultural studies.  



Global Service Corps is assisting PWC with the development of these international field study components, 



utilizing the existing GSC service project trips as a foundation.  While the first class of bachelor degree 



students is not expected to arrive until fall of 1997, PWC will be immediately launching internship programs 



for both Bachelors and Masters Degree students enrolled in other academic institutions.  The Sustainable 



Later-Life Design program is scheduled to begin in the summer or fall of this year, and the Masters Degree 



program soon thereafter.  For further information about these PWC programs and particularly the new 



internship opportunities, contact Global Service Corps.<p>











New Forests Project (NFP), is a project of The International Center, a non-profit research and educational 



organization that focuses on promoting democracy in developing countries, resolving regional conflicts 



and implementing sustainable development projects.  New Forests Project was founded in 1982, and 



present Director Stuart Conway joined NFP in 1990.  While serving as a Peace Corps Volunteer in 



Guatemala, Stuart recognized the vital role reforestation and agroforestry (the combining of trees with 



agricultural crops on the same land) can play in environmental conservation and regeneration in Central 



America.  Stuart was particularly interested in working directly with the campesinos (peasant farmers), the 



people who are on the front lines of the deforestation that is occurring in Central America and



elsewhere in the developing world.  Due to social, economic and political factors over which they have 



little control, such as unequal distribution of land, limited educational opportunities and widespread 



poverty, resource poor farmers are forced to cut forests in order to have a small field to plant enough 



crops to feed their families.  New Forest Project is reaching out to these farmers and their families through 



community tree nurseries and training programs now located in Honduras, Haiti, El Salvador and 



Gautemala, as well as in Ethiopia and the Philippines.<p>







Global Service Corps was introduced to New Forests Project by Jessica Goldberger, a GSC Volunteer on 



the February, 1994 Kenya Biointensive Gardening Project Trip.  At the time, Jessica was the Director 



Coordinator of the NFP World Seed Program and she began supplying seeds to our Kenya project.  Stuart 



Conway and GSC Director Rick Lathrop soon began discussions about GSC Volunteers assisting with NFP 



activities.  Our first collaborative venture will be the initiation of a sustainable mini-farming seminar and 



community training program modeled after the Kenya Biointensive Project.  For further information about 



NFP, visit their World Wide Web site at: http:/www.igc.apc.org/nfp, or contact them at: 



731 Eighth St., SE, Washington, DC 20003; telephone: 2025473800; Email: icnfp@clark.net.



