<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Building with Woodless Lumber By David Lorenz and David C. Pettijohn</TITLE>

<H1>Building with Woodless Lumber</H1>
<H2>By David Lorenz and David C. Pettijohn</H2>

One hundred years ago, most fuels, construction materials, clothes, inks,
paints, fibers and chemicals were made from plant matter. By the 1980s, less
than five percent of industrial products and fuels came from biological
materials.<P>

Now industry may be moving away from the oil derrick and towards the silo for
its supplies. New technologies, new laws and an environmentally aware public
are ushering in a new materials base for the 21st century.<P>

Historically, the abundance of US forests encouraged the use of wood as the
only biological construction material. In coming years, however, wood will be
giving up this monopoly. An increasingly available supply of low-cost,
cellulose-based waste and advancing non-wood processing technologies have set
the stage for the rapid expansion of a new industry.<P>

The wood-products industry has spawned a new generation of materials composed
of waste cellulose made into composite materials. Waste-material fibers are
arranged in varying orientations while a heated press compacts the fibers into
a solid panel of composite board.<P>

In 1994, the wood-products industry used less than 110,000 tons of cellulosic
wastes. In 1996, however, the manufacture of "woodless lumber" products will
increase by 400 percent, and straw will account for two-thirds of the expanded
use. By the year 2000, there may be as many as 40 companies marketing 1.7
million tons of alternative construction materials, attracting $750 million
worth of investment capital and employing more than 3000 workers.<P>

This rapidly expanding industry will experience no lack of raw materials. The
US generates at least 160 million tons of waste cellulose each year. In theory,
simply using all available waste straw could replace as much as 80 percent of
US wood-based construction materials.

<H2>Panels From Waste</H2>

The vast majority of houses built in the US today use "stick" or "platform"
framing, consisting of 2"x4" lumber studs for the walls and roofs.<P>

One alternative building-system uses structural panels consisting of a core of
insulating material (typically  extruded foam or paper) sandwiched between wood
structural panels. The components are glued together to form a wall panel
four-to-eight-inches thick. On average, structural-panel systems use 25 percent
less wood in wall construction than normal stick-framing.<P>

Agriboard Industries of Fairfield, Iowa, began producing Oriented Strand Board
(OSB) panels in 1995. This year, Agriboard will manufacture 200,000 square feet
of structural panels (enough for approximately 500 average-sized homes),
utiliz-ing approximately 900 tons of straw per year. Within the next seven
years, the company plans to triple its production and estimates that OSB will
cost $2.69-$3.12 less per square foot than conventional stick-frame homes.<P>

Cereal grain straws also are being used for the production of particle board
and plywood substitutes. Isobord Industries in Toronto, Canada plans to open
several $50 million facilities, each capable of producing six million cubic
feet of industrial-grade particle board per year. Each plant will use
approximately 180,000 tons of wheat straw per year.<P>

Urban waste wood and construction debris are other underutilized material
sources for panel products, accounting for approximately 20 million tons of all
US municipal solid wastes. Evanite Fiber Corporation in Corvallis, Oregon,
makes a hardboard product for use as paneling and pegboard. Forty-eight percent
of the board is made from urban wood waste and 45 percent comes from scrap
pallets, shakes and utility spools. Only five percent of the final hardboard
fibers is derived from virgin wood. Approximately 1.5 million cubic feet of
hardboard product are produced per year by Evanite, using 40,500 tons of waste
wood fibers.<P>

Several firms use recycled paper to manufacture non-structural panel products.
Gridcore Systems International Corporation, in Long Beach, California, converts
waste corrugated cardboard and recycled newsprint or office papers into 
panels. Construction and demolition debris, rice hulls, kenaf, jute and bagasse
also have been used. Gridcore's new facility will produce approximately 6.3
million square feet of panels annually using about 3100 tons of waste fibers.<P>

The Homasote Company in West Trenton, New Jersey has manufactured panel
products from recycled paper for 90 years.   Homasote(R) board can be sawed,
drilled and fastened to other boards, while providing, on average, better sound
and thermal insulation with lighter weight than traditional wood.<P>

Phenix Biocomposites, Inc. in St. Peter, Minnesota, manufactures Environ(TM)
Biocomposite  from soy flour and recycled newsprint. With the working
properties of wood and the appearance of gra-nite, the product is twice as hard
as oak and provides three times better abrasion resistance. Phenix
Biocomposites currently is producing about 60,000 cubic feet of the product per
year, using 1600 tons of recycled news-print and 50,000 bushels (1100 tons) of
soybeans.

<H2>Local Savings; Local Profits</H2>

Communities that host these manufacturing plants can reap two economic
benefits: a reduction in waste disposal costs by as much as $100 million and an
increase in local economic activity of more than $250 million annually.<P>

Where the burning of agricultural straw is illegal, the cost of disposal can be
as high as $40 a ton for some farming communities. A 50,000 ton per year
manufacturing facility thus collectively could save farmers $2 million.<P>

Farmers who bale and haul the straw  would earn net profits of more than $22.50
per ton. Under this arrangement, a wheat farmer with an average-sized farm of
500 acres would net approximately $11,250 a year. A planned Isobord facility in
North Dakota is expected to generate approximately $6.3 million in additional
income for farmers through sale of wheat straw.<P>

Because these new manufacturing faci-lities tend to be modestly scaled (20,000
to 180,000 tons per year), they lend themselves to local or cooperative
ownership. This arrangement ensures that a large portion of the profits
generated will be retained and returned to the local economy.<P>

Adapted from A New Industry Emerges: Making Construction Materials from
Cellulosic Wastes. The full report is available for $18.75 from the Institute
for Local Self Reliance, 1313 5th Street, SE, Suite 306, Minneapolis, MN 55414;
(612) 379-3815; fax: -3920.


<HR>

