<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Is Zapatista Rebellion Rooted in Oil? by John Ross</TITLE>

<H1>Is Zapatista Rebellion Rooted in Oil?</H1>
<H2>by John Ross</H2>

<I>See also </I><A HREF="s96-20.html#oil">Oil Protesters Attacked</A><I> by Sunita Chethik, Global Exchange</I><P>

Ocosingo -- The exact amount of oil and gas estimated to lie beneath Chiapas' Lacandon jungle is a
closely guarded secret, but it may be a key variable in the Mexican government's response to the
Zapatista uprising that rocked the region in January, 1994.<P>

The roots of the Zapatista rebellion are drenched in oil, observed Jesuit Father Mardonio Morales,
who has spent 30 years walking the canyons of the Lacan-don jungle in the state of Chiapas, the
Zapatista's base area.<P>

"Great interests are at play in the Lacandon -- the lives of the Indian communities and the
unrestricted control of natural resources..." wrote the 70-year-old priest, one of the key religious
workers in Bishop Samuel Ruiz's San Cristobal de las Casas diocese. Everywhere the white-bearded
Morales traveled, from the heart of the jungle to the highland mountains, he saw chapopote (crude
oil) oozing from the ground. The local Mayans continue using chapopote in native medicines.<P>

The Zapatista's enigmatic spokesperson, Subcommander Marcos, also discussed the role played by
oil in the region, saying that the Mexican government's counter-insurgency strategy in Chiapas was
tied to the strategic oil needs of the United States. According to Marcos, US President Bill Clinton's
financial bailout of Mexico came with a condition: "Here is the money, but I want the oil."<P>

Morales and Marcos are not the only ones who have noticed the Lacandon region's oil potential --
for two decades, the giant Mexican national oil company PEMEX has surveyed deposits and drilled
test holes throughout the vast jungle. US interests also studied the region in 1985-1986, but the
results remain secret.<P>

Marcos pinpointed the largest above-ground oil stratum in the world in Valle Amador, under the
Pichucalco ejido (collective farm) in the Lacandon jungle. "It's of a very high quality and very
inexpensive to exploit, because it is under your fingertips. You can practically smell the gas," said
Marcos.<P>

Morales speculated that the reason the Mexican government invited tens of thousands of farmers to
settle in the Lacandon in the 1960s and 1970s was not to raise crops but to provide cheap labor for
the cattle ranching industry and then for PEMEX and its subcontractors.<P>

"Wherever PEMEX waves its magic wand, a road appears," Morales marveled. The January 1, 1994, rebellion by the Zapatista Army of National Liberation (EZLN) temporarily
shut down oil exploration in the Lacandon -- 1400 workers and much equipment were hauled out of
the zone. Morales reported that oil exploration resumed in spring 1995, following the first round
of peace talks between the government and the rebels.<P>

PEMEX is tight-lipped about the Lacandon's oil potential. "We've tried unsuccessfully, for years,
just to get PEMEX to give us a list of wells in the jungle," said Ignacio March, director of the
Southeast Center for Research and Study, a San Cris-tobal environmental research institute.<P>

Mexico has 74 active oil fields -- most of which are offshore -- and has overtaken Venezuela as the
world's sixth-largest oil producer. Additional deposits are clustered in Veracruz and Tabasco, just
across the Chiapas state line.<P>

Three years ago, PEMEX representatives informed their US counterparts that a "large field" had
been discovered in the municipality of Ocosingo, in the Lacandon.<P>

The first recorded clash between the EZLN and the Mexican Army took place in Ocosingo's canyons on
May 21, 1993, just off the dirt road leading to the Nazareth 101-104 wells. The Nazareth wells
were not oil-rich, but they produced natural gas -- millions of cubic feet daily.<P>

"Mexico needs natural gas more than it needs oil right now," said California-based Mexican oil
consultant George Baker. Mexico is committed to natural gas conversion by 1998, and
infrastructure and investment depend on the development of new fields. "Ocosingo could be that new
field," hypothesized Baker.<P>

PEMEX also is interested in the region known as the Marques de Comillas along the Guatemalan
border. In the 1980s, the then-secretary of ecology sent civil engineer Ramon Ponciaga to the area
to troubleshoot environmental concerns. Ponciaga recalled that PEMEX met resistance from settlers
in the region, many of whom already had been radicalized by the Guerrilla Army of the Poor, a
Guatemalan insurgent organization present throughout the border region.<P>

Local settlers' groups blocked roads, kidnapped company officials and seized machinery when
PEMEX failed to pay indemnities and complete promised roads. Souring government-settler
relations led PEMEX to beat a strategic retreat from the region in 1989.<P>

"The petroleum beneath Marques is perfectly exploitable," said Ponciaga, "but the social problems
there make extraction impossible."<P>

After the Zapatista rebellion broke out, drilling sites became staging areas for military retaliation,
and some oil camps now are full-fledged garrisons.<P>

Whatever the extent of oil and natural gas deposits in the Lacandon, mused researcher Arturo
Lomeli, "it's clear that PEMEX is not going to be able to get at those deposits until the government
has signed a peace treaty with the EZLN."<P>

Excerpted from LatinAmerica Press, c/o SoNo, PO Box 410150, San Francisco, CA 94141.

<A NAME="oil">
<H1>Oil Protesters Attacked</H1>
<H2>by Sunita Chethik, Global Exchange</H2>

Mexico -- For more than 20 years, Pemex, Mexico's state-owned oil company, has
plundered and polluted the Mexican environment. Some 125 Pemex spills were
recorded in 1995 alone. Pemex nets an estimated $2 million each day, but
villagers who have lost farms to oil fields still cannot get roads paved;
schools and health clinics remain impoverished. Traditional medicinal plants no
longer grow on lands scoured by acid rains. Fish no longer swim in polluted
streams and lakes. In some regions, production of corn, beans and coconuts has
fallen by as much as 60 percent. Skin rashes and respiratory diseases are
epidemic.<P>

On January 29, thousands of native Chontal Indians in the Mexican state of
Tabasco blocked roads leading to 60 oil wells and demanded an end to oil
expansion, as well as compensation to farmers for environmental and health
damages.<P>

On March 8, thousands of Mexican police and soldiers attacked a blockade in
Nacajuca, clubbing and teargassing more than 2000 nonviolent demonstrators
(mostly women), arresting more than a hundred and brutally beating movement
leader Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador.<P>

"It is the poor who are defending the beauty of our planet," observed a member
of the Tabasco Human Rights Committee."



