<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Japanese Timber Giant SLAPPs Canadian Natives By Joyce Nelson</TITLE>

<H1>Japanese Timber Giant SLAPPs Canadian Natives</H1>

<H2>By Joyce Nelson</H2>

Canada -- A recent Ontario court ruling has ominous implications for free
speech, native rights and economic justice all across Canada. On January 23,
1996, Ontario's Divisional Court released a decision in favor of Manitoba-based
Daishowa Inc. that prohibits Toronto-based Friends of the Lubicon [FoL, 485
Ridelle Ave., Toronto, ON, M6B 1K6, Canada; (416) 763-7500] from continuing its
campaign to promote secondary boycotts of Daishowa's customers.<P>

Timber giant Daishowa Paper Manufacturing Co. Ltd., a Japanese multinational,
has obtained provincial timber rights to log most of the 10,000 square
kilometer (4000 square mile) territory in northwestern Alberta to which the
Lubicon Lake Indian Nation [3536 106 St., Edmonton, AB, T6J 1A4, Canada; (403)
436-5652] claims unextinguished aboriginal rights.<P>

The company turns trees into paper bags and other packaging materials to supply
Japan's inordinate appetite for pulp and paper products. Since 1991, FoL has
led Canadian and European boycott campaigns against Daishowa's packaging
products, effectively persuading some 30 major retail chains in Canada to
switch to other suppliers. But "Daishowa has many customers in the US," FoL
representative Kevin Thomas said, "including the <B>Washington Post</B>."<P>

The January ruling temporarily enjoins FoL from interfering with Daishowa's
business by "unlawful means, including picketing and threats of picketing aimed
at Daishowa's customers." FoL is appealing the ruling, which overturns a May
1995 decision by the Ontario Court's General Division that supported the
legality of FoL's secondary boycott activities. Meanwhile, Daishowa is seeking
an injunction that permanently prohibits FoL from organizing secondary boycotts
and is suing the volunteer group for more than $5 million in damages.<P>

Activists consider this case a classic SLAPP (Strategic Lawsuit Against Public
Participation), a tactic increasingly used by powerful corporations to silence
grass-roots opposition. The purpose of a SLAPP is to intimidate citizen
activists, exhaust their limited resources and keep them from exercising their
democratic rights.<P>

Karen Wristen, a lawyer with the Vancouver-based Sierra Legal Defense Fund
representing the FoL, warned that Daishowa previously had asked that the
injunction apply not only to FoL, but also to any member of the public familiar
with the order. Thomas said, "At this stage, the case has the potential to take
away the boycott tool from everyone. The court is saying that if a boycott
causes harm to a company, it must be illegal."<P>

<H2>The Lubicon and the Land</H2>

For decades, the 500-member Lubicon Lake Indian Nation has struggled for a just
settlement of its land claim in northern Alberta. While no treaty entitling the
Lubicon to their land claim ever was negotiated, the tribe claims territory
located between the Peace River to the west, Wabasca River to the east,
Whitefish Lake to the south and Buffalo Head Hills to the north. Their
traditional territory has been exploited repeatedly, first by oil companies and
now by the forest industry.<P>

In February, 1988, the Alberta government announced that Daishowa would build
the Peace River mill -- the largest hardwood pulp mill in Canada -- west of the
Lubicon community, Little Buffalo Lake. The Lubicon were not informed about the
mill in advance.<P>

And according to Anne Champagne, a researcher for the Future Forests Alliance,
a Canadian forest-protection umbrella group, the Lubicon "were not told, nor
were they informed that the provincial government had sold the trees from their
entire territory." The Alberta and federal governments have given Daishowa more
than $74.7 million in subsidies for the project.<P>

In September, 1989, without any settlement of the Lubicon land claims, Daishowa
and the Alberta government signed a 20-year Forest Management Agreement (FMA)
giving the company a timber lease to 29,000 square kilometers (11,600 square
miles) northern Alberta.<P>

Daishowa agreed, in 1988, to wait for a settlement of Lubicon land claims
before logging. But once the FMA was signed, Champagne charged, the company
proceeded to "sub-contract the logging to smaller companies, which Daishowa
claimed were not bound to honor Dai-showa's no-cut agreement." A Daishowa
subsidiary began logging on Lubicon lands in Fall, 1990 and ceased in November,
1990.<P>

Lubicon protests against Daishowa commenced after its Peace River pulp mill
opened in 1990, and in 1991, FoL was formed. In 1992, Daishowa sold the mill to
Daishowa-Marubeni International Ltd., a joint venture owned by Daishowa Paper
Mfg. Co. and Marubeni Corp., another Japanese forestry multinational.<P>

<H2>Divide and Conquer</H2>

On November 18, 1993, the new federal Minister of Indian Affairs, Ron Irwin,
publicly stated that a Lubicon land settlement was a federal priority.
According to Chief Bernard Orninayak, the strategy of the former Conservative
Party federal government was "to maintain the pretense of sincere negotiations
in order to deflect criticism and buy time until the Lubicon society
deteriorates to the point where the Lubicon people can no longer fight for our
rights." The Liberal Party government, elected in 1993, has continued this
tactic, while at the same time, corporate forces attempt to erode the Lubicon's
resolve.<P>

"The Lubicon believe that the company will begin cutting on their land during
the winter of 1996-97," Wristen says. Meanwhile, the lawsuit seeking a
permanent injunction and damages from FoL is scheduled for a court hearing on
April 29.<P>

Thomas explained, "Every year, the boycott has gotten bigger. Daishowa got
tired of waiting for us to go under, so now they're trying to wipe us out."
Thomas places the case in a larger context: "With the federal and provincial
governments in Canada getting out of the field of regulating corporate
activities, the only resort left is public pressure through things like
boycotts. If that tool is taken away, then what?"<P>

<HR>

Joyce Nelson is an Canadian freelance writer and author of six books.


<HR>

