<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Nuclear Mayhem at Monju by Aileen Mioko Smith</TITLE>

<H1>Nuclear Mayhem at Monju</H1>

<H2>by Aileen Mioko Smith</H2>

<I>See also</I> <A HREF="s96-22a.html#breeder">Fast-Breeder Leak in Russia</A><P>

Japan -- A sodium leak and fire on the night of December 8, 1995, at Japan's
prototype fast-breeder reactor came as no surprise to Japanese citizens who had
been campaigning to prevent the $5.9 billion Monju reactor from operating. Every
prototype breeder reactor in the UK, Russia, France and Germany has been plagued
one way or another with sodium leaks and/or fires. It was bound to happen at
Monju.<P>

Fast-breeder reactors generate both electricity and plutonium: using "fast
neutrons," they actually produce (or "breed") more plutonium than they consume.
While water is used to cool conventional uranium-fueled reactors,
plutonium-fueled fast-breeders must be cooled with sodium.<P>

Monju's primary and secondary cooling systems are designed to carry 220 tons of
the reactor's total 1700 tons of sodium. Sodium reacts violently with air and
water -- the two most abundant substances on Earth -- and is extremely corrosive.
Fast breeders pump hundreds of tons of liquid sodium through pipes immersed in
water shielding the reactor core. These pipes are less than four millimeters
thick.<P>

If an accident occurs in a uranium-fueled reactor, the nuclear core  can suffer a
melt-down; a plutonium-fueled reactor will explode. What activists fear most is
that Monju will erupt, spewing tons of deadly plutonium into the environment.<P>

Of the world's ten known fast-breeder  accidents (in France, Russia and the UK),
the Monju accident in Fukui prefecture clearly was the worst. Former nuclear
engineer and Monju critic Jinzaburo Takagi stated that it was only a matter of
"luck" that there was not "a radioactive release or even an explosion of the
whole reactor."<P>

Using the Chernobyl accident as a guide, a 1994 Greenpeace report estimated that,
if 17 percent of Monju's fission products were released, fallout from the seaside
plant would spread well beyond Guam.<P>

Immediately following the accident, the Director General of the Science and
Technology Agency (STA), the agency in charge of Japan's plutonium program,
rushed to state that Japan's nuclear-power program -- including Monju-- would
continue.<P>

<H2>Storming Monju</H2>

Japan's Power Reactor and Nuclear Fuel Development Corporation (PNC), a
government corporation that operates Monju, lied repeatedly to the public about
the accident. PNC made an unsuccessful attempt to suppress video footage that
showed the cause of the accident: a ruptured pipe in a secondary cooling system
that spilled an estimated 2-3 tons of sodium -- the largest leak in the history
of fast-breeder technology. One of the reasons PNC gave for releasing the
misinformation was that Monju is too important to Japan's energy program to
jeopardize the reactor's operation. Following revelations that the agency itself
had been involved in trying to withhold the video, one PNC official committed
suicide.<P>

Had it not been for a courageous act by a group of Fukui prefectural officials in
the early morning  of December 11, PNC's attempted cover-up probably would have
succeeded and no one ever would have learned the extent of the accident.<P>

In a daring invasion, the officials managed to place themselves inside the
reactor. This desperate action came as the result of a bitter experience at
Fukui's  Tsuruga Unit I reactor in the early 1980s. When Tsuruga Unit I leaked
radiation, Fukui prefectural officials went to the gates of the plant, but were
ordered to leave. They were told that they could be prosecuted for obstructing
the execution of government affairs.<P>

Fukui prefectural officials laid their lives on the line when they made their way
into Monju that night, but once they were inside and reported what they saw to
the world, it was too late -- the national government could no longer put
pressure on them.<P>

<H2>Monju Dangers</H2>

Monju (named by its builders after the Buddhist bodhisattva of wisdom) is located
in Fukui Prefecture on the tip of the Tsuruga Peninsula, facing the Japan Sea.
Fukui is neck-deep in nuclear power, with 15 plants, including Monju -- the
highest concentration in the world. Nuclear power generates a third of Japan's
electricity, and the government has announced plans to produce 42 percent of its
power from reactors by 2010. But many Fukui residents want to break the nuclear
habit. In 1995, more than 220,000 residents signed a petition asking that no
additional reactors operate in Fukui.<P>

Monju was built by the PNC, the same government agency that created an
international scandal in 1994 when it issued an 11-minute pro-nuclear cartoon
featuring "Mr. Pluto." (In this video, a small boy drinks a plutonium-laced glass
of water and merrily visits a toilet, while a flushing sound and a logo announce:
"Feels Great! All Fresh!")<P>

Plutonium is so deadly that it can cause lung cancer in microgram quantities. One
gram of plutonium, evenly distributed, could create hundreds of thousands of
cancer victims. Only a few millimeters of space separate the reactor's fuel rods,
which are inserted between the control rods that slow the nuclear reaction. When
fuel rods overheat, they can bend and stick. If the control rods cannot be
inserted properly, Monju could explode.<P>

Monju uses 1700 tons of sodium and operates at 500 degrees centigrade -- much
hotter than conventional reactors. The reactor, which is particularly vulnerable
to earthquakes, is located 700 meters (2300 feet) from an active earthquake
fault. Damage to highways and structures during the Hanshin earthquake of 1995,
which devastated the city of Kobe, was "never supposed to happen." Earthquake
experts are now pointing to the Tsuruga region in Fukui as the most likely place
for Japan's next major quake.<P>

Both PNC and the STA insist that the reactor will be able to withstand
earthquakes and will never have an explosive accident, but they have refused
repeated requests to support their claim with documentation. PNC and STA also
maintained that there would be no sodium leaks at Monju.<P>

<H2>Heads in the Sand</H2>

At a January 20, 1996, public meeting between PNC, STA and local citizens, it
became apparent that PNC's emergency plans for a reactor accident at Monju were
shockingly inadequate. Monju is the only nuclear plant in Japan that required its
staff to seek approval for emergency shutdowns from its main office in Tokyo.
(PNC has vowed to change its emergency procedures, but has not yet done so.) But
when frantic plant operators telephoned for permission, no one answered the
phone. The technicians kept running the plant,  knowing that it was leaking
volatile sodium. Because of this delay, the shutdown did not take place until
nearly five hours later.<P>

According to Monju's operating manual, reactor operators are supposed to make
their emergency shutdown decisions by reading a sodium-level indicator that
should show leakage. But the indicator's margin of error turns out to be 7.5
tons. During the December accident, the operators saw "no change" in the level of
sodium.<P>

One of the plant design's most important safety precautions is preventing sodium
from contacting air. But Monju's construction is not air-tight. The plant's
safety manual says nothing about shutting off ventilation ducts in the event of a
sodium leak. In the December accident, continued ventilation fueled the fire and
spread fumes thousands of square yards, penetrating six levels of the plant. At
one point, operators actually walked into the room to see what was happening,
letting in more air.<P>

Monju's fire-fighters lacked training and tools to battle sodium fires. There was
virtually no protective gear and only small, conventional extinguishers. But
better tools would have made no difference: the fire-fighters only work during
the day and the accident occurred at night.<P>

And PNC still refuses to call the accident a "fire." Borrowing from US
nuclear-industry terminology, Japan's official government language for this type
of accident is "jisho," which means an "incident." When PNC officials tied to
characterize the event as a jisho, however, they were shouted down by enraged
local officials.<P>

<H2>More Blunders</H2>

The list of design blunders goes on. The exhaust duct is next to the intake duct.
This design sucked escaping fumes from the sodium reaction right back into the
building and further spread the damage.<P>

The only way to stop a reactor cooling pipe from leaking is to drain all the
sodium out of it. But Monju's drainage tank, which is supposed to receive the
super-hot sodium, is not designed to withstand high temperatures. Consequently,
the operators had to wait until the sodium cooled off. In the meantime, they had
no recourse but to let the pipe keep leaking.<P>

There is a steel lining on the floor of the secondary cooling system designed to
prevent leaking sodium from reaching the concrete floor below. Direct contact
with the cement could trigger a hydrogen explosion, and Monju's sodium fire
damaged this steel lining, leaving it rippled and discolored. One portion
actually melted. According to Monju's licensing safety review, this is not
supposed to happen. It is evident that PNC's analyses (approved by STA) simply
underestimated how hot sodium can get.<P>

The Monju licensing safety review claims that the plant can manage a
150-cubic-meter (approximately 150-ton) sodium leak. According to this scenario,
the sodium would fall immediately to the floor (with minimum splattering),
quickly to be whisked away into a sump -- thus causing minimum contact with air.
But does such a scenario reflect reality?<P>

At Monju, an air duct opened directly beneath the leaking pipe. Sodium hit this
duct, then a floor grating below, and splattered, which magnified its surface
area exposed to the air and accelerated combustion.<P>

When citizens asked for video footage of PNC experiments on sodium leaks and
fires conducted at its Oarai research facility, PNC produced clips only of leaks
that fell straight down. PNC said that it "could not find" the video of the
splatter tests.<P>

In the wake of PNC's various embarrassing videotape snafus, the STA has taken
advantage of the government agency's loss of credibility and its inability to
prevent the accident to take nearly total control of the Monju investigation. But
STA is the agency that approved PNC's licensing safety review on Monju. The
investigative situation has become a case of the fox guarding the chicken coop.
The national government needs to establish a truly independent commission with
foreign expertise to examine the accident.<P>

The December accident was not simply the result of a failed sodium temperature
indicator gauge. It was a failure of Japan's entire plutonium program -- with
Monju as its centerpiece -- which is designed to operate with no independent
oversight. Monju is blatantly unsafe, yet the program goes forward with the STA
acting as both promoter and regulator. Japan's Nuclear Safety Commission is
skeletal, lacks enforcement power and is made up of members of the "nuclear
club."<P>

<H2>Flying Blind</H2>

Monju is like an experimental airplane piloted by the PNC, except it does not
"answer the phone" -- the aircraft is on automatic pilot. The hapless passengers
include every man, woman and child in the Fukui region, downwinders, such as the
people of Shiga, Nagano, Fukushima, and Tokyo, and all of Lake Biwa -- the source
of drinking water for eight million people. Unlike a passenger jet, however,
Monju's design does not include a life raft.<P>

The battle to close Monju has just begun. The issue pits the national
government's power against the desire for safety and independent decision-making
in the Kan-sai region -- including greater nuclear enforcement powers, increased
financial autonomy and the public's right to know.<P>

In the future, will the media really inform the public about important nuclear
issues (such as the fact that Japan's fast-breeder reactors will not generate
even one percent of Japan's energy by the year 2050, even if the program goes
forward as scheduled)? Will the Japanese parliament finally act on this issue, or
will the bureaucracy continue to run the show in cooperation with the nuclear
lobby? The answer depends on how much the public gets involved.<P>

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

Green Action is seeking volunteers and contributors to support
the effort to stop the Monju program forever. Petitions (in English and
Japanese), information packets and a Monju video (Yen3800, in Japanese) are
available from Green Action, Suite 103, 22-75 Tanaka Sekidencho, Sakyo-ku, Kyoto
606 Japan; +81-75-701-7223, fax: +81-75-702-1952; amsmith@gol.com; Japan Postal
Transfer Account: 01040-4-34953 (Green Action).


<A NAME="breeder">

<HR>

<H1>Fast-Breeder Leak in Russia</H1>

Russia (Via EcoNet) -- On January 31, 1996, approximately one ton of radioactive
steam escaped from an experimental plutonium fast-breeder reactor in
Dimitrovgrad's Scientific Research Institute near Kiev.<P>

The release occurred when a construction crane struck critical safety equipment.
On February 1, plant officials told the Socio-Ecological Union, a Russian
eco-group, that although the radioactive level was three-to-four times normal,
"there were no victims." That same morning, Echo Moskvy broadcast a report that
radioactivity near NIIAR was about 20 times normal. The accident left nearly 200
square meters (240 square yards) poisoned with radioactive cobalt, iodine and
manganese.<P>

Contaminated snow was collected for disposal as liquid waste. Greenpeace Moscow
reported that "the Dimitrovgrad facility is known for its disposal of liquid
radioactive waste by pumping it directly into the environment."<P>

-- ecodefense@glas.apc.org (Vladimir Slivyak)


