<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Chernobyl Remembered</TITLE>

<H1>Chernobyl Remembered</H1>

<I>See also</I> <A HREF="s96-24a.html#Campaign">A Campaign for Nuclear Abolition</A>.<P>

Ukraine -- In September, 1994, a leaked UN report observed: "The name
'Chernobyl' has... become synonymous with our fear of a technological
catastrophe. Almost 400,000 people have been forced to leave their homes as a
result of the nuclear power plant explosion of April 26, 1986.<P>

"It is estimated that at least nine million people were directly and indirectly
affected by the Chernobyl disaster. An area the size of England, Wales and
Northern Ireland combined -- over 160,000 square kilometers (64,000 square miles)
-- is estimated to have been contaminated...."<P>

Seventy percent of the fallout came down in Belarus, the country most exposed to
Chernobyl's radioactive hazards.<P>

Cesium and strontium have poisoned 60,000 square-miles in Ukraine, turning a
Rhode Island-sized area into an officially designated "Zone of Alienation."<P>

The <B>Los Angeles Times</B> reports that "The zone has become a wildlife refuge." In
the absence of humans, the number of boars has increased 800 percent, while the
moose population doubled. In the decade since the accident, eagles, cranes,
wolves, otters and endangered black storks have returned and appear to be
thriving.<P>

According to the <B>Times</B>, the proliferation of wildlife has lead scientists to the
remarkable conclusion that "the benefits of a human-free environment can outweigh
even the biological costs of radiation."<P>

In the long haul, the prognosis may not be so rosy. After a five-year study in
which minks were fed "relatively small doses" of radioactive contaminated meat,
biologist Victor Riasenko found that the animals lost their fur in the first
year. Fewer animals survived with each succeeding generation and, by the fourth
generation, none of the newborn minks survived.<P>

In April, people around the world will mark the anniversary of the Chernobyl
explosion with marches and support drives for the victims. Major actions are
planned in The Netherlands, Belgium and the UK.<P>

Over April 12-26, the Union Salvation of Chernobyl and for Mother Earth
International [Gewad 15, 9000 Gent, Belgium; fax: +32-9-233-73242; <A HREF="mailto:abolition@motherearth.kooppunt.be">abolition
@motherearth.kooppunt.be</A>] will walk from Kiev to Chernobyl, crossing through the
contaminated landscape. Radiation levels in the abandoned villages around
Chernobyl are still "at least 10 times higher than the officially allowed
level," reports Krista van Zelzen, who visited the area in 1995. Van Zelzen
recalls a landscape of "deserted and decayed houses, plants running wild, a
single village lunatic who refuses to accept that these lands cannot be lived
on...."<P>

The US Green party, Greenpeace and the Nuclear Information and Resource Service
[NIRS, 1424 16th Street NW, #601, Washington, DC 20036] are preparing protests
and victim-relief events in 200 US cities.<P>

More information is available on EcoNet (<A HREF="mailto:Chernobyl@globenet.gn.apc.org">Chernobyl@globenet.gn.apc.org</A> and
<A HREF="mailto:nirsnet@igc.apc.org">nirsnet@igc.apc.org</A>) and on the Chernobyl +10 web site
(http://www.essential.org/nirsnet/).<P>

<A NAME="Campaign"><H2>A Campaign for Nuclear Abolition</H2>

"We have the technical means to create a nuclear weapons-free world in about a
decade," Joseph Rotblat said on accepting the 1995 Nobel Peace Prize. Reminding
his listeners that "the very first resolution of the General Assembly of the UN
-- adopted unanimously -- called for the elimination of nuclear weapons," Rotblat
noted that "the Cold War is over, but Cold War thinking survives" among the
nuclear superpowers.<P>

"Abolition 2000," a global grassroots campaign within the nuclear
Non-Proliferation Treaty negotiations, is committed to abolishing nuclear weapons
"within a time-bound framework of 10 to 20 years."<P>

A related "Citizen's Pledge," circulated by the World Campaign to Abolish Nuclear
Weapons, already has been signed by 34 Nobel Laureates and 11 Nobel Peace
Laureates.<P>

Copies of the Citizen's Pledge and the book, <B>An Unacceptable Risk: Nuclear
Weapons in a Volatile World</B> (a joint-publication of Canada's Project Plowshares
and the Nuclear Age Peace Foundation) is available for $10.95 from the Nuclear
Age Peace Foundation [1187 Coast Village Road, Suite 123, Santa Barbara, CA
93108].<P>

The Center for Defense Information has produced a videotape, <B>Eliminating Nuclear
Weapons</B>, that makes the case for a denuclearized world. The 30-minute video is
available for $15 [CDI, 1500 Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 200005;
(202) 862-0700; fax; -0708].<P>

The Lawyers' Committee on Nuclear Policy [666 Broadway, Suite 625, New York, NY
10012; (212) 674-7790] publishes the World Court Project Report and two booklets,
<B>Highlights of the World Court Case</B> and <B>Implications of the World Court Decision</B>.<P>


<HR>

