<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Echoes From Hiroshima by Mayor Takashi Kiraoka</TITLE>

<H1>Echoes From Hiroshima</H1>
<H2>by Mayor Takashi Kiraoka</H2>

The Hague (November 7, 1995) -- Mr.  President  and Honorable  Members of the
Court, I am Takashi Hiraoka, Mayor of Hiroshima City. I am here today,
representing Hiroshima citizens who desire the abolition of nuclear weapons. More
particularly, I represent the hundreds of thousands of victims whose lives were
cut short and the survivors who are still suffering the effects of radiation, 50
years later.<P>

The atomic bombs dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki shattered all war precedent.
The mind-numbing damage these nuclear weapons wrought shook the foundations of
human existence. Their enormous destructive power reduced utterly innocent
civilian populations to ashes. Women, the elderly and the newly born were bathed
in deadly radiation and slaughtered.<P>

History is written by the victors. Thus, the heinous massacre that was Hiroshima
has been handed down to us as a perfectly justified act of war. As a result, for
50 years we have never directly confronted the full implications of this
horrifying act for the future of the human race.<P>

I am not here in this court, however, to debate responsibility for the dropping
of the atomic bombs. Japan also committed shameful acts during World War II. I
would like to convey to the people of the world what kind of damage befell
Hiroshima and to appeal for the abolition of nuclear weapons so that this tragedy
is never repeated.<P>

<H2>Death: Instant and Indiscriminate</H2>

At 8:15 a.m. on August 6, 1945, the atomic bomb dropped over Hiroshima exploded
580 meters [1914 feet] above the heart of the city. Beneath the atomic bomb's
monstrous mushroom cloud, human skin was burned raw. Crying for water, human
beings died in desperate agony.<P>

The bomb used a single kilogram of uranium 235 to produce energy equivalent to 15
kilotons of TNT. The force of the atomic bomb was the equivalent of... an
instantaneous attack by more than 3000 B29s -- the world's largest bombers in
1945.<P>

An intense flash of light flooded the city center. With the roar that followed,
enormous pillars of flame burst toward the skies. A majority of buildings
crumbled, and many people died.<P>

The unique characteristic of the atomic bombing was its instantaneous and
universal destruction. Old, young, male, female, soldier, civilian -- the killing
was utterly indiscriminate.<P>

On that day, there were approximately 350,000 people in Hiroshima. The city
government presently estimates that some 140,000 had died by the end of December
1945. Entire families were wiped out. The local community was in disarray.
Records were lost to fire. Thus, even today, we have no truly accurate casualty
figures.<P>

I was away when Hiroshima was bombed, so I was spared the atomic bombing itself.
But my most-beloved relatives and many acquaintances were killed. A cousin, a
first-year student at a girls' school, was 800 meters [2640 feet] from the
hypocenter. She died that night.<P>

Those who survived will never escape the psychological and physical effects of
the bombing. Many records, such as diaries, pictures, photos and movies, depict
the damage done to Hiroshima. But those who were there [and survived] universally
emphasize that no depiction comes close to the actual experience. The bomb
reduced Hiroshima to an inhuman state utterly beyond human ability to express or
imagine. I feel frustrated at not being able to express this completely in my
testimony.<P>

I worked for a time on a newspaper in Hiroshima, and I will never forget the
badly scarred face and hands of one of the women who worked with me. She had lost
her husband to the bomb. She was 33 years old at the time of the bombing and was
l700 meters [5610 feet] from the hypocenter. In 1950, she described her
experience in detail.<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

"Somewhere a voice shouted, 'Hey, there's a parachute. A parachute is coming
down!' Without thinking, I looked in the direction indicated by the voice. At
that instant -- flash. The sky in the direction I was looking was pure light. I
don't know how to describe that light, like a fire burning in my eyes. It was
like the eerie bluish-purple sparks that electric street cars make at night, only
trillions of times brighter. But that isn't exactly right either. The light was
followed by a roar that reverberated to the bottom of my belly, and I was
instantly slammed hard against the ground. When I opened my eyes, I saw nothing
but darkness.

</BLOCKQUOTE>

I noticed a terrible stench in the air. Without thinking, I took the towel that
was tucked into my belt and firmly wiped my nose and mouth. That was when I
realized for the first time that there was something wrong with my face. The skin
that I wiped just peeled, slipped right off. I was shocked.<P>

The skin on my right hand slipped off from the second joint of my fingers and
just dangled sickeningly from the tips of my fingers.<P>

She fled in a dream-like state and made it to a relief station in the suburbs.
Summer turned to autumn, and still the flesh of her wounds continued to melt
away. The wounds were the color of a crushed, ripe tomato. No new skin would
form. She died 16 years ago.<P>

<H2>Inhumane Nuclear Weapons</H2>

Today, 50 years after peace was regained, people continue to suffer the effects
of radiation.<P>

At the United Nations General Assembly in 1961, resolution 1653(XVI) was adopted.
The resolution states that:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>

The use of nuclear and thermonuclear weapons would exceed even the scope of war
and cause indiscriminate suffering and destruction to mankind and civilization
and, as such, is contrary to the rules of international law and to the laws of
humanity.

</BLOCKQUOTE>

It is clear that the use of nuclear weapons, which cause indiscriminate mass
murder and leave survivors to suffer for decades, is a violation of international
law. In addition, the development, possession and testing of nuclear weapons is a
violation of international law.  As long as nuclear weapons exist, the human race
faces a real and present danger of self-extermination.<P>

The issue of nuclear weapons should not be a matter of political relationships
among nations. The fate of the human race is in your hands.<P>

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1996, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


