<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: It Takes a Village: West Africa Hosts Ecocity III</TITLE>

<H1>West Africa Hosts Ecocity III</H1>
<H2>by Richard Register</H2>

Senegal -- Two of the most crucial issues of humanity's built habitat -- the
sustain-ability of urbanization and the form of cities -- are unlikely to be
adequately addressed at Habitat II (the UN Conference on Human Settlements set
for Istanbul this summer) but these crucial topics were a major concern at the
Third International Ecocity Conference in West Africa. Habitat II can learn from
"Ecocity III."<P>

EcoCity III  (previous conferences were held in Berkeley, California and
Ade-laide, Australia) took place January 8-12, in the small, traditional
Senegalese village of Yoff on the outskirts of Dakar. The event was co-convened
by Eco-Village at Ithaca, New York, and the Association for the Economic,
Cultural and Social Promotion of Yoff.<P>

Conceived as a meeting of urban and rural peoples, as well as a gathering of
different races, religions, nationalities, languages, levels of wealth and
lifestyles, Ecocity III became a forum both for examining flaws in the
"overdeveloped world" and exchanging the best ideas from mainstream urban
civilization and the traditional village -- in this case, the African, Moslem,
French- and Wolof-speaking town of Yoff.<P>

The spectacular cross-cultural experience of Ecocity III refuted the argument
that urban ecological concerns are only of interest to members of the white
middle-class. Moving beyond progress reports, the conference raised some
compelling questions, some of them aimed directly at Habitat II.<P>

Habitat II's "Action Plan" calls upon the  world to "respond adequately to rapid
urbanization." But is world urbanization really the positive and inevitable thing
that Habitat II organizers celebrate -- to the extent of calling their conference
on "settlements" the "City Summit"? Might it not be healthier to learn something
from rural villages that remain in better balance with nature than cities?<P>

Ecocity III concluded that "rapid urbanization itself may be a disastrous mistake
requiring immediate reassessment and reversal."<P>

"Human beings are at the center of concerns for sustainable development," says
the draft Action Plan of Habitat II. "Yet," counters the Ecocity III declaration,
"human society is wholly dependent upon the health of natural living systems of
our biosphere." Instead of facilitating urbanization, ecocity advocates would
promote the revitalization of villages and small cities, along with restoration
of local agriculture and bioregions.<P>

The concept of a city's  <B>form</B> barely enters into preparations for Habitat II. But
Ecocity III identified the form of modern cities -- sprawl-driven,
automobile-dependent, highway-dominated, oil-addicted -- as one of society's
greatest ecological and human disasters.<P>

It is not just that cities are in bad shape. They are the wrong shape -- flat.
Their very form gobbles land, demands oceans of oil, alters the Earth's
atmosphere, disrupts its climate and exacts the bloody sacrifice of a quarter
million human lives a year on streets and highways.<P>

Instead of relying on a vision of high-powered transportation links struggling to
hold the pieces together, EcoCity III challenges people to build something
fundamentally different. EcoCity III advocates the development of "ecovillages"
and "ecocities" -- compact, primarily pedestrian, communities that closely mix
living, working and social spaces.<P>

<H2>A 500-Year-Old Democracy</H2>

Three hundred Ecocity III delegates from 30 countries -- representing every
inhabited continent -- attended the conference in Yoff, a traditional farming and
fishing village ruled by a democracy of elders. The peaceful village, which has
existed undisturbed for 500 years, employs no police. But urban sprawl now
reaches out from Dakar and threatens the town, as the city closes in from all
sides.<P>

Yoff's population is approaching 40,000, having doubled over the past 20 years.  
     Meanwhile, village farmland is shrinking, sanitation is declining and
beaches and coastal buildings are washing into the sea. While new housing is
needed, the villagers recognize the threats to their culture and environment
posed by most urban models of growth. Yoff joined with EcoVillage at Ithaca in a
bold bid to discover and build a better way of living.<P>

Using homestay arrangements for conference attendees, villagers welcomed 150
delegates into their small, many-roomed homes surrounding private courtyards.
Typically, a husband, two wives, several brothers, sisters, cousins, aunts,
uncles, many children and a few grandparents greeted guests several times a day.<P>

Sitting in a family circle, shoeless on the straw-matted floor, guests ate rice,
millet, vegetables and chili-seasoned fish from a common bowl. Instead of flush
toilets, guests used the traditional hole-in-the-floor.<P>

Although 40 percent of the village is "unemployed," i.e., without salaried  jobs,
everyone is welcome around the dinner plate. In Yoff, one experiences almost no
social insecurity.<P>

<H2>The Conference Begins</H2>

In the morning, buses rented by the Mayor of Dakar rushed Ecocity III
participants four miles to the high-tech conference center. As co-convener Joan
Bokaer, from EcoVillage at Ithaca, settled into one of the huge auditorium's
plush seats -- each equipped with six channels of simultaneous translation -- she
admitted that she was "shocked, overwhelmed by the contrast" between the opulent
center and the traditional village.<P>

Mayor Mamadou Diop of Dakar and Abdoulaye Bathily, Senegal's Minister of
Environment and the Protection of Nature, presided over the opening ceremonies.<P>

A thousand people gathered in the audience, including hundreds of African
villagers, and listened to the panel discuss the state of the Earth's natural,
social, economic and urban environments.<P>

Large blocks of the audience  would stand suddenly, singing and swaying in
response to a comment from the stage, then sit back down. Later a drum would
sound, and another section of the audience would rise and sing.<P>

"Are conferences always like this in Africa?" a conference-goer asked one of the
hosts. "Never," the man said. "Ninety percent of these people have never been at
a conference center before. Nobody ever asked them their opinion. It's the first
time they were invited."<P>

The six-day conference included more than 60 featured talks (in English, French
and Wolof) and slide presentations demonstrating steady ecocity progress in
countries ranging from Malaysia and Australia to Brazil and the US, from Sweden
and Russia to Mali and South Africa.<P>

Tukumbi Lumumba-Kasongo of Zaire, nephew of Patrice Lumumba, sketched the
political and economic context of the conference on a continent attempting to
emerge from 500 years of slavery, colonialism and exploitation, which owes its
creditors (largely the former colonial powers) the equivalent of 30-to-40 years
of work for every person in many countries of Sub-saharan Africa. It is hard to
meet such a system on its own terms, which is why many conferees advocated
learning from villages that live in balance with nature, while moving forward to
renewable technologies.<P>

Amalia Cordova, curator for the Museum of Pre-Columbian Art in Santiago, Chile,
described Caspana, a village that existed for hundreds of years before the
Spanish arrived, and survives today with its traditions, architecture and water
distribution canals still intact. The town is an oasis of green in the vast
barrens of the Atacama Desert.<P>

Representing Curitiba, Brazil (perhaps the world's closest approximation of an
ecocity), was Cleon Ricardo dos Santos, director of the Open University for the
Environment. Dos Santos described how the city's new "double articulated"
bus-trains are attaining transit efficiencies comparable to conventional subway
systems at a small percentage of the cost.<P>

Jeff Kenworthy from Perth, Australia discussed new urban rail lines, "transit
villages" and progress in mixed-use urban development patterns in Vancouver,
Canada and Frieberg, Germany.<P>

US EPA representative Harriet Hill reported that "constructed wetlands"
(artificial marshes for cleansing wastewater) are working well at many sites.<P>

Anders Nyquist discussed the extraordinarily energy-efficient buildings of the
village he founded in northern Sweden. Nyquist's "eco-cycle" architecture and
technology emphasize nearly complete recycling. Farmers buy urine, collected from
Nyquist's "separating toilets," for quality fertilizer, while feces are composted
in worm boxes.<P>

Lee Boon-Thong reported on the exodus from Sarawak's forest villages after
logging and economic interests lured inhabitants to the cities. While cultural
and ecological changes are overwhelming and perhaps inevitable, he argued,
villages could adapt some outside practices to fit their own customs and natural
environments, while halting, or perhaps reversing, the out-migration.<P>

Lim Poh Imm, a Malaysian city planner, proposed the creation of an ecocity
network to exchange ideas and enrich the diversity of economic activities,
agriculture and appropriate technologies in villages around the world. Why not
allow in the best of the outside world, she asked, rather than the worst?<P>

The peaceful and cooperative democracy of Yoff and neighboring villages
profoundly impressed Ecocity III's foreign participants. Listening to the
villagers, we began to understand the importance of human cooperation to keep the
peace and maintain safe streets.<P>

In Yoff, as in most communities of the South, people understand that Northern
consumption can be more environmentally destructive than overpopulation.<P>

The conference demonstrated that "Nobody has all the answers and everybody has
some." People need to keep talking and keep learning from one another. In the
same spirit, Habitat II can learn valuable lessons from the deliberations of
Ecocity III.

<HR>

Richard Register is president of Ecocity Builders and author of Eco-city
Berkeley. A conference report is available for $10 from <B>EcoCity Builders</B> [5427
Telegraph Avenue, Oakland, CA 94609; (510) 649-1817].

<HR>

