<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Habitat II: The Shelter Crisis</TITLE>

<H1>Habitat II: The Shelter Crisis</H1>

In 1995, the world's human population stood at 5.76 billion. While other species
are driven to extinction, the human family keeps growing -- and demanding
shelter.<P>

The United Nations has called the world's "shelter crisis" nothing less than a
"threat to international peace and security."<P>

In four years, most of the world's people will live in cities -- the majority
crowded into 21 sprawling "megalopolises" teeming with populations that exceed
ten million. Third World countries will host seventeen of these megacities.<P>

Environmentalists are concerned that such massive urbanization is unsustain-able,
that the environmental impacts of megacities will prove devastating, that
providing even the most basic human needs for five billion urbanized humans will
be impossible.<P>

Responding to these concerns, the UN will hold its second Conference on Human
Settlements -- "Habitat II" -- in Istanbul, Turkey, from June 3-14. The
conference is expected to draw 25,000 delegates from 180 countries. The main
themes of Habitat II (also known as "The City Summit") are "adequate shelter for
all" and "sustainable human settlement development in an urbanizing world."<P>

The UN Global Report on Human Settlements released in March, estimated that 500
million urban dwellers are homeless or have inadequate housing. With one million
people pouring into the world's cities each week, the report warned, "housing
cannot keep up with an exploding urban population, which will double from 2.4
billion in 1995 to 5 billion in 2025."<P>

Despite the report's alarming finding that one factor in the "unabated
rural-urban migration" is "the gradual transformation of rural areas to urban
centers." Nonetheless, Habitat II remains distinctly pro-city. The preamble to
the Habitat II Agenda calls cities "engines of growth and incubators of
civilization." The report concludes: "Massive urbanization is the only way the
world can survive the massive population increase," since only cities "can
provide essential services more cheaply and on a larger scale than rural areas."
Habitat II's solution to an ever-growing population simply is to envision
ever-bigger cities.<P>

The most controversial phrase in Habitat II's draft "Statement of Principles and
Commitments" and "Global Plan of Action" refers to housing as a "right." At the
final pre-conference meeting in New York City, in February, 1995, The <B>Earth Times</B>
reported that, "The main opposition to the concept of the right to housing came
from the United States." US spokesperson James Rubin, sounding more like an
emissary from Newt Gingrich than Bill Clinton, insisted that, "Any document which
emphasizes a government-oriented approach [to meeting shelter needs]... will be
unacceptable to the US." According to The <B>Earth Times</B>, Rubin insisted that the
final document must emphasize "private sector and market-oriented solutions."<P>

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

Contact: US
Network for Habitat II at (202) 879-4286;<BR>HUD Clearinghouse, (800)
248-8180;http://huduser.aspensys.com:84/habitat.html.


<HR>

