<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Habitat II [ Between the Brackets ]</TITLE>

<H1>[ Between the Brackets ]</H1>


Habitat II's draft Preamble, Statement of Goals and Action Plan contain a number of unresolved
issues, identified in brackets. They include: 

<UL>

<LI>the statement that citizens have a "right" to expect
governments to provide housing<P>

<LI>transfer of technology from North to South<P>

<LI>alleviation of the "undesired impacts of structural adjustment"<P>

<LI>promotion of more equitable access to income<P>

<LI>"liability and compensation" for victims of transboundary pollution and transfers of hazardous
technologies<P>

<LI>improved opportunities for redress of "socially and environmentally harmful decisions and
actions" and<P>

<LI>a provision calling for countries to commit 0.7 percent of their gross domestic product to a global
assistance fund for shelter development.<P>

</UL>

In addition, the UN reports, "much of the draft text on international cooperation and coordination
remains in dispute. Contentious provisions include those relating to the promotion of an open,
equitable, cooperative and mutually beneficial international economic environment."<P>

The draft endorsed  some positive positions, including:

<UL>

<LI>promotion of environmentally sound and affordable construction<P>

<LI>development of community mortgage programs accessible to poor women<P>

<LI>elimination of, prejudice and discrimination in housing<P>

<LI>access to open public spaces with programs for youth and street children<P>

<LI>rational use of energy including solar power<P>

<LI>reduction of auto traffic in favor of  walking and cycling<P>

<LI>reduction of pesticide use and<P>

<LI>elimination of "unsustainable agricultural practices."


</UL>

<H2>The Ecocity III Declaration</H2>

In its concluding plenary meeting, Ecocity III endorsed a plan for an
International Ecological Rebuilding Program for human settlements worldwide.<P>

The recommendations included:

<UL>

<LI>ending automobile subsidies,<P>

<LI>reshaping cities around walkable centers,<P>

<LI>withdrawing from sprawl and simultaneously restoring large tracts of natural
environment,<P>

<LI>revitalizing traditional villages and diverse local agriculture,<P>

<LI>creating strong economic incentives for businesses favorable toward ecovillages
and ecocities,<P>

<LI>funding retooling and retraining for ecological construction and technology,<P>

<LI>establishing government departments with a whole-systems perspective
empowered to assist ecological rebuilding,<P>

<LI>coordinating and combining environmental protection, energy development and
housing under a single department.


</UL>

<HR>

