<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Walking Yoff's Soft Paths by Richard Register</TITLE>

<H1>Walking Yoff's Soft Paths</H1>
<H2>by Richard Register</H2>

Walking through Yoff by starlight, we explored the narrow, nighttime streets
wrapped in the dry, cool breezes off the Sahara. With no smog, no glare, the
desert sky was a velvet-black treasure chest of stars sparkling over the
soft-sand streets.<P>

The entire town is built on deep, fine-grained sand that sandals, thongs and bare
feet float as much as walk through. Yoff's soft streets create an environment in
which children play more freely than I've ever seen. Youngsters congregate on the
rooftops, climb high walls, jump off, chase one another, fall down. But as a
guest from the US observed, "you fall down, but you don't get hurt." Sure enough,
there are none of the bloody knees and elbows and dewy eyes we see in the land of
asphalt and concrete.<P>

By day, the hundreds of smiling, open-faced children run up to shake visitors'
hands and hold on with lingering giggles. There are none of the conversations
that plague adult/child meetings in the wealthy countries -- exchanges hinging on
pretty clothes, new toys, appearances or the presumed suspicion of strangers.<P>

The first French to arrive in Senegal reported that the Lebou villagers
maintained a peaceful republic. (France, at that time, was still a monarchy.) The
people of Yoff also never signed a treaty acknowledging foreign administrative
control. In 1864, the French commander of the Isle de Goree confided, "The
population has an indomitable passion for independence."<P>

Ironically, Yoff did not lose its ancient tribal lands until Senegal gained its
freedom from France in 1978. Shortly after, the new national government -- black,
not white; Senegalese, not French -- privatized large tracts of land and located
the national soccer stadium, airport and conference center directly on top of the
Lebou's ancestral farming lands.<P>

The Senegalese government contracted with China to build the soccer stadium on
farmland expropriated from Yoff. Today, Spanish fishing vessels and large
Japanese factory fishing ships deplete the fish stocks that once sustained Yoff's
economy.


<HR>

<I>Copyright 1996, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


