<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Eco-Housing</TITLE>
<H1>Eco-Housing</H1>

"Buildings use roughly a third of the energy and two-thirds of the electricity in
the US -- and, unfortunately, waste most of it," the Rocky Mountain Institute
reported in its 1994 study, Better Buildings by Design [RMI, 1739 Snowmass Creek
Road, Snowmass, CO 81654-9199; (303) 927-3851]. "The good news -- now being
demonstrated by farseeing architects, developers, contractors and engineers -- is
that the numerous institutional barriers to efficiency can be profitably
overcome."<P>

Here is a brief list of some of the resurgent technologies that represent the
"soft path" approach to meeting human shelter needs.

<H3>Rammed Earth.</H3>

Earth and water, the world's oldest building materials, can be used
to build a home that provides year-round comfort with minimal use of energy. And
the building material comes directly from the building site. One of the best
texts available is <B>The Rammed Earth House</B> [Chelsea Green Publishing, Co. PO Box
428, White River Junction, VT 05001; (802) 295-6300].

<H3>Straw Bales.</H3>

"The idea of building anything out of straw can seem laughable,"
notes the introduction to <B>The Straw Bale House</B> [Chelsea Green Publishing], "but
traditional cultures throughout the world have long recognized the value of
straw, grasses, and reeds as building materials, and have used them effectively
in combination with earth and timber to create shelter for thousands of years."
The first straw bale homes in the US were built in Nebraska more than 100 years
ago. The GreenFire Institute [1509 Queen Anne Avenue North, #606, Seattle, WA
98109; (206) 284-7470] hosts on-site building workshops across the country.

<H3>Cob Cottages.</H3>

Using ancient building techniques from the British Isles, cob
cottages employ "unbaked, unconsolidated, hand-formed earth" to build durable,
energy-efficient homes that can cut lumber consumption by 75 percent. <B>The Cob
Cottage Company</B> [Box 123, Cottage Grove, OR 97424; (503) 942-3021] provides
workshops around the US demonstrating how earthen buildings can be uniquely
hand-formed into beautiful live-in sculptures.

<H3>Earthships.</H3>

Why burn tires and pollute the air when old  tires can be filled with
rammed earth to form Earthship shelters with "virtually indestructible"
three-foot thick walls? Earthship designs [Earthship Global Operations, PO Box
2009, El Prado, NM 87529; (505) 751-0462; fax: -1005; <A HREF="mailto:earthship@ interserv.com">
earthship@ interserv.com</A>]
include water-catching metal roofs, photoelectric panels and dry solar toilets.

<H2>Organizations</H2>

<B>Habitat for Humanity International</B> [121 Habitat Street, Americus, GA 31709-3498;
(912) 924-6935; fax: 924-6541], a nonprofit ecumenical Christian organization
with 1200 US affiliates, is responsible for building 10,000 new homes each year.
Last December, HFHI embarked on an "international effort to enhance environmental
responsibility in the construction and maintenance" of new homes. Habitat homes,
built by volunteers in as little as six-days, are built to last. When Hurricane
Andrew raked South Florida, it flattened homes that took six months to build: all
27 Habitat homes survived the storm. "It is the stated mission of Habitat for
Humanity to eliminate poverty housing from the face of the Earth," states HEFI
founder Millard Fuller. Habitat has built 40,000 homes in 46 countries and all 50
states.<P>

<B>Global Green USA</B> [(310) 277-6200], the US partner of Mikhail Gorbachev's Green
Cross International, promotes "resource-efficient building practices."<P>

<B>Habitat International Coalition</B> [Cordobanes #24, Col. San Jose Insurgentes,
Mexico, 03900, DF; (5) 651-6807; fax: (5) 593-5194] coordinates the global
grassroots Global Campaign for the Right to Housing, and its monthly newsletter
reports on the fight for "just, democratic and sustainable cities."<P>

<B>Ecological Design Association</B> [EDA, The British School, Slad Road, Stound,
Gloschester, GL5 1QZ, UK] was founded to "promote ecological design and link
designers in a global network."<P>

<B>Center for Resourceful Building Technology</B> [PO Box 3866, Missoula, MT 59806;
(406) 549-7678] studies the environmental impacts of building materials and
publishes the Guide to Resource Efficient Building Elements.<P>

<B>The Co-Housing Company</B> [1250 Addison Street #13, Berkeley, CA 94702; (510)
549-9980] assists people interested in creating shared living solutions.<P>

<B>The Ecological Design Institute</B> [10 Liberty Way, #185, Sausalito, CA 94965; (415)
332-5806] offers a comprehensive range of educational, research and design
services.<P>

<B>Natural Building Network</B> [Box 1110, Sebastopol, CA 95473] is a group of
architects and builders promoting energy-efficient and ecological design.

<H2>Publications</H2>

<B>The Adobe Journal</B> [PO Box 7725, Albuquerque, NM 87102; (505) 243-7801] celebrates
earth-based construction techniques that "provides shelter to 40 percent of the
world's population." This beautifully illustrated oversized magazine believes
that modern architects, planners and housing officials can draw lessons from
"generations of earth-builders whose distilled practical knowledge may provide
the most important and available solution for the world's housing crisis, as well
as reducing the problems of deforestation and pollution."<P>

<B>The Natural House Catalog</B> [Gaia Books Ltd., 20 High Street, Stround,
Gloucestershire, GL5 1AS England; 44-1453-752985; fax: 44-1453-752987] was
written by David Pearson, author of The Natural House Book, to provide
"everything you need to create your natural home.<P>

<B>Eco-Interiors</B>, interior designer Grazyna Pilatowicz' guide to environmentally
conscious interior design [John Wiley & Sons, Inc. 605 Third Avenue, NY
10158-0012; (212) 850-6000], identifies the best materials and methods architects
can use to enhance energy consumption and minimize waste and pollution on
fixtures and furnishings.<P>

<B>Greener Building Directory</B> is published by the Association for Environment
Conscious Building [AECB, Windlake House, West End, Coaley, Gloschester, GL11
5DX, UK].<P>

<B>Better Building</B>, the newsletter of the Housing Resource Center [1820 West 48 St.,
Cleveland, OH 44102] offers "ideas and techniques for affordable housing." The
center also operates a home-builders hotline: (216) 281-4670.<P>

<B>Environmental Building News</B> [RR1, Box 161, Brattleboro, VT 05301; (802) 257-7300;
fax: -7304] has been called "the single best source" of information on
sustainable design.<P>

<B>A Holistic Home Building Guide</B> is a straight-forward booklet explaining the
rudiments of using clay-straw building in conjunction with timber-framed housing.
Author Robert Laporte is the founder of the Natural House Building Center [RR1,
Box 115F, Fairfield, IA 52556; (515) 472-7775], which conducts building workshops
around the country.


<HR>

