<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: A New Challenge: Overcoming Green Sexism by Diane Valantne, Joy Belsky, and Sally Cross</TITLE>
<H1>A New Challenge: Overcoming Green Sexism</H1>
<H2>by Diane Valantne, Joy Belsky, and Sally Cross</H2>

The simmering dissatisfaction of female forest activists first boiled over at the
1993 Ancient Forests Conference in Ashland, Oregon. Some women were annoyed about
the phallic humor from the podium; others were concerned about the general lack
of female participation. An ad-hoc session on sexism in the environmental
movement attracted a broad diversity of activists -- first-timers, seasonal
volunteers, staff of national groups and long-time grassroots activists.<P>

Three months of hard work followed, resulting in a statement called "The Ash-land
Principles," which discussed the relationship between the destruction of our
environment, the oppression of women and the denial of so-called "feminine
values." Later work on the principles led to the development of "Guidelines for
Organizations," which presented two major goals:

<UL>

<LI>achieving proportional representation of women and minorities in all areas of
an organization, including leadership ranks; and,<P>

<LI>creating an atmosphere where everyone feels included, respected and valued.<P>

</UL>

The goals were accompanied by guidelines for hiring, leadership development,
meetings, office atmosphere and public conferences.<P>

A few months later, the 1993 Land Air Water (LAW) Conference convened in Eugene,
Oregon under the banner: "Indigenous Peoples: Sacred Roots, Sacred Ties." While
the organizers did include a committee on sexism, the conference was disrupted by
a group of Native American drummers protesting the all-white makeup of the
televised keynote panel. Clearly, many people were becoming frustrated with the
continued lack of diversity within these environmental conferences.<P>

The next year, the 1994 LAW Conference listed two male speakers for every woman.
The meeting's theme, "Raising our Voices for the Earth," should have read:
"Raising our Mostly Male Voices for the Earth."<P>

With a sense of fun, we recommended that attendees send only one-third of the $25
registration fee to reflect the fact that only one-third of the presenters were
women. The conference organizers -- all students at the University of Oregon Law
School -- were not amused. They let us know, in no uncertain terms, how hard they
had worked trying to find more women to invite. They accused us of criticizing
rather than helping.<P>

We responded by sending them the names of 20 women who were well-qualified to
speak at the conference and reminded them that people are judged by results, not
by good intentions. We hold natural resources agencies to this standard in court,
and we did not see any reason to lower standards for environmental organizations.
The LAW conference organizers subsequently were able to find additional women to
invite, including some from our list.<P>

<H2>Genderbusting Goes National</H2>

With this victory in hand, we started deconstructing every conference
announcement we received, pouring over a slew of glossy brochures for events
sponsored by the US Forest Service, Bureau of Land Management and several Western
universities. A conference on "Sustaining Rangeland Ecosystems" listed only six
invited women out of 55 speakers; one on "Ecosystem Management in Western
In-terior Forests" listed three women out of 54 speakers; another on "Forest
Health and Fire Danger in Inland Western Forests" listed five women out 54
speakers. The LAW Conference's one-to-two ratio was looking better all the time.<P>

We wrote to the organizers of each conference, pointed out the seriously skewed
ratios, and explained that "under-representation of women... perpetuates the myth
that only men have the training, the ability, or the interest to participate in
management of our public lands."<P>

Copies of these letters were sent to the secretaries of Interior and Agriculture,
the Chief of the Forest Service, deans of the universities, conference sponsors
and local newspapers -- along with lists of 60-90 women scientists, land managers
and newspaper reporters who were qualified to speak at each conference.<P>

Despite their PhDs, the howls of protest from the professionals were even louder
and more indignant than those of the law students. One letter from Forest Service
and Washington State University organizers used the terms "malicious" and
"slanderous" to describe us.<P>

All the host organizations had strong policies promoting gender diversity. Their
program committees included women, and every one of those committees discussed
the necessity of inviting more women. But they did not. Those women who cared
about balance were voted down and the "good old boys" continued to invite their
buddies. It was not until ONRC chastised the organizers in protests and in the
press that they altered their behavior.<P>

<H2>Women Respond</H2>

Letters, phone calls and flowers started arriving at ONRC from the women we had
recommended as speakers. These women spoke about the pain and frustration of
being left out of conferences and ignored by their peers. The letters were
indescribably sad and familiar -- educated, talented, productive women who had
received little recognition for their work and faced slow career advancement.<P>

An assistant professor of range management wrote: "I constantly battle the
insidious and covert barriers to women in our field. I often tire of the battle,
and, at times, I have considered changing my career. I do not believe I could
have composed such a powerful letter, and I doubt that I would have had the
courage to send it. Thanks for standing up for me and other women professionals."<P>

The media was slow to show interest, but ONRC's request for a Congressional
investigation into sex discrimination at conferences funded by federal monies
gave the story the news value it needed.<P>

ONRC's commitment to gender balance was put to the test when it became one of the
hosts of the 1994 National Forest Reform Rally. We spent days on the phone
recruiting speakers and discovered, once again, the pressures working against
gender balance at conferences.<P>

The ancient forest issue is one of the oldest in the environmental movement, and
most of the leaders are men -- and they all wanted to give talks. On the other
side were women who often had little speaking experience and did not wish to get
their first experience at a national meeting.<P>

The final gender breakdown of speakers at the event was 39 to 36 (male to
female). We had proven that, with extra effort, gender balance could be achieved.
The women added diversity of thought, speaking styles and perspective, and the
conference helped pave the way for a new generation of leaders to gain experience
and recognition.
The authors, staffmembers of the Oregon Natural Resources Council (ONRC), have
worked  tirelessly to attack sexism in the environmental movement. Their campaign
of direct action has helped bring more equitable gender representation to
environmental and scientific conferences.<P>

When the 1995 LAW brochure arrived, we did a quick count: the ratio was two women
to three men. An improvement, but there is still work to be done.<P>

<H2>Some Final Thoughts</H2>

Our first piece of advice is: do not be afraid to confront the issue head-on. As
a movement and profession, environmentalists are committed to the principle of
protecting biodiversity. We should not accept the human equivalent of a
monoculture at our conferences, when, with a little effort, we can have a diverse
and healthy forest.<P>

Second, be prepared for angry responses. In the modern world, everyone imagines
themselves to be totally liberated. Challenges are bound to create anger and
denial. Do not be intimidated.<P>

Third, repetition is the key. Our first letter to the conference organizers had
no effect; the second letter had no effect either; but the third letter broke
through the denial.<P>

We were lucky. Not only were the three of us working together and supporting each
other, but we belong to an organization in which everyone strongly believes in
the importance of diversity; not just as a fairness issue, but as an
environmental issue as well.<P>

It helps to have support. If you have to go it alone, do so, but you will not
really be alone. You will be representing a much larger group, many of whom have
lost the ability or strength to speak for themselves.<P>

<HR>

The authors, staffmembers of the Oregon Natural Resources Council (ONRC), have
worked  tirelessly to attack sexism in the environmental movement. Their campaign
of direct action has helped bring more equitable gender representation to
environmental and scientific conferences.<P>

Adapted from an article in the journal <B>Whole Terrain</B> (department of
Environmental Studies, Antioch New England Graduate Scholl, 40 Avon St., Keene
NH 03431-3516 


<HR>

