<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Attacks on Women: A Tax on Men by June Stephenson</TITLE>
<H1>Attacks on Women: A Tax on Men</H1>
<H2>by June Stephenson</H2>

The greatest US environmental offender is the federal government -- run by
men.... Ninety-four percent of people arrested and sent to jail are men. Whether
robbery, burglary, arson, white-collar crime, crime against children, crime
against women, crime in government, crime against the environment, drug dealing,
drunk driving, murder, treason or gang violence, crime is a masculine statement.<P>

Ten years ago there were approximately 200,000 people in US prisons. Today there
are approximately one million Americans behind bars. Incarcerated men outnumber
women by a ratio of 94 to 6. Men dominate the ranks of individuals on parole or
probation -- all 2.4 million of them.<P>

Male criminals cost this country more than $61 billion each year in incarceration
and judicial expenses. This figure does not include the cost of the
billion-dollar savings-and-loan scandal, nor the costs of toxic-waste cleanup.<P>

We cannot expect men to police their own or take responsibility for their
contribution to violence: they are too much a part of it. So besides building
more prisons and jailing more offenders, what is left? Nothing short of ensuring
that men pay for male-perpetrated crime.<P>

Half of US taxpayers are women and all of these women pay for male crime with
their tax dollars. A $100 criminal justice system "user fee" could be added to
men's IRS returns. Of course, there would be screaming and hollering about such a
fee, but one might ask, is $100 a year too much to ask to help curtail crime?<P>

The concept of one group paying more for services is not new. Insurance companies
in many states charge young men aged 18 to 26 more for car insurance than other
people, because males in this age group cause most of the car accidents.<P>

If men recognize that crime is a male statement for which males must pay more
than females, there is a possibility they might help to "clean up their act."<P>

<HR>

Adapted from <B>Men are Not Cost-Effective: Male Crime in America</B> by June Stephenson
(Harper Perennial).


<HR>

<I>Copyright 1996, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


<A HREF="journal.html"><IMG SRC="jhome.gif"></A><P>
<!- - efooter>

