<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Ebb & Flow</TITLE>

<H1>Ebb & Flow</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Nukes">No Nukes Are Good Nukes</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Catching">Catching the Wave</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Heavy">Heavy Waterworld</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Tobacco">Tobacco Is Haram-ful</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#50th">50th US Park</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Manna">Manna From Hebron</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Whom">Whom Do You Trust?</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#CITI">My CITI by the Bay</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-02.html#Adios">Adios, Mexico City</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="Nukes"><H2>No Nukes Are Good Nukes</H2>

Thailand -- On December 15, 1995, after 12 years of negotiations, Thailand,
Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, Brunei, Vietnam, Burma, Cambodia, Laos and the
Philippines declared Southeast Asia a nuclear- weapons-free zone. The treaty
marked the highlight of the first-ever summit of all ten members of the
Association of Southeast Asia Nations (ASEAN). While Philippine President Fidel
Ramos praised the treaty for helping to "secure a less anxious future for
peoples throughout Southeast Asia," the US and China complained that the
"nuclear-free" declaration could interfere with their nuclear-powered and
nuclear-armed vessel movement.

<A NAME="Catching"><H2>Catching the Wave</H2>

China -- Despite US Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary's 1995 trip to Beijing to
woo contracts for US nuclear reactors, the world's largest nation is not about
to become a nuclear-dependent economy. Since 1958, China has harvested
electrical energy from the ocean's tides. Eight "trial" tidal power stations
already generate 6.12 MW of electricity. The five-station Jiang-sha Trial
Station at Leqing Bay in Zhejiang Province has an installed capacity of 3.2 MW.
Jiangsha, the world's third-largest tidal power station (France and Canada have
larger plants), is the first "two-way" tidal generator -- it produces power
both when the tide flows and when it ebbs.

<A NAME="Heavy"><H2>Heavy Waterworld</H2>

Germany -- In 1973, work began near the Westphalian town of Kalkar on what was
to have been Germany's first breeder reactor. Germany has spent DM7 billion
($4.9 billion) on the reactor without producing a single watt of electricity.
After two decades of technical and financial problems, the Bonn government
decided to throw in the towel. Eight months after Bonn put the abandoned
40-acre site on the auction block, a potential buyer stepped forth. According
to <B>The Week in Germany</B>, the owner of a chain of amusement parks in The
Netherlands "intends to turn the plant into a family recreation center,
complete with hotels and sports facilities, that will feature a variety of
water rides." The Dutch entrepreneur will call his park <B>Kern-Wasser-Wunderland</B>
("Nuclear Water Wonderland").

<A NAME="Tobacco"><H2>Tobacco Is Haram-ful</H2>

Malaysia -- What do Joe Camel and Salman Rushdie have in common? Both have been
targeted for elimination by factions of the Muslim faith. Last fall, the
Malaysian National Islamic Affairs Council passed a <B>fatwa</B> (holy law) declaring
smoking to be <B>haram</B> (a vice forbidden to Muslims). According to the Malaysian
consumer magazine <B>Utusan Konsumer</B>, the Ministry of Domestic Trade and Consumer
Affairs "has informed the Director General of the Islamic Affairs Division in the
Prime Minister's Department that the fatwa should, in fact, be printed on every
pack of cigarettes sold." In addition to containing 4000 hazardous chemicals
(including butane, arsenic, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, vinyl chloride,
radioactive polonium-210 and nicotine), the newspaper notes that "Cigarettes sold
in Malaysia have almost twice the amount of tar and nicotine than those in the
US."

<A NAME="50th"><H2>50th US Park</H2>

Samoa -- The Utah-based Seacology Foundation [(800) 489-1SAV] has presented the
1996 Indigenous Conservationist of the Year Award to A. P. Lutali, Governor of
American Samoa. Lutali was instrumental in creating the 9000-acre National Park
of Samoa -- the 50th US national park and home of the Pacific boa and the Pacific
Island flying fox. The flying fox (actually a large bat) is a major pollinator of
the island's forests. The park will offer new protection to the bat, which has
been hunted for its meat.

<A NAME="Manna"><H2>Manna From Hebron</H2>

USA -- Saltcedar trees (Tamarix) were imported to the US from Israel in 1837 to
stabilize stream banks. Today, the saltcedar ranks as one of the ten worst weeds
in the west, dominating more than 1.5 million acres from Kansas and Texas to
California and Montana. Saltcedar crowds out native cottonwoods, willow and
mesquite, and its salty leaves poison the topsoil. US scientists now believe that
they have found a native predator to control the saltcedar. Israel's manna scale
(<B>Trabutina mannipara</B>), "a beneficial sap-sucking insect the size of a green pea,"
is best known for its starring role in the Book of Genesis, where swarms of
insects excreted sweet streams of honeydew, the "manna that fell from Heaven" and
saved the starving Israelites.

<A NAME="Whom"><H2>Whom Do You Trust?</H2>

UK -- In 1995, according to the annual MORI Business and the Environment survey,
82 percent of British citizens polled claimed that they trusted scientists
working for environmental groups, while only 48 percent trusted industry
scientists. Government scientists had the trust of just 38 percent. According to
<B>BBC Wildlife</B>, MORI also discovered that "the proportion of environmental
activists more than doubled... from 14 percent of the adult population in 1988 to
31 percent in 1991." Since 1993, "a steady two thirds of the public" have
disagreed with the statement: "There isn't much that ordinary people can do to
help protect the environment."

<A NAME="CITI"><H2>My CITI by the Bay</H2>

USA -- A $10,000 electric automobile goes on sale in California this year. The
lead-acid/Ni-Cad battery-powered CITI (Clean, Intelligent Transportation, Inc.)
is based on the Norwegian "City Bee" electric car. The small (five-foot by
nine-foot), 1650-pound CITI features a dent-resistant thermoplastic body over an
aluminum "space frame" body, air conditioning and air-bags. Freeway-ready at
speeds up to 65 mph, the CITI is also "fully recyclable." The CITI will be built
at the former Alameda Naval Air Station, an abandoned defense depot now being
converted for peacetime use.

<A NAME="Adios"><H2>Adios, Mexico City</H2>

Mexico -- Mexico City's government buildings, cathedrals, 20 million residents
and 3.5 million cars are sinking into the ground -- four-and-a-half inches per
year -- as Latin America's largest (and thirstiest) megacity drains underground
aquifers twice as fast as rainwater can replenish them. The city has dropped 22
feet since 1935. The Fine Arts Building, the National Palace and heavy stone
cathedrals are slumping, tilting and cracking. Water and sewer lines are
rupturing, threatening to pollute the city's remaining aquifer with chemical and
organic wastes. Charles DuMars, a University of New Mexico law professor and
co-chair of a US-Mexico water study, told the Cox News Service that once aquifers
are contaminated, "it's economically unfeasible to clean them up. Once it happens
it's irreversible." DuMars estimated that the situation could become "very
urgent... in two, three, five years."

<HR>

