<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: EcoMole</TITLE>

<H1>The EcoMole</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Star">Star Wars Lives</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Bunker">"Bunker Bomb" Being Built</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#NIMS">NIMS (Not In My School)</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#What">What Next, Nuclear Gnats?</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Our">Our Tax Dollars at Work</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Nuclear">Nuclear Hara-Kiri</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Pimping">Pimping for the Pentagon</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Pravda">Pravda -- Not!</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Nip">Mole Nip</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Kiss">Mole Kiss</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-03.html#Headlines">Headlines of Our Times</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="Star"><H2>Star Wars Lives</H2>

Last October 25, an explosion and fire demolished a building at
the 1578-acre Lockheed-Martin facility near Orlando, Florida. Company and
Department of Defense officials refused to discuss the incident, but John Pike of
the Federation of American Scientists believes the explosion involved "special
access, black programs" of the federal government's plan to build a secret
Strategic Defense Initiative ("Star Wars") space weapon. While the government
claims that Star Wars spending cost taxpayers $32.6 billion between 1983-1993,
the Congressional Research Service (CRS) estimates that the Pentagon actually
spent "at least $70.7 billion" on space weapons research. The CRS explained that
the missing $38.1 billion was hidden in off-budget "generic" and "all other
projects" spending. According to the Christian Science Monitor, "The purposes of
most of these programs are not disclosed, even to the lawmakers who vote on the
military's annual budgets."<P>

<A NAME="Bunker"><H2>"Bunker Bomb" Being Built</H2>

At last spring's Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty
Extension Conference, American representatives told the world that the US had no
plans to develop new nuclear weapons. At that very moment, however, the
Department of Energy (DoE) secretly was working to develop the B-61 strategic
bomb, an "earth penetrator" capable of plunging deep underground to destroy
buried targets. Citizens Against a Radioactive Environment [CARE, 5720 East
Avenue, #116, Livermore, CA 94550; (510) 433-7148] reports that the weapon "was
approved outside the regular budget process and without congressional debate, by
means of secret letters to key committee chairs." The DoE insists the weapon is
merely a "modification" of an older bomb. CARE maintains that building this
weapon "undercuts a [nuclear weapons test ban] before it is even signed."<P>

<A NAME="NIMS"><H2>NIMS (Not In My School)</H2>

Arizona Republicans, alarmed that their schoolchildren
had been encouraged to write "advocacy" letters (to save dolphins, forests and
predators), passed a law banning "environmental advocacy" in the state's
classrooms. School officials in Idaho, Oklahoma and Oregon also have placed
restrictions on teaching environmental issues. Florida, North Carolina and
Wisconsin are considering similar laws. Ironically, a study by the nonprofit
Consumers Union found that the most widely available "environmental materials" in
classrooms are sponsored by business groups such as the American Gas Association
and the National Livestock & Meat Board.<P>

<A NAME="What"><H2>What Next, Nuclear Gnats?</H2>

After Glen James, a former engineer at California's
San Onofre nuclear power plant, contracted terminal leukemia, he sued the plant's
owner, Southern California Edi-son, for failure to ensure plant safety. James
cited a Nuclear Regulatory Commission report that faulted SCE's monitoring
systems for not being sensitive enough to detect "fuel fleas," radioactive specks
of reactor fuel that can run loose inside the work spaces of nuclear plants. Fuel
fleas are even more dangerous than the "radon daughters" that can enter homes
from buried radioactive rock deposits. After a two-month trial, however, a jury
failed to find in James' favor. SCE released a report praising the jury's
verdict, claiming that its corporate heart went out to James' family and signing
off with the observation that, after all, "today, one out of three Americans will
die of cancer."<P>

<A NAME="Our"><H2>Our Tax Dollars at Work</H2>

Last November, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
dispatched 100 members of the State Security Service to London. Press reports
identified the armed men as "hit squads" sent to "liquidate the Egyptian regime's
enemies abroad." According to wire service reports, 40 of the killers sent to
track down and eliminate Islamic fundamentalists were "trained in the United
States."<P>

<A NAME="Nuclear"><H2>Nuclear Hara-Kiri</H2>

In Japan, Nuclear power plant manager Shigeo Nishimura
reported that his company had covered up the severity of an accident at the
experimental Monju breeder-reactor. On January 13, shortly after his findings
were made public, Nishimura penned a letter of apology to his boss and plunged to
his death from the window of a Tokyo hotel.<P>

<A NAME="Pimping"><H2>Pimping for the Pentagon</H2>

The rape of a schoolgirl galvanized Okinawa, Japan,
against the presence of US military forces, but the situation in South Korea may
be even worse. Gwy Kirk, Director of Women's Studies at Antioch College, reports
that "every day, US military personnel [in South Korea] commit two or three
crimes against Korean civilians --  murders, rapes and sexual abuse, arson,
theft, fraud -- all beyond the reach of Korean law." In most countries subject to
US military occupation, prostitution routinely is supported and supervised by the
Pentagon. "Since 1945," Kirk reports, "there has been an agreement between the
two governments authorizing the sexual servicing of US personnel." An estimated
18,000 South Korean "bar girls" currently are registered with health authorities.<P>

<A NAME="Pravda"><H2>Pravda -- Not!</H2>

Disgusted by the level of Kremlin disinformation on Russia's war
in Chechnya, one leading news agency felt compelled to add the following caveat
to its dispatches: "Dear subscribers! Interfax does not exclude the possibility
that sometimes these reports are intended to serve purposes other than to
inform."<P>

<A NAME="Nip"><H2>Mole Nip</H2>

To Native American activist/actor Russell Means, who is lending his
name to a plan by First Entertainment Inc. to revive two classic Harley-Davidson
"Indian" motorcycles from the 1940s -- the "Chief" and the "441 Straight." Means
reportedly is asking American Indian casino owners to contribute the $30 million
needed to kick-start the assembly lines.<P>

<A NAME="Kiss"><H2>Mole Kiss</H2>

To neo-Vegan Lisa Simpson of Fox Network's <B>The Simpsons</B> for pitching
the concept of meat-free diets to an audience of more than 14 million viewers.<P>

To director Jodi Foster for a nice anti-fur moment in her wicked
family comedy, <B>Home for the Holidays</B>.<P>

<A NAME="Headlines"><H2>Headlines of Our Times</H2>

"Rare Wetlands Imperil Gary Stadium Proposal" -- <B>Chicago
Tribune</B>, November 19, 1995.


<HR>

<I>Copyright 1996, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


