<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Good News</TITLE>

<H1>Good News</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Moth">Moth-Mashing Microbes</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#AKZO">The AKZO-Nobel Prize</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Solar">Solar Market Dawns in Far East</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Mattress">Mattress Matters</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Charcoals">Charcoals to Newcastle</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Saving">Saving Trees Creates Jobs</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Do">Do-it-Yourself Development</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Eco">Eco-City Campaign</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Green">Green Solvents From Down Under</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-04.html#Congress">"Congress, Have you Flipped?"</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="Moth"><H2>Moth-Mashing Microbes</H2>

USA -- After a 14-year effort by Louis A. Falcon, a University of California
professor emeritus of entomology, the EPA has approved the use of a microbial
pesticide (the granulosis virus) to protect apples, pears and walnuts from attack
by the codling moth. While standard spraying with the pesticide Guthion
(azinphosmethyl) kills all insects, both good and bad, Fal-con's baculovirus only
affects a few specific insect pests. When chemical companies refused to back the
research, the US Department of Agriculture and Cali-fornia's Environmental
License Plate Fund came to the rescue. Half of the $5 million research cost was
provided by the nonprofit Association for Sensible Pest Control, Inc. (ASPCI), a
coalition of  organic growers. ASPCI boardmember and apple farmer Tim Bates
claims that Falcon's microbe "works better" than the other biological pesticides
like ryania and Bacillus thuringensis.

<A NAME="AKZO"><H2>The AKZO-Nobel Prize</H2>

The Netherlands -- Ten years ago, chemical stench and eye-watering pollution
drove local residents to blockade the Diosynth chemical plant in the southern
Netherlands. In the last two years, reports Environmental News From The
Netherlands, "a detailed environmental management system reduced [the plant's]
solvent emissions by 95 percent," and Diosynth, a branch of the Dutch chemical
group AKZO-Nobel, has gone on to win a national prize for environmental care.
According to Environmental News, "the driving force behind the change was the
workforce."

<A NAME="Solar"><H2>Solar Market Dawns in Far East</H2>

Germany -- The Munich-based company Siemans Solar GmbH predicts that the market
for photovoltaic power in the Far East -- now generating approximately 15,000 KW
annually -- will grow 25 percent by the year 2000. In India alone,
solar-generated electricity is expected to jump from 5000 KW to 20,000 KW by
1997, thanks to the government's program to equip 100,000 rural homes with
sun-powered lighting. Siemans will ship more than one million solar cells to
India from its manufacturing plants in California.

<A NAME="Mattress"><H2>Mattress Matters</H2>

USA -- Each year, two million tons of waste pour into US landfills, and among the
bulkiest items are mattresses. The Outcycle Project works to reduce the nation's
annual $4 billion landfill bill by returning "virtually all used mattress
components to other industries for use in new products." This first-of-its-kind
project was created by The Verlo Mattress Company, Inc. [Rt. 4, Hwy. 59E, PO Box
298, Whitewater, WI 53190]. Verlo "outcycles" discarded mattresses by reclaiming
fabric, foam and cotton padding, wood and steel. Is there a downside to
outcycling? Perhaps just this:  according to Verlo's press release, "Each
mattress is broken down into its base components by prison labor forces."

<A NAME="Charcoals"><H2>Charcoals to Newcastle</H2>

UK -- Britain's backyard barbequers burn 60,000 tons of charcoal each year to
bake their burgers and bangers. Ninety-five percent of the charcoal is imported,
with a third coming from Southeast Asia's mangrove forests. A newly designed
Viper Kiln, developed by Yorkshire inventor David Hutchinson, promises to revive
the British charcoal industry with small, highly efficient, portable burners.
While a ton of waste wood sells for #18 ($28) a ton as pulp, it is worth #700
($1100) once it has been turned into charcoal. BBC Wildlife reports that the
revival of small-scale charcoal operations "not only rejuvenates British
woodlands, it also provides labor-intensive rural jobs and takes the strain off
endangered habitats."

<A NAME="Saving"><H2>Saving Trees Creates Jobs</H2>

USA -- After logging in national parks was curbed in 1991 to protect the northern
spotted owl, Republican lawmakers complained that the restrictions would cost
thousands of jobs. A December 1995 report by the Natural Resources Defense
Council found that, as of 1993, 2254 loggers had lost their jobs -- a 21 percent
decline. However, the NRDC reported, after logging restrictions were enacted,
total employment in the region actually swelled by 45,363 jobs -- mainly from
increased tourism and retail sales. Surveying economic data from 17 of
California's Sierra Nevada counties, the NRDC found that logging accounted for
only one percent of employment and income in the timber towns. "For every
timber-related job lost, 20 new jobs were created," the NRDC reported.

<A NAME="Do"><H2>Do-it-Yourself Development</H2>

Eritrea -- Despite average annual incomes of less than $150, citizens in the
African nation of Eritrea have spurned international development loans. "We have
the capacity for self-sufficiency. We don't believe aid can solve our problems,"
said President Isaias Afewerki. The government has mobilized workers to build
rail lines and roads by offering donated foodstuffs as payment. Eighty percent of
Eritreans are still farmers, and agriculture accounts for 70 percent of export
earnings. Each summer, Eritrean schoolchildren spend two months planting trees
and restoring mountain sides. Eritrea's minister of marine resources, Saleh Meky,
curtly explained the reasoning behind his country's maverick path: "Handouts have
brought nothing to Africa but disaster."

<A NAME="Eco"><H2>Eco-City Campaign</H2>

Denmark -- Responding to the challenge of Agenda 21 (the guide to environmental
sustainability produced at the 1992 Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro), delegates
from 32 countries met in Aalborg in 1994 and signed a Charter of European Cities
and Towns Towards Sustainability. Two existing "eco-cities"in the New World -- 
Davis, California and Curitiba, Brazil --helped inspire the European eco-city
campaign.

<A NAME="Green"><H2>Green Solvents From Down Under</H2>

Australia -- Most industrial and household solvents are derived from alcohol and
hydrocarbons, which can damage  the environment and human health. Ren Kenbao, a
research student at the Victoria University of Technology in Melbourne [c/o Dr.
Douglas Kagi, VUT, PO Box 14428, MMC, Melbourne, VIC 3000, Australia] has created
a range of "organic solvents" that are "worker-friendly and environmentally
sound." The water-based emulsions and solutions can be used in place of toluene,
xylene and mineral turpentine.

<A NAME="Congress"><H2>"Congress, Have you Flipped?"</H2>

USA -- With the backing of Earth Island and 20 other eco groups, Gary Hirshberg,
president of Stonyfield Farm, has placed a unique appeal on the lids of millions
of yogurt cups. Yogurt  lovers are asked to send their lids to Congress and
demand laws that protect "a healthy Earth."


<HR>

<I>Copyright 1996, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


