<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Earth Island in the News</TITLE>

<H1>Earth Island in the News</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#Victory">Victory for Sea Turtles</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#Wild">Wild and WACky</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#Journal">Journal Wins Reporting Award</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#As">As Goes Maine</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#Carl">Carl Anthony Goes to Harvard</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#On">On the Web</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-10.html#Bon">Bon Voyage</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="Victory"><H2>Victory for Sea Turtles</H2>

 On January 5, in a ruling dubbed one of the greatest
conservation victories of all time, the US Court of International Trade (CIT)
determined that all shrimp-exporting countries must adopt sea turtle conservation
measures by May 1, 1996, or face an embargo of shrimp products destined for the
US.<P>

The lawsuit, challenging the US Secretaries of State, Treasury and Commerce, was
filed by EII's <A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">Sea Turtle Restoration Project</A> [STRP, Box 400, 40 Montezuma
Avenue, Forest Knolls, CA 94933; (415) 488-0370], the American Society for the
Preservation of Cruelty to Animals, the Humane Society of the US and the Sierra
Club.<P>

"This decision will save more than a hundred thousand sea turtles from needlessly
drowning in shrimp nets every year, ending the largest killing of en-dangered
species occurring in the world right now," stated STRP director Todd Steiner.
"We're overjoyed that [federal judge Thomas J.] Aquilino had the courage to
overturn the US State Department, putting environment protection ahead of
so-called 'free-trade' issues."<P>

The ruling compels the State Department to ban shrimp imports from all nations
that have not reduced sea turtle mortality by 97 percent -- a level easily
achieved with the use of Turtle Excluder Devices. TEDs are inexpensive ($50-$400)
metal grids sewn into shrimp nets to guide turtles toward an escape hatch.<P>

Industry lobbyists have long claimed that using TEDs would force shrimpers out of
business, but Steiner noted that US shrimp trawlers have used TEDs successfully
since 1989. According to Jack d'Antiagnac, president of the Georgia Fisherman's
Association, "TEDs save turtles, reduce the unnecessary killing of countless fish
and protect the marine environment on which we all depend. It will be easy enough
for countries to adopt the use of TEDs, if they have a sincere desire to do so."

<A NAME="Wild"><H2>Wild and WACky</H2>

 Earth Island's Board of Directors has approved EII's newest
project, <B>Wildlife Alive</B> -- California (WAC), dedicated to the protection and
restoration of wildlife and habitat throughout the state. WAC also works to
defend state laws such as the California Endangered Species Act, recently under
fire from right-wing legislators. WAC played a  role in the successful statewide
effort to defeat Proposition 197, a mountain lion "management plan" designed to
repeal a 1990 initiative and reinstate mountain lion trophy hunting.<P>

WAC director Mark J. Palmer, a former executive director of the Whale Center and
the Mountain Lion Foundation, most recently has worked with EII's <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">Marine Mammal
Project</A> coordinating congressional efforts to protect dolphins.

<A NAME="Journal"><H2>Journal Wins Reporting Award</H2>

 Project Censored has selected two <B>Earth Island
Journal</B> stories -- "EPA Study Reveals Dioxin Dangers" by <B>Stephen Lester</B> (Spring
EIJ) and "<A HREF="methbro.html">Campaign Against Methyl Bromide: Ozone-Killing Pesticide Opposed</A>" by
Anne Schoenfield (Summer EIJ) -- from more than 700 nominations nationwide to
rank among the 25 top "censored" stories for 1995. Schoenfield's article  was
judged one of the "Top Ten Best Censored Stories of 1995." For the full story,
see the new book, Censored, with an introduction by Walter Cronkite (Seven
Stories, 632 Broadway, New York, NY 10012. $14.95).<P>

The Journal's expose of Project HAARP, the Pentagon's plan to "burn holes" in the
ionosphere (one of the "Ten Best Censored Stories of 1994"), recently generated 
documentary on the Canadian Broadcast Corporation's "Undercurrents" and two
reports on Fox Network's "Sightings."<P>

In other media news, UTNE Reader saluted <A HREF="../brower/browerbr.html">David Brower</A> as one of 1996's leading
"Visionaries" in its March issue, and Mother Jones ran a long feature on the
shrimp-saving efforts of <A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">STRP</A> and the 
<A HREF="../map/map.html">Mangrove Action Project</A>, headed by Alfredo
Quarto.

<A NAME="As"><H2>As Goes Maine...</H2>

 The director of EII's <B>Northern Forest Forum</B>, Jamie Sayen, has
joined forces with the Ban Clearcutting Campaign (BCC) in Maine to support a
referendum on November's statewide ballot that would prohibit clearcutting. "This
is not just a local issue," says BCC director Jonathan Carter. "It not only sets
a national precedent for eliminating clearcutting, but it puts industry on notice
that the citizens of Maine and the rest of the nation will not tolerate the
wanton destruction of our natural heritage in the name of huge corporate
profits."<P>

Because the pro-forest referendum has wide popular support, pro-industry forces
have launched a campaign of distortion and misinformation to defeat it.
Grass-roots support is crucial -- whether you live in Maine or not. To get
involved, contact: BCC, Box 2218, Augusta, ME 04438; (207) 623-7140.

<A NAME="Carl"><H2>Carl Anthony Goes to Harvard</H2>

 Earth Island president and Urban Habitat Program
director <A HREF="../eins/carls_msg.html">Carl Anthony</A> is a resident  fellow at Harvard University's Institute of
Politics at the John F. Kennedy School of Government. Carl will spend the spring
leading a non-credit study group focused on environmental justice issues.

<A NAME="On"><H2>On the Web</H2>

 EII's presence on the worldwide web
continues to grow with more than 380 pages of on-line publishing (including
issues of the 
<A HREF="journal.html">Journal</A>; 
Race, Poverty & the Environment; 
<A HREF="../baikal/baikal.html">Baikal Currents</A>; 
<A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">STRP</A> Newsletter and 
<A HREF="../immp/keiko.html">IMMP</A>'s Ocean Alert). In addition to these full-text publications,
EII's web site offers  simple-to-use, advanced 
<A HREF="/scripts/wwwwais/config=ei">search capabilities</A> (to find all
our information on dolphins, for example, just type the word "dolphins.") EII's
web page is registering 27,000 "hits" each month.

<A NAME="Bon"><H2>Bon Voyage</H2>

 Managing editor Justin Lowe, an eight-year veteran of <B>Earth Island
Journal</B>, has pulled up stakes and set off on a six-month tour of Asia. Assistant
editor John Sterling has accepted a new position reviewing grant proposals for
Patago-nia, the outdoor clothing manufacturer. EII would like to extend warm
thanks to both Justin and John for their support over the years and welcome
Journal intern <B>Charmaine Oakley</B> who has come on-board as the Journal's new
assistant editor.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1996, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


<A HREF="journal.html"><IMG SRC="jhome.gif"></A><P>
