<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Bio-Watch</TITLE>

<H1>Bio-Watch</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Rarest">Rarest US Tree Is Dying</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#El">El Nino and Strandings</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Matter">A Matter of Taste</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Windsor">Windsor, Spare That Tree</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Born">Born to Be Different?</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#In">In Search of Mr. Chubby Toes</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Elephant">Elephant ER</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Killer">Killer Whale Killer</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Japan">Japan to Kill More Whales</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-12.html#Bacteria">Bacteria Go Wild</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="Rarest"><H2>Rarest US Tree Is Dying</H2>

USA -- The Florida torreya, the rarest tree in North America, grows exclusively
along a short span of river flowing between Florida and Georgia. Nicknamed the
"stinking yew," after its foul-smelling needles, and closely related to the
taxol-yielding Pacific yew, the newsworthy torreya's population has been
falling since the 1950s. Plant biologists at Cornell University report that a
usually benign fungus called <I>Pestalotiopsis microspora</I> is ravaging the rare
trees, and the consequent die-off threatens the torreya with extinction.
Researchers are baffled as to the cause.

<A NAME="El"><H2>El Nino and Strandings</H2>

USA -- University of San Diego student Wendy Dunlap-Harding reviewed National
Marine Fisheries Service (NMFS) data on California coast marine mammal
strandings from 1982 to 1992 and concluded that El Nino -- the oceanic weather
change -- drove sea lions ashore. In an average year, NMFS recorded fewer than
750 stranded sea lions, but when the warm waters of El Nino began to push
northward, the average number of stranded sea lions soared to 1750.
Dunlap-Harding theorized that warm water displaces supplies of cold-water fish
that marine mammals feed upon and forces the beaching-behavior on starving sea
lions.

<A NAME="Matter"><H2>A Matter of Taste</H2>

UK -- Many British environmentalists scorn sycamore trees as invasive pests
imported from the European mainland. But scientists at London's Roehampton
Institute have found a British subject that absolutely loves the sycamore --
the lowly dormouse. Dormice ordinarily are thought to be berry, nut and pollen
connoisseurs, but researchers discovered that this food vanishes by June,
leaving the dormice to survive on a diet of caterpillars, beetles and aphids.
And the best place to dine on insects? The sycamore tree.

<A NAME="Windsor"><H2>Windsor, Spare That Tree</H2>

UK -- Hundreds of trees along Queen Anne's Ride in Queen Elizabeth's Windsor
Great Park were saved from the ax last year, when scores of citizens, shocked
by the prospect of their destruction, trespassed onto royal land and took up
residence in the treetops. The royal ranger had intended to clearcut a one-mile
stretch of "untidy" trees -- some of them 275 years old -- and substitute a
neat row of 1000 saplings. HRH the Duke of Edinburgh bowed to the public outcry
and promised to protect the trees in the interests of biological diversity and
arboreal seniority.

<A NAME="Born"><H2>Born to Be Different?</H2>

USA -- In a study of 700 children, Harvard psychology professor Jerome Kagen
found that 20 percent of babies responded with fear when presented with new
stimuli (lights, bells, a new face). Two-thirds of these infants grew up to
become shy, right-brain-dominant children. Another 35 percent of the babies
welcomed new experiences and, by the age of three, most had become extroverted
left-brain-dominant "chatterboxes." If true, the difference between a happy,
novelty-seeking child and a wary, change-fearing child (and, perhaps, liberally
inclined vs. conservative-minded adults) may simply be the result of an
immutable biological imprint.

<A NAME="In"><H2>In Search of Mr. Chubby Toes</H2>

Indonesia -- While the abominable snowman, Sasquatch and Yeti, still elude
scientists, researchers claim to be closing in on <B>orang pendek</B>, the cagey
bipedal primate of West Sumatra. <B>BBC Wildlife</B> has published photos depicting
plaster casts of the pendek's unique footprints. Unlike any other primate, the
pendek's large toe is stepped-back, angling out sharply from a curved heel. The
pendek stands at least 1.2 meters (four feet) tall and sports a coat of short
buff-to-black body hair. Researchers at the Kerinei Seblat National Park have
identified several distinct footprints belonging to individuals they have named
"Marathon Man," "Mr. Burglar," "Newcomer" and "Chubby Toes."

<A NAME="Elephant"><H2>Elephant ER</H2>

Thailand -- The Western mindset has had a deadly impact on Thailand's
elephants. "For hundreds of years, men treated elephants as friends. Now that
relationship has been broken," veterinarian Preecha Puangkam told the
Associated Press. "People treat them like a car -- if it breaks down, they get
rid of it and get a new one." Puangkam, who runs an "elephant hospital" in
Lampang, reports treating growing numbers of elephants suffering from beatings,
festering wounds and overwork. At the turn of the century, 100,000 domesticated
elephants lumbered through Thailand's cities and villages, while hundreds of
thousands roamed free. Today there are fewer than 5000 domesticated elephants
and only 2000 in the wild. Friends of the Elephant reports that the domestic
population is sinking at a rate of 2-5 percent annually. Puangkam's elephant
hospital survives, in part, from donations sent by the producers of the 1995
Disney film, <B>Operation Dumbo Drop</B>.

<A NAME="Killer"><H2>Killer Whale Killer</H2>

USA -- A pod of killer whales caught in the 1989 <B>Exxon Valdez</B> oil spill is
dying a slow death. Before the Chevron tanker leaked 11 million gallons into
Prince William Sound, the pod numbered 36 whales. Today the pod has dwindled to
22. The deaths of females and juveniles has destroyed the pod's complex social
structure and surviving members now swim alone. Since the spill, the number of
harbor seals, the orcas' prey species, has fallen six percent each year.

<A NAME="Japan"><H2>Japan to Kill More Whales</H2>

Japan -- In 1994, when the International Whaling Commission created an
eight-million-square-mile whale sanctuary in the waters surrounding Antarctica,
Japan was the only IWC member to vote against the reserve. This February, Japan
ordered its whaling fleet to enter the sanctuary and slaughter 360-to-440 minke
whales -- a 33 percent increase over Japan's 1995 whale kill. The White House
has decided not to apply trade sanctions against Japan.

<A NAME="Bacteria"><H2>Bacteria Go Wild</H2>

The Netherlands -- Scientific experts assumed that the release of genetically
engineered biological pesticides was fairly safe -- believing that naturally
occurring biological pesticides were not capable of long-term survival in the
wild. Dutch studies now reveal that the popular biological pesticide <I>Bacillus
thuringiensis</I> (Bt) does not die within a few days, but can remain active a year
or more. Bt spores were found to thrive in both dead and living insects. "There
are no previous examples of the spores reproducing in living organisms," Dutch
researchers marveled. Because Bt sometimes resembles Bacillus cereus (a
bacteria that can cause diarrhoea) and Bacillus anthracis (which can cause
anthrax), Dutch authorities are calling for mandatory DNA testing before the
release of biological pesticides.


