<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: AFBF Backs Hemp, Plant Kenaf and Help Us Plant Trees!</TITLE>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-13.html#National">National Farm Bureau Backs Hemp</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-13.html#Read">I Read the News Today, Oh Boy</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-13.html#Plant">Plant Kenaf and Help Us Plant Trees!</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="National"><H1>National Farm Bureau Backs Hemp</H1>

Via EcoNet -- The American Farm Bureau Federation (AFBF), the largest farming
organization in the US, with 4.6 million members, unanimously passed a
resolution at its 77th annual convention in Reno, Nevada on January 10, that
reads: "We recommend that the American Farm Bureau Federation encourage
research into the viability and economic potential of industrial hemp
production in the US. We further recommend that such research include planting
test plots in the US using modern agricultural techniques."<P>

The AFBF's endorsement coincided with the introduction of the Industrial Hemp
Production Act in the Colorado state legislature. The Hemp Production Act (Bill
96-67), sponsored by Senator Lloyd Casey (D-Northglenn), would allow regulated
cultivation of industrial (low-THC) hemp by Colorado farmers. The bill permits
planting no more than 40 acres of industrial hemp in Colorado in 1996 for
agricultural, commercial and scientific research. The bill would allow hemp
production to increase in subsequent years.<P>

Bob Winter, president of the Weld County Farm Bureau, is working with Colorado
State University to develop a research plan for producing the first hemp crop
in Colorado. International Paper, Masonite and Inland Container Corporation
have expressed interested in Colorado hemp as an alternative fiber source. Some
environmental groups view hemp as a viable alternative to trees for paper
manufacture.<P>

Industrial hemp production also has been endorsed by the Colorado Farm Bureau,
the Kentucky Farm Bureau and the Wisconsin Agribusiness Council.<P>

"The support of the American Farm Bureau Federation adds great credibility to
the industrial hemp movement. Hopefully, our state legislators will see the
economic potential of industrial hemp... and allow Colorado to become the first
state to produce hemp in the US in over 40 years," said Laura Kriho of the
Colorado Hemp Initiative Project [PO Box 729, Nederland, CO 80466; (303)
784-5632].

<HR>

<A NAME="Read"><H1>I Read the News Today, Oh Boy</H1>

In January, the cost of home delivery for San Francisco's two daily papers
jumped nine percent. Announcing the price increases, the <B>San Francisco Examiner</B>
and <B>Chronicle</B> jointly explained that "after salaries, newsprint is the largest
expense for American newspapers. [The papers] consume about 100,000 tons of
newsprint each year. Two years ago, a metric ton of newsprint cost $437. Today,
it costs $811 -- an increase of 85 percent." <B>San Francisco Chronicle</B> business
reporter Herb Greenberg explained the root cause of the rising costs: "Paper
producers are running out of virgin forests and, in the past half-dozen years,
a number of newsprint plants have shut down." Has the cost of your newspaper
gone up in the past year? If so, contact <A HREF="mailto:rtp@earthisland.org">Rethink Paper</A> at Earth Island
Institute for information about non-wood paper alternatives.

<HR>

<A NAME="Plant"><H1>Plant Kenaf and Help Us Plant Trees!</H1>

Celebrate Earth Day 1996 by planting  kenaf, a fast-growing, annual African
plant that can grow as high as 15 feet in five months. Earth Island Journal is
the only US magazine printed on  tree-free paper made from kenaf.<P>

The Journal provides seed packets, an eight-page Grower's Guide and background
information on kenaf for a minimum donation of $3. The donations are used by
the Journal's Green Pages Fund to plant trees throughout the world.<P>

To date, Green Pages donations have helped plant trees in Kenya, Haiti, Costa
Rica, Nicaragua, Mexico, Papua New Guinea and India.<P>

To order a Kenaf Seed Kit, send a check to "Green Pages Fund" c/o EIJ, 300
Broadway, Suite 28, San Francisco, CA 94133.<P>

