<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: The Global Marketplace</TITLE>

<H1>The Global Marketplace</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Free">Free Trade Gasses Clean Air</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Carrot">The Carrot and the Celery Stick</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Britannia">Britannia Waives the Rules</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Neem">Neem Tree Patent Blocked</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Computers">Computers Cause Urban Sprawl</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Merge">Merge, Merge, Merge</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Purge">Purge, Purge, Purge</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Welcome">Welcome to McPlanet</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Kassel">Kassel Burgers Bite Back</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Suit">The Suit Is on the Other Foot</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#Ronald">Ronald's Secret Agents</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#BBC">BBC Censors Vandana Shiva</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#McDonald">McDonald's is Scared Shirtless</A>
<LI><A HREF="s96-14.html#McSpotlight">McSpotlight Hits the Web</A>
</UL>

<A NAME="Free"><H2>Free Trade Gasses Clean Air</H2>

Geneva -- The World Trade Organization (WTO), successor to the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade (GATT), issued its first-ever ruling by a
dispute-settlement panel on January 18, finding that the US Clean Air Act
constituted a restraint to free trade. Oil companies in Venezuela and Brazil
had complained that US Clean Air Act regulations interfered with their ability
to sell their dirtier petroleum products on the US market. According to Trade
News, "The WTO panel said that, while the US had every right to set its own
environmental standards, it was in breach of fair trade rules by discriminating
against imports." Under the WTO ruling, the US must either lower its air
quality standards or face unspecified trade sanctions. US trade rep. Mickey
Kantor (a pro-Free-Trader who stubbornly insisted that such an anti-US ruling
would be unlikely), has vowed to appeal the ruling. (While he is at it, perhaps
Kantor could also lodge a WTO complaint against foreign fruit importers who
insist that US produce be treated with the soil fumigant methyl bromide.)

<A NAME="Carrot"><H2>The Carrot and the Celery Stick</H2>

USA -- During his 18 years in the Senate, Jim Sasser repeatedly voted against
granting China "most-favored-nation" trading status because of its poor human
rights record. Now US ambassador to China,  Jim Sasser pragmatically is placing
corporate need before human rights by  supporting trade with China. "When we
trade with China, we do more than sell them goods," Sasser argues. "Some of our
values and some of our customs and some of our culture goes with it." This,
Sasser says, is the best way to assure that China will "ultimately conform...
to our definition of human rights." (Among the culture-altering US goods that
Sasser is pushing in China -- cars and nuclear reactors.)

<A NAME="Britannia"><H2>Britannia Waives the Rules</H2>

UK -- Britain's reputation as a haven for political dissidents took a hit in
January when the government's Home Office ordered the deportation of Mohammed
Masari, a leading critic of the oil-rich Saudi Arabian monarchy. Explaining the
order to deport Masari to the Caribbean island of Dominica, Home Office
minister Ann Widdecombe said simply, "We have got enormous export
considerations." In December, the Saudi royal family threatened to halt new
contracts with UK firms unless Masari was expelled. Parliament member George
Galloway called Britain's capitulation "a sordid act of obeisance to the arms
dealers in Britain and the dictators in Riyadh." UK firms provide the Saudi
monarchs with $7.77 billion worth of arms.

<A NAME="Neem"><H2>Neem Tree Patent Blocked</H2>

India -- In 1993, the Research Foundation for Science, Technology and Natural
Resource Policy [New Delhi-110 016, India] launched a campaign against plans by
WR Grace, a US multinational, to acquire a patent on the neem, a tree with many
healing properties. The campaign collected over a million signatures of
individuals from all walks of life opposed to patenting the tree. The neem is a
cultural and religious symbol in India, and its use is part of every home's
daily routine. The US-based Foundation for Economic Trends has joined forces
with Indian campaigners to challenge WR Grace's neem patents in the US Patent
Office. In the closing days of 1995, India's hotly debated Patent Amendment
Bill failed to clear the Upper House of the Parliament. The bill's failure
means that Indian laws will not be changed to protect transnational
corporations. [Note: A Conference on Genetic Engineering in Food and
Agriculture, is scheduled for May 24-25 at Ft. Mason Center in San Francisco,
CA. For more information, call; (415) 522-0352]

<A NAME="Computers"><H2>Computers Cause Urban Sprawl</H2>

USA -- Last September, Republican budget-cutters bludgeoned the Congressional
Office of Technology Assessment (OTA) out of existence. During its 23-year
span, OTA research provided timely warnings about the downside of chemical,
industrial and medical technologies. The OTA's final report, "The Technological
Reshaping of Metropolitan America," issued a surprising warning that new
information technologies could torpedo urban economies and accelerate suburban
sprawl.<P>

Since employers now can use computers to export work to distant terminals, a
new "footloose economy" will arise, making metropolitan areas "larger, more
dispersed and less densely populated." The OTA's report claimed that the
"information highway" threatens to have the same impact on the core city that
the federal Interstate Highway System had in the 1950s -- it will subsidize
sprawl and encourage the middle-class to abandon the inner city.

<A NAME="Merge"><H2>Merge, Merge, Merge</H2>

USA -- The US set a record for corporate mergers in 1995 with 9008 business
"marriages" -- up nearly 400 percent over the previous year. The Associated
Press reports that the average deal topped $51 million. It was a great year for
US banks, as well. Citicorp earned $3.46 billion, Chemical Banking Corp. netted
$1.8 billion, Wells Fargo earned $1 billion and First Interstate Bancorp took
in $885.1 million. First Interstate might have done better but it wound up
being swallowed by Wells Fargo in a $11.6 billion hostile takeover. As part of
its assault on First Interstate, Wells Fargo placed a full page ad on January
17, claiming that it had "committed $45 billion to community reinvestment
lending over the next ten years, contingent upon a merger with First Interstate
Bank." (Just a friendly reminder, Wells Fargo.)

<A NAME="Purge"><H2>Purge, Purge, Purge</H2>

USA -- In 1995, worker  benefits and wages fell three percent  below 1994
levels, marking the smallest gain since the US began keeping records in 1982.
The Bureau of Labor Statistics reports that half of the  workforce is forced to
find a  new  job every four years. Workers lucky enough to find new  jobs take
an average 14 percent drop in wages. "Labor is not in a position to argue,"
observed Robert G. Dederick, a consultant for Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
Princeton economist Henry Farber found that more men (15 percent) lost jobs
during the 1991-93 economic recovery than during the 1981-83 recession. While
slack work is the main cause of job loss during a recession, the new tide of
unemployment results from "abolished positions," the  result of corporate
"restructuring" and "down-sizing" required by  the "globalized economy." In
January, US companies fired 97,379 employees, one of the largest monthly
layoffs in history. Challenger, Gray & Christmas, an international outplacement
firm, predicts that "worse could be in store this year as more companies  merge
and slash redundant employees."

<A NAME="Welcome"><H2>Welcome to McPlanet</H2>

USA -- In 1995, a new McDonald's restaurant opened somewhere on Earth every 17
hours. Now McDonald's Corp. plans to double its global restaurant expansion to
eight restaurants per day over the next two years -- i.e., a new restaurant
every three hours. McDonald's wants to open 2500 to 3200 restaurants in 1996
and 1997. Between 1800 and 2200 will take traditional restaurant form --
approximately two-thirds of these will be built outside the US. The remaining
700 to 1000 will comprise satellite restaurants in airports, retail stores and
gas stations (40 percent to be built abroad). McDonald's currently operates
more than 18,000 restaurants in 89 countries.

<A NAME="Kassel"><H2>Kassel Burgers Bite Back</H2>

Germany -- A German court has ruled that McDonald's must pay an anti-rubbish
tax on disposable dishes, cans and packaging.  The fast-food giant challenged
the tax, first levied two years ago in the city of Kassel, on the grounds that
it would swallow up to 80 percent of McDonald's profits. Unmoved by the plea,
the court upheld the tax, noting that each McDonald's generates 60 tons of
plastic rubbish a year.  The Australian publication <B>New Vegetarian</B> reports that
McDonald's already owes the city 800,000 Deutschmarks in back taxes.

<A NAME="Suit"><H2>The Suit Is on the Other Foot</H2>

South Africa -- Britain's Sky News reports that when McDonald's attempted to
open two new restaurants in South Africa, it ran into an unusual (for
McDonald's) obstacle -- a trademark lawsuit. During the apartheid years, the
corporation allowed its South Africa trademark to lapse. Two local entrepeneurs
snapped it up and opened their own fast food restaurant called McDonald's --
complete with golden arches. A South African supreme court judge has ruled that
McDonald's failed to re-register its trademark properly and had, therefore,
forfeited the right to use it. According to <B>The Financial Times</B>, Ron McDonald
has found a ready ally in the person of US commerce secretary Ron Brown, who
reminded South African officials that more than 230 US companies have invested
in South Africa and warned that future investments could be jeopardized unless
the trademark issue was resolved.

<A NAME="Ronald"><H2>Ronald's Secret Agents</H2>

UK -- In 1995, the McLibel Trial, a mammoth legal battle between the $26
billion a year McDonald's Corporation and two unemployed London activists,
became the longest civil case in British history. McDonald's filed suit over a
leaflet entitled "What's Wrong With McDonald's?"<P>

According to the British magazine <B>Private Eye</B>, McDonald's recruited seven
"agents" to infiltrate London Greenpeace (not affiliated with the well-known
environmental group) in hopes of thwarting the anti-McDonald's leaflet
campaign.<P>

At its peak, the activist group claimed only ten members. The spys, to disguise
their identity, threw themselves  into the anti-McDonald's campaign, even
agreeing to hand out the leaflets that became the subject of the libel
complaint. Private Eye opines that this may be the first case in libel history
where a company has sued over material  distributed by its own agents.

<A NAME="BBC"><H2>BBC Censors Vandana Shiva</H2>

UK (Via EcoNet)  -- In January, BBC Radio 4 invited Vandana Shiva, director of
The Research Foundation for Science and Ecology, to discuss the effects of
multinational corporations on India's farmers, environment and culture.<P>

The night before the program was to air, BBC lawyers, fearing libel suits,
informed Shiva that they would not allow her to speak -- even after she offered
not to mention any companies by name.<P>

"This is an illustration of the insidious nature of Britain's libel laws,"
claimed the McLibel Support Campaign. "Large organizations, like McDonald's,
take advantage of this by threatening to sue at every opportunity."

<A NAME="McDonald"><H2>McDonald's is Scared Shirtless</H2>

USA -- Last October, McDonald's demanded that Vegan Action (VA), a national
nonprofit educational organization, "immediately cease manufacturing and sale"
of their popular McVegan T-Shirt design, citing trademark infringement law.
McDonald's abruptly decided to withdraw its threats after Vegan Action went
public with news of the impending suit. One of the main issues stressed by VA
is that McDonald's uses its logo, its mascot Ronald McDonald and its cast of
cartoon characters to market a high-fat, junk-food diet directly to young
children. McDonald's clearly does not want to see a serious public debate on
these important issues.<P>

During a victory party held at Smart Alec's Healthy Fast Food Restaurant, in
Berkeley, California, VA's mascot, Reggie McVeggie, handed out complimentary
veggie burgers.<P>

VA Coordinator Leor Jacobi expressed relief that, "Now that this nonsense from
McDonald's is over, we can continue with our  vital  mission,  enhancing public
awareness about the many benefits of a vegan diet. This is a victory for
everyone concerned with the public's health."<P>

<H3>What You Can Do</H3>

Vegan Action can provide props, literature, signs, stickers
and veggie burgers to pass out at your local McDonald's franchise. VA can
arrange a meeting between Ronald and Reggie McVeggie. Contribute $35 or more to
 VA's campaign and receive a McVegan T-shirt and a campaign packet. Contact
Vegan Action, PO Box 4353, Berkeley, CA 94704; (510) 654-6297;
http://www.vegan.org/; email: <A HREF="mailto:leor@vegan.org">leor@vegan.org</A>.<P>

For information on the McLibel Trial, contact US McLibel Support Campaign, PO
Box 62, Craftsbury, VT 05826-0062; http://www.interlog.com/eye/Misc/McLibel/; 
dbriars@world.std.com.

<A NAME="McSpotlight"><H2>McSpotlight Hits the Web</H2>

UK -- On February 16, McLibel defendants Dave Morris and Helen Steel launched
the McSpotlight World Wide Web site [http://www.mcspotlight.org/] from the
street in front of McDonald's London office, using a cellular phone/modem
connected to the Internet.<P>

McSpotlight, the most comprehensive database on a multinational corporation
ever assembled, was compiled by a huge team of volunteers working in 14
different countries.<P>

McSpotlight's founders claim that the web-site will drive "the final nail
in[to] the coffin of McDonald's attempts to suppress criticism. They cannot
hide the truth any more."<P>

With the power of the Internet, advertising budgets no longer are the
restraining factors dictating how far a message can be heard. McSpotlight
potentially could reach 70 million people across the globe with everything that
McDonald's doesn't want the public to know.


<HR>

