<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: US-Canada "Free-Trade Freeway"</TITLE>

<H1>US-Canada "Free-Trade Freeway"</H1>
<H2>by Randy Ghent/APM</H2>

USA -- On November 20, 1995, a consortium of highway developers led by
Washington, DC-based Transportation Industries International (TII) unveiled its
plan to build a massive 370-mile, four-lane, heavy-freight toll road from
Winni-peg, Manitoba to Duluth, Minnesota.<P>

The $1.3 billion project proposes the first truck-only route in North America.
The route would permit Canadian grain now shipped to Thunder Bay, Ontario to
cross the border into Duluth.<P>

James Ball, president of TII, called the project "an innovation that could very
easily spread continent-wide." He plans to propose similar projects elsewhere.<P>

The Alliance for a Paving Moratorium   has launched a campaign to stop the toll
road, which APM calls "an environmental, health and safety nightmare."<P>

The toll road would displace wetlands, farms and local landowners. Under the
banner of "eminent domain," developers could seize any property in the toll
road's path after offering "just compensation." By creating a wildlife
migration barrier, the road would threaten the integrity of the "Minnesota
Biosphere Recovery Strategy" formulated by conservation biologists.<P>

The road would increase safety hazards by doubling the weight limit on US
interstates and allowing quadruple-trailer trucks. Project backers also have
declared: "Our goal is never to allow the highway to be closed by inclement
weather."<P>

According to Citizens for Reliable and Safe Highways, a US automobile-driver
advocacy group, "crash rates increase when the weight of the truck increases.
Trucks that weigh 65,000 pounds are involved in more than twice as many fatal
crashes as trucks weighing 35,000 to 50,000 pounds. Very long trucks pose a
hazard, because they cannot turn safely and are liable to incur more severe
crashes." In 1990, the fatality rate of combination trucks
per-billion-ton-miles was nearly four times greater than that of freight
railroads.<P>

Use of the new highway, instead of the current railroad system, would increase
petroleum dependence and air pollution. Oak Ridge National Laboratory research
shows that trucks consume about eight times more energy than trains. Compared
to freight trains, trucks emit three times the nitrogen oxide and carbon
monoxide, and ten times the volatile organic compounds and diesel particulates
per-billion-ton-miles. Because Canada has been cutting its rail subsidies,
highway developers see the toll road as an opportunity to further undermine
rail's share of the grain-shipping market.<P>

"Developers cannot remedy the scheme's disastrous social and environmental
effects, so we all suffer as they get a fossil-fueled free lunch," said APM
founder Jan Lundberg.<P>

Expenditures to defend US oil supplies cost taxpayers $15 billion per year, or
$23.50 per barrel, Lundberg explained. Similarly, the US-Canada toll road would
be impossible without $690 million in Minnesota state and US federal loans,
available with five percent interest and delayed-debt servicing.<P>

In addition to forging ties with citizens' groups in communities along the
proposed route, the APM has sent letters to more than 200 Minnesota officials
citing the project's risks and requesting local vetoes. Under Minnesota law,
each city and county along the route has veto power over the project.<P>

"We should invest in rail for the long term, instead of wasting money and
increasingly scarce petroleum on destructive modes of shipping," Lundberg said.
"It's foolish to fund and build new roads with government assistance when we
can't even afford to maintain the roads we've got."<P>

From Auto-Free Times, available from APM, PO Box 4796, Arcata, CA 95518; (707)
826-7775 (memberships: $30).


<HR>

