<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: US Fast-Food Giants Rock India</TITLE>

<H1>US Fast-Food Giants Rock India</H1>

India (Via EcoNet) -- US-based McDonald's plans to open several stores in
Bombay and Delhi this spring. Unable to promote beef burgers in a country that
reveres cows, McDonald's instead will sell mutton burgers. The sheep meat will
come from Al Kabeer abattoir near Hyderabad, India. Al Kabeer, Asia's largest
meat-packer, kills about 5000 animals per day.<P>

US-owned Kentucky Fried Chicken (KFC is, in turn, owned by PepsiCo) hopes to
invest $40 million to open a chain of its restaurants across India. Last year,
when KFC opened its first outlet in a Delhi suburb,  a coalition of farmers,
vegetarians and environmentalists immediately besieged the restaurant.<P>

Local officials closed a KFC shop in Bangalore after excessive levels of
monosodium glutamate were found in KFC chicken. In response, the New Delhi
government announced that national health standards would be rewritten to allow
higher amounts of MSG in Indian food.<P>

On January 30, more than 100 irate farmers stormed the reopened Bangalore
restaurant, smashed windows and demanded that KFC leave India. The protesters,
from the ten-million-member Karna-taka Rajya Ryotha Sangha (KRRS) Indian
farmers' union, contend that foreign fast-food chains will degrade India's
culture, agriculture and environment.<P>

Scores of farmers were jailed and charged with looting, despite the testimony
of an anonymous KFC employee, who reported that no equipment was damaged,
nobody was injured and no money was stolen.<P>

On February 3, KRRS' 62-year-old founder, Prof. MD Nanjundaswamy, was jailed,
denied bail and charged with looting, attempted murder and other offenses,
although he was not even present during the farmers' protest.<P>

The farmers maintain that multinational entry into the food sector threatens
the livelihoods of more than 70 percent of the Indian population and is the
first step toward destruction of India's food security. One of the worst
aspects of fast-food chains, KRRS claimed, is KFC's introduction of large-scale
factory-farming of chickens.<P>

KFC  plans to open six outlets in Delhi by this year. However, the company's
ride will not be easy. In fact, India could be the first place where the
expansion of multinational fast-food chains is halted.<P>

-- McLibel Support Campaign (UK); Consumers Association of Penang (Malaysia)<P>

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

Send letters to Prime Minister Sh. Narasimha Rao (fax
+91-11-301 9817) and messages of support to Prof. Nanjundaswamy (fax +91-80-330
3271).

