<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: "Bangladesh Effect" Hits US</TITLE>

<H1>"Bangladesh Effect" Hits US</H1>

Last September, the prestigious Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change
concluded that Earth's weather is changing and that human activities -- most
prominently the burning of fossil fuels and the cutting of forests -- are the
cause. According to the <B>New York Times</B>, climate change will bring "widespread
economic, social and environmental dislocation...."<P>

In recent years, the world's cities have been pummeled by violent snowstorms,
floodwaters, tornadoes and  blistering temperatures. Summer heat killed 300 in
Chicago; winter snows from Vermont to Georgia buried millions. The number of
Atlantic hurricanes doubled in the last year; tornadoes have increased
five-fold since the 1950s.<P>

On January 22, <B>Newsweek</B> boldly linked the winter's massive snowstorms to
"catastrophic global warming" and indicated that the future promised "more
floods, worse hurricanes, longer droughts and, yes, heat waves."<P>

1995 was the year that the "Bangladesh Effect" hit the US. As torrential rains
pounded the continent, mountainsides stripped of forest cover began to move. In
January, British Colom-bia's logging-ravaged Clayoquot Sound suffered 260
landslides during a single four-day storm.<P>

President Clinton rushed $65 million in flood aid to Oregon, Washington and
Idaho. By February of 1995, Clinton had issued only one weather-related
disaster declaration; by the second month of 1996, Clinton had issued 27.<P>


For the first time in history, Portland's water supply  became undrinkable as
mud spilled into the Bull Run watershed off hills that have lost a third of
their forests to logging in the last 33 years.<P>

Winter mudslides brought together forest activists and politicians, who
demanded an end to the "timber salvage" rider. The timber industry has used
"salvage" logging as a pretext to cut both dead and living trees in US forests.
Even President Clinton now admits that signing the bill was a mistake.<P>

A Global Action Day on climate change is set for May 15. [Contact: Climate
Campaign Information Office, Reforesting Scotland, PO Box 12218, South
Queensferry EH30, 9ZA, Edinburgh, Scotland; fax: +44 131 558-1550;
<A HREF="mailto:reforscot@gn.apc.org">reforscot@gn.apc.org</A>; http://www.scotweb.co.uk/reforscot/climate.]        -- GS

<HR>

