<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Ecologists Buy Ecosystems</TITLE>

<H1>Ecologists Buy Ecosystems</H1>

<H2> by Brian Vincent, NWEA</H2>

Via EcoNet -- Conservationists are employing a surprising new tactic to keep
cattle off sensitive lands and timber-cutters out of forests -- outbidding
ranchers and loggers for federal grazing permits and timber sales on public
bids.<P>

Last October, the Northwest Ecosystem Alliance [NWEA, PO Box 2813, Bellingham,
Washington 98227; (360) 671-9950;  <A HREF="mailto:bvincent-@pacificrim.net">bvincent-@pacificrim.net</A>] submitted a sealed
contract bid for the Thunder Salvage timber sale offered in Washington state's
Oka-nogan National Forest. NWEA offered $4.25 per board foot of timber -- one
penny higher than the minimum acceptable bid of $4.24 -- for the right to keep
the trees standing. The US Forest Service rejected the bid, claiming that it
had been sent to the wrong address. The <B>Omak-Okanogan County Chronicle</B> reported
that the USFS later admitted that it would have had a "very difficult time
awarding them [NWEA] the sale."<P>

The Thunder Salvage sale would involve constructing new roads and  logging 3.5
million board feet of timber from one of the largest undeveloped areas
remaining in Washington state. USFS studies state that logging could jeopardize
imperiled salmon runs and rare species, such as lynx. But conservationists
cannot challenge the project on environmental grounds, because of the "logging
without laws" rider, passed last August.<P>

Like most USFS timber sales, Thunder Mountain will cost the government far more
than it will generate in revenues. Planning alone has already cost the USFS
well over $200,000, whereas the minimum bid will gross the government only
$15,000 -- less than a tenth of its costs -- or about 30 cents per tree.<P>

"The Forest Service is managing our forest like a soup kitchen for timber
companies, so we've come to take our place in line," said Mitch Friedman, NWEA
Executive Director. "The $15,000 we're offering is a great deal for the public,
since we promise not to cut the trees or ask for additional federal hand-outs
for road construction and replanting."<P>

According to NWEA ecologist Evan Frost, "Those trees are worth far more
standing -- to protect wildlife, soils, water quality and fisheries -- than
what the Forest Service is asking to cut them down. The least the Forest
Service can do is sell us the timber and prevent the environmental damage that
would come with salvage logging."<P>

On December 20, at an auction held at Okanogan National Forest headquarters,
NWEA was declared the highest bidder for contract rights to the Thunder Salvage
timber sale. This marked the first time in the history of the National Forest
system that a party apparently has won rights to a timber sale with no intent
to cut the trees.<P>

NWEA's winning bid of $8.25 per thousand board feet beat out three competing
timber companies and actually doubled the government's profit to about 60 cents
per tree.<P>

"It was like a post-Christmas sale at Walmart, with public forests at bargain
prices," said NWEA's Friedman. "The Forest Service is playing Santa to the
timber industry, but Grinch to taxpayers. You can't blame us for shopping a
bargain -- we, at least, will pay our money, but leave the trees and wildlife
habitat intact."<P>

Meanwhile, in New Mexico, Forest Guardians and the Southwest Environmental
Center successfully bid on 2078 acres of state trust lands in the Rio Embudo
region in 1995. The two environmental groups have also gone after leases
traditionally held by ranchers on lands administered by New Mexico's Land
Office. These lands represent some of the most imperiled ecosystems in the
southwest. Transferring the management of thousands of acres of overgrazed land
to environmental groups would allow for the restoration of habitat degraded by
years of livestock-grazing.<P>

"We believe removing cattle is the only way to restore these once-rich
ecosystems," stated Forest Guardian's John Horning. In February, Horning
informed the <B>Journal</B> that Forest Guardians [612 Old Santa Fe Trail, Suite B,
Santa Fe, NM 87501; (505) 988-9126; <A HREF="mailto:fguardians@igc.apc.org">fguardians@igc.apc.org</A>] had won the rights
to four new parcels but "rancher pressure" had blocked nine other conservation
bids. "Cowboy socialism still reigns supreme in the Old West," Horning
declared. But insurgent eco-capitalism is starting to turn the tables.<P>         


<HR>

