<TITLE>Spring 96 Journal: Holy Humanure! by Sara Chamberlain</TITLE>

<H1>Holy Humanure!</H1>

<H2>by Sara Chamberlain</H2>

Joseph Jenkins describes Americans as "phecophobes" -- people afraid of their
own excrement. Jenkins, the author of <B>The Humanure Handbook</B> [PO Box 607, Grove
City, PA 16127], argues that flushing "humanure" (feces and urine) down the
toilet not only wastes an "essential and critical agricultural resource," but
also needlessly pollutes the environment. Jen-kins, who is privy to a great
deal of practical experience, notes that humanure, properly composted, is an
excellent, free source of soil-enriching nitrogen, potassium and phosphorous
for home fertilizer use.<P>

With each flush of the toilet, Americans waste five-to-six gallons of drinking
water -- five billion gallons a day. Every year, Americans flush 1.4 billion
pounds of nitrogen, 456 million pounds of potassium and 194 million pounds of
phosphorous into septic tanks and sewer pipes. Each year, wastewater treatment
in the US employs 1.2 billion pounds of chlorine -- a known human carcinogen
and fish mutagen.<P>

If Americans composted humanure instead of dumping it into drinking water,
pollution could be curbed, water saved and soil fertility improved. Jenkins
cautions, however, that "raw humanure carries with it a significant danger in
the form of... pathogens," such as intestinal parasites, harmful bacteria and
viruses. Fortunately, a composting process that employs heat-producing
microorganisms to digest organic materials can raise temperatures significantly
above that of the human body and destroy the pathogens.<P>

The <B>Humanure Handbook</B> clearly explains, in a breezy, amusing and
well-illustrated format,
everything- you- need- to- know- to- bring- the- out-house- in-house. The Jenkins family
has been composting its wastes since 1971 -- collecting humanure in a
five-gallon bucket under a toilet seat in the bathroom and covering it with
sawdust to eliminate odors. Every couple of days, they add a fresh bucket of
humanure to their compost pile and cover it with leaves or straw. The compost
rapidly produces a fine, dark, disease-free humus to fertilize the vegetable
garden.<P>

The "moldering method," another composting technique, involves the slow, cool
decomposition of excrement in a sealed receptacle. Excrement -- covered with
sawdust, leaves, dolomite (calcium) and ashes to eliminate odors -- is left
undisturbed for a number of years. Although this passive composting method
destroys most pathogens in about three months, it may not kill all of them,
which makes it inappropriate as fertilizer on food crops.<P>

Jenkins concludes that we must overcome our phecophobia and follow the example
of the Chinese, who cultivate "night soil" as an art form and "give prizes for
the best compost in a county, then have inter-county competitions," or the
Taiwanese, whose appreciation for humanure makes this natural fertilizer a hot
commodity on the black market.


<HR>

