<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: To Burn or Not to Burn?</TITLE>

<H2>To Burn or Not to Burn?<BR>
By Bill Stern</H2>

Some 30,000 tons of chemical weapons currently are stockpiled on eight US
military bases, with smaller amounts scattered in more than 30 states, and an
additional 45,000 tons stored in the former Soviet Union. Left over from every
international conflict from WW I to Vietnam, these weapons contain HD (mustard
gas), VX, GB-sarin, GD-soman and GA-tabun (all nerve agents). Under a joint
US-Russian agreement, these weapons (which are capable of killing the entire
human population many times over) are to be destroyed by the year 2004.<P>

Some of the aging stockpile of US chemical weapons -- rockets, bombs and
artillery projectiles -- have already shown signs of leakage. If chemicals
seeping from an M55 rocket were to reach a neighboring chamber containing
explosives, the interaction could trigger an explosion in a bunker containing
hundreds of rockets and set off a chain reaction.<P>

While both countries agree that these weapons should be destroyed as quickly as
possible, controversy surrounds the methods of disposal. The US Army destroyed
4000 tons of GB-sarin through chemical neutralization experiments between 1972
and 1976, but in the process produced a greater tonnage of toxic chemical salts
containing traces of the nerve agent. This line of research has been abandoned.<P>

In 1979, the Army built a pilot incineration plant at Tooele, Utah. Despite
inconclusive results, the Army chose incineration as the primary means of
carrying out its Chemical Stockpile Disposal Program.<P>

Since 1982, the incineration program has been plagued with problems, not the
least of which has been the growth of cost estimates from $1.7 billion in 1985
to more than $11 billion in 1995. The first full-scale incineration program,
conducted at Johnston Atoll in the Pacific, experienced extensive technical
problems, including parts failures, a fire, an explosion and nerve gas
releases.<P>

Despite these problems, the Army continues to assure Congress that incineration
is safe and effective, and has built a second large incinerator in Tooele. This
facility has yet to begin operation, due largely to the whistleblowing of its
chief of safety, Steve Jones, who compiled a list of 119 specific safety
problems. As Jones complained to <B>The New York Times</B>, "It's just an unsafe
design."<P>

Nonetheless, the Army has received $134 million to start building a chemical
weapons incinerator at the Anniston Army Depot in Alabama and $13 million for
incinerator construction design at Umatilla, Oregon and Pine Bluff, Arkansas.
Lawsuits and permit acquisition likely will delay construction.<P>

Communities near incineration facilities increasingly have banded together to
protest predicted releases of dioxins, furans and unburned agents. The Army has
no information on the effects of the long-term release of trace amounts of
nerve gas on human populations. Locals also fear that once the weapons are
gone, the Army will ignore its promise to dismantle the incinerators and
instead bring in other toxic wastes to burn.<P>

Fortunately, research into disposal alternatives has advanced. In 1991,
Greenpeace produced a report citing 28 disposal methods that promised to be
cheaper and safer than incineration. Lobbying by the Chemical Weapons Working
Group convinced Congress and the Army to consider alternatives to incineration.
In 1995, research at the Army's Aberdeen Proving Ground revealed that the
addition of near-boiling water and sewer sludge induced microbial activity that
completely broke down the mustard gas. Now the Army is considering building a
pilot plant that uses this technique. Researchers also found that simply adding
room-temperature water to VX and allowing it to sit for 50 days resulted in
near-complete breakdown, producing only non-lethal byproducts.<P>

Activists also are urging the Army to adopt the technique of weapons
"recom-position." This process minimizes the danger of explosions by separating
the agents from their aging containers and adding water or other catalysts to
begin their breakdown. The stabilized chemicals are then placed in new
containers. Recompo-sition renders the chemicals useless as weapons while
allowing more time for the research and testing of alternative disposal
methods. Recomposition is relatively inexpensive and is technically much
simpler than incineration, and thus has less potential for human error and
mechanical failure -- unlike incineration technology, which rivals nuclear
energy in its complexity and potential for failure.<P>

Russia has also built an incinerator, but public protests prevent it from
operating. While the country has disposed of some 120,000 tons of chemical
weapons, sometimes unsafely and haphazardly, it has no comprehensive disposal
plan. Russian scientists reportedly oppose importing US incineration
technology.<P>

A joint US-Russian scientific team is now exploring a number of simpler,
cheaper, safer and more effective treatment options, including low-temperature,
chemical and pressure-neutralization techniques. It remains to be seen if this
news will reach US and Russian decision-makers.

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

Write Congress requesting funding for the recomposition of chemical weapons,
continued research into neutralization and a neutralization pilot plant; ask
for a halt to the incinerator boondoggle. For more information, contact the
Chemical Weapons Working Group c/o PO Box 467, Berea, KY 40403; (606) 986-7565;
fax: -2695; E-mail: kefwilli@acs.eku.edu.

<HR>

