<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: The Rise of the Independent Nation of Hawai'i</TITLE>

<H2>The Rise of the Independent Nation of Hawai'i</H2>

<H3>January 15, 1893: A Date that will Live in Infamy</H3>

On January 15, 1873, two Americans, John Schofield and B. S. Alexander, arrived
in the sovereign republic of Hawai'i for a two-month "pleasure excursion."
Though their true mission was not revealed for 25 year, both men were Army
generals sent by US Secretary of War Belknap to map Pearl Harbor and evaluate
its military and commercial potential.<P>

The generals liked what they saw. US Minister to Hawai'i John Stevens
subsequently advised US Secretary of State Hamilton Fish that the US would be
able to "annex" the 132-island chain if "... the planters, merchants, and
foreigners... will induce the people to overthrow the [Hawaiian] government,
establish a republic, and then ask the United States for admittance into its
Union."<P>

The story of the secret US plot to overthrow the Hawai'ian monarchy is told in
Rich Budnick's richly illustrated book, <B>Stolen Kingdom: An American Conspiracy</B>
(Aloha Press, PO Box 4183, Honolulu, HI 96812). Seizing Hawai'i was a logical
extension of the racist doctrine of Manifest Destiny. As Republican Secretary
of State James Blaine saw it "The decline of the native Hawaiian element in the
presence of newer and sturdier growths must be accepted as an inevitable
fact...." Turning Hawai'i into a white-run empire would, in Blaine's view, assure
"replenishment of the vital forces of Hawai'i...."<P>

A group of powerful US, Canadian and European landholders organized a secret
"Hawai'ian League" to topple the reign-ing government and establish themselves
as Hawai'i's new rulers. As one of the league's sugar-barons put it, the new
government would assure "the rights of the white people...."<P>

In 1892, Stevens warned that Hawai'i had reached "the parting of the ways. She
must now take the road which leads to Asia, or the other, which outlets her in
America... and binds her to the care of American destiny." On January 4, 1893,
the <B>USS Boston</B> steamed off of Honolulu for ten days of "target practice" with
US Minister Stevens aboard, ostensibly enjoying a "vacation."<P>

On January 16, Stevens ordered US troops ashore "to protect American lives and
property." The next day, fearing loss of lives and the bombardment of the
Iolani Palace, Queen Lili'uokalani yielded to the US demand for abdication.
Stevens promptly appointed an 18-member provisional government -- 15 of them
Americans, none of them native Hawai'ians.<P>

In her statement of surrender, however, Lili'uokalani chose her words
carefully. She accepted her fate "under protest" and yielded her authority only
"until such time as the government of the United States shall, upon the facts
being presented to it, undo the actions of its representatives...."<P>

One hundred years later, Lili'uokalani's request for a fair hearing was
granted. In 1993, the US Congress held hearings and passed Public Law 103-150,
which acknowledged that "American and European sugar planters... and financiers
deposed the Hawai'ian monarchy" abetted by John Stevens who "caused armed naval
forces of the United States to invade the sovereign Hawai'ian nation...." PL
103-150 acknowledged that the invasion largely destroyed an Indigenous culture
characterized by "a highly organized, self-sufficient, subsistent social system
based on communal land tenure...."<P>

The law also offered an apology "on behalf of the people of the United States
for the overthrow of the Kingdom of Hawai'i on January 17, 1893" and directed
the president of the US to "acknowledge the ramifications of the overthrow."
Under international law, the ramifications are quite clear.<P>

In 1994, 400 Native Hawai'ians gathered at the Iolani Palace and cheered as
Iaukea Bright of the Ohana Council declared, "The <I>kanaka maoli</I> [Hawai'ian
people] proclaim our right of self-determination as a people in accordance
with... the United Nations Charter."<P>

The Hawai'ian sovereignty movement continues to grow, with hundreds of
sometimes competing native support groups calling for self-rule. One of
thesegroups is the Nation of Hawai'i [Executive Office, PO Box 80, Waimanalo,
O'ahu, Hawai'i] which, on January 16, 1995, ratified a new Hawai'ian
Constitution that contains a fundamental environmental component. The preamble
pledges to "maintain our spiritual relationship with nature and all our
surroundings, in universal harmony, for the rights of humanity, in peace, love
and understanding." The Constitution also enshrines a citizen's right to "a
healthy and sustainable environment" and calls for "a nuclear-free and
independent Pacific."<P>

Pu'uhonua Kanahele, the Nation of Hawai'i's appointed leader, realizes that
"the restoration of peace in paradise" is still a dream, but points proudly to
a September 8, 1994 White House letter in which President Clinton wrote: "I
share your interest in <I>malama pono</I> -- universal balance -- and I want to do what
is right with respect to native Hawai'ians...."<P>

The letter is addressed to "The Honorable Pu'uhonua Kanahele, Head of State of
Hawai'i."<BR>-- GS

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

For official documents from the Nation of Hawai'i, visit the World Wide Web
page: http://hawaii-nation.org/nation/ or address letters to 41-275 Nakini
Street. Waimanalo, O'ahu, Hawai'i 96795.<P>

<HR>

