<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Exxon vs. Wisconsin's Chippewa</TITLE>

<H1>Exxon vs. Wisconsin's Chippewa</H1>

<H2>By Rose Palmer</H2>

For the last 20 years, Exxon Minerals Company of Texas has dreamed of building
a zinc and copper mine in Wisconsin's North Woods, just a mile from the
Chippewa Mole Lake Reservation. From the beginning, the Sokaogon (pronounced
so-COG-in) Chippewa, Wisconsin's smallest Indian tribe, have resisted Exxon's
plans, arguing that the mine would poison their land and water.<P>

"We're the canary for the rest of the nation," said Chippewa Fred Ackley. "Our
people who eat the fish and deer meat are getting poisoned first. When will I
have to shut down my drinking well and say it's contaminated?"<P>

In 1975, the Chippewa's resistance to Exxon gave birth to the Watershed
Alliance to End Environmental Racism (WATER), a historic Indian-environmental
alliance. As University of Wisconsin professor Al Gedicks noted in his book <B>The
New Resource Wars</B>, this alliance brought a "new level of political organization
and resistance" to the native rights struggle that challenged "the unquestioned
assumptions of global industrialization and the inevitable disappearance of
native subsistence cultures."<P>

The Chippewa's opposition, combined with depressed mineral prices, derailed
plans for the mine until 1993, when Exxon and Rio Algom, a Canadian mining
company, formed the Crandon Mining Company and resumed vigorously pursuing the
project.<P>

On Exxon's side are business leaders and top state politicians led by
Republican Governor Tommy G. Thompson, who contends that the mine would help
the area's economy and would not pollute its streams and rivers.<P>

The Crandon/Mole Lake mine would be one of the largest in North America, with a
surface area of 866 acres and an underground shaft a mile long and a half-mile
deep. Approximately 30 acres of wetlands would be obliterated by the
construction of the mine, roads, a rail spur, mill complex and mining waste
treatment facility.<P>

The Chippewas fear that the mine will destroy the water and land that they
depend on for fishing, hunting and growing wild rice. Environmentalists share
their concern that mining operations could draw down groundwater for miles
around, lowering lake levels and reducing water flow to the streams in the
state and federally protected Wolf River watershed.<P>

According to tribal environmental planner John Griffin, the full impacts of the
proposed mine are difficult to predict since "a lot of data [are] missing.
Exxon could conceivably get a permit by meeting all the state's requirements
without knowing the true impact of the mine."

<H2>Sacred Rice, Troubled Waters</H2>

Wild rice is an integral part of Chippewa culture and economy and the tribe is
a leading producer of the grain. Wild rice, known as <I>Manomin</I> ("gift from the
creator"), forms an important part of the tribal diet and serves a sacred role
in Chippewa religion. If mining contaminates water supplies or depletes Mole
Lake, Chippewa tradition, as well as fish and wild rice, may be lost.<P>

Mine opponents charge that Crandon Mining's tests in the area have already
affected the water levels of Rice Lake. "The rice came up and died," said Fred
Ackley, Sokaogon Chippewa chair of the tribal mining-impact committee. "We had
no rice [last season] -- we were the only [tribe] without it. Loss of our rice
beds is critical to the community."<P>

Dave Blouin, a Madison-based Sierra Club activist, said that even if the cause
of the damage cannot be proved, "it does show how amazingly sensitive the wild
rice is. It doesn't take much to put it out of balance."<P>

Exxon admits that the amount of water flowing into the mine will be significant
-- more than 1000 gallons per minute by some estimates, totaling more than one
million gallons a day. After being treated to remove mine wastes, the water
will be piped 37 miles and dumped into the Wisconsin River. The Chippewa
estimate that 15 trillion tons of fresh water will be lost over the life of the
mine.<P>

An estimated 5500 tons of sulfide ore would be processed over 28 years. A giant
on-site pulverizing mill would process the ore into sand-like concentrates of
zinc and copper that would be shipped by rail for further refining and
smelting. The mine would also generate 60 millions tons of material, enough
waste, as Gedicks notes in <B>The New Resource</B> Wars, to build "12 Great Pyramids
of Egypt."<P>

To handle an estimated 44 million tons of toxic waste known as "tailings,"
Exxon has proposed creating a 340-acre "management" area resembling a municipal
landfill. It would be sealed with a plastic liner, covered with a clay cap and
monitored for leaks.<P>

"How can the mining company guarantee protection from waste rock -- whose
potential for harm can last thousands of years -- when liners are only
guaranteed for 100 years at most?" asked Dave Blouin. "Who will take
responsibility for replacing the liner?"<P>

The permitting process for the mine will take another two years. Meanwhile, the
Sokaogon Chippewa have gone ahead with their own investigations of the mine's
potential impacts. Using federal and private grants, and revenues from its two
casinos at Mole Lake, the tribe has hired experts to evaluate the proposed
mine. They have also built alliances with other northern Wisconsin tribes,
sought help from environmentalists and joined forces with recreationists and
non-native neighbors concerned about pollution.<P>

Ironically, the federal government may be the mine opponents' ace in the hole.
In November 1994, three federal agencies -- the National Park Service, the
Bureau of Indian Affairs and the Fish and Wildlife Service -- expressed strong
reservations about the project. The US government holds certain lands in
"trust" for Native Americans and the government's strict responsibility to
protect tribal resources transcends the state's powers to grant mining permits.

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

For more information, contact: Madison Treaty Rights Support Group, 731 State
St., Madison, WI 53703; (608) 246-2256; WATER, Box 31 Springbrook, WI 54875;
(715)766-3408. To comment on the permitting process for the proposed mine,
contact: Department of Natural Resources, PO Box 7921, Madison, WI 53707; US
Army Corps of Engineers, District Engineer, St. Paul District, 190 5th St.
East, St. Paul, MN 55101 (refer to project 94-01298-IP-DLB).<P>

