<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: "Lord Take My Soul... the Struggle Continues"</TITLE>

<H1>"Lord Take My Soul... the Struggle Continues"</H1>

On November 10, Nigerian environmentalist, author and Ogoni tribal activist Ken
Saro-Wiwa was taken from the Port Harcourt army camp where he had been
imprisoned for more than a year and led to the city's civilian prison.
Saro-Wiwa, along with eight other members of the Ogoni tribe, had been
convicted on October 31 of inciting the murder of four Ogoni elders who died in
a riot that erupted at an Ogoni rally. Saro-Wiwa was not even present at the
event; police prevented him from attending.<P>

Despite evidence that they had been framed, the Ogoni activists were found
guilty by a secret military-appointed tribunal. Saro-Wiwa, winner of the 1995
Goldman Environmental Prize for Africa, was the first to mount the hastily
constructed gallows. It took five attempts to hang the inspirational Ogoni
leader, but, after uttering the words, "Lord, take my soul, but the struggle
continues," Saro-Wiwa died.<P>

Saro-Wiwa earned the wrath of Nigeria's military government by speaking out
against oil operations on the Ogoni's 404-square-mile tribal territory in
Nigeria's Rivers State. Royal Dutch/Shell first discovered crude on Ogoniland
in 1956 and has since pumped $30 billion worth of petroleum, while the Ogoni
live in squalor in an environment devastated by the oil companies. Ogoni oil
reserves account for more than 50 percent of Nigeria's petroleum production and
14 percent of Shell's global production.<P>

Shell enjoys the support of Nigeria's military regime, which derives more than
80 percent of its revenue from oil sales. Saro-Wiwa claimed that Shell funded
and directed repeated acts of military violence against Ogoni villages. As
leader and spokesperson for the Movement for the Survival of Ogoni People
(MOSOP), Saro-Wiwa galvanized the 550,000 Ogoni and condemned Shell's
"environmental terrorism" against the tribe and its land.<P>

Though his execution shocked the world, it likely came as no surprise to
Saro-Wiwa himself. Twelve days before being arrested in May 1994, the Ogoni
leader said, "This is it... [the military is] going to arrest us all and execute
us. All for Shell."<P>

Immediately after the executions, eight nations, including the US, recalled
their ambassadors from Nigeria, the Commonwealth of Britain suspended Nigeria's
membership and the World Bank canceled a $100 million loan for a natural gas
project in the Niger River Delta. On November 15, South African President
Nelson Mandela announced that he would lead a campaign to boycott Nigerian oil
imports worldwide, and to push for democratic reforms in Nigeria. The Clinton
administration stated that it would not join Mandela's embargo because it would
threaten US economic interests in Nigeria. The US imports roughly 50 percent of
Nigeria's oil.<BR>
-- John Sterling<P>

Send letters to Phillip Carroll, CEO Shell Oil Company, PO Box 2436, Houston,
TX 77252-2436.<P>

