<TITLE>Korean Activist Defend an Island</TITLE>

<H1>Korean Activist Defend an Island</H1>

<H2>by David Helvarg</H2>

Choi Yul became an environmental activist the hard way. As a student dissident
during South Korea's military dictator-ships of the '60s and '70s, he was
expelled from school, drafted into the military, arrested and tortured --
ultimately serving more than five years in prison. While in solitary
confinement, Choi asked Amnesty International to send him environmental books
from overseas. Because such texts were not viewed as "political," prison
authorities let him read some 250-300 of them. Released from prison in the
early 80s, he formed the Korean Federation for Environmental Movement (KFEM),
the country's first environmental group.<P>

KFEM's protests against environmental abuses helped mobilize Koreans for the
pro-democracy battles of 1987 and 1988.<P>

These days, South Korea's environmental movement is fighting a two-front war
against air, water and ground pollution produced by the nation's booming
industrial economy (moving forward under the banner of "globalization") and the
government's unwavering commitment to fuel this metastasizing growth through
an ambitious nuclear-power program.<P>

South Korea's ten nuclear power plants produce 40 percent of the nation's
energy and the government plans to build 35 more by 2030. Already a world
leader in steel, autos, shipping and electronics, South Korea hopes to add
nuclear technology to its list of exports. In addition to a US-brokered deal to
build two light-water reactors in North Korea at a cost of $4 billion, the
Seoul government also plans to help build reactors in Turkey, Taiwan and
China.<P>

A turning point for South Korea's environmental movement came in 1990, when
10,000 Anyan Island residents took to the streets to protest a government
project to store nuclear waste there. The plan was canceled. Subsequent
KFEM-led protests resulted in the cancellation of six more planned nuclear
waste sites.<P>

South Korea's nuclear-power boom, which involves spending at least $1 billion a
year on new construction and $2.5 billion a year on joint government/industry
R&D, also has more ominous implications. Despite present nonproliferation
agreements, critics are concerned that South Korea's nuclear power industry
could, given the right circumstances, rapidly convert to a nuclear weapons
industry.<P>

One justification for South Korea's plans to build a plutonium reprocessing
plant and produce its own weapons-grade plutonium is its fear of Japan's
breeder-reactor program, which continues to move forward despite growing
evidence that it is economically unfeasible. This has helped convince the
already suspicious Koreans (both North and South) that their former colonizer's
real intent is to use the program to produce the raw material for a
nuclear-weapons stockpile.<P>

For the average South Korean, however, the problem with nuclear power is not
its potential to produce atomic bombs (they have lived for more than a
generation with US nuclear weapons stationed on their soil) but traditional
NIMBY fears of reactor accidents and atomic waste. Opinion polls have shown
that a solid majority of South Koreans (like their US counterparts) oppose
nuclear power.

<H2>Small Islands, Big Protests</H2>

Last spring, half of the 650 fishers and summer-resort operators on the small
island of Duk-juk, 30 miles off the coast of South Korea, assembled near the
Ministry of Science and Technology building in the thick yellow-white smog of
downtown Seoul to protest plans to site a national nuclear waste dump on
Kul-up, a neighboring island. Kul-up, a tiny, jewel-like 500-acre assemblage of
mossy rocks, white sand beaches and saltwater marsh, is surrounded by
treacherous currents and  earthquake faults. KFEM believes that Kul-up was
chosen because its location and negligible population of seven residents would
mean smaller protests.<P>

Within moments of the protesters' arrival at the ministry, squads of
body-shielded riot police appeared. There was some spirited pushing and shoving
until Choi Yul got on a megaphone to remind everyone that it is now legal to
protest in South Korea. (The country now functions as a nominally democratic
nation since student-led protests in the late 1980s led to national
parliamentary elections in 1992).<P>

The government decision to name Kul-up a national depository for low- and
medium-level nuclear waste, and a temporary storage site for spent fuel rods,
was made without any public hearings or review. After KFEM exposed the secret
decision in December 1994, government representatives visited Kul-up and
Duk-juk and tried to reassure the islanders that they would benefit
economically from the government's $650 million project (the cost includes
stationing 3000 anti-riot troopers in nearby Inchon).<P>

Meanwhile, the mostly elderly Duk-juk island residents fear losing their
traditional livelihood, resort-owners are concerned that summer tourists will
stop coming and fishers complain that people have already stopped buying their
fish out of fear of nuclear contamination.<P>

"Because they haven't listened to the people from the islands and because they
made a secret decision to site the waste there, I'm adamantly against it," said
Choi Yul, whose group has organized the people of the islands to protest. "The
main reason I first got involved in the environmental movement was to help
people without a voice, the victims of pollution."<P>

The only known scientific review of the Kul-up project (a 1991 site survey done
by the government's Korean Resource Research Institute) recommended against the
site because of its high groundwater level, earthquake faults and unsafe
docking facilities. The survey also noted that Kul-up was the island located
farthest from South Korea's nuclear plants.<P>

The Ministry of Science and Technology has argued that the project's
endorsement by the UN's International Atomic Energy Agency is proof that Kul-up
is a safe place to store 50,000 barrels of nuclear waste.<P>

Choi Yul counters that it was the IAEA that assured the safety of a
little-known Ukrainian power-station called Chernobyl three years before its
meltdown.<P>

