<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Washington's Top Ten Worst Environmentalists</TITLE>

<H2>Washington's Top Ten Worst Environmentalists
<BR>by John Sterling</H2>

Use these links to email 'em:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="mailto:email@murkowski.senate.gov">Frank Murkowski</A> (R-AK)
<LI><A HREF="mailto:senator_gorton@gorton.senate.gov">Slade Gorton</A> (R-WA)
<LI><A HREF="mailto:senator_domenici@domenici.senate.gov">Pete Domenici</A> (R-NM)
<LI><A HREF="mailto:chtaylor@hr.house.gov">Charles Taylor</A> (R-NC)
<LI><A HREF="mailto:askhelen@hr.house.gov">Helen Chenoweth</A> (R-ID)
<LI>Billy Tauzen (D-LA)
<LI>Ernest Istook (R-OK)
<LI>Jim Hansen (R-UT)
<LI>Don Young (R-AK)
<LI>Richard Pombo (R-CA)
</UL>

Meet the 104th Congress' anti-environmental alliance -- a posse of senators and
representatives supported by the Wise Use movement, corporate polluters, real
estate developers and industries that derive their profits from exploiting
federal lands for oil, timber, minerals and grazing. There are so many of them
that it is hard to track their hyperactivity, but their aim is clear -- they
intend to dismantle 25 years of bipartisan environmental legislation (despite
polls showing that more than 60 percent of Americans think environmental
regulations should remain unchanged or be strengthened). Though they are mostly
white, male, Western Republicans, their actions affect anyone who values clean
air and water, healthy forests, respect for non-human species and the
stewardship of our public lands system. Rating the environmental voting records
of the 435 House members on a scale of 1-100, the League of Conservation Voters
handed out "zeros" to 179 representatives -- 41 percent of the House. The
following short list only recognizes the ringleaders -- the environment's Ten
Least Wanted.<P>

As Chair of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee, <A HREF="mailto:email@murkowski.senate.gov">Frank Murkowski</A>
(R-AK) is the most powerful member of the tribe and he uses his position to
advocate oil exploration in the Alaska National Wildlife Refuge and increased
timbering in the Tongass National Forest. "The agenda in our state has been to
provide for the economy," said Murkowski, who received $240,000 from energy
companies from 1987-1992.<P>

Fellow Alaska Republican and Chair of the House Interior and Insular Affairs
Committee <B>Don Young</B> echoes Murkowski's resource development stance as he rails
against the "waffle-stomping, Harvard-graduating, intellectual bunch of idiots"
who support strong environmental safeguards. Young's favorite target is the
Endangered Species Act (ESA), which he complains favors "saving crickets over
saving babies."<P>

Young and <B>Richard Pombo</B> (R-CA) co-sponsored the anti-ESA Endangered Species
Conservation and Management Act of 1995, which a coalition of 20 environmental
groups claims would lead to "an end to biological diversity in America." Pombo,
a fourth-generation California rancher, repeatedly lashes out against the ESA's
protection of the endangered San Joaquin kit fox, which inhabits his own
ranchlands and those of many of his constituents. The current ESA prevents
Pombo and his neighbors from destroying kit fox habitat, subdividing their land
and cashing in on development schemes.<P>

Guiding the Senate attack on the ESA is <A HREF="mailto:senator_gorton@gorton.senate.gov">Slade Gorton</A> (R-WA), who accepted
$82,688 from the forest products industry and then recruited timber industry
lobbyists to help him write a proposed revision to the law. Under Gorton's ESA,
the fate of species would be determined not by law, but by a Department of
Interior appointee.<P>

Utah's <B>Jim Hansen</B>, a Republican long reputed to be one of the most hostile
anti-environmentalists in the House, has proposed closing some "problem"
national parks, including Nevada's Great Basin National Park. Hansen advocates
transferring all 272 million acres of Bureau of Land Management (BLM) holdings
to the states in which they lie. Hansen used his status as chair of the
National Parks, Forests and Lands Subcommittee to push a bill that would open
1.8 million acres of Utah wilderness to industrial development and motorized
recreation.<P>

Joining Hansen's attack on public lands is Senator <A HREF="mailto:senator_domenici@domenici.senate.gov">Pete Domenici (R-NM)</A>, whose
Livestock Grazing Act would mandate that 200 million acres of BLM and Forest
Service range- and grassland be designated exclusively for grazing, stripping
any non-grazing users of their land-use permits. Domenici, who received
$232,000 from the oil and gas industries from 1987-1992, also supports oil
exploration in the Alaska National Wildlife Refuge.<P>

In a stealth attack against the environment, Rep. <B>Ernest Istook (R-OK)</B>, known
for his opposition to abortion and his support of prayer in school, penned an
amendment that would prevent lobbying by nonprofit organizations that receive
federal grants. The Istook Amendment, commonly known as the "gag rule,"
reflects its author's belief that nonprofit groups should not participate in
"political advocacy." The law would affect many of the 225,000 nonprofits,
including many environmental groups, that receive federal funds.<P>

The most controversial environmental bill to be signed into law by President
Clinton during the 104th Congress was the salvage logging rider, written by
Rep. <A HREF="mailto:chtaylor@hr.house.gov">Charles Taylor</A> (R-NC). The law permits the timber industry to harvest 6.2
billion board feet of "dead and dying" trees from Forest Service and BLM land
without any environmental review. Taylor's "logging without laws" bill was
enacted in July and has spawned widespread protests and a 75-day hunger strike
by Oregon forest activist Tim Ream.<P>

Not all the legislative eco-damage is advocated by Republicans. Rep. <B>Billy
Tauzen (D-LA)</B>, who collected $93,550 from oil companies and energy utilities in
the two years preceding the 1994 election, introduced legislation that would
cripple federal protection of private land. Tauzen's bill targeted the ESA,
Clean Water Act, safeguards for wetlands and laws protecting water flow in the
West. He also wrote a bill that would allow business to undermine existing
health, safety and environmental rules.<P>

Proving that the men in Congress do not hold a monopoly on ecological
ignorance, Idaho's republican Rep. <A HREF="mailto:askhelen@hr.house.gov">Helen Chenoweth</A> earned a spot on our list by
saying, "a species goes out of existence every 20 seconds. Surely a new species
must come into existence every 20 seconds."

<HR>

