<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Get the Hogs Out of the Creek!</TITLE>

<H1>Get the Hogs Out of the Creek!</H1>
<H2>By Jim Hightower</H2>

The most astute political observation I ever heard was made by my Aunt Eula, who
farmed years ago in Northeast Texas: "The water won't ever clear up 'til we get
the hogs out of the creek," she said.<P>

Now that's our problem today, isn't it? The big hogs have hefted their hulks
directly into the middle of the creek, damming it up for themselves and fouling
our country's economic and environmental waters.<P>

We've simply got to get the hogs out of the creek. As Aunt Eula knew, this is
not a chore to undertake in your best trousers, politely pleading: "Here hog,
here hog... pretty please." To get hogs out of the creek, you have to put your
shoulders to them -- and shove.<P>

Yet most national environmental organizations today are indeed dressed in their
Sunday trousers, engaged in the soft-hands work of lawyers and lobbyists in
Washington, sincerely but futily attempting to negotiate the relative position
of hogs with such corrupt louts as Loudspeaker of the House Newt Gingrich.<P>

Surely it is time to concede that we environmentalists will not even deter --
much less defeat -- the spoilers and speculators, big shots and bastards by
focusing so much of our fight inside the Beltway, where the "debate" is
tolerant only of viewpoints ranging from the moderate-right corporatism of Bill
Clinton's White House to the kooky-right extremism of Gingrich's Congress.<P>

Rather, our place for the next several years has to be in the countryside,
putting the bulk of environmentalism's considerable resources (money, brain
power and energy) into grassroots organizing, local legal battles and hands-on
political campaigns going head-to-head in urban neighborhoods, small towns and
rural areas with the polluters, "wise abusers" and other forces of ignorance
and arrogance. Indeed, it would not hurt my feelings one bit if every
environmental group in Washington were to abandon the Capital City, except for
a token sentinel or two, and relocate en masse out where America's
environmental majority actually lives, works and struggles.<P>

Environmental majority? Yes. Not merely the card-carrying organizational
members, but just ordinary folks -- the "pollutees." They mostly don't call
themselves "environmentalists," and they probably know more about the PTA than
the EPA, but they damn sure know pollution when it hits them. After all, you
don't have to be in Who's Who to know What's What.<P>

I'm talking about the family with a $70,000 mortgage on a little home in that
far out housing development up against the cotton fields, noticing that their
roses died after the seventh spraying this summer, and beginning to connect
that to their child's recurring rashes.<P>

I'm talking about workers in the plastics plant who have learned they'll die
ten years earlier than normal because of where they work, at the same time
they've learned the company is cutting back their health benefits.<P>

I'm talking about the Mexican-American mother who finds out her daughter's
bouts with nausea and a neighboring boy's fainting spells might both come from
a gasoline tank farm in their neighborhood that's leaking toxins into the
groundwater.<P>

Our challenge is not to create a mass movement, but simply to get with it. All
over America, there's a rebellion against the poisoning -- not just a rebellion
among the beansprout eaters, but among the snuffdippers as well. You don't find
noxious waste dumps on Nob Hill and the North Shore, and there are no
toxic-spewing factories in River Oaks and Saddle Brook. All such nasties are in
working-class neighborhoods and poor rural areas -- these are the folks who are
spontaneously-combusting into local, mad-as-hell groups called HALT, OUCH,
CRUD, WOW and NOT!<P>

There's our future, that's where our fight is and there is no shortcut to
victory through Washington. Indeed, these folks look to the Capital and see
Gingrich drinking his own bathwater and thinking it's champagne, while Clinton
seeks compromise with Newt and calls it "progress."<P>

The only integrity -- the only victory -- will come from the bloody give-and-take
of the grassroots war. How important is it? Just think in terms of raw
politics, not counting all the substantive fights over waste incinerators,
aquifers, pesticide regulations and so forth. Unbeknownst to most of the big,
national environmental organizations, the term-limits movement has been so
successful at the state level that some 2600 state house and senate seats
(nearly 40 percent of the total) are going to come open in 1998 and 2000.<P>

Are we recruiting candidates, training campaign managers, organizing, raising
money, getting ready? The polluters are. And remember, the legislative class
elected in '98 and 2000 will be the one that reapportions every congressional
district in the country. To ignore this historic battle, which can only be won
in the trenches, is simply to surrender the cause well into the next century.<P>

Besides, we should relish these state legislative fights and jump into them
with both feet for the very good reason that we can win them -- at the local
level, our numbers and energy can overpower their money. And, even more
important than the legislators we can elect, we would genuinely become a
national movement, unifying and solidifying a grassroots majority that really
can shove the hogs out of the creek.<P>

<HR>

Jim Hightower is a former Texas Agricultural Commissioner and progressive radio
talk show host. Contact Hightower and Associates, PO Box 13516, Austin, TX
78711; (512) 477-5588.<P>

<HR>

