<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Ebb & Flow</TITLE>

<H1>Ebb & Flow</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#McDonald">McDonald's Cowed by Protest</A>: USA
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Young">Young, Employed, Bald</A>: Japan
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Nestle">Nestle Sucks</A>: USA
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#To">To Dive in Venice</A>: Italy
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Here">Here Come the Bugs</A>: Geneva
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Gulp">"Gulp War" Syndrome</A>: NutraSweet
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Does">Does Growth Cut Pollution?</A>: NAFTA
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Think">Think Locally, Expand Globally</A>: R. J. Reynolds
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Jobs">Jobs? Don't Get Lean; Go Green</A>: USA
<LI><A HREF="w95-03.html#Zoo">Zoo-Busters Claim Victory</A>: Canada

</UL>


<A NAME="McDonald"><H2>McDonald's Cowed by Protest</H2>

USA -- On October 1, animal rights activists saluted "World Farm Animals Day" by
blocking the drive-thru lane at a southern California McDonald's restaurant
with a dead cow. "Technically, this is simply 'yet-to-be-processed food',"
explained Orange County People for Animals (OCPA) spokesperson Jerry Friedman.
OCPA's intention was to "jolt the public out of denial" and force burger-buyers
to "face the triple whammy of meat-eating" -- animal suffering, damage to human
health and destruction of habitat for grazing.

<BR CLEAR=ALL>

<A NAME="Young"><H2>Young, Employed, Bald</H2>

Japan -- The stress of modern living is causing women to lose their hair, and
that is good news for Japan's Yen3.8 billion ($43.7 million) hair tonic industry,
which has seen its profits  double in the last five years. But don't worry:
according to Seiji Kato of the Japan Hair Research Institute, "Worrying is
itself bad for the hair." Kato also claims that US-style fast-foods cause hair
loss by disturbing female hormone balances. The leading women's hair tonic,
distributed by the Tsumura company, is called "Molty."

<A NAME="Nestle"><H2>Nestle Sucks</H2>

USA -- Residents of the small Texas town of Eustace are boiling mad over a Swiss
multinational's plans to bottle their underground water and sell it on the
international market. Ozarka Drinking Water Co., a subsidiary of Perrier (which
is a division of the Swiss-owned Nestle Corporation), plans to tap into
historic Rohr Spring, the town's sole source of water. While Nestle can legally
claim the residents' water under Texas' "Right to Capture" law, the Rohr Spring
Citizen's Committee complains that the would-be water-robber-barons represent a
"foreign invader."

<A NAME="To"><H2>To Dive in Venice</H2>

Italy -- At the start of the 20th century, St. Mark's Square in Venice flooded
seven times a year. Today the famous square is under water more than 40 times a
year. While average sea levels have risen 11 cm (4.3 inches) this century,
draining of underground aquifers has caused Venice to sink 12 cm (4.7 inches).
If this trend continues, reports Rueters, St. Mark's could be submerged
"virtually the entire year."

<A NAME="Here"><H2>Here Come the Bugs</H2>

Geneva -- If climate change pushes tropical weather toward the poles, can
mosquitoes be far behind? The European Commission's Joint Research Center
fears that much of Europe, Australia and North America may be overrun with
disease-carrying insects within the next few decades. Malaria, customarily
confined to the tropics, claims two million lives a year. Not only is
population density greater in the North, but also the North's city dwellers
have not developed any immunity to <I>Plasmodium falciparum</I>, the most virulent of
the malarial parasites. The UN Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change 
predicts that rising temperatures will elicit 50-80 million additional cases of
malaria and 3.5 million new cases of river blindness and help spread tropical
diseases like dengue fever and yellow fever.

<A NAME="Gulp"><H2>"Gulp War" Syndrome</H2>

USA -- A new theory has emerged that may explain the spectrum of illnesses
known as Gulf War Syndrome. During the sweltering months of the Persian Gulf
War, US soldiers consumed enormous quantities of carbonated soft drinks
artificially sweetened with NutraSweet (aspartame), manufactured by Monsanto.
Left in the desert sun, temperatures inside Coke and Pepsi cans may reach
120-150* F. At temperatures above 86*F, aspartame liberates methanol, a severe
metabolic poison. Even at room temperatures, drinking chemically sweetened
sodas can trigger a condition known as phenyl-keta-neuria, which can trigger a
range of symptoms, including memory loss, headaches, chronic fatigue, joint
pain and vision loss.<P>

See Also <A HREF="w95-04.html#Reaching">Reaching-for-an-Angle Award</A>,<BR>
<A HREF="w95-10.html#EPA">EPA's PCB Cover-up</A>


<A NAME="Does"><H2>Does Growth Cut Pollution?</H2>

USA -- Free-market advocates claimed that treaties like NAFTA would benefit the
environment in countries like Mexico. While pollution might increase with
industrialization, the argument ran, growing incomes and profits would
eventually pay for environmental clean-ups. But a new study by the
Environmental Law Institute (ELI) finds little evidence for this wishful
thinking. While sulfur dioxide and particulates appeared to show a "turning
point," the ELI study found that "municipal solid waste and carbon dioxide
emissions continue to grow with income."


<A NAME="Think"><H2>Think Locally, Expand Globally</H2>

Romania -- The miracle of the post-Communist "free market" left Romania so
impoverished that it could not provide light bulbs for the capital city's
traffic signals. But now capitalism has come to the rescue in the form of Joe
Camel. Tobacco giant R. J. Reynolds agreed to pay for Bucharest's traffic
lights, but there was a catch -- all the lights came emblazoned with the Camel
cigarette logo. "It was really fantastic at night, when only the yellow lights
were on, and you'd just see the camel everywhere, blinking on and off," one ad
agency honcho told the <B>San Francisco Chronicle</B>. (Globalization works both ways.
On October 1, it was announced that BAA, a British firm, would begin running
the Indianapolis International Airport.)

<A NAME="Jobs"><H2>Jobs? Don't Get Lean; Go Green</H2>

USA -- A National Commission for Employment Policy study reports that
Washington's $4 billion investment in environmental programs in 1994 created
70-80,000 jobs. "The numbers show that the jobs/environment dichotomy is a
fallacy," concluded Commission chair Anthony Carnevale. This finding was
corroborated in an Economic Policy Institute study cited in <B>Scientific
American</B>. Economist Eban S. Goodstein, using Labor Department figures from
1987-1990, found that, on average, only 0.1 percent of job-losses had resulted
from environmental regulation. Change of company ownership resulted in 35-times
more lay-offs, Goodstein found.

<A NAME="Zoo"><H2>Zoo-Busters Claim Victory</H2>

Canada -- In an unprecedented "zoo coup," animal rights campaigners have shut
down a municipal zoo in North America. By mid-October, Vancouver's Stanley Park
Zoo was down to its last 21 Humboldt penguins and one 34-year-old polar bear
named Tuk. "There are more and more people questioning whether zoos are good
things," observed Zoocheck Canada director Rob Laidlaw. In 1993, 54 percent of
Vancouver voters called for the zoo's closure. The British-based Born Free
Foundation had touched the hearts of many voters by documenting the prevalence
of "zoochosis" -- a set of destructive behaviors in caged animals, ranging from
neurotic pacing and head-bobbing to gnawing on bars and walls, and
self-mutilation.

<HR>

