<H1>EcoMole</H1>

<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: EcoMole</TITLE>

Quick links:
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Bank">Bank Bumbles; Schemes to Scam Taxpayers</A>: World Bank
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Men">Men of Letters</A>: GOP
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Reaching">Reaching-for-an-Angle Award</A>: Monsanto
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Cars">Cars for Alarm</A>: Clinton
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Fueling">Fueling Suspicions</A>: Z.E.V.
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Primed">Primed to Blow</A>: Atomic energy
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Corruption">Corruption Index</A>
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Sting">Sting Stung</A>: Overpopulation
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Who">Who Owns the Weather?</A>: Privatization
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Nip">Mole Nip</A>: CA governor, <I>George</I>
<LI><A HREF="w95-04.html#Kiss">Mole Kiss</A>: "Car Talk" DJ

</UL>


<A NAME="Bank"><H2>Bank Bumbles; Schemes to Scam Taxpayers</H2>

World Bank documents leaked to the <B>Financial Times of London</B> reveal that many
Third World borrowers will never be able to repay their loans. (Third World
borrowers have called for debt relief for years, but this marks the first time
that the bank itself has admitted that many of its loans are uncollectable.)
Canada's <B>Probe International</B> [225 Brunswick Avenue, Toronto, Ontario, Canada
M5S 2M6; (416) 964-9223, ext. 227] reports that the bank, to protect its
triple-A credit rating, "plans to engineer a disguised taxpayer bailout" by
using the Multilateral Debt Facility (MDF) as a "bailout body" to write off $11
billion in bad loans. In the past, bad loans have been covered up through the
banking ploy of "defensive lending." (One recent example was Mexico's $730
million "repayment" on its $12 billion US loan. Mexico actually borrowed this
money from foreign banks at <B>higher</B> interest rates than those in force on the
original US loan.) To avoid the appearance of "self-entanglement," the document
says, the MDF bailout "would be financed by taxpayer funds from the
industrialized countries...."

<A NAME="Men"><H2>Men of Letters</H2>

The GOP's House Majority Leader Dick Armey (R-TX) committed a "technical
violation" of House rules by sending letters written on Congressional
stationery warning corporate executives to stop funding "liberal" nonprofit
charities like the Children's Defense Fund, the American Cancer Society and the
NAACP. Armey, who wants to abolish the minimum wage, complained that "big
business is firmly behind the welfare state." In an attempt to deny political
access to nonprofits receiving federal funds, Rep. David McIntosh (R-IN)
created a bogus letter on Alliance for Justice stationery (a grassroots
coalition promoting equal access to the legal system) to attack the Sierra Club
Legal Defense Fund, the Native American Rights Fund and the Juvenile Law
Center. Alliance founder Nan Aron called the forgery "appalling."

<A NAME="Reaching"><H2>Reaching-for-an-Angle Award</H2>

To Monsanto, which touted the "environmental" benefits of its dioxin-laced
Round-Up pesticide by claiming that it "is used in Kenya, Africa, to keep
grasses from short-circuiting electric fences that protect the endangered black
rhino."<P>

See Also <A HREF="w95-03.html#Gulp">"Gulp War" Syndrome</A>,<BR>
<A HREF="w95-10.html#EPA">EPA's PCB Cover-up</A>



<A NAME="Cars"><H2>Cars for Alarm</H2>

Defying safety and environmental concerns, President Clinton signed the GOP-led
repeal of the national 55 mph speed limit. As a result, oil companies will reap
millions in profits and highway fatalities may soar. Meanwhile, in an attempt
to help US automakers "compete and win in the global marketplace," the Clinton
administration demanded that Japan relax its auto-safety regulations to allow
increased sales of US cars in Japan.

<A NAME="Fueling"><H2>Fueling Suspicions</H2>

In an attempt to stall California's promotion of emission-free transportation,
Big Auto and Big Oil companies jointly hired the Rand Corporation to produce a
critical study of Zero Emission Vehicles. <B>Automotive News</B> reported that the
funds were laundered through the California Manufacturers Association.

<A NAME="Primed"><H2>Primed to Blow</H2>

The International Atomic Energy Authority (IAEA) has named Bulgaria's Kozloduy
nuclear power station the world's most dangerous reactor. The IAEA estimated
that four of the plant's six reactors run a 25 percent risk of suffering a core
meltdown within five years. The IAEA made this prediction in mid-1993.

<A NAME="Corruption"><H2>Corruption Index</H2>

Berlin-based Transparency International has published its first Corruption
Index, rating the influence of bribery in awarding government contracts in 41
industrial and developing countries. The most honest countries: New Zealand,
Denmark and Singapore. The world's most corrupt countries: China and Indonesia.
The US ranked 14th on the corruption scale, slightly ahead of France and Japan.

<A NAME="Sting"><H2>Sting Stung</H2>

With British rock star Sting and wife Trudie expecting their fourth child in
December (Sting also has three children from a previous marriage), Hollywood
gossipmonger Liz Smith was moved to observe: "Geez! This guy is so big on
environmental issues... but hasn't he heard about the problems of overpopulation?
You're a fertile guy, Sting. We're impressed. Now stop it."

<A NAME="Who"><H2>Who Owns the Weather?</H2>

Taxpayers might be surprised to learn that the government's National Weather
Service (NWS) data has been "privatized." <B>San Francisco Chronicle</B> business
reporter Michelle Quinn has disclosed that the NWS "cheaply sells the raw data
to private companies who then resell it, at higher rates" to TV networks,
newspapers and airlines. Private companies like Accuweather Inc. and WSI Corp.
buy the data for $40,000 and reap millions by reselling it to small businesses
and large corporations. Last May, Jan Null, NWS' lead forecaster, tried to
create an Internet site so users could quickly acquire weather data. Two months
later, Null was told to close the World Wide Web site. Why was Null nullified?
The scuttlebutt says that the free service competed with WSI, which sells the
same information to CNN and NBC's <B>Today Show</B> -- at a profit.

<A NAME="Nip"><H2>Mole Nip</H2>

To Earthwatch, a Massachusetts-based research/ecotourism operation, for
subsidizing the man-handling of dolphins in Sarasota Bay, Florida. Researcher
Randy Wells pursues and restrains dolphins to extract teeth and blood samples.
Ben White of Friends of Animals [1234 Garfield Street, Port Townsend, WA 98368;
(360) 379-5168] has proposed tracking down and capturing Mr. Wells in order to
obtain teeth and blood samples. Humanely, of course.<P>

To California's race-baiting governor and failed presidential candidate Pete
Wilson. Having failed to recycle his political career, Wilson returned from the
campaign trial and immediately repealed California's landmark law requiring the
use of recycled materials in paper products and packaging. Wilson's action
(which was cheered by food giant Kraft and the Weyer-hauser paper company) came
five days after the US Supreme Court dismissed the food and paper industry's
challenge to the law. Wilson claimed his act would ensure "consumer-friendly
parameters." Californians Against Waste says that Wilson's act means that
anything can now be "labeled 'recycled' whether it's recycled or not."<P>

To Camelot-lite John F. Kennedy, Jr., editor of the lavishly illustrated,
ponderously empty <B>George</B> magazine. Explaining his "ET" approach to political
reporting, JFK, Jr. editorialized: "We suspect that Americans want to know more
about the people who seek to govern and less about the correctness of their
politics." Coming soon in <B>George</B>: Pat Buchanan's favorite barbecue recipes and
Newt Gingrich's personal battle to perfect his golf swing.<P>

<A NAME="Kiss"><H2>Mole Kiss</H2>

To Boston radio jock Tom Magliozzi who, with his brother Ray, holds forth on
National Public Radio's popular "Car Talk" broadcast. <B>Auto Free World</B> reports
that Tom's preferred commute vehicle is a bicycle. "Sure, cars give us
freedom," Tom observes, "but as Benjamin Franklin said, 'There is no such thing
as freedom without responsibility.' " The "car guy" advocates limiting the
number of cars on roads.<P>

<HR>

