<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Good News</TITLE>

<H1>Good News</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>

<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Clearcut">A Clearcut Victory at The Times</A>: USA
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Now">Now You're Cookin'</A>: South Africa
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Save">Save Trees; Save the Fish</A>: Japan
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Clearing">Clearing Chlorine</A>: Alternative paper products
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Mafia">A New Kind of Mafia Protection</A>: Overfishing
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Good">Good News for Crabs</A>: Australia
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Not">Not to be Skipped</A>: Children's quarterly
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Don">Don't Bank on Growth</A>: Beyond Sprawl
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#60">60 Minutes Wins One</A>: Tobacco industry
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Agenda">Agenda 21 at the City Level</A>: Netherlands
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Suds">Suds-less Scrubbing</A>: Envirocloths
<LI><A HREF="w95-05.html#Nose">A Good Nose</A>: LPG train

</UL>

<A NAME="Clearcut"><H2>A Clearcut Victory at The Times</H2>

USA -- In November, after a two-year blitz of letter-writing and appeals from
subscribers and environmentalists, <B>The New York Times</B> canceled its paper
contract with MacMillan Blodel, the Canadian timber giant responsible for
clearcutting the ancient forests of Clayoquot Sound. The action finally puts
the paper in compliance with its own environmental policies. In Clayoquot
Sound, meanwhile, the clear-cutting continues, despite an agreement to apply
"sustainable" logging practices.

<A NAME="Now"><H2>Now You're Cookin'</H2>

South Africa -- Eastern Transvaal Premier Mathews Phosa has vowed to move solar
energy from the back burner to the forefront of his development agenda. Home
solar water heaters are more than 50 percent more efficient that fossil-fuel
systems and installing photovoltaic arrays on rooftops is cheaper than building
hundreds of miles of transmission lines. According to <B>New Ground</B> magazine,
solar power will "enable needy communities to rise above poverty." Using solar
ovens to cook food will slow deforestation and free women from the
time-consuming hunt for wood.

<A NAME="Save"><H2>Save Trees; Save the Fish</H2>

Japan -- In order to save traditional fisheries from silt washing out to sea 
off eroded hills, Japanese women have been replanting inland forests. "The seas
and the mountains are one," Urakawa Fisheries Cooperative Association director
Masahito Inoue told <B>Look Japan</B>. The Women's Auxiliary of the Hokkaido Fisheries
Association has vowed to keep planting trees for 100 years. In the last 30
years, the women have planted more than a quarter-million trees.

<A NAME="Clearing"><H2>Clearing Chlorine</H2>

USA -- The environmentally damaging element chlorine can be found in paper,
swimming pools and drinking water. In 1994, paper production alone released
more than 1.5 trillion gallons of chlorine-laden wastes into US waters. Where
can you find alternatives? Try the Chlorine Free Products Association, 102
North Hubbard, Algonquin, IL 60102; (708) 658-6104.<P>

See also <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">Rethink Paper</A>


<A NAME="Mafia"><H2>A New Kind of Mafia Protection</H2>

Tanzania -- In 1995, the Tanzanian Parliament established the country's first
marine park at Mafia Island, 120 kilometers (74 miles) south of Dar-es-Salaam.
The decision capped a three-year effort by islanders and the Worldwide Fund for
Nature. Mafia Island's seagrass beds, tidal flats and coral reefs had been
threatened by coral collection and overfishing with seine nets and dynamite.
Dynamite fishing is especially harmful, since it kills non-target fish and
blasts gaping holes in the reefs.

<A NAME="Good"><H2>Good News for Crabs</H2>

Australia -- Last September, the province of Victoria enacted a law that, for
the first time, extended prevention-of-cruelty-to-animals protection to fish
and crustaceans. Agriculture Minister Bill McGrath assured Parliament that
penalties would be increased for violations and police would be given greater
powers to enforce the law.

<A NAME="Not"><H2>Not to be Skipped</H2>

USA -- <B>Skipping Stones</B>, a unique quarterly that publishes multilingual stories,
poems and pictures from children around the world, has won the Educational
Press Association of America's 1995 Golden Shoestring Award. Congratulations to
tireless editors Arun N. Toke and Amy E. Brant, and to all the young
contributors. [Skipping Stones, PO Box 3939, Eugene, OR 97403; (503) 342-4956.
Subscriptions: $20/year.]

<A NAME="Don"><H2>Don't Bank on Growth</H2>

USA -- In 1995, Bank of America, the California Resources Agency, the Low Income
Housing Fund and the Greenbelt Alliance produced a study called <B>Beyond Sprawl:
New Patterns of Growth to Fit the New California</B>, warning that the social,
environmental and financial costs of building new suburbs were unsustainable.
The report found that the loss of farms and woodlands to housing developments
had made the state a "less desirable location for business owners and potential
employees" and called for developers to begin paying for the full costs
"associated with new road construction... new water supplies and mitigation of
ecological problems."

<A NAME="60"><H2>60 Minutes Wins One</H2>

USA -- In November, CBS' news magazine <B>60 Minutes</B> was forced to censor a report
on the tobacco industry, because the network's corporate owners did not want to
risk a lawsuit. In 1989, <B>60 Minutes</B> broadcast a report claiming that children
were at risk from eating apples treated with the chemical Alar (daminozide).
Applegrowers sued CBS. In October 1995, a US Court of Appeals dismissed the
suit and confirmed the EPA's finding that exposure to Alar, a probable human
carcinogen, posed an "unacceptable risk" to human health.

<A NAME="Agenda"><H2>Agenda 21 at the City Level</H2>

The Netherlands -- Despite the focus on national governments, two-thirds of the
more than 2000 points covered in Agenda 21 (the program-of-action adopted at
the 1992 Earth Summit) must be implemented at the municipal level.
<B>Environmental News from The Netherlands</B> reports that the Dutch government
provides grants to cities to develop Agenda 21 plans. Amsterdam's plan seeks
"insulated, affordable housing, with enough playgrounds and parks, and many
cultural and recreational facilities" by the year 2015. The city of Oostzaan
has cut municipal wastes by 60 percent. The town of Houten boasts 25 percent
fewer cars than the national average and 72 percent fewer auto accidents.
Motorists trying to enter Houten's residential areas find themselves "caught in
a maze of small streets, difficult bends and junctions where cyclists have
priority."

<A NAME="Suds"><H2>Suds-less Scrubbing</H2>

USA -- Envirocloth has been used in European hospitals, hotels, restaurants and
schools for more than ten years to save costs by avoiding the use of caustic
cleansers. Ordinary cloth towels are woven flat, but the tiny Envirocloth
fibers stand up like spikes so they can penetrate surfaces and capture dirt by
mechanical action rather than chemical reaction. No detergents are needed, only
water. Envirocloths can last up to two years and are recyclable. [Environmental
Technologies Co., PO Box 10395, Prescott, AZ 86301; (800) 757-0993.]

<A NAME="Nose"><H2>A Good Nose</H2>
USA -- California's Napa Valley Wine Train has become one of the country's first
locomotives to convert to clean-burning natural gas. Replacing diesel fuel with
less expensive natural gas should cut fuel costs by 25 percent while reducing
nitrogen oxide emissions by as much as 16 percent.


