<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Around The World</TITLE>

<H1>Around The World</H1>


Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Smog">Smog on the Roof of the World</A>: Nepal
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Wise">Wise Use Down Under</A>: New Zealand
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Butterflies">Butterflies Aren't Free</A>: India
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Unleaded">Unleaded, Please</A>: Canada
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Gambling">Gambling on Debt</A>: World Bank
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Nuke">Nuke Ship Turns Over New Leaf</A>: Japan
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Poland">Poland's Royal Forest Is Spared</A>
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Hemp">Hemp, Hemp, Hurray!</A>: Canada
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Bosnia">Bosnia and the Oil Connection</A> 
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#US">US to Resume Nuclear Testing</A> 
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Near">Near Melt-Down Revealed in UK</A> 
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Sabotaged">Sabotaged Reporter Wins Suit</A>: Pacific Gas & Electric
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#The">The Colonel Bombs in Bangalore</A>: India
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#EPA">EPA's PCB Cover-up</A>: Missouri USA
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Canadian">Canadian Cod-Saver Jailed</A> 
<LI><A HREF="w95-10.html#Free">Free Trade Buys a Country</A>: Costa Rica

</UL>

<A NAME="Smog"><H2>Smog on the Roof of the World</H2>

Nepal -- Kathmandu will become one of the most polluted cities in the world
within 10-15 years if vehicle and industrial emissions continue without
regulation, according to a study completed by the Kath-mandu Valley Vehicular
Emission Control Project (KVVECP). The report, funded by the United Nations
Development Program, claims that the emissions from more than 95 percent of the
75,690 vehicles in Nepal's largest city exceed world pollution standards. The
Canadian magazine Alternatives reports that the towering Himalayan peaks
encircling the bowl-shaped Kath-mandu Valley create a wind-block that traps
pollution. The study concludes that owners of Kathmandu's aging buses and
three-wheeled taxis using two-stroke engines must implement emissions control
devices or Nepal's Shangri La could surpass even Mexico City in airborne filth.

<A NAME="Wise"><H2>Wise Use Down Under</H2>

New Zealand -- Forest and Bird, the magazine of the Wellington-based Forest and
Bird Protection Society, charges that a US-owned timber firm called MRGC(NZ)
"is riding cowboy-like over local law and convention in the clearance of native
vegetation for pine plantations." MRGC has cleared more than 200 hectares (494
acres) of native kanuka, manuka and shrublands in the Wairau Valley without
obtaining the proper permits from New Zealand's Conservation Department. The
company also "inadvertently" flattened four hectares (ten acres) of the Mt.
Richmond Forest Park, for which it could suffer an NZ$80,000 ($59,376) fine.
Forest and Bird recommends contacting MRGC's Norm Schaaf [PO Box 2498, Port
Angeles, WA 98362; fax 360-452-6224] to demand that the company recognize the
New Zealand Forest Accord that protects the manuka and kanuka forests.

<A NAME="Butterflies"><H2>Butterflies Aren't Free</H2>

India -- The Environment Ministry has moved to protect Indian butterfly and
moth species under the government's Wildlife Act in an attempt to prevent
smuggling of the winged insects. The CUTS Newsletter reports that the ministry
has provided a detailed identification chart for customs officials to help them
thwart the bug-smugglers. This protective measure came after two German
tourists were caught trying to leave the country with 15,000 preserved
butterflies and moths in their luggage.

<A NAME="Unleaded"><H2>Unleaded, Please</H2>

Canada -- The Canadian government announced in July that it will ban the use of
lead shot and fishing weights in May 1997 in an effort to reduce toxic
pollution in  wetlands and waterways critical to migratory birds. The US banned
lead shot in 1991 and will outlaw lead sinkers this year. BBC Wildlife reports
that the North American example is being followed in Europe, where the British
government has asked hunters to give up toxic shot voluntarily.

<A NAME="Gambling"><H2>Gambling on Debt</H2>

USA -- More than 2000 protesters gathered outside the World Bank's Washington
DC headquarters in October to condemn the bank's structural adjustment
programs, claiming that the policies devastate developing countries. The
protests, which coincided with the World Bank's annual meeting, attracted both
Southern and Northern activists, says Toward Freedom. World Bank programs have
"turned the economies of developing nations into casinos for foreign
investors," said former Mexican Finance Ministry official Carlos Heredia.
"Mexico was the biggest casino of them all."

<A NAME="Nuke"><H2>Nuke Ship Turns Over New Leaf</H2>

Japan -- Japan's first nuclear-powered ship is being retrofitted with a
conventional power plant and put to work researching global climate changes,
according to Revealing Japan. The Mutsu suffered a radiation leak during its
maiden voyage in 1974 and did not sail again until 1991. Japan will spend Yen20
billion ($214 million) to replace the nuclear reactor with a conventional power
plant. In 1997, the Mutsu will begin its new role as the world's largest marine
observation ship by laying 35 recording buoys in the equatorial Pacific to
collect data that will further the study of El Nino and other meteorological
phenomena.

<A NAME="Poland"><H2>Poland's Royal Forest Is Spared</H2>

Poland -- In July, Poland's General Director of National Forests approved an
immediate moratorium on logging trees from the Bialowieza Primeval Forest,
Europe's last lowland old-growth forest, which straddles Poland and Belarussia.
According to Native Forest Network [NFN, PO Box 8251, Missoula, MT 59807] the
logging ban is an important first step toward converting the entire forest into
a national park. The 1400-sq-km (560-sq-mi) forest was formerly the protected
hunting preserve for Polish, Russian and Lithuanian royalty until the
early-1900s, when a budding timber industry started extracting trees.
Belarussia has protected all 800 sq km (320 sq mi) of its forest domain, but
only 47 sq km (18.8 sq mi) on the Polish side has been set aside as a core
reserve. "The logging moratorium gives us a lot of breathing room, but no one
campaigning for the Bialowieza can rest until it is per-manently protected as a
national park," said NFN's Tom Fullum. NFN is urging people to write letters in
support of Bialowieza to Polish Prime Minister Josef Olesky [Urzad Rady,
Ministrow, 00-902 Warsaw, Poland; fax 48-2-628-4222].

<A NAME="Hemp"><H2>Hemp, Hemp, Hurray!</H2>

Canada -- The government has issued a total of nine licenses authorizing
Canadian farmers to grow industrial hemp for paper and clothing production.
Five of the permits went to farmers in Manitoba, where Agriculture Minister
Harry Enns is enthusiastic about the crop's economic potential. The province
funded a $25,000 experimental growing program that produced low-THC hemp on ten
acres of Manitoba farmland. The program was an attempt to learn "what this
plant can do and to see what varieties are commercially viable," said Martin
Moravcik of the Manitoba Hemp Alliance. The Manitoba-based Eco-Journal reports
that the province could become North America's hemp-production center. In
Australia, meanwhile, the state of Victoria has authorized hemp farmers to
plant ten field trials over the next ten years. New Delhi-based Down to Earth
reports that hemp's "amazing potential [for] paper-making, fabrics, food, oil
and herbal remedies -- makes it too precious to be abandoned."<BR>--JS<P>

See Also <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">ReThink Paper</A>

<A NAME="Bosnia"><H2>Bosnia and the Oil Connection</H2>

Bosnia -- San Francisco Chronicle reporters Frank Viviano and Kenneth Howe have
discovered that "major oil firms conducted field studies in the former Yugoslav
republic before 1992 under the auspices of the World Bank." Coal and oil
deposits reportedly were located beneath a 300-mile geologic zone known as the
Dinarides Thrust -- "the primary battlefront of [last] summer's massive
Croatian Army offensives against rebel Serbs...." AGIP, the Italian state-owned
petroleum company is already drilling for oil in waters off the Croatian
Adriatic, and the Chicago-based Amoco oil company established a Bosnian
subsidiary in 1989. According to Vivano and Howe, the results of the
multinationals' field studies "have since vanished from the Ministry of Energy
in Sarajevo" and are now believed to be in the possession of the Serbs.

<A NAME="US"><H2>US to Resume Nuclear Testing</H2>

USA -- In November, the US Department of Energy announced plans to detonate six
"hydronuclear" blasts at the Nevada Test Site. The first test, code named
"Rebound," is set for June 18, 1996. Hydronuclear tests involve high explosives
and a nuclear component such as plutonium. The US maintains that, because the
tests have no "nuclear yield," they are not nuclear explosions. Anti-nuclear
groups condemned the US decision, contending that it makes a mockery of the
global moratorium on nuclear testing. Such explosions can, in fact, produce a
small fission reaction. Greenpeace New Zealand campaigner Stephanie Mills
warned that such tests "could be a death knell for the compre-hensive test ban
talks" slated for early 1996. Environmentalists are urging President Clinton to
halt the tests and keep his promise to uphold the US moratorium.

<A NAME="Near"><H2>Near Melt-Down Revealed in UK</H2>

UK (Via EcoNet) -- On July 31, 1993, Reactor 1 at the Wylfa nuclear power
station on the island of Anglesey in North Wales came close to a melt-down.
During routine refueling, part of a crane broke and fell into the reactor,
causing a blockage. Nuclear Electric, the plant's operator, initially rated the
problem "zero" on an international scale used for assessing nuclear events (the
top of the scale, a seven, is reserved for disasters like Chernobyl). Two years
after the fact, Nuclear Electric officials admitted that they had waited nearly
ten hours before shutting the reactor down. According to a BBC-TV report last
September report recorded by the Media Monitoring and Transcription Service,
the delay occurred because the managers "put money before safety." A Crown
Court was told that "only luck" prevented a reactor core melt-down. The
government-owned utility ultimately pleaded guilty to four violations of
Britain's Health and Safety Act. The BBC reported that the revelation "comes at
a highly sensitive time for the nuclear industry as it heads towards
privatization."

<A NAME="Sabotaged"><H2>Sabotaged Reporter Wins Suit</H2>

USA -- In 1986, San Francisco reporter J. A. Savage was fired from her job as
West coast correspondent of McGraw-Hill's Energy User News and subsequently
kicked off the nuclear-power beat by her new employers at the
Knight-Ridder-owned Journal of Commerce. Savage discovered that her employment
problems stemmed from phone calls placed by officials at Pacific Gas & Electric
(PG&E), who objected to Savage's past work as an anti-nuclear activist. Savage
sued for damages, charging slander, libel and contract interference. In
November, after an eight-year battle, PG&E agreed to settle out of court. As
San Francisco Bay Guardian publisher and PG&E critic Bruce Brugmann observed,
Savage's victory "established a major First Amendment precedent protecting
reporters and the free press. We are all in her debt."

<A NAME="The"><H2>The Colonel Bombs in Bangalore</H2>

India -- Pepsi Foods Ltd.'s attempt to open the first Kentucky Fried Chicken
outlet in Karnataka state has run afoul of the Ban-galore City Corporation. The
Colonel's "secret recipe" was found to contain impermissibly high levels of
monosodium glutamate. KFC was also condemned by the State Farmers'
Organization, former Indian Environment Minister Maneka Gandhi and Vandana
Shiva, director of the Research Foundation for Science, Technology and Natural
Resource Policy. Gandhi and Shiva warned against the health, cultural and
environmental risks of admit-ting "junk food" conglomerates into India.

<A NAME="EPA"><H2>EPA's PCB Cover-up</H2>

USA -- The Missouri-based Times Beach Action Group (TBAG) has charged that at
least one fourth of the dioxin-contaminated soil from a 1972 chemical spill at
Times Beach, Missouri also contains polychlorinated biphenyls (PCB) in
concentrations up to a thousand times higher than the levels of dioxin.
According to the Compost-Dispatch newsletter [Gateway Green Alliance, PO Box
8094, St. Louis, MO 63156], records uncovered by TBAG suggest that "the EPA has
participated with corporations in a cover-up that spans at least two decades."
Compost-Dispatch reports that one letter confirms that the EPA and Monsanto
scientists shared "lab reports and physical samples" as early as the summer of
1972. The documents reveal that the EPA has been aware of PCB contamination in
the Times Beach soil for more than 20 years and secretly worked with scientists
at Monsanto's research labs to test soil samples for contamination a decade
before the government ordered the evacuation of Times Beach residents.<P>

See Also <A HREF="w95-03.html#Gulp">"Gulp War" Syndrome</A>,<BR>
<A HREF="w95-04.html#Reaching">Reaching-for-an-Angle Award</A>

<A NAME="Canadian"><H2>Canadian Cod-Saver Jailed</H2>

Canada -- On October 10, Sea Shepherd Conservation Society head Paul Watson was
convicted of "simple mischief" and sentenced to serve 30 days in a
maximum-security jail in Newfoundland. Watson was found guilty of firing a
fusillade of stink bombs to prevent a Cuban trawler from fishing in the
spawning grounds of the endangered North Atlantic cod. Watson was cleared of
two charges of criminal mischief and fined $35. The judge admitted that many
Canadians saw Watson as a "patriot," but ordered him  jailed to send the
message that "no Canadian has the right to take the law into their own hands."
One year after Watson's action, the Canadian government began boarding foreign
ships and arresting fishing crews in the Grand Banks. "Instead of going to
jail," author Farley Mowat (Never Cry Wolf) objected, "Paul Watson should be
given the Order of Canada, the highest civilian award."

<A NAME="Free"><H2>Free Trade Buys a Country</H2>

Costa Rica -- "In the last two years," reports InterPress Service, "more than
ten of Costa Rica's largest companies have been sold to transnational
corporations." CPC International, the world's third-largest food company,
bought out Productos Lizano, maker of the country's most popular brand of
tomato sauce. Phillip Morris wrested control of chocolate and jam maker El
Gallito Industrial (which had been owned by the same family since 1909).
Foreign companies have also seized control of the country's largest bakery, ice
cream maker and tuna cannery. Nestle, the multinational food giant, reportedly
is prepared to take over the country's Milk Producers
Cooperative.<BR>		-- GS


