<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Light Snacks: Eat 'em or Heat 'em</TITLE>

<H1>Light Snacks: Eat 'em or Heat 'em</H1>

Everyone knows that "food is fuel," but when it comes to some of the most popular
corporate snack foods, the catch-phrase is more than a metaphor. While nacho
chips may be intended to go down the hatch, at the touch of a match, they will
also go up in smoke. The fact is that some tortilla chips can take off like wood
chips.<P>

The <B>Journal</B> recently put some of the most hotly advertised corporate crackers and
chips to a competitive test. The goal was to answer the burning question: "Which
snack offers more combustibility-for-the-buck?" To settle the matter, we
conducted, not a bake-off, but a "flame-off."<P>

Our initial tests -- pitting two popular crackers against two popular chips --
produced the following results.<P>

Under standard, laboratory flame-off conditions, a Triscuit wafer burned for 15
seconds, a Cheez-It flickered for 46 seconds, a Frito-Lay potato chip flared for
1.3 minutes and a Dorito burned with a steady orange flame for an amazing 3.5
minutes. While the crackers were merely singed, the potato and corn chips both
burned vigorously. The Dorito was almost totally consumed.<P>

A six-ounce, 120-chip bag of Frito-Lay potato chips contains 60 grams of fat,
nearly matching theUS recommended 65-gram "daily value" (DV) for fat intake.
While fat comprises more that one-third of every bag of chips, there is no
Surgeon General's warning not to eat an entire bag in a single day. Instead,
Frito-Lay bags sport a cartoon of Bugs Bunny challeng-ing: "Betcha Can't Eat Just
One, (TM) Doc."<P>

Another problem: Dr. Michael F. Jaco-son of the Center for Science in the Public
Interest (CSPI) notes that "the bad trans fat is not included" on nutrition
labels.<P>

A single Dorito is a virtual "fat grenade." A 4.5-ounce, 50-chip bag of Doritos
contains 31 grams of fat, nearly half the DV total. But there is more to a Dorito
than fat. Following the flame-off test, the burn site revealed that the
incinerated chip left behind a long trail of a slick, sticky fluid. The oily
track resembled grease but, because it had not burned, it could not have been
fat. A spokesperson at Dorito headquarters in Texas had no idea what the mystery
residue was.<P>

If Doritos are one-quarter fat while potato chip are one-third fat, why do
Doritos out-flame chips? The spokesperson had an answer: Doritos are "much
thicker than a potato chip" and spuds are "full of water."<P>

Based on <B>EIJ</B>'s "flame-off" tests, campers would be well advised to carry Doritos
along on their next wilderness expedition -- not for food, but for starting
campfires. (Why use woodchips when corn chips will do? It's better for the
forests and it's certainly better for your health.)<P>

And here's a tip for the confirmed urbanite: the next time the power fails, don't
bother fumbling around for candles. Just light a Dorito. 			 -- GS<P>

<H2>What You Can Do</H2><P>

For more information about healthy food choices, contact CSPI, Suite 300, 1875
Connecticut Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20009-5728; (202) 332-9110.

