<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Pesticide Protest Targets Markets</TITLE>

<H1>Pesticide Protest Targets Markets</H1>

Last November, Food & Water, Inc. (FWI), a grassroots food safety organization,
launched a national campaign to convince supermarkets to stop selling foods grown
with toxic and carcinogenic chemicals.<P>

"We're going directly to the supermarket industry to stop toxic pesticides," FWI
explained. The targeted supermarket chains are Albertson's, Safeway, Hy-Vee,
Kroger, Winn-Dixie, Grand Union and Shaw's.<P>

By selling fruits and vegetables grown with dangerous chemicals, supermarket
corporations enable agribusiness to steadily increase its use of dangerous
pesticides. Meanwhile, supermarket corporations have lobbied the  government to
ease pesticide regulations. As a result, federal regulators currently assess risk
without considering real-life factors, such as multiple exposures to different
pesticides and children's increased sensitivity to toxic chemicals.<P>

"Despite what we know about how toxic pesticides are poisoning us and our
environment, federal regulations still protect corporations, not people," said
FWI executive director Michael Colby. "But when the public calls on supermarket
corporations to do something about the pesticide problem, supermarkets will
answer... We're going to do what Washington won't."<P>

Food & Water promoted the campaign last summer and fall with advertisements in
<B>The New York Times</B> and other national publications highlighting the connections
between increased pesticide use and rising cancer rates.<P>

The US cancer rate is approaching one in 2.5. Cancer incidence has increased
almost 50 percent in the last 50 years. At the same time, pesticide use in the US
has grown almost 33 times. In 1993, at least 71 active ingredients in pesticides
used on US food crops were known to cause cancer in humans or animals.<P>

<H2>What You Can Do</H2><P>

For more information, contact: FWI, RR 1, Box 68D, Walden, VT 05873; (802)
563-3300; fax (802) 563-3310.

