<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Chindogu Awards</TITLE>

<H1>Chindogu Awards</H1>

<I>Chindogu</I> is the Japanese-word for a "completely worthless invention." The
Journal salutes two new Chindogu Award winners.

<H2>Hooked on Petrol</H2>

Worried about your electric vehicle (EV) running out of electrons? Fisher
Electric Motor Technology, Inc. has just what you need. The <B>Fisher Ranger</B>,
an electrical generator that hooks to the back of a car, produces 13.5 kW of
power to recharge your EV as you tool down the road. Some purists might be
bothered by the fact that the Ranger's 20 hp motor is fueled by gasoline.<P>

<H2>Checkout Clerks, Please Check-Out</H2>

Symbol Technologies Inc. believes that its hand-held <B>Portable Personal Shopper</B>
will help "speed shoppers through the checkout line" by allowing them to scan
package prices directly as they pluck items off the shelves. Store managers love
the concept: it should lower overhead costs by helping to speed checkout
personnel to the unemployment line.<P>

<H2>Old Chindogus Never Die</H2>

Last year, Sandia Labs made news (and our last <B>Chindogu</B> list) by
demonstrating a "<B>Goo Gun</B>" designed to immobilize people under streams of
sticky, swelling foam. Were US tax dollars well-spent on this technology? The
question might better be: were tax dollars <B>re</B>-spent on this technology?
The <B>Journal</B> recently uncovered a Sandia Labs document bragging about the
"Taffy Machine," which generates "a sticky foam personnel barrier [that] quickly
fills the protected area, leaving little room for the intruder to maneuver." The
document is dated January 8, 1979. Congrats to Sandia for showing how easy it is
to make big bucks through recycling. (Goo-guns, meanwhile, are slated for use by
US troops in Bosnia.) -- GS

