<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: McDonald's in Cyberspace</TITLE>

<H1>McDonald's in Cyberspace</H1>

USA -- The McDonald's Corporation is now on-line. "McFamily," a "family-friendly
computer community" featuring "information about parenting" leavened with
corporate plugs and a catalog of "McStuff" for sale via an 800-number.
McFamily's "Hey Kids" activity area offers downloadable computer games,
contests and news on upcoming Happy Meals.<P>

David Green, McDonald's senior vice president for marketing, predicted that
McFamily "will provide us with a new way to communicate and build stronger
relationships with our customers." "McFacts About McDonald's" answers
frequently asked questions and puts a positive spin on "McDonald's and the
environment."<P>

A "Share A Thought" feature invites users to "submit their own contributions."
There is little chance of any anti-McDonald's opinions making it into the
corporate chat room. All suggestions "will be reviewed by the McFamily editor
before they are posted."<P>

Meanwhile, in London, the two-year-old "McLibel Trial" of two activists charged
with slandering the multinational food giant (</B A HREF="?">Winter '94-95 EIJ</A>), has now
become the longest trial in the history of the British Empire.
<HR>

