<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: US Patents Human Beings</TITLE>

<H1>US Patents Human Beings</H1>

USA -- In 1995, the National Institutes of Health patented the genes of a member
of the Indigenous Hagahai tribe in Papua New Guinea (US patent 5,397,696),
marking the first time that any country has claimed genetic ownership of a
citizen of another country. A Solomon Islands citizen is also subject to a
similar US patent.<P>

The genetic material was obtained by the Human Genome Diversity Project (dubbed
the "Vampire Project"), which seeks to collect blood and tissue samples from
more than 700 Indigenous groups. While UN-ESCO's Bioethics Committee is opposed
to such acts of "bio-colonialism," US Department of Commerce Secretary Ron
Brown has declared that "Under our laws... human cells [are] patentable...." <P>

"The veneer of the HGDP as an acade-mic, non-commercial exercise has been
shattered," the Rural Advancement Foundation International declared. RAFI noted
that a California-based firm has already sold blood drawn from Tristan De Cunha
islanders to Germany's Boeh-ringer Ingelheim medical firm for $70 million.
"This patent is another major step down the road to the commodification of
life," said RAFI's Pat Roy Mooney. RAFI is preparing a World Court challenge to
the patenting of human genetic material.<P>

<HR>

