<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: The Sun Can Save a Million Lives</TITLE>

<H1>The Sun Can Save a Million Lives</H1>

USA -- Two million children die each year because one billion of the Earth's
people lack access to safe drinking water. When a cholera epidemic hit Peru in
1994, health officials ordered residents to boil drinking water for ten
minutes. Unfortunately, doing so would consume nearly one-third of a poor
household's income. In countries lacking utilities, water must be boiled by
burning firewood, coal or coke. Because it takes a kilogram (2.2 pounds) of
wood to boil each liter (1.1 quarts) of water, the result is often rampant
deforestation.<P>

But it is not necessary to boil water to prevent disease. It is now known that
"solar water pasteurization" can kill disease-causing microbes. Temperatures of
149* F (65* C) -- far below the boiling point of 212* F (100* C) -- are
sufficient to kill worms, giardia, E. coli, cholera, polioviruses and the
hepatitis A virus.<P>

While these temperatures can be obtained easily in cheap, simply built solar
box cookers, it is difficult to determine precisely when the device becomes hot
enough to pasteurize the water. It is easy to see when water boils, but
impossible to see when a microbe dies.<P>

<B>Solar Box Journal</B> [7036 18th Avenue, NE, Seattle, WA 98115] recently announced
a breakthrough that should make "solar pasteurization" as simple and safe as
boiling water.<P>

A water pasteurization indicator consisting of a clear plastic tube filled with
solidified soybean fat is placed in the bottom of the water container. When the
water temperature reaches 69* C., the fat melts and the water is safe to drink.
Dr. Bob Metcalf at Solar Cookers International [1324 43rd St., Sacramento, CA
95819] reports that it "takes about four hours to pasteurize a gallon of water
in the summer." Metcalf notes that these cheap temperature tubes will protect
lives and "save much fuel... wasted by excessive heating."

<HR>

