<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Bio-Watch</TITLE>

<H1>Bio-Watch</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Whales">No More Whales in 100 Years?</A>
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Sagebrush">Sagebrush on the Summits?</A>: global warming 
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Weed">Weed Rather Dye</A>: eco-friendly industrial development
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Hazed">Hazed and Confused</A>: pollution and frog eggs.
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Fertilizing">Fertilizing Frogs to Death</A>: ammonium nitrate fertilizer and frogs.
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#No">No More Bull...</A>: bull-fighting
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Do">Do Released Fish Survive?</A>
<LI><A HREF="w95-14.html#Nuclear">Nuclear Plant's "Quasimodo Fish"</A>:
</UL>

<A NAME="Whales"><H2>No More Whales in 100 Years?</H2>

United Kingdom -- The London-based Environmental Investigation Agency (EIA)
[1611 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Suite 3B, Washington, DC 20009; (202) 483-6621]
has warned of "a major environmental catastrophe" that could lead to the
extinction of 12 species of great whales and 69 other whale and dolphin
species. Whales are being "starved as global warming destroys aquatic
ecosystems and overfishing decimates their food supply," EIA charged. Toxic
wastes, heavy metals and organochlorines continue to pour into the seas, and
EIA cites new evidence that whales are now being "scorched by UV-B radiation"
coming through the hole in the ozone layer. EIA concluded that the Earth's
"whales, dolphins and porpoises are threatened with absolute extinction within
the next century unless action is taken now."

<A NAME="Sagebrush"><H2>Sagebrush on the Summits?</H2>

USA -- For the last five years, scientists at the University of California at
Berkeley (UCB) have been baking a 9580-foot-high meadow in the Colorado Rockies
under the glare of infrared heat lamps. The lamps are meant to duplicate the
3-8 degree Fahrenheit (1.5 to 4.5*C) temperature rise predicted over the next
50 years due to global warming. "To get an idea of the effect of global warming
could have on mountain meadows," UCB energy and resources professor John Harte
explained, "imagine the opening scenes of <B>The Sound of Music</B> filmed outside
Elko, Nevada." Under the influence of the heat lamps, sagebrush typically found
2000 feet lower on the mountain replaced the meadow's lush carpet of flowers.
Harte notes that since "sagebrush absorbs more sunlight than most forbs
[non-woody flowing plants] it replaces," this could trigger "a positive
feedback, causing more warming."

<A NAME="Weed"><H2>Weed Rather Dye</H2>

India -- In the late 1960s, the pesky Mexican banmara weed (<I>Euphatorium
adenophorum</I>) reached South Asia along with a load of wheat shipped under a US
food-aid program. Banmara took root and flourished, invading woodlands,
pastures and tea gardens, defying all eradication attempts. <B>Himal</B> magazine
reports that Darjeeling environmentalist Umesh Dwivedi has a plan "to turn this
ecological menace into a resource that can be used for the economic benefit of
rural folks, employment generation and eco-friendly industrial development."
The plant has been found to produce a "commercially viable" green dye. Dwivedi
also has managed to process banmara into handmade paper.

<A NAME="Hazed"><H2>Hazed and Confused</H2>

USA -- Scientist Forest M. Mims III has warned that a hazy or cloudy sky can be
more dangerous than a clear sky to sun-sensitive amphibians. "A very hazy sky
can be the source for between 85 and 90 percent of the UV-B striking Earth,
with only between 10 and 15 percent coming directly from the sun," Mims
informed <B>New Scientist</B>. Frog eggs are known to be harmed by exposure to UV-B
and, with hazy air now found over major portions of the US and Europe, Mims
believes that "shade-seeking organisms probably now receive considerably more
UV-B than before the industrial era."

<A NAME="Fertilizing"><H2>Fertilizing Frogs to Death</H2>

United Kingdom -- Every spring, British farmers spread 1.8 million tons of
ammonium nitrate fertilizer granules over their fields -- at just about the time
that frogs begin migrating. After witnessing the "horrific" deaths of frogs
that blundered into fields salted with nitrates, Rob Oldham of Leicester's De
Monttort University established a link between the use of chemical fertilizers
and what <B>BBC Wildlife</B> has called a "massive epidemic of frog deaths in the UK."
Oldham believes that "by being absorbed, the fertilizers affect the balance of
chemicals in [the frogs'] moist skin. They suffer a massive toxic attack." If
true, frogs risk being fertilized to death not only in the UK, but also around
the world.

<A NAME="No"><H2>No More Bull...</H2>

Mexico -- Representatives of more than 350 animal rights groups from 75
countries gathered in Mexico City last October for Latin America's first-ever
Conference to End Bullfighting. Animal activist Bridgitte Bardot called
bullfighting "a cruel, archaic and degrading spectacle." The World Society for
the Protection of Animals [29 Perkins St., PO Box 190, Boston, MA 02130; (617)
522-7000] convened the conference under the slogan "Torture is NOT Culture."
Mexico, the heart of Latin America's bullfighting culture, boasts the world's
largest bullfighting ring and Mexico's bullfighting establishment did not take
kindly to the conference. Three hotels refused to host the conference and the
meeting proceeded under threats of violence.

<A NAME="Do"><H2>Do Released Fish Survive?</H2>

USA -- "Release-fishing is catching on as never before," reports <B>Marlin: the
International Sportfishing Magazine</B> [PO Box 2456, 330 W. Canton Avenue, Winter
Park, FL 32789-3195]. As populations of ocean fish plummet, "a growing number
of anglers are releasing fish voluntarily in order to conserve fish. 'Limiting
their kill,' as they say, instead of 'killing their limit.' " But if those fish
do not survive the trauma of capture, <B>Marlin</B> notes, catch-and-release "becomes
just a 'feel-good' gesture and nothing more." A fish that swims away after
being released may look like a "survivor," but 24 hours later, it could be
dead. To improve the chances of survival, <B>Marlin</B> suggests using high-speed
lures rather than baited, barbed hooks. Hooks containing toxic tin and cadmium
should be avoided, and a fish should not be fought to the point of exhaustion.

<A NAME="Nuclear"><H2>Nuclear Plant's "Quasimodo Fish"</H2>

Taiwan -- Fishing has been banned near the cooling-system outlet of the Taiwan
Power Corporation's Number Two nuclear plant, but Fan Jeng-Tang, of the Taiwan
Environmental Protection Union, decided to see what he could reel in. <B>Nuclear
Report from Taiwan</B> published photos of mutated therapon -- a fish that usually
reaches ten centimeters. Today the fish never grow larger than 5-6 centimeters.
They also are distinguished by twisted bodies and "a disgusting lump resembling
a camel's hump." Local fishermen claim that they regularly find these "Q-fish"
(short for "Quasimodo-fish") floating dead on the waters near the General
Electric-built nuclear plant. The most likely culprits are the excessively high
temperatures produced by cooling water flowing out of the plant. Shellfish and
seaweed also have nearly disappeared from the vicinity.

<HR>

