<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Mexico's Deadlist Predator?</TITLE>

<H1>Mexico's Deadlist Predator?</H1>

Mexico -- Jorge Hank Rhon, the son of former Mexican cabinet minister and
billionaire Carlos Hank Gonzales, loves wildlife -- dead or alive. "Animals are
my only vice," Hank likes to brag. That may be an understatement. According to
<B>Latinamerica Press</B> reporter John Ross, Hank is "one of Mexico's premier
traffickers in rare and endangered species."<P>

Last year, Hank was caught at Mexico City's International Airport with a dozen
suitcases filled with ivory tusks and two ocelot-skin coats. It takes six
ocelots to make a single coat. Despite the fact that ocelots are an endangered
species in Mexico (there are only 300 left in the country), Hank was held only
a few hours.<P>

Mexico boasts the world's greatest number of mammal (448) and reptile (717)
species, but 34 percent of the mammal population now faces extinction due to
the pressures of development, pollution, hunting and animal traffickers like
Hank.<P>

Hank and David Ibarra, the son of a former finance minister, opened Promotora
Beta, an exotic pet emporium that displayed endangered birds and manatees.
Investigators from the Convention of International Trade in Endangered Species
of Wild Flora and Fauna (CITES) found that 40 percent of Promotora's exotic
birds were endangered species. In 1989, Promotora Beta served as a way-station
in an international conspiracy to ship endangered birds from Indonesia, through
Singapore, Japan, Spain and Costa Rica. The birds (as many as 500 a month) were
then smuggled into the US aboard private yachts, netting $2 million a month.<P>

Hank has a way of surviving criticism. An inspection into Promotora Beta's sale
of puma cubs ended abruptly when the lead inspector was mysteriously murdered.
In 1988, Hector Felix Miranda, a columnist for the Tijuana weekly Zeta, was
gunned down by two of Hank's security guards after writing too many critical
columns. The guards were sent to prison for 25 years. Hank avoided
investigation.<P>

Hank and Ibarra also hatched plans for a wild animal park called Reino Aventura
and illegally acquired an orca to serve as their star attraction. The park was
sold to Mexico's media conglomerate Tele-visa and the whale, "Keiko," went on
to international fame as the star of the film <A HREF="../immp/keiko.html">Free Willy</A>.<P>

-- John Ross,  Latinamerica Press [Apartado 18-0964, Lima 18, Peru. For
subscriptions, contact: SoNo/LAP, PO Box 410150, San Francisco, CA 94141].<P>

