<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Bomb Blasts Turtle Activists</TITLE>

<H1>Bomb Blasts Turtle Activists</H1>

Greece -- Last summer, the Sea Turtle Protection Society of Greece [STPS, 35
Solomou Street, GR-106 82 Athens, Greece; tel/fax: 01-3844 146] presented a
petition signed by 51,000 tourists demanding that the Greek government
establish a National Marine Park on the island of Zakynthos, the most important
Mediterranean nesting site for loggerhead turtles. The government, which has
been slow to resist powerful development interests, now risks being taken
before the European Court for failing to demolish a number of illegal buildings
constructed on a nesting beach.<P>

Over the last five years, Zakynthos' turtle defenders have been shot at and
beaten and their offices have been set afire. Verbal harassment and telephone
threats increased over the summer as the Zakynthos prefectural council prepared
to approve a plan to create a marine park at Laganas bay, a critical nesting
beach for the loggerhead turtle (<I>Caretta caretta</I>).<P>

On September 29, five days before the scheduled prefectural council vote, 1.5
kilos (3.3 lbs.) of dynamite were placed on the roof of the STPS and Zakynthos
Ecological Movement (ZOK) office. The terrorist bomb ripped into the building
while 15 ZOK staffers and three children were working on the organization's
newsletter. Most escaped serious injury, but architect Nikos Lykouresis, one of
ZOK's founding members, was wounded.<P>

Local activists reported via EcoNet that environmentalists "have been the
target of an unprecedented defamation campaign led by local politicians closely
tied with interest groups opposed to any regulations on the tourist development
of Zakynthos' coastal areas." Only hours before the attack, the EcoNet dispatch
noted, one pro-development politician called for "throwing all ecologists out
of Zakynthos."<P>

Greenpeace spokesman Elias Efthimio-poulos complained that the local police had
"tolerated" violence against the environmentalists and had "at times, reversed
reality by treating the victims as villains."<P>

Such acts of hostility, however, are not typical. According to the <B>Athens
News</B> "most Zakynthos residents, as well as the local hoteliers' chamber,
support the marine park." The European Union has also promised funding for the
proposed park.<P>

Despite the bombing, park advocates remained optimistic. As the October 4 vote
neared, it was expected that the park plan would be passed. To everyone's
shock, however, the council rejected the Environment Ministry's proposal,
calling instead for more "dialogue." The council's turnaround could doom any
chance of progress on creating the marine park -- GS

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

Express your concerns to Minister of the Environment Konstantinos Laliotis,
Physical Planning and Public Works, Amaliados 17, 115 21 Athens, Greece; fax:
30-1-645-1793. Send copies of your letters to STPS. To join STPS as an
international volunteer at the Sea Turtle Rescue Center in Glyfada, contact
STPS' Athens office. Minimum four-week assignments run from mid-May through
October and involve work on nesting beaches in Zakyn-thos, Crete and
Peloponnesus.<P>

