<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: The "Next Clayoquot Sound"</TITLE>

<H1>The "Next Clayoquot Sound"</H1>

Canada -- On September 28, three hereditary Nuxalk chiefs were jailed for 23 days
after blocking a logging road under construction in the Fog Creek region of
British Columbia's King Island.<P>

International Forest Products (Interfor) plans to log 2340 forest acres over
the next 30 years. The chiefs claim that the sales are illegal since the
2000-member Nuxalk tribe never signed a treaty with the Canadian government and
never ceded its sovereignty. "We have exhausted all domestic efforts," chief Ed
Moody declared. "Our only recourse is international opinion."<P>

"As hereditary chiefs, it is our obligation to protect this land for our
children and grandchildren," said Chief Charlie Nelson. "At one time, the
wildlife, fish and plants of our land supported 30,000 people," Moody declared.
"Why would we want to embrace the corporate alternative [when the] monetary
option hasn't worked?" Nuxalk elder Lawrence Pootlass pointed out that the
timber sale encompasses a Nuxalk sacred site -- the spot where tribal lore holds
that the first woman descended to Earth from heaven.<P>

Interfor Vice President Fred Lowenberger sees no reason not to log the area.
"The rate of reproduction growth is incredible in this part of the world," he
told the <B>San Francisco Chronicle</B>. "You could pave the forest and it would still
come back."<P>

On December 5, the chiefs and 19 other Nuxalk elders and supporters, including
members of the Forest Action Network, walked out on their Supreme Court trial.<P>

"The court was forcing us into their system and handcuffing our sovereignty,"
chief Moody explained. "The white man's court system cannot define our people.
Our law allows us to protect our land; their law allows destruction."<P>

Supreme Court Justice Smith refused to issue arrest warrants and rescheduled
the trial for January 15.

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

Contact Premier Mike Harcourt, Legislative Buildings, Victoria, BC, V8V 1X4;
fax: (604) 387-0087. Assembly of First Nations; fax: (613) 241-5807/8.
Rainforest Action Network, 450 Sansome St., #700, San Francisco, CA 94111;
(415) 398-4404.

