<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Farmers Snub US; Tokyo Retaliates</TITLE>

<H1>Farmers Snub US; Tokyo Retaliates</H1>

Ryukyu -- Although they comprise less than one percent of Japan's territory,
Okinawa's 125 islands host 75 of the 100 US bases and two-thirds of the 45,500
US soldiers in Japan. Much of the islands' best agricultural land now lies
buried beneath US barracks, roads and airfields.<P>

"Toxic wastes and other forms of pollution from military industries have
destroyed much of the islands' environment," reports Antonia Levi, a professor
of history and Asian studies at Whitman College in Washington state. "Noise
from firing ranges is a constant irritant and accidents from unexploded shells
are a fact of life."<P>

The rape of a 12-year-old Okinawan schoolgirl, allegedly by three US soldiers,
has become a symbol of what many Okinawans see as the abuse of their homeland
by the US military. Until it was annexed by Japan in 1869, the region was known
as Ryukyu -- the name still preferred by the native people. After WW II, the US
set up a puppet government and occupied Okinawa as a military staging area. The
US returned Okinawa to Japan's control in 1972.<P>

With the first of the Pentagon's leases on private land in Okinawa set to
expire in March, 2937 farmers and landowners have vowed not to renew their
contracts.<P>

A US military intelligence-gathering site sits on a 200-sq-meter (2200 sq. ft.)
plot of land owned by 47-year-old Shoichi Chibana. Chibana has refused to renew
the lease, the first set to expire. "We don't need any military bases in
Okinawa," Chibana told the Japan Times. The land was given to him by his
father, a pacifist who was forced to lease the land to the US in 1972.<P>

Chibana contends that the US-Japan security treaty "violates [Japan's] pacifist
Constitution," which bans military collaboration with other nations.<P>

In 1972, Okinawan pacifists began selling small strips of land as a means of
thwarting expropriation attempts. Today nearly 3000 people lay claim to 1557
sq. meters (17,127 sq. ft.) inside Kadena air base and another 67 sq. meters
(737 sq. ft.) at Futenma air base.<P>

In November, under increasing US pressure to resolve the dispute, Japanese
Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama began steps to force landowners to renew the
leases. When Okinawan Governor Masahide Ota refused to authorize the leases,
Murayama began a legal process to overrule the local government and force the
farmers to comply. Ota has vowed to raise "constitutional questions" about
Murayama's actions.<P>

Many Japanese are questioning the need and the cost of a continued US armed
presence. Japan Times reports that Japan pays 70 percent of the expense of
maintaining US troops on its soil, a sum estimated to top Yen625 billion ($6.7
billion) a year.<P>

"The real threat for all countries is the instability caused by poverty,"
international affairs writer Yoko Kitagawa informed the San Francisco
Chronicle. Kitagawa is among a growing number of Japanese citizens that
believes the money Japan spends on supporting the US military would be better
spent on domestic social welfare programs.<BR>-- GS

<H2>What You Can Do</H2>

On November 19, a coalition of academics and peace and environmental activists
called for the removal of US bases in Japan and Okinawa. Contact: Foreign Bases
Project, c/o the East Timor Action Project, PO Box 150753, Brooklyn, NY
11215-0014; (718) 788-6071; Email: fbp@igc.apc.org.


