<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: US Radiation Expert Beats Ban</TITLE>

<H1>US Radiation Expert Beats Ban</H1>

United Kingdom -- A leading American scientist, who has challenged the medical
and nuclear establishments on the dangers of low-level radiation, is at the
center of a dispute over his latest research.<P>

On the basis of detailed scientific analysis, Dr. John Gofman, Professor
Emeritus of Molecular and Cell Biology in the University of California at
Berkeley, concluded that approximately three-quarters of current cases of
breast cancer in the US are caused by previous exposure to ionizing radiation --
primarily medical X-rays. Cancer cases being diagnosed now, he says, can be
attributed to exposure from as many as 40 years ago.<P>

Gofman says breast cancer is a largely preventable disease. But he stresses
that this does not mean that women should avoid X-rays when needed. The problem
is that many radiology units give patients ten, 20 or even 50 times the dose
needed to obtain a good X-ray image. Because government authorities have set
radiation exposure levels far higher than warranted, Gofman maintains, they do
not accept that these dose levels constitute a serious risk.<P>

Soon after publication of the results in his 1995 book, <B>Preventing Breast
Cancer</B> [Committee for Nuclear Responsibility, PO Box 421993, San Francisco, CA.
1995], Britain's 20-20 Television approached Gofman with plans for a
documentary on his findings, with supporting evidence from research in the US,
Israel and Britain.<P>

A storm broke out when <B>20-20 Television</B> asked Britain's official radiation
watchdog, the National Radiological Protection Board (NRPB), to take part in
the program. The NRPB refused, saying, "We feel Dr. Gofman's report is so poor
that we do not want to be associated with it." It then released information to
London newspapers designed to undermine the credibility of Gofman and the
proposed documentary.<P>

The NRPB even approached Britain's TV authorities seeking to have the program
banned, but were rebuffed.<P>

The film, <B>The X-Ray Effect</B>, was broadcast nationwide in Britain on August 3. In
it, the associate director of the Radiation Effects Research Foundation in
Hiroshima described Gofman as "a superb analyst [who] has always been at the
cutting edge of medical science, particularly when it comes to protecting
people."<P>

In a point-by-point rebuttal of the agency's criticisms, Gofman stated that
some of the arguments are simply untrue, while others misrepresented his
argument or ignored evidence in order to reach lower risk estimates that give
poorer protection of public health.<P>

"[I] agree that [my] estimates are indeed some ten times higher than those of
the NRPB," Gofman stated. "But no valid scientific analysis of the evidence
could possibly lead to the underestimates of the NRPB."<P>

Why has Britain's radiation watchdog gone to such lengths to stifle debate on
this issue? Gofman himself is clear: "Aside from the general activity of NRPB
in protecting the nuclear and radiology programs in the UK, there is a very
specific reason: they have not done the job they were supposed to be doing."<P>

-- Excerpted from <B>Cornerstones</B>, the newsletter of the Right Livelihood Award
Foundation, 5 Harrowby Court, Harrowby Street, London W1H 5FA, UK.


