<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Tropical Dams and Global Warming</TITLE>

<H1>Tropical Dams and Global Warming</H1>

"Hydropower plants produce no carbon dioxide... no air emissions at all."<BR>

-- US Department of Energy, 1994<P>

<HR>

In June 1995, Alison Bartle, co-editor of <B>The International Journal on
Hydropower & Dams</B>, told a dam-builders conference: "Each kilowatt-hour produced
from a gas-fired plant is accompanied by 600 grams of carbon dioxide (CO2)
emissions and for each kWh from a coal-fired plant the figure is as high as
1000 grams. The figure for a unit produced by hydro is, of course, zero."<P>

New research by Philip Fearnside, however, refutes dam industry claims that
hydropower is a zero-greenhouse-gas-emitting technology. Fearnside, of the
Brazilian National Institute for Research in Amazonia, reports in the academic
journal <B>Environmental Conservation</B> that the reservoirs behind tropical dams can
contribute far more to global warming than fossil-fuel-burning powerplants.<P>

Fearnside calculates that, in 1990, emissions of CO2 and methane from
vegetation rotting in the waters in the reservoir behind Brazil's Balbina dam
had 26 times more impact on global warming than the emissions from a coal-fired
power station generating the same amount of electricity.<P>

Emissions from the reservoir behind the Tucurui Dam, also in the Brazilian
Amazon, had only 60 percent as much impact on global warming in 1990 as an
equivalent coal-fired plant -- but 50 percent more impact than a gas-fired power
station. The 4000 megawatt Tucurui Dam is the world's tenth most-powerful hydro
dam. It has less impact on global warming than Balbina, since it floods far
less land per unit of electricity generated.<P>

Although CO2 releases from Balbina will slowly decline over the years as the
flooded trees decay, emissions will always be higher than those from equivalent
fossil-fuel powerplants. Fearnside notes that while only four large reservoirs
have been created in Brazilian Amazonia, another 75 dams are planned.
Fearnside's paper follows research published in 1993 showing that reservoirs in
northern Canada emit substantial amounts of CO2 and methane.<P>

"The social and environmental damage caused by large hydro was once justified
by dam proponents on the grounds that dams provided cheap power," says Patrick
McCully of International Rivers Network [IRN, 1847 Berkeley Way Berkeley, CA
94703 USA Tel: (510) 848-1155 Fax: (510) 848-1008]. Today, however, "private
investors are reluctant to fund large dams, favoring cheaper and less risky
smaller dams and gas-fired plants. In recent years the big-dam lobby has
adopted a new argument -- that hydropower should be supported by aid agencies
and governments because it is 'carbon-free.'<P>

"Dams such as Bakun in Malaysia and Nam Theun II in Laos are being justified on
the grounds that -- although they would uproot thousands of people and destroy
hundreds of square kilometers of forest -- they would provide 'clean' energy.
But the research from Amazonia and Canada shows that hydro-industry lobbyists
will have to think again."


<HR>

