<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Bringing home the Bakun</TITLE>

<H1>Bringing home the Bakun</H1>

Malaysia -- Last September, Sarawak Chief Minister Tan Sri Abdul Taid Mahmud
told a crowd of political supporters that a planned series of dams in the upper
Rajang basin would produce 5000Mw of electricity and make Sarawak the "hydro
powerhouse" of Malaysia. "We will be able to attract investors to set up an
aluminum plant which will bring benefits worth thousands of millions of ringgit
[the national currency]. We will also draw people to set up a pulp and paper
plant. We can build possibly the world's biggest integrated steel mill plant in
Sarawak."<P>

The 2400Mw Bakun, the first and largest of the planned dams, would flood the
homes of 9500 villagers. With the first evictions set for July 1997, the
government has still not explained where it plans to relocate the ousted
villagers.<P>

The crusading Malaysian monthly, <B>Utusan Konsumer</B>, reports that the chief
minister is one of the top 20 shareholders of Ekran Bhd, the single largest
partner in the Bakun dam project. The minister, as chair of the government's
Natural Resources and Environment Board, is also the one who set the conditions
for the dam, approved the environmental impact report and is responsible for
monitoring compliance. His two sons are also among the top 20 shareholders in
Ekran Bhd. The Chief Minister granted the contract to clear 17,750 hectares
(43,861 acres) of forest to Pacific Chemicals, a "sister company of Ekran Bhd."
And who are the major shareholders in Pacific Chemicals? The minister and his
two sons.<P>

On November 24, the government announced that dam construction would begin in
May, 1996, and take six years to complete. Companies  from Brazil, China,
Malaysia, France, Germany, Korea and Sweden have contracted to work on the dam.<P>

Construction will require the cutting of 27 million cubic meters (105 million
cubic feet) of timber. Ekran Bhd hopes to raise roughly $8.3 billion by selling
logging rights to private timber concessions.<P>

Meanwhile, Malaysia's economy is suffering and the state-owned power company
already generates more power than it can sell. The <B>Singapore Business Times</B>
reports that environmentalists fear that Ekran "may just log the huge timber
concession and not build the dam at all."<BR>-- GS


