<TITLE>Winter 95-96 Journal: Climate news cont'd</TITLE>

<H1>Climate news cont'd</H1>

Quick links:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="w95-19b.html#IPCC">IPCC Confirms Global Warming</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="w95-19b.html#Greenhouse">Greenhouse Goals "Insufficient"</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="w95-19b.html#US">US Solutions at Climate Talks</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="w95-19b.html#Asia">Asia to Become Greenhouse Threat</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="w95-19b.html#Could">Could the Earth's Climate "Flip?"</A><P>
<LI><A HREF="w95-19b.html#Greenpeace">Greenpeace Spurns Ozone Award</A><P>
</UL>

<A NAME="IPCC"><H2>IPCC Confirms Global Warming</H2>

Spain -- In late November, the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC)
announced at the conclusion of its meeting in Madrid that recent increases in
global temperature can no longer be attributed to natural "climatic
variations." Overcoming lobbying pressure from the "Carbon Club" of
industrialized countries, IPCC scientists declared that global warming is a
fact, it is already happening, and human beings are responsible. The IPCC,
whose work is peer-reviewed by 2500 of the world's leading scientists, warns
that "Climate change is likely to have wide-ranging and mostly adverse effects
on human health, with significant loss of life." Among the "potentially
irreversible" impacts, IPCC listed increased desertification, melting icecaps,
rising seas, widespread forest di-off and catastrophic species extinctions.

<A NAME="Greenhouse"><H2>Greenhouse Goals "Insufficient"</H2>

Japan -- Last October, delegates to the Third Local Government Leaders Summit
on Climate Change in Omiya, Japan, warned that "reductions of greenhouse gas
emissions, even as much as 50 percent, will not be sufficient to prevent global
climate change." The UN Framework Convention on Climate Change, signed by 153
countries at the 1992 Earth Summit in Rio de Janeiro, called for cutting
greenhouse gas emissions to 1990 levels by the year 2000. The Omiya delegates
labeled this goal insufficient and called on industrialized nations to reduce 
emissions by "20 percent from 1990 levels by 2005-2010."

<A NAME="US"><H2>US Solutions at Climate Talks</H2>

Switzerland-- Delegates to the IPCC's October-November climate negotiations in
Geneva heard dire warnings of rising costs from drought, hurricanes, typhoons
and disease. Droughts in China and Russia have cut  global grain harvests to
the lowest levels in 20 years, doubling  prices and driving up the cost of
imports. While the US delegation was criticized for obstructing attempts to
rein in fossil-fuel burning, a "working group" co-chaired by US and Zimbabwean
officials concluded that "significant reductions in net greenhouse gas
emissions are... economically feasible." Energy efficiency gains of 10-30
percent are possible at "no net cost in many parts of the world" and
"efficiency gains of 50-60 percent could be technically feasible" over the next
two-three decades.

<A NAME="Asia"><H2>Asia to Become Greenhouse Threat</H2>

Malaysia -- An eight-country study by the Asian Development Bank reports that
climate change could inundate coastal populations, contaminate fresh water
supplies, diminish food crops and flood Asia with millions of environmental
refugees. <B>Utusan Konsumer</B> magazine reports that Asia and the Pacific region
will soon become "the world's largest producer of greenhouse gas emissions,"
with half of the projected increase coming from industrial development alone.

<A NAME="Could"><H2>Could the Earth's Climate "Flip?"</H2>

Germany -- Researchers at the Institute of Marine Sciences at the University of
Kiel have warned that global warming could trigger a sudden climate "flip,"
ushering in a new Ice Age. If this were to occur, the Gulf Stream could reverse
its flow, causing Europe's temperature to drop by as much as five degrees
Celsius (41* Fahrenheit) -- about the same as during the last Ice Age.
Meanwhile, scientists at the Scott Polar Research Institute in Cambridge have
reported what appears to be a troubling, and possibly related, decline in the
strength of convection currents in the Greenland Sea.

<A NAME="Greenpeace"><H2>Greenpeace Spurns Ozone Award</H2>

Germany -- On October 24, Greenpeace Germany refused to accept the US
Environmental Protection Agency's Stratospheric Ozone Protection Award.<P>

Greenpeace Germany was offered the award for its role in developing hydrocarbon
refrigeration technology. Thanks to Greenpeace Germany's promotion of the
"Greenfreeze" technology, the German domestic refrigeration industry now uses
absolutely no ozone-depleting substances. US industry relies heavily on HCFCs
and US policy promotes the continued use of these ozone-depleting chemicals.
Some European countries plan to phase out HCFCs as early as 1998, while the US
insists that they are necessary until 2030.<P>

"While it gives us no great joy to decline this award, we felt that we simply
had no other option," said Greenpeace Germany's Wolfgang Lohbeck. "We simply
cannot accept an award for ozone protection from ozone destroyers.... The US
has led the way in promoting policies which will prolong damage to the ozone
layer. If the US modifies its position to the minimum that is necessary, we
will be pleased to accept their award in Vienna."<BR> 		      
-- GS

