<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Thousands Rally for Headwaters</TITLE>

<H1>Thousands Rally for Headwaters</H1>

<H2>by John Sterling</H2>

A teenage girl crossed the green borderline, stepped onto Pacific Lumber Company
(PL) property and joined the mass of forest advocates waiting for a Humboldt
County Deputy Sheriff to arrest them for trespassing. The girl turned, waved to a
middle-aged woman on the other side of the line, and said, "'Bye mom! I love
you!"<P>

The girl was one of 264 people, including a half-dozen juveniles, arrested
on September 15 during a protest against PL's plans to conduct salvage <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">logging</A> in
three of the six old-growth groves of Headwaters Forest, the largest unprotected
ancient redwood forest ecosystem in the world.<P>

"This is the largest forest-defense action in the history of the United States," Earth First! activist
Darryl Cherney told a jubilant crowd of roughly 2000 people. Supporters rallied
for several hours outside PL's Carlotta, California mill before setting off on a
1.5-mile march to the gates of Headwaters, where dozens of police waited to carry
out the arrests. For more than three hours, activists patiently awaited their
turn to pass through the police line and on to a temporary booking station set up
in a nearby field. Absent was the confrontation that has marked Northern
California timber protests in the past.<P>

"Environmental groups met with police for
many hours of planning before this event," said Ingrid Hanson, the Humboldt
County Sheriff's spokesperson. The result was a feel-good atmosphere that kept
the protest focused on timber issues, not on tensions between demonstrators and
police.<P>

<H3>Maxxamized Devastation</H3>

The struggle over Headwaters began in 1985, when Houston-based Maxxam Corporation
completed a hostile takeover of PL, a company known for its ecologically
sensitive logging practices. Maxxam CEO Charles Hurwitz financed the purchase of
PL with a $300 million bank loan and $450 million in high-interest "junk bonds."
He lured investors to the deal by promising to accelerate timber cutting and
terminate PL's $62 million employee pension fund to pay off the debt. Following
the takeover, PL tripled its timber cutting and has repeatedly threatened to log
the 72,000-acre Headwaters Forest, a complex that contains six ancient forest
groves totaling 5400 acres of old-growth redwoods. The forest is also prime
habitat for two endangered birds, the marbled murrelet and northern spotted owl,
while its streams are home to a dwindling population of coho salmon.<P>

Since 1987,
the Garberville-based Environmental Protection Information Center (EPIC) has
filed 14 lawsuits against PL, winning seven of them and helping to expose the
company's questionable forestry practices. In a landmark decision earlier this
year, a federal judge issued a permanent injunction against PL's logging in
Headwaters' Owl Creek Grove after EPIC established that the operation threatened
the habitat of the marbled murrelet and thus violated the federal Endangered
Species Act (ESA).<P>

Though litigation has slowed PL's assault on the redwoods, the
company has already managed to harvest 40,000 acres of old-growth from its
196,000-acre forest empire since the Maxxam takeover. "EPIC lawsuits are only a
temporary and limited reprieve for the ancient forests," said EPIC's Cecilia
Lanman. "Ultimate protection for Headwaters will only come from public support
and political pressure," she said.<P>

<H3>The "Headwaters Swap" Plan</H3>

The September 15 rally was scheduled to coincide with the end of the marbled
murrelet nesting season. Despite EPIC's victory in the marbled murrelet case, the
California Department of Forestry (CDF) subsequently issued a special exemption
permitting PL to log "dead or dying" trees from three of Headwaters' six groves
after September 15, without any public comment or environmental review. Many
foresters criticize such "salvage" logging operations because they ignore the
value of decaying trees to a forest ecosystem (see story on page 22) and note
that, because of their age, most old-growth trees could be considered "dying."<P>

The rally, sponsored by a coalition of more than 30 environmental, Native
American and social justice organizations, convened at noon before a backdrop of
logged trees and milled lumber. Speakers and musicians addressed the crowd,
encouraging ongoing support for forest protection. "Why is it when we destroy
something made by man, it's called vandalism, but when we destroy something made
by nature, it's called progress?" asked actor and environment activist Ed Begley,
Jr.<P>

Speakers pledged support for a proposed "debt-for-nature swap" that would
transfer Headwaters to protected public ownership. In August 1995, the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) filed a $250 million lawsuit against
Maxxam's Hurwitz for his alleged role in the 1988 collapse of United Savings
Association of Texas. United Savings, which suffered a $1.6 billion loss, was
bailed out by the FDIC using US taxpayer funds. In 1992, long before the FDIC
suit, Headwaters supporters suggested that the government could "forgive"
Hurwitz' debt to the American people in exchange for Headwaters Forest. Hurwitz
says that he is willing to sell Headwaters for $600 million, which he insists is
"fair market value."<P>

<H3>Bari at the Barricades</H3>

Earth First!er and timber war veteran Judi Bari echoed the debt-for-nature theme.
"Charles Hurwitz says he wants fair market value for Headwaters forest, but the
American taxpayers have already paid for it. We own it, now it's our job to
repossess it. We are the Earth repo team," she said.<P>

Bari explained that she
could not walk the 1.5 miles to the forest gate "thanks to Pacific
Lumber/Maxxam," referring to permanent injuries she sustained when a bomb
exploded in her car during the 1990 Redwood Summer anti-logging protests (the
bomber has still not been identified). But Bari was first in line when the
arrests began and when police led her to the booking area, the crowd responded
with a rousing and respectful cheer.<P>

While many of the marchers were experienced
forest advocates, the crowd was diverse. Among those joining the march was John
Maurer, a cabinetmaker from Carlotta who worked for PL until shortly after the
Maxxam takeover in 1985. Maurer is one of 20 plaintiffs in a lawsuit against PL
that aims to recover benefits from the employee pension fund that Hurwitz
liquidated to help pay off his bond debt.<P>

Over the years, Maurer observed, a
wider range of people has become active on the Headwaters issue. "The local media
tries to paint the protesters as a small group of fringe radicals. But look at
the numbers and look at the diversity," he said. Maurer noted that roughly five
percent of Carlotta's 400 residents attended the rally.

<H3>Battle in the Courts</H3>

As dawn broke on the morning of the protest, EPIC's lawyers were working
feverishly to obtain a temporary restraining order (TRO) to halt PL's plans to
log Headwaters. As evening set in and more than 200 people had been arrested,
EPIC's Laurel Sarachek scrambled onto the bed of a flatbed truck to announce that
US District Court Judge Maxine Chesney had granted a TRO for one week, during
which time EPIC would be allowed to argue its case.<P>

The jubilant crowd roared its
approval. A police officer asked Darryl Cherney if the protesters would now like
to halt the protest. Looking back at the line of people still awaiting arrest,
Cherney said, "Looks like there are still a lot of folks who want to get
arrested." The officer merely shrugged and said, "Whatever you say. We're a
full-service police force."<P>

On September 28, Judge Chesney, citing evidence
"sufficient to show a likelihood of jeopardizing" the endangered birds, issued a
Preliminary Injunction, temporarily halting new PL logging pending a federal
hearing. The ruling offered temporary protection to roughly 40,000 acres.<P>

On the same day, Senator Dianne Feinstein (D-CA) strongly appealed to the Clinton
Administration "to explore all options, including a debt-for-nature-swap" to save
"the magnificent ancient forest grove" known as Headwaters.<P>

<R>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Urge the FDIC to pursue a debt-for-nature swap, trading
Headwaters Forest for Charles Hurwitz' S&L debt [Ricki Helfer, Chair, FDIC,
Washington DC 20429]. To contribute to the Headwaters Legal Defense Fund, contact
EPIC, PO Box 397, Garberville, CA 95542; (707) 923-2931.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


