<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Reforesting the Wastelands</TITLE>

<H1>Reforesting the Wastelands</H1>

<H2>by Stephanie Mills</H2>

Tamil Nadu, <A HREF="../strp/strpindi.html">INDIA</A> -- Auroville is a 25-year-old, 2500-acre intentional community
in southern India. It aspires to become "a city that the Earth needs." To call
the ground the Aurovilians first confronted "soil" would be a misnomer. It is
laterite, baked terracotta-solid by the tropical sun, although it once was
permeated by rich scrub jungle.<P>

Local farmers were willing to part with the land
that Auroville occupies, land that had been <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">deforested</A> long ago, then cropped or
grazed beyond its limits.<P>

Even now, with much of the land in some stage of
regeneration and with attractive households, administrative centers and
appropriate technologies the norm, it is not difficult to picture the desolation
that was Auroville in the beginning -- broad stretches of gullied, parched red
earth and not much else. One longtime Aurovilian wrote that in 1969 the land
looked like "a once-living Earth dying back into a moon."<P>

Now, flecking the gullied landscape, one sees the exotic acacias that serve as the beginnings of
the new forest. In some places, grasses have actually begun to take hold. And
looming in the distances are lines of tall, limber palms, their typecast tropical
silhouettes accenting the horizons. In Auroville, afforestation and all the
effort that supports it, effort oriented toward a certain kind of human future, a
future of living in the land, is called Greenwork.<P>

Auroville was begun in 1968
with grants from UNESCO and other world philanthropies and is, at present,
somewhat of a colony, with members of 26 nationalities, mostly Europeans and
Americans. Of the 900 Aurovilians, approximately 250 are Indians. It is very much
a hybrid situation; West come to the East.<P>

<H3>An Alternative Vision</H3>

To secure a living beyond the extremely modest 1200-2000 rupees ($39-65) per
month subsistence support that the community provides its full-fledged members,
Aurovilians may commute back to their mother countries in Europe or the US to
make a little money however they can.<P>

Aurovilians may be said to come from the
ranks of the world's privileged. They live where they do by choice; they have the
luxury of being able to subscribe to the belief that, as Greenworker Ed Giordano
puts it, "pushing Nature to get the maximum for our own existence cannot
continue." Although it is by no means the only such intentional sustainable
community in India, its condition of being a multinational settlement may be
unique.<P>

Auroville's landscape is dotted with scores of windmills, 70 solar
water-heaters and more than 50 biogas plants. More than 50 homes are equipped
with photovoltaic panels, solar-box cookers and other household-level appropriate
technology experiments, like lagoon-pond systems for treating "black" and "gray"
water. "Almost all the energy we use here, we produce here," said Giordano,
indicating his sleek, solar and biogas-powered home. Thanks to a solar
photovoltaic system made of components almost entirely of Indian manufacture, he
says, "we've never had a power crash."<P>

The village of Forecomers was among the
first of Auroville's two dozen or so settlements and it remains one of the main
"Greenwork" centers. Afforestation began as a matter of stark necessity shortly
after the first settlers arrived. "What you see here," said Giordano, indicating
the surrounding Forecomers vegetation, "basically has been placed here."<P>

One entirely understandable impetus to tree planting at Auroville, I instantly
grasped, was the need to provide some shade. Without tree cover, existence in
those lands would be nearly intolerable. In the tropics, however, if things can
grow at all, they will grow rapidly. In those latitudes life really wants to
live. So trees planted and tended by the first Greenworkers had, in a
quarter-century, become almost majestic. Two species of Australian acacias were
planted as "pioneer" trees in the hope that indigenous vegetation might soon come
to grow on the restored earth.<P>

Tineke Smith was among the "Forecomers." She and
another woman lived in a hut and spent their first few years in Auroville
planting trees. To dig pits for the saplings they had grown in their nurseries,
the Greenworkers had to begin by breaking the ground with crowbars. The
transplants were nestled in compost and sprinkled with water that was hand-pumped
and hauled bodily. This hard work has produced good results. Afforestation in
Auroville has already improved the microclimate. There are no more dust storms
and the residents say that the shade provided by the trees keeps the ground
temperature lower. The effect is most noticeable in the evening, when the ground
radiates back less heat after sundown.<P>

In the mornings it was cool -- a sweet,
refreshing moment before the truly astounding heat of the day. Each morning I
awoke to a mounting chorale of bird song, the sound of healing. (The first
Auroville bird survey, done in 1972, documented 40 species. The next, in 1986,
recorded 102.) Loud, brilliant, and varied, this music of regeneration was a
welcome contrast to the entirely human din of the cities -- Benares, Delhi,
Madras and Pondicherry. I was out in the country -- resurrected country -- and
found it amenable.<P>

<HR>

This excerpt was adapted from <I>In Service of the Wild: Restoring and Reinhabiting
Damaged Land</I>, (c)1995 by Stephanie Mills (Beacon Press, 1995). Available for $23;
to charge by phone, call (617) 742-2110, ext. 596. For more information, contact:
Auroville International USA, PO Box 162489, Sacramento, CA 95816-2489.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


