<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Women's Summit Report</TITLE>

<H1>Women's Summit Report</H1>

<H2>by Sara Chamberlain</H2>

China <I>via WomensNet</I> -- In the last week of August, 28,000 women converged on Huairou, a
pre-fab "conference town" 40 miles north of Beijing, the controversial site for the NGO Forum on
Women. The August 30-September 8 conference of non-governmental organizations (NGOs)
overlapped the September 4-15 United Nations Fourth World Conference on Women (WCW) but,
because communication between the two meetings was limited by distance and transportation
difficulties, NGO delegates felt cut off from the UN proceedings in Beijing and unable to influence
the WCW's Platform for Action.<P>

The isolation of the NGO Forum was compounded by polluted skies,
torrential downpours and 80 percent humidity throughout much of the proceedings. Damp
restaurants, half-finished concrete apartment blocks and neon-lit supermarkets lined the streets
of Huairou. The forum site itself was a maze of tents, school buildings and auditoriums. The layout
was complicated by contradictory "official maps" and numerous security checks.<P>

However, despite weather and logistical problems, the mood of the NGO conference was one of solidarity, strength and
optimism, as women from around the world condemned the degradation of the environment. Their
circumstances, priorities and strategies for action may have differed substantially, but they shared
many similar concerns. Veiled Muslim women from Palestine and Kuwait discussed the negative
environmental impacts of war with Rwandan lawyers in batik turbans. African-American
teenagers sang raps about industrial pollution in their communities while Indian activists in saris
discussed seed patent laws with Japanese delegates in suits.<P>

At the NGO Forum, the Women's
Environment and Development Organization (WEDO) stated that "women's health and the health of
the natural environment are inextricably linked." Northern women from the US, Canada, Europe,
Eastern Europe and the former Soviet Union, brought a diversity of environmental issues to the
conference, but they remained united by their concern for the links between disease and
environmental degradation.<P>

Northern NGOs overwhelmingly attributed environmental problems to
unsustainable production and consumption patterns. Sascha Kranendonk, director of Women in
Europe for a Common Future, emphasized the links between toxic substances and birth defects,
cancers, and other new and resurgent diseases. Kranendonk told delegates that dioxin levels in Dutch
women's breast milk are so high that they are advised not to breast-feed their <A HREF="babies.html">babies</A>. WEDO noted
that "cancer incidence rates have reached epidemic proportions in many Northern countries, with
one in every three people in the United States expected to develop a form of cancer."<P>

Women of color, Indigenous women and poor women throughout the North are also exposed to toxic substances
while working on production lines and in agricultural production. Mily Trevino-Sauceda, director
of Lideres Campesinas en California (the Farm Workers Leadership Project of California),
described how unsustainable agricultural production is affecting the health of women agricultural
workers. She said that migrant workers suffer from a variety of health problems, including
"breathing difficulties, impaired eyesight, a variety of cancers, difficult pregnancies and <A HREF="babies.html">babies</A>
born with birth defects," all of which she attributed to pesticide exposure.<P>

Environmental justice delegations made up of Indigenous women and women of color observed that a disproportionate
amount of environmental degradation is being perpetrated on their lands and in their communities.
Indigenous women spoke out against unsustainable mining, drilling and logging practices that are
contaminating the water, air and lands of Indigenous peoples. African-American Margaret Prescod,
Director of the International Network of Women of Color, described the "toxification of African
American, Latino and Native American communities" as a "life or death situation." Connie Tucker,
Executive Director of the Southern Organizing Committee for Economic and Social Justice, accused
multinational corporations and the US government of treating Indigenous and African-American
communities as if they were "expendable."<P>

<H3>A Platform Without Justice?</H3>

Despite a petition campaign and active lobbying by NGOs at the UN conference, the terms
"environmental racism" and "environmental justice" were not included in the Platform for Action,
the official UN document signed by more than 180 nations.<P>

Members of the NGO environmental
caucus lobbied UN delegates to include the following paragraph in the environmental section of the
document: "Black, Indigenous and other peoples of color, and other sectors of poor people in both the
North and South, are particularly affected by environmental racism and the disproportionate
impact of military pollution, as well as the storage and dumping of toxic materials and drugs, and
the siting of polluting industries and activities on their lands and in their communities." However,
the paragraph was rejected in favor of two brief phrases noting that "Poverty and environmental
degradation are closely related" and "risks to women's health are particularly high in urban areas,
as well as low-income areas."<P>

The links between nuclear pollution, testing and power, uranium
mining, and women's and children's diseases were also a major concern at the NGO conference.
Kathy Sanchez, programs manager of Tewa Women United, a Native American group, told delegates
how her pueblo in New Mexico is being poisoned by the adjacent Los Alamos National Laboratory and
nuclear waste storage facility. She commented that "there are laws to protect endangered species,
but none to protect endangered peoples.... There are only 500 of us [native Tewa] left and now we
are being poisoned by nuclear radiation."<P>

Anna Syomina, the director of MAMA-86, informed
delegates that health problems in Ukraine have escalated since the 1986 Chernobyl disaster.
MAMA-86 is named after the mothers who founded the organization after the radiation-related
sicknesses that their children had developed since 1986 were left untreated. According to Syomina,
a shocking 70 percent of Ukrainian children are born with birth defects and, of the 30 percent who
are born healthy, only 20 percent were still healthy by the time they graduated from high school.
She added that "Chernobyl AIDS," an immune-deficiency disease, is now prevalent among Ukrainian
children. Syomina also told NGO delegates that one in six women in Ukraine is infertile and 40
percent cannot carry their pregnancies to term. In addition, thyroid problems, which barely
existed before the Chernobyl disaster, are now widespread.<P>

At the UN conference, anti-nuclear
NGOs supported strong language opposing the transboundary transportation of nuclear waste in the
Platform for Action. However, despite objections by Fiji, Panama, Nigeria and the Marshall
Islands, text calling for the "immediate" prohibition of transboundary toxic waste movement was
watered down to a pledge to "consider taking action."<P>

Language linking nuclear energy and weapons
to environmental degradation that was agreed upon during preparatory sessions in New York was
also omitted in Beijing. Meanwhile, wording calling for an immediate ban on nuclear testing was
radically altered. The US and Canada pushed through an alternative sentence, stating that countries'
nuclear testing programs "should exercise extreme restraint."

<H3>Consuming Desires</H3>

Fortunately, Northern delegates at the NGO conference did more than merely testify to the negative
health impacts of environmental destruction. Earth Island's delegation joined other NGOs to develop
strategies for action that included forming international environmental networks and exchanging
information about initiatives underway to change unsustainable production and consumption
patterns.<P>

Eco-labeling schemes were cited as an exemplary method for educating consumers about
their purchasing choices. Indian eco-feminist and Earth Island Advisory Board member Vandana
Shiva proposed a "Food Miles" labeling system that would indicate the amount of fossil fuels and
natural resources consumed to manufacture and transport food products.<P>

Although Northern delegates focused primarily on the negative impacts of unsustainable production and consumption
patterns in their communities, the impacts of these practices on Southern women were made clear
by sister delegates from the South. Roopa Vajpaie, director of VOICE, a New Delhi-based consumer
association, spoke out on behalf of Southern women whose environments are being destroyed by
Northern pesticides used on export crops; whose natural resources are being sold to the highest
foreign bidder; and "whose only consumer choice is no choice."<P>

Leslie O'Dowd, director of Friends of
the Earth Ireland, concluded that "we [in the North] must radically readjust our consumption and
production patterns if a sustainable future is to be ensured for all." After much lobbying, the UN
Platform for Action did finally include a sentence stating that "the major cause of continued
deterioration of the global environment is the unsustainable pattern of production and consumption,
particularly in industrialized countries."<P>

<H3>Platform Pluses</H3>

The UN Platform for Action does contain some strong language on environmental issues and endorses
Agenda 21's "precautionary principal" (requiring an immediate response to potential worldwide
catastrophes -- such as global warming -- without waiting for conclusive scientific proof). It also
insists on clean water for all by the year 2000, recognizes gender-differentiated impacts of
environmental problems and policies, and acknowledges women's unique environmental expertise in
the promotion of renewable energy sources.<P>

The document states that "resource depletion, the
degradation of natural systems and the danger of polluting substances... are destroying fragile
ecosystems and displacing communities, especially women, from productive activities and are an
increasing threat to a safe and healthy environment." The Platform for Action also notes that
"poverty and environmental degradation are closely related," and that "environmental risks in the
workplace may have a disproportionate impact on women's health because of women's different
susceptibilities to the toxic effects of various chemicals."<P>

The Platform for Action concludes that
"women have expressed their commitment to create a new development paradigm that integrates
environmental sustainability with gender equality and justice..." which will require "women's
participation and leadership at every level."<P>

Nonetheless, the document's treatment of nuclear,
environmental justice and other critical "green" issues, was a disappointment to environmental
NGOs. "We were in the door, but not at the table," summarized Earth Island Advisory Board member
Claire Greensfelder of Plutonium Free Futures. In contrast, the NGO Forum, which successfully
conducted 6000 workshops in the space of a week, was a tremendous learning and networking
experience that produced concrete strategies for action and forged powerful relationships.<P>


<HR>

