<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Global Weather Grows More Severe</TITLE>

<H1>Global Weather Grows More Severe</H1>

<H2>by Rhys Roth</H2>

A National Climatic Data Center (NCDC) study shows that weather has been growing more extreme.
It scrutinized US records for the last 80 years to track summer droughts, drenching rainstorms,
wet winters and other types of unusual weather events that are expected to increase in a
greenhouse-heated world. <P>

The NCDC discovered that since the late 1970s, the climate has been stuck in a greenhouse-type mode, in which extreme weather occurs more often. Statistical analyses
showed only a five percent probability that the "latest surge toward the greenhouse side is just
another fluctuation of an otherwise stable climate," according to Science writer Richard A. Kerr.<P>

Most of the extra heat added to the climate by greenhouse gases is absorbed by the oceans, which
cover 70 percent of the Earth. At 63.8 million square miles, the Pacific Ocean is roughly the same
size as all the Earth's land masses. <P>

In the past 20 years, Bernice Wuethrich reported in the
February 4, 1995 <I>New Scientist</I>, the surface of the central Pacific has warmed by 0.5 degrees
Celsius and "a giant pool of unusually warm water has settled down in the middle of the Pacific and
is showing no signs of moving."<P>

Nicholas E. Graham of the Scripps Institution of Oceanography
claims that not only has the temperature of Pacific Ocean surface waters been climbing since the
mid-1970s, but evaporation, air moisture and rainfall over tropical waters have increased as
well.<P>

Graham warns that while the changes since the 1970s could be natural, "there is disquieting
similarity" with the early climate changes predicted from an increase of greenhouse gases in the
atmosphere.<P>

<H3>Clear the Air (Cook the Planet?)</H3>

The impact of carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions on the Earth's climate has been underestimated
because of the cooling effect of sulfur dioxide (SO2), another form of fossil fuel pollution. Like
CO2, SO2 releases from fossil fuel burning are also affecting the Earth's atmosphere.<P>

It is easier to measure the impact of SO2 than CO2 on climate because, instead of trapping heat like CO2, particles
of SO2 suspended in the atmosphere reflect sunlight away from the Earth, cooling the climate
beneath. Sulfur dioxide does  not travel far because it is washed out of the atmosphere within a
couple of weeks. This means that SO2 veils the regions around the biggest polluters -- eastern
North America, Europe and eastern Asia. In contrast, greenhouse gases like CO2 survive for decades
in the atmosphere, long enough to spread evenly around the globe and affect climate for several
generations.<P>

NCDC research has demonstrated that in regions where SO2 emissions are highest,
temperatures are cooler compared to unveiled parts of the globe. The greatest cooling was found to
occur during summer days, when there is more solar energy for SO2 to reflect. After the Clean Air
Act began limiting SO2 emissions beginning in 1970, the cooling trend in the US ended.<P>

These observations offer compelling evidence that humans are changing the climate, and according to
NCDC's Thomas R. Karl, "the reduction of temperature is large enough to have an impact on global
temperatures." Over the last 140 years, the Earth's temperature has risen by 0.6 degrees Celsius.
Karl estimates that, had it not been for the cooling effect of SO2 em-issions, the planet would have
warmed more than one degree Celsius by now.

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Rhys Roth is Director of the Atmosphere Alliance.<P>

For more information, join The Atmosphere Alliance (regular memberships:
$20). Members receive both Earth Island Journal and TAA's No Sweat News, a fact-filled
newsletter featuring "jarring newsbolts from the lightening tip of atmospheric science." TAA has
also published Life Support! A Citizen's Guide to Solving the Atmospheric Crisis ($5).  TAA, PO Box
10346, Olympia, WA 98502. (Please make checks payable to: Earth Island Institute/TAA.)

<HR>

