<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Blowing Holes in the Montreal Protocol</TITLE>

<H1>Blowing Holes in the Montreal Protocol</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

"This is a crucial year for the Montreal Protocol," noted United Nations Environment Program
(UNEP) spokesperson Tore Brevik, referring to the UN agreement that commits 150 signatory
countries to phase out ozone-destroying chlorofluorocarbon (CFC) production by the year 2000.<P>

Under the Montreal Protocol, Brevik noted, "production and consumption of ... [CFCs have] been
dramatically cut by nearly 70 percent... [and] industrialized countries are expected to virtually
eliminate the consumption of [ozone-depleting substances] by the end of 1995." EPA spokesperson
Mary Nichols repeated this point when she told the press that "December 31, 1995 is the last day
on which CFCs can be legally manufactured...." <P>

However, according to a September 14 Ozone Action report [1621 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20009; (202) 265-6738], the
December 31 deadline is  a "myth." Ozone Action's report, "Deadly Complacency," reveals that
"loopholes in US law and international regulations" will leave large chemical companies free to
"produce more than 200,000 tons of new CFCs in 1996, more than 100,000 tons a year from
1997 to 1999 and more than 50,000 tons per year from 2000 to 2005." The waiver grants
extended CFC-production rights for both "essential use" within the US and for export to developing
countries. <P>

The four corporations that will continue to manufacture "outlawed" CFCs in the US are
DuPont, LaRoche, Allied Signal and Elf Atochem. "This production will, most likely, be consolidated
and handled by one or two of these companies," the report states.<P>

 Ozone Action contends that "Operation Cool Breeze," the industry-backed joint-EPA/FBI/CIA/Interpol crack-down on illegal 
CFC production, is actually "a strategic effort by Western corporations and governments to protect
and enhance their market-share of global CFC production. This bid for control over the
ozone-destroying refrigerant market represents a 'New Cold War,' with the battle lines once again
drawn between East and West."<P>

This view is shared by India's Environment Ministry, which
recently criticized Western governments for "eliminating competition from [developing] countries
and handing over the developing countries' market for ozone-depleting substances on a platter to
multinational companies of developed countries."<P>

Under the Montreal Protocol, Western corporations can produce almost 2.19 million tons of CFCs between now and 2005. US companies
are expected to account for 629,000 tons of the total. Operation Cool Breeze's assault on "illegal"
CFCs could drive the US share of the global CFC market from its current 24 percent to 31 percent
by 1997.<P>

The Ozone Action report also revealed that the 500 tons of CFCs already confiscated by the
Feds will not be destroyed. The government plans "to either sell them or have the US military use
them." 

<HR>

