<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: McDonald's To Abandon UK Court Fight?</TITLE>

<H1>McDonald's To Abandon UK Court Fight?</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

UK -- The longest civil lawsuit in British history resumed in September as the
McDonald's Corporation renewed its campaign against two unemployed activists
charged with libel for distributing a leaflet criticizing the fast-food giant
[Winter '94-95, <I>EIJ</I>]. Over the last year, the $26 billion burger chain has spent
$1.5 million on the trial, called 56 witnesses, produced 40,000 documents and
hired one of England's best libel lawyers, Richard Rampton, at a rate of #2000
($3140) a day. The two defendants, Helen Steel, 29, and David Morris, 41, cannot
afford expensive legal counsel and are representing themselves.<P>

In mid-July, McDonald's lawyers announced that they would no longer provide photocopies of
their daily trial transcripts to the defendants unless they were paid #350 ($550)
a day -- a fee well beyond the defendants' means. Declaring that this action left
him feeling "uncomfortable," the presiding judge announced that he would spurn
the corporation's costly transcripts and, like the defendants, rely on tedious,
incomplete manual note-taking.<P>

The trial has proved highly embarrassing to McDonald's. In a confidential memo leaked to the defense,   McDonald's Australian
branch  begged the parent company to "minimize any further negative publicity"
and "contain it as a UK issue."<P>

With the trial expected to last another six
months, McDonald's is quietly attempting to settle with the defendants out of
court. Members of the corporation's US Board of Directors flew to Britain twice
for discussions with Steel and Morris.<P>

The "McLibel Two" have set clear
preconditions for allowing McDonald's to withdraw from the case: an agreement to
never again sue any individuals or groups for making similar criticisms of
McDonald's; a promise to apologize to everyone McDonald's has sued in the past;
and, payment of a "substantial sum to a mutually agreeable third party in lieu of
compensation to us."<P>

In a joint statement, Morris and Steel declared that it is
"a duty to criticize the practices of multinational corporations which dominate
our lives, our environment and the world's economy."<P>

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

To contribute to the defendants' legal costs, contact: McLibel
Support Campaign, 5 Caledonian Road, London N1 9DX, UK; Phone/fax;
+44-171-713-1269. For more information, contact: US McLibel Support Campaign,
Press Office, PO Box 62, Craftsbury, VT 05826-0062. Phone/fax: (802) 586-9628.
Email: dbriars@world.std.com.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


