<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: France Resumes Nuclear Tests</TITLE>

<H1>France Resumes Nuclear Tests</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

Following France's detonation of a 20-kiloton nuclear bomb on September 5,
outraged citizens around the world stepped up protests against President Jacques
Chirac's decision to resume nuclear tests in the South Pacific. Facing a global
boycott of the $7 billion French wine-export industry, the French Defense
Ministry declared haughtily: "The nuclear deterrent guarantees... the ultimate
protection of our vital interests." This argument failed to sway the residents of
French Polynesia, who condemned the tests, set fire to cars and buildings in the
capital of Tahiti and demanded independence from France.<P>

Since 1988, France has conducted more than 130 underground nuclear blasts at Moruroa atoll (the exact
figure remains a state secret). The tests have left Moruroa's lagoon polluted
with as much as 20 kg (44 lbs) of plutonium and the atoll fractured to a depth of
200 meters (656 feet). One disastrous bomb test sheared off a large undersea
section of the atoll, triggering a tidal wave and causing parts of the island to
sink beneath sea level. Cesium-134 and tritium have leaked into the surrounding
ocean and plutonium-239 has been detected in plankton.<P>

Because of the accumulated damage to Moruroa, larger nuclear tests (which could reach 150 kilotons) may have
to be relocated to the nearby atoll of Fangataufa, an unpopulated island that is
now a sanctuary for seabirds.<P>

"Instead of rehabilitating and decontaminating the
nuclear test site," stated Gabriel Tetiarahi, leader of the Polynesian Indigenous
rights organization, Hiti Tau, "Mr. Chirac has decided to increase the volume of
radioactive materials stocked in the womb of Moruroa and Fangataufa. This is the
stinking heritage France has given to our children and to Maohi generations of
the future -- a heritage of pollution by radioactive materials for several
thousand years. This is simply a crime against humanity.... It is nuclear
racism."<P>

Recently, it was learned that Major General Jean-Claude Lesquer has been
made a Grand Officer of the Legion of Honor. Lesquer led the team of secret
agents that bombed and sank the Greenpeace ship Rainbow Warrior in New Zealand in
1985. The Warrior had been protesting French nuclear testing when it was
attacked. This act of state-sponsored terrorism claimed the life of a Greenpeace
photographer.<P>

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Boycott French goods and address your concerns about nuclear
testing to: President Jacques Chirac, Palais de L'Elysee, 55-57 rue de Faubourg
Saint-Honore, 75008, Paris, France; fax: 33-1-474-22465.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


