<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Green-Scare Down Under</TITLE>

<H1>Green-Scare Down Under</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

Australia -- "Sabotage, eco-terrorism and monkey-wrenching are often used to
discredit environmental campaigns" reports Australia's <I>Chain Reaction</I>
magazine [Friends of the Earth Australia, PO Box 45, O'Connor, ACT, 2601
Australia; (06) 248-0289]. But as CR reporter Bob Burton discovered, the evidence
behind most incidents of "eco-terrorism" appears to point not to greens, but to
police agents.<P>

In 1991, an explosion and fire at the Coode Island chemical terminal in
Melbourne, caused A$20 million ($14.8 million) in damages. The Victoria police
subsequently informed the press that they had "conclusive" forensic proof that
the fire was caused by saboteurs using an oxy-acetylene torch to cut the plant's
pipes.<P>

Eight months later, however, it was revealed that the pipes had burst due to
metal fatigue (a conclusion that the Department of Labor and Industry had quietly
reached from the start).<P>

In January 1993, Victoria police Sergeant Terry Walsh jetted off to address
Tasmanian police and the Victorian Association of Forest Industries on the threat
of "eco-terrorism." Walsh made a point of citing the US-based environmental group
Earth First! and, soon after Walsh's briefing, a joint industry-police press
conference was called to raise the specter of "eco-terrorism." Up to that time
there had never been any instance of eco-terrorism in Tasmania. But that was soon
to change.<P>

Two days before Tasmania's 1993 federal elections, a dummy bomb was discovered on
a local railroad line. Attached to the bomb was a banner bearing the name "Earth
First!" As citizens walked to their ballot boxes, they passed news racks carrying
headlines boldly accusing environmentalists of using terror tactics. The
Tasmanian Green Party candidate for the Senate failed to win a seat by one
percent of the vote.<P>

Months later, police admitted that there was no link between the bomb and any
environmental group. The perpetrators of the hoax were never identified.<P>

In 1994, Tasmania was swept by a string of mysterious "tree spiking" hoaxes. One
tree-spiking letter, replete with "environmentalist" phrases, was released to
coincide with the publication of the Tasmanian Green's three-year study of the
impacts of the Forestry Commission's herbicide spraying programs.<P>

Later that year, six-inch-long galvanized nails appeared in the trees of southern
forests on the very morning government minister Ian McLachlan arrived for a
visit. Soon, these nails were showing up in logs arriving at timber mills.<P>

In October, 1994, Sgt. Walsh was back before the microphones, this time in
Canberra at a Parliament House press conference. "The acts of individuals engaged
in eco-tage is [<I>sic</I>] no less than those of an environmental terrorist,"
Walsh raged. "What they are doing is against the law and the acts could
eventually result in serious injury or loss of life."<P>

The press, recalling the embarrassing reversals on the Coode Island fire and the
"Earth First!" railroad bomb, challenged Sgt. Walsh to cite a single instance in
which environmentalists had engaged in a violent act. Walsh declined to
answer.<P>

"It is widely known in police circles that there have been many violent attacks
on environmentalists," CR's Burton noted, but Sergeant Walsh chose to ignore this
fact. "Indeed, the only people charged and convicted of violence in the forest
debate in the last decade have been from the forest industry," Burton stated.<P>

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


