<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Greenpeace Halts UK Nukes; British Police Raid Greenpeace</TITLE>

<H1>Greenpeace Halts UK Nukes; British Police Raid Greenpeace</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

United Kingdom -- On April 17, while discussions opened in New York on extending
the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), nearly 300 Greenpeace (GP) activists
staged pre-dawn invasions at two major nuclear facilities in the UK.<P>

At Sellafield, 20 anti-nuclear campaigners blocked the main road leading to the
British Nuclear Fuels Laboratory and 250 activists entered the plant to try and
halt plutonium production at the Thermal Oxide Reprocessing facility. Meanwhile,
a Greenpeace ship hovered near a discharge pipe that GP claimed was spilling
radioactive waste into the Irish Sea.<P>

Meanwhile, at the Aldermaston nuclear
weapons factory 40 miles southwest of London, three protesters attempted to
parachute into the top-secret site. The chutists missed their target, but a team
of 15 activists on the ground managed to infiltrate the plant and shut down the
facility's main discharge pipe, which GP claimed was pouring radioactive waste
into the River Thames.<P>

The UK Ministry of Defense (MoD) gruffly informed the
press that Greenpeace had not penetrated security at Aldermaston, had not sealed
any pipes and had not impeded weapons production. When a television crew produced
footage contradicting the MoD and showing that the pipe had indeed been blocked,
the government seized the videotapes.<P>

To the chagrin of security officials, news reports soon appeared with photos showing how GP had not only closed
Aldermaston's 12-mile-long pipe, but poured six tons of quick-hardening concrete
down an access hole to finish the job.<P>

As GP nuclear campaigner Janet Convery
told the press, the officials entrusted with the security of "the most sensitive
military installations in the UK" had been "outwitted by a handful of dedicated
Greenpeace volunteers."<P>

"Instead of getting rid of nuclear weapons, Aldermaston
is increasing production of warheads for the new Trident submarines," Greenpeace
charged.<P>

GP predicted that blocking the pipe would halt weapons work for two
days. In fact, production was interrupted for almost two weeks.<P>

The MoD waited until the close of the NPT negotiations before striking back. On May 17, 50 MoD
police descended on GP's London headquarters [Canonbury Villas, London, N1 2PN,
UK; (0171) 354-5100] to search for evidence of a "conspiracy to cause criminal
damage." Five GP activists were charged with causing #15,000 ($23,550) of damage
at Aldermaston, an offense that carries a ten-year maximum prison sentence. But
there was another reason for the MoD's wrath.<P>

BBC Wildlife revealed that the
"heavy-handed raid, which included a massive confiscation of Greenpeace's files
and computer disks"  was  "a direct result of [GP's] success at exposing the
illegal  ties between the US and UK nuclear programs."<P>

The same day that NPT negotiations opened in New York, GP released a report accusing the US of
"breaking the spirit of the [NPT]" by storing approximately 520 nuclear weapons
(mostly 175-kiloton B-61 tactical bombs) at 15 bases in Italy, Germany, Belgium,
Greece, Turkey, the Netherlands and the UK. GP also revealed how a little-known
"executive agreement" -- the 1958 US/UK Mutual Defense Agreement (which is set to
run until December 31, 2004) -- violates the NPT by allowing the US to provide
nuclear technology, materials and components to the UK.<P>

"Although [the agreement] has served as the cornerstone of US/UK nuclear cooperation and British nuclear
weapons development for over 30 years," GP charged, "as an 'executive agreement'
it has avoided scrutiny by the US Congress... [and the British] Parliament...."<P>

The Mutual Defense Agreement sanctions the transfer (by sale, loan or barter) of
such items as: up to 500 kg (1100 lbs.) of uranium; 100 kgs (220 lbs.) of
thorium; beryllium, boron and high explosives; nuclear weapons switches and
relays; and "nuclear weapons test debris samples." The report concluded that,
"the UK's nuclear weapons arsenal and its delivery systems... [were] highly or
entirely dependent on US assistance."<P>

The issues raised by the GP report were
subsequently broached at the NPT meeting. Much to the discomfort of the US and
UK, a conference committee concluded that "such acts run counter to the spirit
and letter of the Treaty, in particular Articles I and II, and give rise to
proliferation of nuclear weapons...."<P>

The GP report also unmasked the corporate
beneficiaries of nuclear proliferation. There are two other "nuclear cooperation"
agreements, GP discovered -- the Polaris and Trident sales agreements. "Both
these agreements allow for the UK to purchase missiles and equipment on the same
or more favorable terms as the US government and thus provide significant
advantages to the UK."<P>

Under these agreements, the MoD was able to deposit
billions of British pounds into the corporate bank accounts of two major US
nuclear weapons makers, General Dynamics' Electric Boat division and Lockheed
(now the newly merged $28 billion Lockheed-Marten Corp.).<P>

<I>BBC Wildlife</I> noted that the seizure of GP files, membership lists, financial records and campaign
strategies "has sinister implications... for the whole environmental movement."
Given the nature of past UK/US cooperation, the magazine observed, there is
nothing to stop the MoD from sharing this information "by way of a favor, [with]
any other government interested in suppressing environmental protest."
		
<HR>

