<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Atomic Audit Tallies the Toll</TITLE>

<H1><I>Atomic Audit</I> Tallies the Toll</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

The US nuclear weapons program has been more costly than Washington has ever
admitted, consuming "between one quarter and one third of all defense spending
since WW II," according to the US Nuclear Weapons Cost Study Project [NWCSP, 1775
Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20036; (202) 797-6030]. The full report
will be available in book form in early 1996.<P>

In <I>Atomic Audit: What the US Nuclear Arsenal Really Cost</I>, a preliminary study released on July 11, NWCSP
tagged the cost of the weapons program at "nearly $4 trillion, not including an
additional $500 billion to $1 trillion for numerous essential, but
often-overlooked, programs." (Not surprisingly, NWCSP found Defense and Energy
Department officials were "reluctant to retrieve, declassify and release relevant
historical budgetary information....")<P>

Even though the US has reduced its number
of nuclear weapons from 21,000 to 14,000 over the past five years, NWCSP found
that the nation still spends "at least $33 billion a year on nuclear weapons" and
related activities -- about 13 percent of all military spending. Disassembling
weapons and cleaning up nuclear pollution cost $8 billion a year.<P>

In September
1994, the Pentagon's <I>Nuclear Posture Review</I> claimed that nuclear weapons spending
had dropped from about $53 billion in 1964 to some $12 billion in 1994. NWCSP
charges that these figures are misleading since "they do not include the billions
of dollars spent annually... to develop, test, produce, maintain and eventually
dismantle every bomb in the stockpile." Pentagon figures also omit the cost of
the Navy's nuclear-powered ships and submarines, and exclude most of the global
nuclear infrastructure needed "to support and control the arsenal."<P>

<I>Atomic Audit</I> also uncovered a host of poorly conceived dead-end projects that were begun and
abandoned. These ranged from plans for nuclear-powered airplanes and rockets to
such ill-fated programs as the MX missile, the Strategic Defense Initiative and
the Navajo cruise missile. While these "budgetary bombs" never delivered a
finished product, they did funnel more than $75 billion worth of taxpayers'
dollars into the hands of a powerful clique of defense contractors.<P> 

<HR>

