<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: "Why We Need Nuclear Weapons"</TITLE>

<H2>The US' Secret World Court Plea</H2>

<H1>"Why We Need Nuclear Weapons"</H1>

 <H2>by David Orr</H2>
 
Fifty years after the bombing of Hiroshima, the "nuclear option" is alive and
well in the Oval Office. President Clinton set the tone in July 1993, by
threatening North Korea with atomic attack. In 1995, Clinton refused to apologize
for America's use of nuclear weapons against civilian populations in Japan and
proceeded to approve a Nuclear Policy Review that calls for expansion of the
nation's nuclear arsenal.<P>

Even the president's call for the unconditional
extension of the nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) is not what it seems.
According to <I>Peacework</I> magazine [American Friends Service Committee, 2161
Massachusetts Avenue, Cambridge, MA 02140; (617) 661-6130] extending the NPT only
serves to "preserve the terrorizing monopoly of the present nuclear weapons
states."<P>

Earlier this year, <I>Peacework</I> obtained a leaked copy of the Clinton
administration's June 1994 submission to the United Nations' International Court
of Justice in The Hague (aka the "World Court"). The  court is considering a
complaint by the World Health Organization (a UN agency) that contends that the
possession of nuclear weapons of mass destruction threatens human life and
thereby constitutes a violation of international law.<P>

In its May issue, <I>Peacework</I>
quoted extensively from the leaked document. Let's listen in as the government's
best legal minds make the case for preserving America's nuclear arsenal.<P>

"There is no general prohibition in conventional or customary international law on the
use of nuclear weapons..." the government's lawyers insisted. "[N]othing in the
body of international humanitarian law of armed conflict indicates that nuclear
weapons are prohibited per se...." [<I>The "Not specifically stated" argument --
ed.</I>]<P>

"It is well known that the permanent members of the Security Council (and
perhaps other states) possess nuclear weapons and have developed and deployed
their systems for their use in armed conflict. These states would not have borne
the expense and effort of acquiring and maintaining these weapons and delivery
systems if they believed that the use of nuclear weapons was generally
prohibited." [<I>The "We had no idea" defense backed by the "We're heavily invested"
corollary.</I>]<P>

"[T]he possible use of these weapons is an important factor in the
structure of [the nuclear states'] military establishments, the development of
their military doctrines and strategy, and their efforts to prevent aggression
and provide an essential element of the exercise of their right of
self-defense...." [<I>The "Generals know best" rationale.</I>]<P>

"Subject to the right of
reprisal... it is unlawful to make civilians or civilian objects the object of
attack as such. This rule would not be violated by the use of nuclear weapons to
attack targets that constitute legitimate military objectives." [<I>The "If a
nuclear weapon kills a civilian, we'll just call it 'reprisal' " ploy.</I>]<P>

"With respect to the use of nuclear weapons, customary law could not be created over
the objections of the nuclear-weapons states, which are the states whose
interests are most specially affected...." [<I>The "Don't tell us what to do; we
have the Bomb" stratagem.</I>]<P>

<HR>		

Source: Joseph Gerson, May 1995 Peacework magazine. Joseph Gerson's new book,
<I>With Hiroshima Eyes</I>, is now available from the AFSC's Cambridge office.

