<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Ozone Loss Reported Worse Than Ever</TITLE>

<H1>Ozone Loss Reported Worse Than Ever</H1>

In August, <I>The New York Times</I> reported that ozone loss over Antarctica "has reached about the most
severe levels possible." Meteorologist Jonathan Shanklin told the <I>Times</I> that, despite praise for the
Montreal Protocol (the global treaty designed to reduce emissions of ozone-destroying gases),
"we've not seen any slowdown at all. If anything, there's an acceleration of the depletion."<P>

Shanklin, one of three British Antarctic Survey scientists who reported discovery of the ozone hole in 1985,
noted that the Antarctic's ozone depletion, which initially ran from August through October, now
extends from August through February of the next year. Even if ozone-destroying chemical
pollution peaks in the late 1990s, Shanklin warned, "it still will be perhaps 50 years before the
ozone hole disappears."<P>

On a typical summer day (July 23), the EPA's index of ultraviolet-B
radiation revealed that only one of 60 US cities monitored (Anchorage) registered "low" UV-B
exposure (UV-B causes skin cancer, cataracts and immune-system disorders).<P>

Forty-eight cities were exposed to "high" levels of exposure to UV-B. Of these, 11 cities (Albuquerque, Charleston,
Dallas,  Honolulu, Jackson, Las Vegas, Los Angeles, Miami, Mobile, New Orleans and Phoenix) were
sizzling under "very high" levels.<P>

Unlike Australia and Canada, the EPA's UV Index officially lists only "estimates" for each coming day's UV levels. The EPA does subsequently record the actual
readings at its monitoring sites but, according to Ozone Action's John Passacantando, "They don't
make [those figures] public." <P>

Given the continuing severity of ozone depletion, the budget for the
EPA's UV Index should be increased to improve the quality and number of monitoring stations, as
well as to assure that the information is made widely available to the public in a timely fashion.
With newspaper, television and radio announcements of daily UV-B levels, Canada provides an
excellent model.<P>

Unfortunately, it is likely that the EPA's short-changed, short-lived and
under-publicized UV-B Index will soon be nothing but a memory, because the program is not
expected to survive the <A HREF="greengop.html">GOP</A>'s budgetary clearcutting. Even if the index escapes a direct assault by
the Republican's Contract On America, the budget axes whacking away at the EPA and National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration will likely extinguish any hopes that such a low-profile
public service will survive into the next fiscal year.<P>

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Take solar monitoring matters into your own hands. The hand-held, one-ounce,
solar-powered Sunsor(R) Ultraviolet Meter provides instant digital readouts to determine the
UV-B hazard. [Available from Sunsor(R) Inc., Box 537, Allison Park, PA 15101 for $44.95 plus
$4.50 shipping and handling; (800) 285-6352.]

<HR>

