<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Earth Islanders Spark McDonald's Protest in China</TITLE>

<H1>Earth Islanders Spark McDonald's Protest in China</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>


The last person EII Beijing delegates Emily Miggins and Sara Chamberlain expected to meet in China
was Ronald McDonald. To their horror, they found a McDonald's franchise selling burgers and fries
at the NGO conference site. (McDonald's has 33 shops in Beijing and plans to open two more.)<P>

Acting spontaneously, Emily and Sara painted protest signs and went into action. To the dismay of
Chinese security guards, the world press heard the ruckus and came running.  As cameras whirred 
and pencils scratched, the two-woman demonstration turned into an international event.<P>

A group of Indian women joined the protest, complaining that fast-food chains had seized India's
potato market, robbing their families of a basic food item. Women from Africa condemned the rise
of imported fast foods and called for support for traditional meals.<P>

The women ripped a Ronald McDonald statue from a bench and, led by EII Advisory Board member
Vandana Shiva, carried it off on their shoulders and dumped it in a sewage pond.<P>

The incident was reported around the world. While numerous reporters from the US witnessed the
event, the "anti-Mac" demo went virtually unreported in the US media.

