<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Dolphins and MMPA Under Attack by GOP Bill</TITLE>

<H1>Dolphins and MMPA Under Attack by GOP Bill</H1>

<H2>by Nathan LaBudde</H2>

<I>See also: <A HREF="greengop.html">A Call for a Green GOP</A> by Gordon E. Gurnil<P></I>

Before the Marine Mammal Protection Act (MMPA) was reauthorized in 1992, more than 100 US
and foreign fishing fleets roamed the Eastern Tropical Pacific (ETP) in search of yellowfin tuna.
Exploiting the peculiar tendency of large schools of yellowfin to swim beneath schools of dolphins,
the tuna industry began setting nets around dolphins as a means of catching tuna.<P>

By the 1970s, this brutal technology had become the dominant fishing method in the ETP. When a tunaboat crew spotted
a dolphin school, it dispatched chase boats to traumatize and corral the dolphins, often using small
explosives to slow down the fleeing school. Helicopters often coordinated the entire process from
overhead via two-way radio. In the time it took to exhaust the frightened, sensory-shocked
dolphins, the mothership had already begun encircling them with huge purse-shaped nets. Scores of
battered dolphins routinely died in a chaos of tuna, tangled nets and blood. Those that escaped were
often injured and vulnerable to shark predation.<P>

<H3>Hidden Slaughter Exposed</H3>

For years, the slaughter of dolphins in tuna nets went unnoticed. Then, in 1988, Earth Island's
International Marine Mammal Project (IMMP) dropped a media bombshell: the first undercover
video footage of a deadly tuna "set." This video allowed millions to witness helpless dolphins trapped
in nets, suffocating or crushed in net winches. The soundtrack was a chorus of loud clicks and
whistles produced by nature's most social mammals as they were slowly and painfully put to death
en masse. <P>

The public was outraged. Consumers boycotted tuna, schoolchildren wrote letters to
elected officials and corporate executives, and the environmental community united to demand
legislative action. The force of public opinion and environmental activism finally prompted
corporate action. The world's largest tuna companies stopped selling tuna caught by setting nets on
dolphins. <P>

Under the provisions of the MMPA, dolphin-deadly fishing practices used by US boats
were to be phased out and dolphin-unsafe tuna was banned from sale in the US. It was one of the
greatest environmental victories of the decade. IMMP went on to create an international monitoring
program to ensure strict dolphin-safe fishing standards in foreign canneries producing tuna for the
US market. Domestic tuna companies supported this program and committed to implementing
dolphin-safe standards. By 1994, dolphin mortality worldwide had dropped more than 96 percent,
from a 1986 high of 130,000 to approximately 4000.<P>

<H3>Return to the Dark Ages</H3>

Just when it appeared that the tuna/dolphin issue was finally being resolved, a new threat surfaced.
In August, 1995, a group of four House Republicans introduced HR2179, a bill that would amend
the MMPA and repeal laws currently protecting dolphins from needless slaughter. <P>

Authored by Representative Randy "Duke" Cunningham (R-CA), the bill calls for the lifting of all tuna import
embargos against Mexico, Venezuela and other countries that have not complied with the
dolphin-protection standards of the MMPA. Once again, tuna caught using techniques resulting in
dolphin deaths could be sold in the US. HR2179 would also repeal the MMPA provision requiring
proper labeling of dolphin-safe tuna and would allow US fishing fleets to again catch tuna by
encircling schools of dolphins.<P>

IMMP Director David Phillips said, "This bill ought to be named the Dolphin Extermination and Consumer Fraud Act. It is an outrageous plan to gut the Marine Mammal
Protection Act and sacrifice thousands of dolphins. Under his bill, even tuna caught by killing
thousands of dolphins could be labeled as 'dolphin-safe.' In our view, this is consumer fraud and a
tragic death sentence for dolphins."<P>

Rep. Cunningham claims that dolphin-safe tuna fishing methods cost American jobs and that the current law is "too stringent." However, he has not produced any
evidence to demonstrate how a return to killing dolphins will generate new US jobs.<P>

Congressman Gerry Studds (D-MA), who co-authored the 1990 dolphin-safe labeling law, observed that
Cunningham's bill would allow cheap tuna from Mexico, Venezuela and other countries to flood the
American market. "The point of this proposal isn't to protect dolphins or to help US fishermen, as
its proponents claim," said Studds. "Dolphins are already protected under US law, and American
fishermen are fishing safely and profitably under an arrangement with the island nations of the
Western Pacific."<P>

<H3>A Call to Action</H3>

Starkist, Chicken of the Sea and Bumble Bee, the world's three largest tuna companies, have all
affirmed their commitments to market only dolphin-safe tuna. But, they also recognize the dire
economic consequences if foreign producers are allowed to "dump" cheap, dolphin-unsafe tuna onto
the US market.<P>

Since the dolphin-safe laws have been enacted, the tuna industry has shown it can catch ample supplies of tuna without killing dolphins. Most of the US fleet that once fished
dolphin-unsafe in the ETP now fishes dolphin-safe, primarily for skipjack, in the Western
Tropical Pacific. These fleets enjoy some of the highest catches anywhere in the world.<P>

Representative George Miller (D-CA) criticized the Cunningham bill as an environmental sellout to
free-trade interests. "This is exactly what we warned about when we fought NAFTA and GATT, and
this is exactly what we were told would not happen. We warned that American environmental laws
would be subject to challenge by foreign governments that don't want to meet standards set by the
American government and supported by American industry and the American people," he observed.<P>

"This bill continues a string of offenses. First, we were asked to jeopardize American workers by
passing trade bills to benefit Mexico. Then we were asked to put at risk billions of US dollars to
bolster the peso. Now we are being told by the Republicans in Congress that we should sanction the
slaughter of tens of thousands of dolphins and undo a mammal protection program that has worked
efficiently and that is supported by American industry," said Miller.<P>

Despite widespread popular support for strong laws to protect dolphins, House Republicans are proceeding with consideration of
the bill. Earth Island urges its members and supporters to oppose HR2179, whose co-sponsors
include Rep. Brian Bitbray (R-CA), Duncan Hunter (R-CA) and Ron Packard (R-CA).<P>

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Write, phone, fax and/or e-mail your representatives and senators, urging
them to oppose HR2179. Tell them to resist any increase in the level of dolphin mortality and to
maintain the prohibition on the sale of dolphin-unsafe tuna. House of Representatives:
202-224-3121.

<HR>

