<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Democratizing Transportation</TITLE>

<H1>Democratizing Transportation</H1>

<H2>by Cameron Yee</H2>

The costs and benefits of our country's transportation system are not always equally shared.
Different people are affected differently by the way we implement transportation policy.<P>

"Equity analysis" is a planning technique that looks at the distribution of the cost-and-benefit effects of
transportation on different socio-economic groups. Typical divisions include income, neighborhood
and ethnicity. But how do these studies assess the effects of public policy on low-income groups and
people of color?<P>

National, regional and local transportation policies usually focus on reducing automobile use or increasing the efficiency of traffic-clogged freeways. Congestion on freeways
typically occurs during peak-travel periods, but these periods do not include many low-income
people. Because congestion is usually defined in terms of level of service (e.g., the average traffic
speed or the degree of vehicle delay), this leads to analyses that are narrow in scope, since they
focus on the equity impacts affecting the mobility of cars and not the mobility of the region's people.<P>

One common method of defining costs in equity analyses is by valuing people's time. The cost of
congestion to a person is thus measured in terms of time lost due to traffic delays. The dollar
amount of this lost time can be measured in terms of a person's wages or income. As a result,
poorer people's time is undervalued because their wages are lower and they tend to travel less in
private cars. Using this analysis, the value of busses and other forms of mass transit also tends to
be undervalued.<P>

As the realization grows that building more roads to accommodate single-passenger vehicles does not solve congestion problems, market-based transportation policies such as
"congestion-pricing" are being considered. Congestion-pricing essentially charges a fee to drivers
who use roads during the most congested periods. Congestion-pricing promises to make freeways
less congested by penalizing drivers who use the freeways at the most-congested time. Like most
other policies, this type of program focuses on improving freeway access for auto users.<P>

In November 1992, the Federal Highway Administration (FHA) solicited proposals to fund up to five
congestion-pricing pilot programs across the US. The FHA accepted only one plan, the Bay Bridge
Congestion Pricing Demonstration Program (BBCPDP), developed by the San Francisco Bay Area's
Metropolitan Transportation Commission. The BBCPDP proposes to raise the toll of the
Oakland-to-San Francisco Bay Bridge from $1 to $3 during the 6-to-9 am and 3-to-6 pm
commutes, when congestion is worst.<P>

In the process of developing this pricing scheme, the BBCPDP team acknowledged that there were concerns regarding the "equity" impacts of the increased toll on
low-income drivers. It addressed the problem in two ways:<P>

<UL>

<LI>Revenues from the project will be used to expand affordable alternatives to driving in the Bay Bridge corridor; and<P>

<LI>A "lifeline" toll rate of $1 will be offered to low-income drivers who can prove that their household income is at or
below 150 percent of the federal poverty level.<P>

</UL>

 While the program designers put a great deal of effort into trying to address the impacts of transit policy on low-income drivers, many questions
remain before congestion-pricing and other market-based programs can be fairly implemented:<P>

<UL>

<LI>How will the revenues be used? While the proposed use of BBCPDP revenues is to mostly improve
mass transit alternatives in the Bay Bridge corridor, there is no guarantee that the revenues will
actually be used in this manner. Such revenues must be used to improve the overall mobility
alternatives for the entire transportation system, not just for automobile users.<P>

<LI>What potential spillover effects could congestion pricing have on other freeways and corridors? Harmful health
and air-quality impacts could be transferred to other freeways and interchanges. Also likely to be
affected by changing land-use patterns are the Bay Area's "flatland" communities, where many
people of color and low-income residents live.<P>

<LI>Will congestion pricing encourage or discourage sprawl? Will the transportation and land-use link be better addressed? Higher-income drivers
may find that improved travel time will allow them to live in neighborhoods further from their
place of employment. Urban areas could become more impoverished while new suburbs chew up
more farmland and open space.<P>

</UL>

While addressing these issues is a difficult task, it is an important one in terms of building a socially just transportation system that provides equal mobility
alternatives for all people. It is imperative that the goals of the transportation system should be
appropriately defined before any analysis takes place. Policymakers must realize whose lives and
health are at risk before making decisions that can affect human and community health.<P>

Earth Island's Urban Habitat Program is currently developing a framework and methodology to address
the impacts of market-based transportation-control measures and transportation policies.

<HR>

Cameron Yee is a Transportation Policy Associate with the Urban Habitat Program. This article is
reprinted from the October 1995 issue of UHP's magazine, <I>Race, Poverty & the Environment</I>,
which is devoted to "Transportation and Social Justice" (cost $5). Yee's full report is
available at a cost of $12. For a complete list of publications, contact UHP, c/o EII.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


