<TITLE>EIJ Fall 95: Mapping the Pathways to Survival</TITLE>

<H1>Mapping the Pathways to Survival</H1>

<H2>by Joe Lamb and Martha Belcher</H2>

In August, nine members of Earth Island's Borneo Project (BBP) returned from a
two-week visit to the village of Uma Bawang Keluan, a longhouse community of Kayan Indigenous
people in the rainforest of Borneo that has been at the forefront of Indonesia's Indigenous rights and
rainforest preservation movement for almost a decade.<P>

In 1987 a logging company illegally bulldozed a road through the village's orchard and so angered a majority of the people that they
blockaded the logging road and formed the Uma Bawang Residents' Association (UBRA) to oppose the
logging. When more than 40 of the villagers were arrested in logging blockades, their actions
caught the attention of a small group of environmental activists in Berkeley, California. In 1991
UBRA and the city of Berkeley joined together as "Sister Communities" to foster cultural and
educational exchanges and to lend each other support in their common quest for an ecologically
sustainable future.<P>

The BBP had four reasons for its most recent trip to Uma Bawang: to honor Berkeley's sister community for its vision and courage; to chronicle UBRA's ongoing efforts to
return control of the rainforest to its Indigenous inhabitants; to assess the potential for
micro-hydro and/or solar electrification of the village; and to teach the Indigenous peoples of
Borneo's Sarawak state how to map their ancestral lands. <P>

In the past 20 years, enormous tracts of the Sarawak rainforest have been severely damaged by overlogging. Now the native people face the
very real threat that their land will be converted into oil-palm plantations. Mapping skills may
prove critical to Indigenous peoples as they struggle to regain control of their lands. The Sarawak
Constitution recognizes Indigenous land claims according to traditional means of marking territory,
including the location of ancestral orchards, ancient swidden fields and graves of ancestors. Maps
made by native peoples may soon appear in court as Indigenous peoples attempt to document their
territorial rights and sue for damages done to their forests and farms.<P>

Mapping may also help to prevent environmental damage. Community maps may be able to stop the logging of forests that have
been customarily set aside as habitat preserves for game and community nurseries for rattan and
other essential plants. Maps can also mark places of value to the community and thereby preserve
the knowledge of their significance. Knowledge of the land is an essential part of any Indigenous
culture -- when that knowledge dies, part of culture dies with it.<P>

Leading the mapping workshop were BBP's Judith Mayer, Daniel Scollon, and Mark Talley, with support from Anushka Drescher,
Richard Hayman, Didi Sugandi, Martha Belcher and John Paisley. A majority of the people from
Uma Bawang, from very young to very old, attended the workshop. They were joined by two
representatives from Friends of the Earth-Malaysia, and by delegates from three other
communities.<P>

Judith, Dan and Mark introduced the basics of mapping by having small groups sketch from memory a rough map of their community. For these "sketch maps," scale and exact locations
were not considered important. The purpose was for the mappers to record features of their
community and in so doing to discover what parts of the material world are important to them. The
participants all threw themselves into the task with enthusiasm, cooperation and good humor.<P>

An elderly man, one of the chief warriors of the village, drew a picture of a wild boar to indicate where
hunting is the best; a young boy drew the soccer field; a woman put down choice places to collect
fern shoots. The participants worked on the sketch maps late into the night, carefully drawing fruit
trees and arguing about the exact locations of trails and rivers. The final sketch maps bulged with
information and were impressive in their creativity and artistry.<P>

When the workshop turned to the more challenging technical phase, participants remained interested and engaged as they learned how
to survey their land using a compass and tape measure. They were also shown how to use two Global
Positioning Systems (GPS) to measure precise locations on the Earth's surface by bouncing radio
signals off Department of Defense satellites. The GPS units (which cost $3800) were donated by the
Magellan Systems Corporation [960 Overlook Court, San Dimas, CA 91733; (909) 344-5000;
fax: (909) 344-7050].<P>

Leaving the longhouse to put theory to practice, workshop participants and BBP members scrambled through dramatically beautiful and very rugged rainforest terrain to
survey UBRA's project boundaries. They complete a survey of the village's agroforestry project, an
area that has been set aside for growing fruit trees, rattan and meranti, a tree that is currently
endangered by the blades of Borneo's timber companies. They also surveyed the communal forest
preserve, an area to be maintained as "tended wilderness" -- i.e., a community-owned forest for
hunting and gathering.<P>

For the final phase of the workshop, the participants took the data they had collected and drafted a scaled map. In an open-air pavilion, women tattooed from wrist to elbow
chewed betel nut while plotting the GPS coordinates they had gathered the previous day.
Neon-colored butterflies the size of bats flitted through the pavilion. Children tossed inflated globes
back and forth while their parents checked and cross-checked the data. The air was sometimes thick
with excitement. Loud communal "aaahhhs" escaped when sections of the map were finished and
pinned up for display. It was a magical experience.<P>

The workshop was a great success. Villagers finished their map and, after our return to Berkeley, we received word that UBRA had been invited
to teach mapping to several other nearby communities.<P>

Regardless of the outcome of future legal struggles, the mapping was significant: it honored the knowledge and aspirations of the villagers, it
united generations in common work, it reinforced links with the land and with ancestral caring for
the land.

<HR>

Joe Lamb and Martha Belcher are co-directors of the BBP [1137 Hearst Avenue, #D, Berkeley, CA
94702: (510) 649-8460].

<HR>

