<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: McLibel Trial Revelations:  McDonalds' Appetite for Trees</TITLE>

<H1>McLibel Trial Revelations:<BR>
 McDonalds' Appetite for Trees</H1>
 
 <H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

United Kingdom (via EcoNet) -- Claiming that it had been defamed by a six-page leaflet criticizing
its operations, the McDonalds' fast-food chain brought a libel action in the UK against two London
activists, Dave Morris and Helen Steel (Winter  '94-95 EIJ). Denied their right to a jury trial at
McDonalds' request, Morris and Steel are conducting their own defense against McDonalds' team of
top libel lawyers. Some 180 British and international witnesses are set to testify. Now expected to
run until at least December, the McLibel case has become the longest libel trial in British history.
The following highlights were drawn from e-mail reports for February (weeks 20-24 of the
trial).

<H3>McAttack on Forests</H3>

Theo Hopkins, an independent researcher on the degradation and destruction of temperate and boreal
forests, testified for the defense on the damaging effects of modern industrial forestry and
McDonald's use of hundreds of thousands of tons of paper packaging in Europe and the US.<P>

 Hopkins outlined the troubled state of the forests in countries that provided the source for McDonald's
packaging -- North America, the Czech Republic, Finland, Sweden and the UK. In Britain, Hopkins
noted, more than 40 percent of the country's surviving ancient woodland had been felled since
WWII, largely replaced by conifer plantations. Hopkins testified that the scale of world paper pulp
production has "increased by five times over the last 40 years" to become the major <A HREF="../paper/woodfact.html">use of timber</A>.
To protect forests, Hopkins stated, the first priority is to reduce paper consumption, especially in
rich countries. Hopkins also told the court that <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">alternative plant sources of paper fiber</A> (e.g., <A HREF="../paper/kenaf.html">kenaf</A>,
hemp, bagasse, cotton waste) offered better quality paper than wood pulp.<P>

 David Walker, chairman and owner of McKey Foods (a former McDonald's subsidiary that has been the sole supplier of UK
hamburgers since 1978), admitted that he had personally organized the direct import of five
consignments of Brazilian beef for McDonald's UK stores in 1983-4.<P>

 A letter from Walker written in May, 1983 and introduced in court revealed that the imports were a matter of great controversy.
In the letter, Walker recalled an occasion when Prince Philip, President of the World Wildlife
Fund, had confronted the president of McDonald's Canada and had said (quoting from Walker's
letter): "So you are the people who are tearing down the Brazilian rainforests and breeding cattle!"
Following this encounter, Fred Turner, the chairman of McDonald's Corporation, issued a
worldwide edict that no McDonald's plant was to use Brazilian beef.<P>

But, according to the Walker letter, the then-managing director of McDonald's UK gave Walker permission to continue using
Brazilian beef imports. The imports were kept secret from Prince Philip, the World Wildlife Fund,
the BBC and environmental groups. The issue only came to light when McDonald's lawyers
mistakenly included the handwritten letter in a bundle of other documents released to the McLibel
defendants last year.<P>

<H3>McDonald's Defended by Stump</H3>

Stacy Stump, the manager of a trouble-plagued McDonald's in Chelsea, UK, admitted under oath that
there had been many complaints about the store's trash and litter, but claimed that "trash walks" to
pick up litter were conducted "approximately every 30 minutes."<P>

Stump testified that his store generated "something like 10,500 potential items of litter" (bags, straws, cups and napkins)
every day. Stump admitted that the litter ended up far from the store -- in local residents'
basements, under cars and in bushes. <P>

He said the company made cleanliness a high priority. However, the defendants pointed out that the company's "observation checklists" for employees'
work habits assigns higher marks for "crew person smiles... as often as possible" than for
neighborhood litter patrols. <P>

In response, McDonald's called Professor Graham Ashworth, Director-General of the Tidy Britain Group (TBG), to the stand. Lawyers for the McLibel Two,
however, got Ashworth to admit that TBG was sponsored by McDonald's to the tune of #200,000
($316,000) per annum and also accepted corporate funding from Coca-Cola, whose cans, Ashworth
agreed, appeared to be "the most numerous on the streets of Britain." Ashworth was also forced to
admit that TBG accepted funding from <A HREF="ogoni.html">Shell Oil</A>, which has been repeatedly convicted and fined for
pollution incidents.<P>

 Ashworth conceded that McDonald's was in the "top one or two percent" of all companies whose products end up as litter and acknowledged that packaging, including polystyrene,
"has been mistaken as food and swallowed by animals," causing the wildlife to starve to death, while
other litter ended up being blown into rivers and the sea.<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2> 

For more information, contact: US McLibel Support Campaign Press Office, Box
62, Craftsbury, VT 05650-0062; (802)586-9628; dbriars@world.std.com.

<HR>

<H2>Polluted Burgers To-Go</H2>

During the McLibel trial, meat supplier David Walker explained how all raw beef supplies were
microbiologically tested and labeled "satisfactory," "passable" and "unsatisfactory."
("Unsatisfactory" describes meat with a total colony of more than 10 million bacteria per gram).
Walker then admitted that consignments designated as " unsatisfactory" were, in fact, not rejected
and were used for McDonald's hamburgers.<P>

John Atherton, McDonald's Head of Training, admitted that McDonald's receives between 1500-2750 customer complaints of food poisoning a year.
McDonald's also receives an estimated 800 reports of "foreign bodies" in burgers, mostly bits of
plastic. -- EcoNet

<H2>Worldwide Anti-Mac Day</H2>

On April 15, activists marked the 40th anniversary of McDonald's with hundreds of demonstrations
at McDonald's outlets in New Zealand, Spain, Scotland, Sweden, Switzerland, Ireland, Poland,
Denmark, Australia, <A HREF="../immp/immp3.html">Norway</A>, The Netherlands, Germany, Finland, Croatia, the Czech Republic, UK
and US. In Chicago, Helen Steel and David Morris (the "McLibel Two") held a press conference at the
site of the first McDonald's restaurant. Morris and Steel smashed a birthday cake to protest "40
years of junk food, junk jobs, and discarded mountains of just plain junk." In the UK, McDonald's
customers  received a shock when 200 bicyclists participating in a "Critical Mass" pro-bike
demonstration staged a "bike through"  at the restaurant.              -- EcoNet

<HR>

