<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Golf Endangers Hawai'ian Ecology and Culture</TITLE>

<H1>Golf Endangers Hawai'ian Ecology and Culture</H1>

<H2>by Sara Chamberlain</H2>

Hawai'i -- South Kona district, on the west coast of Hawai'i Island, is an historic treasure trove,
with more than 800 traditional Hawai'ian archeological sites, including temples, stone carvings,
dwellings and burial mounds. Direct descendants of the buried dead still live in South Kona's
small-scale farming and fishing communities. The preservation of the region's rural environment
is crucial for the survival of traditional Hawai'ian culture. Protecting South Kona's coastal
environs is also critical for the <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">dolphins</A> in the national Marine Life Sanctuary at Kealakekua Bay.<P>

However, the tranquillity of South Kona is about to be irrevocably disrupted by the construction of
a resort complex and three nine-hole golf courses only three kilometers (1.86 miles) from the
marine sanctuary. In 1990, Japan Air Lines (JAL) bought 1540 acres of agricultural land in South
Kona and established a company, Oceanside 1250, to develop a resort called "The Village at
Hokukano," consisting of 1440 luxury home sites, a private members' lodge of 100 units and the
golf courses. JAL owns   75 percent of the $41 million development.<P>

 Local residents, Native Hawai'ians and environmentalists are united in their opposition to the plan. According to the
Malaysia-based Global Anti-Golf Movement (GAG'M), golf courses "destroy natural ecosystems,
contaminate the environment and threaten human health." At South Kona, more than 175 sacred  
sites and numerous <A HREF="../tibet/tibet.html">indigenous plant species still used for medicinal purposes</A> would be destroyed by
bulldozers.<P>

 "Invaluable biological diversity will be replaced with a package of imported grass, fertilizers and a wide range of chemicals, including pesticides, herbicides, chemical fertilizers,
fungicides, soil improving agents, 'understrata hardening agents,' coagulants and artificial coloring
agents," wrote Chee Yoke Ling of GAG'M in a letter to JAL's president, Matsuo Toshimitsu.<P>

According to a New York State Department of Law report, "Toxic Fairways: Risking Groundwater
Contamination from Pesticides on Long Island Golf Courses," a typical 18-hole golf course annually
uses 50,000 pounds of dry and liquid chemicals (containing approximately 1000 pounds of active
ingredients) -- about 18 pounds per treated acre (seven times the amount used by large-scale
agriculture).<P>

In South Kona, the introduction of thousands of pounds of chemicals would pose a risk to the health of local residents, while chemical runoff could threaten marine life. A recent study by
the Golf Superintendents Association of America noted an alarmingly high rate of cancer deaths
among former members and recommended that current members reduce exposure to pesticides.
Meanwhile, the US Ladies Pro Golf Association offers free mammograms to its members because of a
marked increase in breast cancer among women professional golfers.<P>

With golf courses consuming 500,000-800,000 gallons of water per day, The Village at Hokukano would intensify South Kona's
water shortage, possibly forcing local Kona coffee and macadamia-nut farmers off their lands. <P>

"This huge urban project does not belong in this small rural community," said Nancy Pisicchio, president
of Plan to Protect South Kona.<P>

 Kekuni Blaisdell, coordinator of Ka Pakaukau-Indigenous Hawai'ian Coalition, added that most jobs created by the resort complex would be menial, which would
"contribute to the further subordination of our local residents, who are determined to preserve a
rural, agricultural and subsistence fishing lifestyle in the tradition of our ancestors."<P>

 Charles Villa, vice-president of Plan to Protect South Kona, has collected 1300 signatures against the
project, representing one-quarter of South Kona's local population. Villa and a coalition of groups,
including GAG'M, have filed a lawsuit against the county of Hawai'i, alleging that JAL arranged to
have the property's zoning illegally changed to accommodate the development. Despite local and
international opposition, JAL plans to begin construction in early 1996.<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Write Matsuo Toshimitsu, President, JAL, Tokyo Building, 7-3 Marunouchi 2-Chome, Chiyoda-Kui, Tokyo 100 Japan.

<HR>

<H2>If You Can't Beat 'Em, Join 'Em</H2>

Each year, 350 new golf courses are built worldwide -- an average of nearly one new course per
day. In 1987, the New York Audubon Society (NYAS), an independent state Audubon Society, created
the Audubon Cooperative Sanctuary System and the Signature Cooperative Sanctuary Program to
"encourage builders to go above and beyond government requirements" for golf construction and
management.<P>

Both programs offer environmental education, "guidance" and certification to participating projects. However, once registered, golf courses do not have to adhere to specific
environmental standards. A developer simply pays the $4500 membership fee and adopts the NYAS'
"principles for sustainable resource management" as a "guidance document." One principle declares
that "recreational opportunities should not detract from or destroy natural areas." Because they are
obviously unable to uphold this principle, the 1500-member courses probably registered for
advertising purposes.<P>

Although NYAS' attempt to educate golf course developers is praiseworthy, it does give them an opportunity for greenwashing. For instance, the Colliers Reserve course in
Florida, which has been awarded "signature status," uses chemical pesticides, herbicides and
fertilizers that contain 500 pounds of active ingredients. Native grasses and recycled plastic chairs
cannot offset the negative impacts of a golf course.<P>

The National Audubon Society has stated that it has nothing to do with  NYAS's certification programs.

<HR>

