<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: The Genesis of GENI</TITLE>

<H2>A Plan for a Fuller Future?</H2>

<H1>The Genesis of GENI</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

USA -- On September 22, 1994, ex-Alaska Governor Walter Hickel addressed 1000 delegates at
the United Nations in New York and proposed that the solution to world peace was to stop spending
trillions of dollars on war and, instead, spend trillions of dollars on "big projects." Hickel even had
a particular big project in mind -- the Global Energy Network International. <P>

GENI [<I>PO Box 81565, San Diego, CA 92138</I>] is a nonprofit organization that advocates installing giant electrical
transmission lines across continents and through oceans. GENI claims that its mission is "For all
people to have access to ecologically sustainable energy."<P>

 "War puts people to work and gives them a purpose," Hickel told the UN delegates, "But why war? Why not big projects? After all, war is just
a big project." Hickel admitted the concept was not new: "It's as old as the pyramids and the
aqueducts of Rome."<P>

Powerlines have a major environmental impact since, on average, building each mile of a GENI-sized transmission line requires clearing nearly five acres of land. By 1992,
27,000 acres of Canadian land had been cleared to make room for one 550-mile-stretch of
GENI-linked powerline.<P>

GENI's stylish quarterly newsletter is salted with quotes from Margaret Mead and Dwight D. Eisenhower, and photos of luminaries like UN Secretary General Boutros
Boutros-Ghali. GENI also notes that the concept of an intercontinental power grid has been endorsed
by Noel Brown, the recently retired head of the UN Development Program and by Vice President Al
Gore in his book, <CITE>Earth in the Balance</CITE>.<P>

The newsletter promotes the idea that GENI is simply advancing the goals of Buckminster Fuller, the visionary engineer who first proposed linking all
continents to a global electricity grid. Fuller's portrait is featured prominently on GENI literature,
while an insert announces a July 14-16 Buckminster Fuller 100th Centennial Symposium &
Celebration in San Diego (cosponsored by GENI).<P>

GENI's proponents argue that "there is a direct tie-in between energy and poverty." At the UN population conference in Cairo last year, GENI's
backers decorated their display booth with a series of impressive charts designed to demonstrate
that increased electrical consumption reduces population growth, lowers infant mortality,
increases life expectancy, boosts literacy levels and improves water quality.<P>

<H3>GENI's Corporate Beneficiaries</H3>

But global mega-projects (even well-meaning ones) are not financed or built by visionaries. As
documents uncovered by the <CITE>Journal</CITE> disclosed in 1992, "GENI's participants include the World
Bank, Westinghouse, PG&E, Mitsubishi, General Electric and Siemens." <P>

World-energy use mirrors other prevailing North-South inequities. Sixty percent of the world population uses less than 1000
kilowatt-hours/capita/year (kwh). Approximately 20 percent of the population (in the
industrialized countries of Latin America, Southeast Asia and the Middle East) consume
1000-2000 kwh per year.<P>

 Only 20 percent of the world population (1.1 billion people) enjoys access to more than 2000 kwh per year. <P>
 
World electric-energy use in 1990 was estimated at 12,000 terrawatt-hours (a terrawatt is 1000 gigawatts; a gigawatt is 1000 megawatts) per year.
There is an estimated 13,000 twh of <A HREF="hydroque.html">hydroelectric</A> potential in Earth's free-flowing rivers, only
about 15 percent of which has been tapped. But who really stands to benefit from electrifying the
planet?<P>

While GENI proclaims that a global grid would benefit underdeveloped countries, the globalization of electricity would also unleash a new race to control, develop and exploit Third
World resources.<P>

In August, 1994, M. Maher Abaza, Egypt's Minister of Electricity and Energy, gave the keynote speech to the International Conference on Large High-Voltage Electric Systems
(CIGRE), spelling out a plan to build an electrical grid connecting Africa and Europe. Abaza claimed
that building hydroelectric dams and long-distance transmission lines was "the aim of
environmentalists as well as hope for the peoples of developing countries."<P>

Hydropower would be cleaner than fossil-fueled power and the "revenues from export... would contribute to the sustained
development of the producing countries," he rationalized.<P>

According to Abaza, an "Egypt-Zaire Interconnection" would harness the Zaire River's powerful flow with hydroelectric dams and send
the power north to Europe to supply "clean hydroelectric energy to replace <A HREF="codsquad.html">fossil fuel-burning
power plants</A>." Successive steps would move to tap "the exploitable hydroelectric potentials in
Northern Africa," estimated at approximately 1000 twh/year. Beyond that, Abaza claimed, lie the
untamed rivers of "Africa, Latin America and Asia, where hydro potentials are available and could
be exported to the industrialized countries...."<P>

Fostering a "power pool of Mediterranean Sea countries" would be the "first step" toward "increasing imports of clean electricity from Africa."
In the meantime, CIGRE will be working to assure the "integration of power systems with and
between continents."<P>

In its determination to interconnect its campaign with Fuller's legend, GENI has produced a version of Fuller's Dymaxion(TM) Map with a Global Energy Grid stamped
prominently on top of it (available for a $15 donation). There are also videos, T-shirts, brochures
and even a GENI key ring.<P>

The most Bucky-boggling promotion of all, however, is GENI's "A Buck-a-Day for Bucky." Alongside a portrait of Fuller, GENI's literature "invites you to commit a
minimum of just one dollar a day... in support of GENI's work this year -- in honor of
Bucky."<P>


<HR>

