<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: A Visionary Proposal for the Desert West</TITLE>

<H1>A Visionary Proposal for the Desert West</H1>

<H2>by John Sterling</H2>

Infamous desert denizen Edward Abbey lamented in his book <CITE>Desert Solitaire</CITE> that too many people
were visiting the deserts of southern Utah where he worked as a park ranger in the 1960s.
Tourists arrived in droves, surveyed the desert from their car seats, then left. Few who visited
truly understood the desert or respected its unique beauty. This, said Abbey, was a terrible fate.
Today's deserts should be so lucky.<P>

American deserts, most of which are public lands, are victims of some of the most destructive human activities imaginable. Ranchers graze cattle on desert lands,
trampling the delicate ecosystem; mining companies extract millions-of-dollars worth of minerals
from the desert by stripmining and cyanide heap-leach mining; the federal government uses the
Nevada desert for underground nuclear bomb testing; the Air Force nearly built a bombing range in
the scenic Idaho desert; and, recreationally, the deserts of the West are a favorite playground for
off-road vehicle users.<P>

These sparsely populated and, for the most part, rarely visited lands have recently become the battleground for some of the most important environmental conflicts of the
'90s. The Wise Use movement considers the arid regions of the West to be only as valuable as the
resources they contain. This "use-it-or-lose-it" mentality has inspired conservationists to form
local desert-protection movements throughout the Western states, most notably in California,
where vigorous efforts won the 1994 passage of the California Desert Protection Act, designed to
protect eight million acres of southern California desert -- the largest wilderness area in the
continental US. But in the same year as this milestone victory, Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt
led losing efforts to strengthen the laws that regulate mining and grazing on federal lands, much of
which occurs in desert areas. Many desert advocates think it is time to protect the arid West not
state-by-state, but as a single, vast bioregion.<P>

In July, 1994, leading desert activists met at the Sierra Club lodge on California's Donner Summit to discuss the Great American Desert Protection
Act (GADPA), a visionary proposal, still in its infancy, to unite the many state desert wildlands
proposals under a comprehensive, national legislative act. GADPA would create a 30-40
million-acre desert wilderness out of non-wilderness Bureau of Land Management (BLM) lands in
the arid regions of Idaho, Oregon, Nevada, California, Utah, Montana, New Mexico, Arizona,
Colorado, Washington and Wyoming. "It's going to take a long, long time and lots of work, but we
take it very seriously," said Marge Sill, a Sierra Club activist in Nevada.<P>

GADPA is the brainchild of Bill Marlett, director of the Oregon Natural Desert Association, who dreams of a unified Western
desert coalition. Marlett has been fighting for several years to protect Oregon's deserts from
grazing, but has been foiled by what he calls "parochial state politics." Marlett thinks that GADPA
would benefit from a national debate. "Western senators are still in the back pockets of the
cowboys," said Marlett. "But if we elevate the debate to the national level, I think we have a better
chance. These are national-interest lands and their fate deserves a national discussion."<P>

<H3>Gazing Rights vs. Grazing Rites</H3>

The Federal Land Policy Act of 1976 mandated that the BLM inventory its lands to determine which
should be protected as wilderness areas. As a result of this inventory, the agency recommended that
roughly eight million acres of desert be converted to wilderness status, guarding it from oil, gas
and mining development. GADPA supporters have taken the BLM recommendations and added
millions of additional acres to comprise their proposed wilderness.<P>

"The BLM recommendations would protect the cream of the crop of the bureau's desert lands," said Marlett, noting that GADPA
would safeguard five times more land than the BLM. "GADPA would achieve a more holistic,
ecological approach to wilderness. It aims to protect biodiversity, not just scenery."<P>

Before mounting an aggressive national campaign, GADPA advocates must first agree on the level of land
protection they hope to attain, a contentious issue that comes down to a single factor -- cattle.
Ranching is the only industry the BLM permits in its wilderness areas, but ironically, grazing has
caused far more damage to desert lands than any other activity.<P>

Whether to allow grazing on public lands represents a struggle between principles and politics for GADPA supporters. "Most people
believe that cows and public lands are anathema, but the political returns for taking on the cowboys
are so small that most environmental groups don't do it," said GADPA supporter John Horning,
director of watershed protection for Forest Guardians, a New Mexico-based group that focuses on
Southwest public land issues.<P>

The GADPA coalition unanimously opposes desert grazing, but some think that, to be realistic, the proposal should not prohibit grazing. Marlett insists that "the
question is not whether cows in wilderness are OK, but how and when to remove them. It is not a
question of ecology, but strategy."<P>

Once the grazing issue is resolved, GADPA still faces an uphill battle. Raising the GADPA debate to the national level may be the only way to win a grand desert
wilderness, but it will likely trigger vicious opposition from the growing number of people in the
West who think that public lands belong not to all Americans, but to the states in which they lie.
This perplexing notion is no less radical than GADPA, but it appeals more to the miners, ranchers
and loggers who seem to fear everything about the federal government, except the subsidies that
they receive to exploit public lands.<P>

Though still in its planning stages, GADPA may join the Wildlands Project and the Northern Rockies Ecosystem Protection Act (NREPA) on the list of
visionary wilderness proposals that at first may be criticized for being politically unrealistic, but
eventually gain recognition because they make good ecological sense.<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Contact the Oregon Natural Desert Association, 16 NW Kansas, Bend, OR, 97701; (503)385-6908.
<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


