<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Beyond Clayoquot Sound</TITLE>

<H1>Beyond Clayoquot Sound</H1>

<H2>by Christopher Genovali</H2>

As the struggle to prevent industrial logging from destroying the ancient rainforests of Vancouver
Island's Clayoquot Sound is being played out under the spotlight of international scrutiny, the
temperate rainforests of Canada's British Columbia coast are being ravaged almost unnoticed by
rampant clearcutting.<P>

An estimated 56 percent of the world's ancient temperate rainforests, located primarily in Chile and British Columbia, has been destroyed. Only 10 percent of the original
forests of New Zealand and the conterminous US still remain. BC contains the majority of the
planet's extant intact acreage.<P>

The remote and rugged rainforest wilderness of the BC mainland coast remains largely unknown. It is an enormous region comprising approximately 30,000 square
miles. Though its Pacific Coast is dominated by scrub forests and muskeg-like lowlands, the
landscape becomes more dramatic toward the interior, with huge granite buttresses, deep-water
fjords and sedge-filled estuaries leading to steep, narrow river valleys carpeted with western
hemlock, Sitka spruce, Pacific silver fir, yellow cedar and western red cedar.<P>

The river valleys are the biological core of the mainland coast, providing critical habitat for wild salmon, grizzly
bears, bald eagles, wolves and a host of other wildlife. The <A HREF="../paper/woodfact.html">timber industry</A> principally covets this
wildlife habitat in the river valleys for its productive lowland forests.<P>

<H3>Unsustainable Logging</H3>

According to Vancouver-based Sierra Legal Defense, the BC Ministry of Forests purposely sets the
rate of logging in BC at unsustainable levels in order to quickly cut valuable old-growth trees and
then implement plantation forestry. Last year, approximately 120,000 acres of temperate BC
rainforest were clearcut (roughly 24 percent of all old-growth forest cut in the province).<P>

Despite government and logging industry propaganda (embodied in such empty sloganeering as "forest
renewal," "world-class logging" and "getting greener all the time"), shade-dependent coastal
rainforest species cannot adequately develop in sunny clearcuts. The trees never fully mature and
are appropriate only for pulping.<P>

A mere ten companies control nearly 60 percent of the timber-harvesting rights on BC's public lands. These monopolies secure non-competitive access to
huge volumes of rare and valuable timber by making meager "stumpage payments" that return a
fraction of the wood's value to the province.<P>

The lax regulatory climate and expanding corporate control does not bode well for BC's mainland coast. Due to the remoteness and inaccessibility of the
region, the destruction is taking place almost in a vacuum. The Raincoast Conservation Society
(RCS), a grassroots BC environmental organization, has taken the initiative to lift the "clearcut
curtain."<P>

RCS founder and long-time BC forest activist Peter McAllister has spent the last four years exploring the mainland coast by schooner, zodiac, kayak, canoe, plane and foot. McAllister has
documented the wilderness areas at risk and has compiled an extensive inventory of the
salmon-producing rivers and streams that have been destroyed by clearcutting and those that are
threatened by continued logging.<P>

"We are staggered by the probable extinction of wild salmon populations," said McAllister. "Most of the rivers we have reviewed show a remarkable consistency
of decline." Wild coho and sockeye have been acutely impacted as a result of habitat degradation
caused by clearcutting.<P>

Grizzly bears on the mainland coast require large stretches of intact wilderness to survive. However, much of the ecologically rich ancient forest wilderness has already
been liquidated in the big river valleys, causing widespread fragmentation of grizzly habitat and
populations.<P>

According to McAllister, the BC Ministry of Forests plans to allow approximately 95 percent of the productive rainforests on the mainland coast to be clearcut. The federal government
said in a 1991 "State of the Environment" report that most of BC's coastal temperate rainforest
will be cut by 2008. Mc-Allister warns that this will practically guarantee the extinction of one of
the densest grizzly populations left on Earth. The Raincoast Conservation Society has called for a
public investigation into the grizzly habitat destruction on the mainland coast. McAllister calls it
"one of the most serious wildlife scandals in North America."

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

For information, contact: Canadian Forest Protection Project, Pacific Environment & Resources Center, Fort Cronkhite, Bldg. 1055, Sausalito, CA 94965; (415)
332-8200; fax: 332-8167; Rainforest Conservation Society, #9 416 Dallas Rd., Victoria, BC
V8V 1A9, Canada; (604) 361-3402.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


