<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Hydro Quebec is Back</TITLE>

<H1>Hydro Quebec is Back</H1>

<H2>by Alexis Lathem</H2>

For the last 50 years, Hydro Quebec (HQ) has led an assault on one of North America's last great
wildernesses -- the sub-Arctic region of vast boreal forests, fragile tundra, and networks of
freshwater rivers and lakes. HQ's industrial invasion began with the damming of the wild rivers of
eastern Quebec and Labrador, a region called <I>Nitassinan</I> by its aboriginal people, the Innu.<P>

The James Bay project, a four-phase hydroelectric scheme involving dozens of pristine rivers in
Quebec, brought HQ's hydroelectric projects into the international spotlight. The Cree people of the
region have been challenging this project since the 1970s, gaining widespread international
support. Much of Phase I has been completed, but construction continues. Phase II would divert the
Great Whale River and three of its tributaries, reducing flow by 85 percent and flooding 1090
square kilometers (436 square miles) of land. In Quebec's current political climate, it is unlikely
that Phases III and IV will go forward, but building plans are complete.<P>

In November, 1994, after New York state canceled the second of two $19 billion contracts for James Bay electricity, Quebec
Premier Jacques Parizeau announced that he was postponing Phase II, known as the Great Whale
project.<P>

The jubilant mood that surrounded the announcement was quickly dampened when Great Whale's opponents learned that Parizeau refused to instruct the state-owned utility to pull out of
the environmental permitting process. Many believed that the announcement was only a political
gesture intended to silence Quebec's international critics prior to a 1995 referendum on Quebec's
independence from Canada.<P>

With the spotlight on Great Whale, HQ continued to build access roads for the Sainte Marguerite 3 (SM3) project on Quebec's North Shore. Meanwhile, the Innu opposing
SM3 fought the project in isolation from the international support networks that brought the plight
of the James Bay Cree to the world's attention.<P>

SM3 is an HQ proposal to build a new dam and restore two abandoned dams on the Ste. Marguerite River, which flows through Innu territory in
Quebec. In comparison to Great Whale, the SM3 project would be small, but its consequences would
be equally devastating to Innu culture. SM3 would join a collection of 14 existing dams erected on
the St. Lawrence River's tributaries that have already flooded an area comparable to the reservoirs
created by Phase I of the James Bay project.<P>

Nitassinan territory follows the North Shore of the St. Lawrence from Quebec City to Labrador. In this region, HQ has dammed the Bestiamites,
Manicougan, Outards and Ste. Marguerite rivers, flooding seven percent of the rich river basins
that the Innu have inhabited for thousands of years.<P>

The SM3 proposal also calls for diverting two of the Moisie River's tributaries -- the Pekan and Carheil -- into the Ste. Marguerite to increase
SM3's power-generating capacity. The Atlantic Salmon Federation has called the Moisie one of the
world's three most important salmon rivers, and the most important Atlantic salmon river in
North America. The Innu consider it their "Great River." For the Innu community of Mani-Utenam,
descendants of the Moisie band, it remains their most important tie to traditional life. For all these
reasons, HQ's proposal to divert the Pekan and Carheil rivers faced serious opposition.<P>

<H3>SM3 Construction Begins</H3>

Widespread opposition prohibited the Quebec government from authorizing the diversions of the
Moisie's tributaries, so HQ divided the SM3 project into two phases and agreed to conduct a
two-year study on the project's potential impacts on the Moisie salmon's seven-year life cycle. HQ
was thus able to proceed with the project without obtaining the necessary permits.<P>

Despite a non-binding recommendation from Quebec's environmental review board that the entire project be
rejected (because HQ could not prove that there was sufficient need for the energy to justify the
enormous economic, environmental and social costs), phase one of SM3 was authorized and
construction began in April, 1994.<P>

Innu traditionalists from Mani-Utenam initially opposed the construction through a series of referendums. When those efforts failed, they started a nonviolent
campaign that has lead to the jailing of more than 15 percent of their community.<P>

In mid-February, 1995, HQ proposed redesigning SM3 so that diverting the Pekan and Carheil rivers
would not be necessary, thus sparing the Moisie River. But when an HQ spokesperson was
subsequently asked if HQ had abandoned its plan to divert the rivers, he replied: "If there is a
demand at a later time, it could be an option." <P>

Though eliminating the immediate threat to the Moisie and its tributaries is cause for celebration, the remnants of the SM3 project would still have
significant impacts. The areas that would be flooded are fertile and biologically rich. The dam would
be built on the Grand Portage waterfalls, an Innu sacred site. Roads to the dam site would open up
inaccessible forests to clearcutting and further industrial development.<P>

The impacts of the SM3's initial construction have already been deeply felt in Innu communities. The four-year battle to
defend their land from SM3 has burdened the Mani-Utenam people with two 30-year court
injunctions. The first denies their constitutional right to public demonstrations in their own
community; the second prohibits them access to the dam site, thus denying the people access to their
federally sanctioned hunting grounds, to their ancestral burial grounds and to the Grand Portage.<P>

Twenty-three Innu face prison terms for blocking construction of an access road during a 17-day
protest in June, 1994 that was supported by an international coalition assembled by the Native
Forest Network.<P>

HQ claims that even though the territory in question is the subject of pending land claims, the utility has the right to proceed with its project. The Innu claim that to begin
construction on SM3 before the question of their land rights has been settled is a breach of those
rights. "What will it mean," asks Yvette Michel, spokesperson for the Innu traditionalists, "to have
a right to our land, if the land itself has been destroyed?"<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

 Contact Friends of Nitassinan, POB 804 Burlington VT 05402; (802) 425-3820; Eastern North America Native Forest Network, POB 57, Burlington VT 05402; (802)
863-0571.

<HR>

