<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Mekong River Plan</TITLE>

<H1>Mekong River Plan: A Disaster in the Making</H1>

<H2>by Andrew Lam</H2>

Chiang Rai, <A HREF="../gsc/thai.html">Thailand</A> -- On April 5, the governments of Cambodia, Laos, Thailand
and Vietnam signed the UN Development Program-facilitated "Agreement on the
Cooperation for the Sustainable Development of the Mekong River Basin."<P>

"Despite its environmentally friendly sounding title, the agreement could hasten the
impoverishment of human communities and the destruction of the biological
diversity of the Mekong River Basin," said Patrick McCully, Campaigns Director
for International Rivers Network [<I>IRN, 1847 Berkeley Way, Berkeley, CA 94703;
(510) 848-1155; fax: (510) 848-1008</I>].<P>

The agreement envisions construction of a six-dam cascade on the Mekong that would displace at least 60,000 people and have
extensive and irreparable effects on the rich and diverse fisheries, ecosystems
and farmlands of the lower Mekong Basin.<P>

According to IRN, the proposal (written by Canadian and French dam engineering firms) is based on flawed methodology and
incomplete technical and economic analyses. Behind the talk of "sustainable
development," McCully charged, "the world's leading hydropower firms from
Scandinavian, Australia, Canada, France and the US are lining up to grab some
'aid' money and turn the findings of this flawed report into concrete."<P>

The proposal gives the impression that these are "small" dams when, in fact, what is
proposed is a staircase of 30-to-60-meter-high (99-200-foot) dams flooding more
than 1000 kilometers (620 miles). The impacts on the Mekong River, one of the
world's most productive and diverse fisheries, would probably be severe. Mekong
fish are the main source of protein for millions of people in the river basin and
the delta's rice fields play a vital role in Vietnam's economy.

<HR>

