<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: A New Land War Rages in Vietnam</TITLE>

<H2>Rice or Riches</H2>

<H1>A New Land War Rages in Vietnam</H1>

<H2>by Patricia J. Cummings</H2>

Can Tho Province -- The landscape of Asia is sculpted by rice, from flat paddies
in floodplains to rising terraces etched into mountainsides. Rice has been
harvested in Asia for more than 7000 years and is deeply embedded in both the
land and cultures of the region.<P>

About half of the world's people live in Asia, and in rural areas, most of them are engaged in producing, transporting or
trading rice. Rice is the staple food of the poor throughout the world.<P>

Worldwide, most rice is consumed in farm households or sold locally in domestic
markets. Of the 530 million metric tons of rice grown annually, only 15 million
metric tons are sold in international trade. The rice trade is a potent political
and economic issue, especially for the largest exporters: <A HREF="../gsc/thai.html">Thailand</A>, the US and
Vietnam. Thailand is the largest exporter, but the US is the strongest player in
world markets and in setting prices and trade policy.<P>

The Vietnamese Ministry of Agriculture (MAFI) is spending millions of dollars on a new farm-diversification
program to protect the country from unpredictable domestic food shortages. MAFI
wants to encourage farmers to be less dependent on rice, to try new "high-yield"
varieties of grains and fruit trees, and to grow crops for export, like coffee
and tea.<P>

Money will be spent on educating farmers about new products and buying new animal varieties, including dairy cows. Presumably, this broader agricultural
base will act as a buffer against losses from natural disasters.<P>

Not only are small farmers suffering from the encroachment of industrial agriculture, they are
also being forced off the land by rampant uncontrolled development. Vietnam's
Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet recently called for a halt to projects that take land
out of rice production. Throughout Vietnam, hotels, houses and office buildings
are eradicating farmland. The construction boom in urban areas has already
contributed to rice shortages and a drastic rise in rice prices in the north.<P>

Ricelands are not the only targets coveted by developers. The Vancouver
investment firm, Mekong Holdings Ltd. (MHL), wants to develop Phu Quoc, a sleepy
island off Vietnam's southern coast, into an "Asian Bermuda," featuring a blend
of tourism and unregulated offshore banking.<P>

Phu Quoc Island consists of approximately 600 square-kilometers (240 square-miles) of quiet villages that are
home to 60,000 people who make their living by farming and fishing. There are no
paved roads, only unreliable power and less than ten cars on the island.<P>

MHL plans to spend $500 million on a master plan for banks, hotels, an airport, an
export processing zone and a port intended to lure investment. None of the
expensive studies commissioned to justify the project mention anything about the
environmental impacts of such development  or its consequences for the local
people.<P>

On April 30, a bright Sunday morning in Ho Chi Minh City, as I watched
the 20th-anniversary celebration of the reunification of Vietnam, the large
Soviet-style posters lining the parade route were clearly celebrating
Western-style economic progress rather than the Vietnamese military victory.
Tanks have been replaced by shiny new Mercedes Benz' (costing $200,000, if
purchased legally). Mansions are springing up and international flights are
crowded with Vietnamese wearing designer clothes and businessmen sporting
diamond-studded Rolex watches.<P>

The cabinet ministers and political leaders I have met show few signs of adopting the trappings of Western capitalism themselves,
but they seem in danger of being made rapidly irrelevant by the enormous greed
and avarice that has been let loose in this country. Newspapers reported in May,
for example, that when a few local police tried to stop the transportation of
stolen <A HREF="../paper/woodfact.html">timber</A>, the loggers simply hired some young men to beat up the police and
then left with their booty.<P>

More than 51 percent of Vietnam's population lives below the world poverty standard (earning less than $370 per year in 1990
dollars). The true test of social and economic progress will be who ultimately
gains and who loses. After being here for a year, it seems to me that the poor
are not the ones responsible for laying waste to the land and the workers are not
the ones benefiting from the bribes. The marketplace forces now rampant in
Vietnam may overcome any resistance put up by social planners or the poor.<P>

There are few watchdog groups to hold the government accountable to international
standards of environmental protection. The World Wide Fund for Nature, one of the
few environmental groups in Vietnam, is working with the Ministry of Forestry to
train local groups in conservation and wildlife-protection practices.<P>

Vietnam's development is taking place in an atmosphere of unmitigated marketeering, which
is widening the gap between a few rich and powerful people and a great many poor.
There are absolutely no consumer rights, no provisions for a right-to-know, no
accountability for transnational businesses and no citizen enforcement of weak
legal protections. It is economic change in a political landscape that the
current Republican-dominated 104th Congress could only dream about.<P>

-- From The Rice Paper, PO Box 5124, Mill Valley, CA 94942; Tra Noc Rice
Facility, Can Tho Province, Vietnam. Email: pcummings@igc.apc.org. The Rice Paper
is available via "thericepaperinfo@igc.apc.org."

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


