<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: The World's Biggest Militias</TITLE>

<H2>Weapons Incorporated</H2>

<H1>The World's Biggest Militias</H1>

<H2>by William Thompson</H2>

War-making is the world's biggest business. The US military is itself a major
multinational corporation with assets equal to half of all US manufacturing
companies combined. Nearly 40 percent of US industrial plants and equipment are
devoted to military manufacturing. In 1989, approximately 30 percent of all US
industrial output was purchased by the Pentagon. In the US, seven out of every
ten dollars urgently required for environmental and social redress are devoted to
military research and development.<P>

In terms of employment, capital investment and pollution, the world's military is already a much bigger business than
mega-corporations, such as Time-Warner, Sony or General Motors. In every country
except <A HREF="../gsc/costa.html">Costa Rica</A>, the military dwarfs secondary sectors, such as public health,
education or environmental protection, whose funding, expertise and attention are
preempted by its national-security priorities.<P>

The transnationals that serve military clients have become virtually a law unto themselves. The close
cooperation between buyers, wielders and makers of weapons has largely usurped
the democratic process in high-level decision-making.<P>

From Washington, DC to Guatemala, the question no longer concerns the military's allegiance to their
respective governments, but its allegiance to the transnational corporations that
make and market its arms.<P>

The US Chamber of Commerce reports that, by the turn of the century, a few hundred multinational corporations will likely control more
than half of the production assets of the entire planet. Six multinationals now
control one-quarter of all US defense contracts. War as a primary instrument of
national policy is one of the most bankrupt ideas of old-paradigm thinking. The
spiritual and moral failure of this 5000-year-old experiment in male dominance
has also resulted in financial bankruptcy. High-stakes players are running out of
chips and high-deficit bluffs are being called. But, despite cutbacks,
war-related concerns still account for most government expenditures.<P>

<H3>An Appetite for War</H3>

Preparing to destroy large areas of the planet is a major enterprise. The world's
militaries consume more aluminum, copper, nickel and platinum than all the
developing nations combined. Nine percent of all iron and steel used on Earth is
consumed by the military.<P>

During the Vietnam War, a single B-52 Stratofortress guzzled 3612 gallons of fuel per hour, while carriers like the USS Independence
consumed 100,000 gallons of fuel in a single day. At its peak, the Vietnam War
consumed more than one million barrels of oil a day. The costs of converting
natural resources and precious metals into bombs and bombers helped push the US
economy into a deficit-driven recession from which it never fully recovered. One
big difference between the US military and multinational corporations is that the
taxpayer-supported military is not concerned with profitability or even
cost-effectiveness.<P>

As Kristen Ostling and Joanna Miller point out in <CITE>Taking Stock: The Impact of Militarism on the Environment</CITE>, the US military is not only
the biggest single source of environmental pollution in the country, it is also
the biggest environmental outlaw. Of 383 EPA citations issued to federal
facilities in 1989, nearly three-quarters went to military installations.<P>

<H3>War Is a Dirty Business</H3>

According to environmental analyst Ruth Leger Sivard: "The world's armed forces
are the single largest polluter on Earth." A <CITE>Canadian Peace Report</CITE> study found
that today's armed forces are responsible for ten-30 percent of global
environmental damage, six-ten percent of worldwide air pollution, and 20 percent
of all <A HREF="../x/atmosph.html">ozone-destroying chlorofluorocarbon</A> use.<P>

The Government Accounting Office (GAO) reports that the US Department of Defense currently generates 500,000 tons
of toxic waste annually -- more than the top five chemical companies combined.
Even under the strictest regulations, the production, testing, maintenance and
deployment of conventional, chemical, biological, electromagnetic and nuclear
arms would generate enormous quantities of toxic and radioactive waste.<P>

Every step of war preparation involves significant ecological damage. Excavating the
Earth to extract uranium and rare metals for weapons production poisons large
tracts of land and precious groundwater. Multinationals' stripmines also strip
rights and customs from the Indigenous peoples whose sacred lands are often
expropriated by war-makers.<P>

The world's armed forces control between 750,000 and 1.5 million square kilometers (300,000-600,000 square miles) of land. The US
Department of Defense and the nuclear weapons complexes own or lease roughly
100,000 square kilometers (40,000 square miles) of land. As much as half the US
airspace is restricted for military use. Outside its own borders, the US military
controls another 8100 square kilometers (3240 square miles) of territory.<P>


According to the World Watch Institute, the Pentagon is the single largest energy
user domestically -- and very likely worldwide. In 12 months, it uses enough
energy to run the entire US urban mass transit system for 22 years. World Watch
adds that these energy figures would be substantially higher if the power
expended to manufacture weapons were included.<P>

<H3>War's Real Casualties</H3>

World War II killed 50 million people, most of whom were civilians. The 40-year
Cold War claimed the lives of 25 million people who died in more than 125 wars
fought on the periphery of the industrialized North. By the 1980s, civilian
deaths accounted for 85 percent of the world's war casualties.<P>

Besides its gruesome toll in human lives, the mass insanity unleashed by World War II also
destroyed farmland and forests, while consuming natural resources at incredible
rates.<P>

In addition to two Japanese cities obliterated by atomic weapons, scores of pristine Pacific atolls were blasted, burned and pulverized under intensive
air and naval bombardments. More than 450,000 acres of Libyan farmland were sown
with five million mines. Nazi troops flooded 17 percent of Dutch farmlands --
200,000 hectares (494,000 acres) -- with seawater. European bison were
slaughtered to near extinction to supply the mess kitchens of German and Soviet
troops in eastern Poland.<P>

During the Korean "police action," the most punishing US air attacks were directed against North Korea's major irrigation dams.
Ironically, after the Korean war, the 151-mile-long by 2.5-mile-wide
Demilitarized Zone (DMZ) became an abundant oasis in a ravaged landscape.<P>

Heavily patrolled against human incursions, the DMZ grew into a lush habitat of marshes,
meadows, and great forests of oaks, pines and maples. Lynx now prowl through what
wildlife researchers Richard and Joyce Wolkomir call one of the world's "great
wildlife paradises." Birds endangered by South Korea's post-war industrial boom
also found sanctuary in the DMZ. About ten percent of the world's 1200-1500
red-crowned cranes winter in this former killing ground.<P>

<H3>Ecocide in Vietnam</H3>

The US war against Vietnam marked the first time that military technology was
employed to destroy the environment of an entire country.<P>

Carrying 20 tons of bombs into the stratosphere, a B-52 could strike from 30,000 feet without
warning, turning entire villages into sudden eruptions of flaming sticks, human
limbs and thatch.<P>

A formation of B-52s could obliterate a "box" approximately five-eighths-of-a-mile wide by about two-miles long. These behemoths dropped 13
million tons of bombs on North and South Vietnam, Cambodia and Laos -- triple the
total tonnage dropped in World War II. Their ferocious carpet-bombing left at
least 25 million craters  -- each averaging 50 square meters (60 square yards) --
in a country the size of Washington state.<P>

When the tropical rainforest canopy -- up to 50 feet thick -- resisted the onslaught of bombs, shells and bullets, US
forces developed the 15,000-pound Daisycutter bomb, which exploded with a
shock-wave that killed earthworms 100 meters (330 feet) from the impact crater.
The aerial and ground bombardment detonated the equivalent of an eight-kiloton
bomb over Vietnam every 24 hours.<P>

Heavy bombing and herbicide spraying contributed to the precipitous decline of the red-shanked duoc langur -- one of
11 mammals found only in Southeast Asia. Air-dropped poisons and high explosives
also prodded the lemur, the pileated gibbon, Ouston's civet and the wild forest
ox to the brink of extinction. South Vietnam's lobster industry was wrecked by
over-production to satisfy American soldiers. The tiger population was similarly
decimated for the souvenir trade. Elephants and water buffalo used by the Viet
Cong to move supplies were attacked and slaughtered by US pilots and ground
troops just as the Romans had targeted Hannibal's elephants centuries before.<P>

<H3>Poison Rain and Jungle-Eaters</H3>

Encouraged by Defense Secretary Robert McNamara's fixation on technological
solutions, President Kennedy ordered chemical spraying to commence in the early
1960s. By 1966, specially modified C-130 aircraft had destroyed nearly 340,000
hectares (850,000 acres) of rainforest and crops by spraying them with
herbicides.<P>

All told, 72.4 million liters (18.8 million gallons) of pesticides were sprayed over 20 percent of the forests of South Vietnam. In approximately
one decade, 990,000 acres of prime agricultural lands were poisoned.<P>

Agent Orange, the most commonly employed defoliant in Vietnam, spread DNA-damaging
mutagens throughout Vietnam's war-torn biological web, as the rate of
miscarriages and birth defects began to increase among Vietnamese women.<P>

Precious ancient tropical forests were splintered by the blades of giant bulldozers
weighing two-and-a-half tons. Dubbed "Rome" plows by their historically minded
operators, these earth-wrecking "jungle eaters" plowed under the entire village
of Ben Suc and scraped clean 1400 acres of fertile rice paddies tilled by the
community's 3000 inhabitants.<P>

South of Saigon, in the Plain of Reeds, the five-foot-tall eastern sarus crane came under attack as US forces dug hundreds of
drainage ditches across 39,000 acres of sedge marshes. Once the coastal <A HREF="../map/map.html">mangroves</A>
were dry, the soldiers sprayed the shrubbery with flame-throwers. By war's end,
more than half of the mangrove swamps in South Vietnam had been destroyed by
chemical poisoning and napalm. When the smoke cleared, an estimated two million
hectares (5 million acres) of inland tropical forests had been heavily damaged by
bombs, shells, bulldozers and toxic defoliants.<P>

The displacement resulting from this environmental holocaust brought suffering to entire populations of animals
and humans. An ecological domino effect took place when starving hill tribes were
forced to turn from contaminated rice fields to the forests for survival. Logging
for cash and land clearing accelerated, as did subsistence hunting. In Ba Be
National Park, threatened leaf monkeys were shot by villagers to provide meat for
their families.<P>

Before the US entered the fray, southern Vietnam had been predominantly rural, with 85 percent of its population living simple lives in the
lush countryside. By the war's end, three million of Vietnam's 17 million
inhabitants had become refugees living in cities.<P>

Deforestation, erosion, drying water sources and flooding have increased drastically since the shooting stopped.
The primary cause of this water-related havoc is the decrease in Vietnam's forest
cover from 44 percent of the total land area in 1943 to only 24 percent 40 years
later. Between 100,000 and 200,000 tons of topsoil per hectare are washing down
swollen rivers to the sea each year.<P>

Deforestation is continuing in post-war Vietnam as surviving forests are felled to rebuild ten million homes, schools,
hospitals, roads and irrigation systems.<P>

This inexorable pressure is shrinking the forests the country needs for long-term sustainability at a rate of 200,000
hectares (494,000 acres) a year.<P>

With more than two-fifths of southern Vietnam's once-verdant countryside a post-war wasteland, unusable for either agriculture or
forestry, a report by the International Union for Conservation of Nature and
Natural Resources calculates that "much of this ecological damage can never be
repaired." Even more ominous is a report by Asia-Pacific's Environment Network of
Malaysia, which concluded that Vietnam is a country facing "gradual extinction."<P>

For this unlucky country, the war is not over.<P>

<HR>

-- Adapted from <CITE>Scorched Earth</CITE> by William Thompson (1995, 227 pages, $16.95. New
Society Publishers, 4527 Springfield Avenue, Philadelphia, PA 19143; (800)
333-9093).

<HR>

