<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Green Plans: The Netherlands Leads the Way</TITLE>

<H1>Green Plans: The Netherlands Leads the Way</H1>

<H2>by Huey D. Johnson</H2>

The Netherlands' 400-page National Environmental Policy Plan (NEPP),is the best
job of technical environmental planning done by any nation to date. Not only does
the NEPP "Green Plan" successfully weave together complex systems, such as water,
<A HREF="../x/atmosph.html">air</A>, soil and energy; it also meshes them with human factors of economics, health
and carrying capacity. It is a comprehensive, long-term, well-thought-out plan,
and the Dutch are putting billions of guilders into implementing it.<P>

The Dutch chose 25 years, or one generation, as a framework for achieving environmental
recovery. They use the phrase "each generation cleans up" to express this
principle as a clear, easily understandable goal that every citizen can support.<P>

There are many good reasons why the Netherlands became the first nation to adopt
a comprehensive national environmental strategy. It has always been a country of
limited natural resources, with many complex problems packed into a very small,
heavily populated area.<P>

Situated at the mouth of the Rhine, one of Europe's most polluted rivers, the Netherlands is heavily dependent on polluting industries,
such as commodity chemicals, metals and agriculture. Since 1970, the number of
cattle in the Netherlands has doubled, putting even more pressure on land and
water resources.<P>

The NEPP is now so deeply rooted in the Dutch political system that it is no longer controversial. Public support has been evident ever since
the first parliamentary vote on the plan.

<H3>The Philosophical Basis</H3>

Like most Western countries, the Dutch first began passing environmental
legislation in the early 1970s. This first wave of environmental law was devoted
to single issues -- regulating toxics, cleaning up wastes and so on. While the US
(and most of the world) has continued to use this single-issue approach, in the
1980s the Netherlands began to realize that it was not working.<P>

One of the tools the Dutch used to develop their integrated approach was a century-old law called
the Nuisance Act, which was originally designed to deal with disturbances like
unwelcome noise or odors.<P>

In the late 1980s, the Dutch began to transform that act into the centerpiece of their integrated environmental strategy. In its new
form, the act says that a facility should be considered in terms of its total
impact on the environment -- including clean air, water, soil and so on -- before
a permit is drafted.<P>

When the NEPP was presented to the parliament in 1989, it contained 223 policy changes aimed at reducing pollution and establishing
economic sustainability.<P>

The government now requires each of the 12 Dutch provinces to write a green plan and to provide an update every four years. The
provinces are mostly responsible for the implementation and enforcement of
environmental policies. The Netherlands' plan outlines three important mechanisms
for achieving sustainability: integrated lifecycle management, energy
conservation and improved product quality.<P>

<UL>

<LI>Integrated lifecycle management goes beyond simple recycling or reuse programs. It attempts to close economic and
resource-use cycles by doubling the lifespan of products and reducing the
quantity of materials used by industry.<P>

<LI>While most developed nations are using energy at a rate that will exhaust current supplies within a few
generations, the Dutch have set aside roughly $385 million per year for energy
conservation over the next four years. The national energy policy requires an
energy-efficiency improvement of at least two percent per year, installation of
1000 megawatts of wind turbine power by the year 2000, and stabilizing energy use
by the same year.<P>

<LI>Improved product quality assures that products last longer and are easier to recycle or dispose of. For example, the Dutch government now
requires auto manufacturers to figure out what can be done at the drawing-board
stage to ensure that it is easier to dispose of an old car.<P>

</UL>

The Dutch government has also established a program for developing sustainable technology through a
technique called "backcasting," which assesses what needs to be done over the
next 40-50 years to create a sustainable economy and technology by the year 2040.
Backcasting determines where the government should spend money, what sorts of new
materials it should develop, and what kind of alternative energy to adopt to
achieve sustainability.

<H3>Guiding Principles</H3>

There are a number of fundamental principles the Dutch have incorporated in the
NEPP in order to achieve sustainability. These include:<P>

<UL>

<LI>The "stand-still" principle (environmental quality may not deteriorate).<P>

<LI>Abatement at the source (remove causes rather than ameliorate effects).<P>

<LI>The "polluter pays" principle (the user of a resource pays for the negative effects of that use).<P>

<LI>Prevention of unnecessary pollution.<P>

<LI>The application of the "best practicable means" (following the development of abatement technology).<P>

<LI>Carefully controlled waste disposal.<P>

<LI>Internalization of environmental concerns (motivating people to behave responsibly).<P>

</UL>

The Dutch have taken principle six, "carefully controlled waste disposal," and mandated that no waste
will be exported: whatever is produced in the Netherlands must be taken care of
there. This is a renunciation of some countries' practice of shipping trash to
poor nations and dumping it for a fee.<P>

With 27 percent of its countryside below sea level and almost 50 percent less than one meter above sea level, the
Netherlands would be greatly affected by rising seas caused by <A HREF="../x/atmosph.html">global warming</A>. If
other nations do not follow its example, the Netherlands is doomed. That is why
the Dutch are so involved in environmental education and negotiation about
climate change at the diplomatic level.<P>

The NEPP set a goal of stabilizing the Netherlands' carbon dioxide (CO2) emissions at 1990 levels by the year 2000 (this
has since been advanced to 1995). In addition, the size of the wastestream is to
be reduced 70-90 percent.<P>

The target groups for these reforms are: agriculture, traffic and transport, industry, the energy sector, the building trade, consumers
and the retail trade, water suppliers, the waste sector, research and education,
and public organizations. The government's ability to secure business'
cooperation is a remarkable accomplishment and an essential part of the NEPP. So
far, the government knows of no business that has left Holland or gone bankrupt
because of environmental policies.<P>

To provide more information to the consumer, the government has adopted eco-labeling of environmentally friendly products and
logos that identify how to dispose of certain products. The Environmental
Advertising Code, enacted in 1991, forbids misleading claims about the
"environmental friendliness" of products.

<H3>Victories and Setbacks</H3>

One of the NEPP's management strengths is its built-in mechanisms that carefully
monitor progress and setbacks. The thoroughness and honesty of the Netherlands'
monitoring and reporting are remarkable.<P>

During the period from 1980 to 1990, emissions of sulfur dioxide, nitrogen oxides, ammonia and volatile organic
compounds were reduced by 30 percent, while phosphorus and nitrogen emissions
from wastewater and agricultural runoff decreased by five percent. As of 1992,
pesticide use had been reduced by 20 percent from 1988 levels and
chlorofluorocarbon use has been virtually eliminated in the Netherlands. By the
end of 1995, discharges of industrial wastewater into the Rhine are expected to
be 50-70 percent less than in 1985. Although not all the NEPP goals will be met,
the upward trend for most emissions has been reversed.<P>

One innovation that has caught the world's attention is the flooding of a part  of the Dutch lowlands,
drained a century ago. Previously known for building dikes rather than breaching
them, the Dutch expect to restore roughly 600,000 acres of wetlands, with the
dual goal of returning the land to the wildlife that once lived there and halting
the fall of the water table.<P>

The Dutch also have an ambitious plan to expand wildlife habitat by almost 50,000 acres and to plant almost 99,000 acres of
forest. The energy distribution target group's action plan achieved 90 percent of
its CO2 reduction target in its first year. Such large-scale projects would be
next-to-impossible without a comprehensive and integrated plan, because they
involve several ministries.<P>

The Dutch have also encountered setbacks. They were not able to reach their initial goals for CO2 reductions because the greatly
reduced price of gasoline in recent years encouraged the number of
fuel-inefficient cars to increase at a greater rate than anticipated. The Dutch
are considering imposing a carbon tax on fuels, but prefer to do so in
conjunction with other members of the European Union.<P>

An additional setback was the Netherlands' sudden rise in population, due to immigration from developing
countries and from Eastern Europe.<P>

Despite these difficulties, the latest reports the government has received show that NEPP implementation is on schedule and that
most targets will be met.<P>

In Amsterdam's Rijksmuseum there is one painting that looms above all. It is Rembrandt's "The Night Watch." Rembrandt startled the
world with that painting, so much so that it changed our ideas of art forever.<P>

I believe that the Dutch NEPP will similarly change the way people see themselves
and their actions in relation to the environment. The individuals who produced
the Netherlands' plan should be remembered as having created a work at least as
important as Rembrandt's.

<H3>Green Plans in the US</H3>

In 1980, the Carter administration issued <CITE>The Global 2000 Report to the
President</CITE>, a comprehensive assessment of global environmental and resource issues
projected over the following 20 years.<P>

Ironically, Global 2000 had its most significant impact abroad. In conversations with environmental officials from New
Zealand, I have been told that it was probably the most important inspiration for
that country's push toward a comprehensive environmental policy. The writings of
thoughtful US activists, such as David <A HREF="../brower/browerbr.html">Brower</A>, Barry Commoner, Aldo Leopold,
Rachel Carson and others have also had a greater impact on the rest of the world
than they have had in the US.<P>

The days of "unlimited" resources are largely over. The US is moving from a nation that exploited resources without thought for the
future to one that must shift to sustainability if it is to maintain the quality
of life for present and future generations.<P>

If a green plan were proposed in this country, would it survive the political process? I believe the answer is yes, for
a number of reasons. Several  states -- including New Jersey, Washington and
California -- are already positioned to adopt green plans within the next few
years.<P>

Washington has implemented a master plan called "Environment 2010" and has enacted air-quality laws, water- and energy-conservation strategies,
environmental education programs, oil-spill prevention policies and
managed-growth laws.<P>

New Jersey, one of the most environmentally pressured states, is also one of the most environmentally progressive, with some of the
country's strictest environmental standards. The state's planning commission has
developed a comprehensive environmental and land-use strategy and has established
an ongoing environmental monitoring and evaluation program.<P>

Vermont has created a state environmental board and district commissions with the power to establish
comprehensive development and land-use plans.<P>

Florida's Environmental Strategic Plan will provide long-term strategic planning, budget development, and
environmental program evaluation.<P>

"Benchmarks," Oregon's 1989 risk-assessment-based strategic planning effort, set five-, ten-, 15-, and
20-year goals in three categories: people, economy and quality of life. The
quality-of-life category includes approximately 35 benchmarks dealing with
environmental issues, among them CO2 emissions, wetlands and forest preservation,
erosion control, transportation and water quality.<P>

Minnesota has began a process called "Minnesota Milestones" to create a sustainable development plan for the
state. One goal is to reduce average annual energy use per person 22 percent by
2020.<P>

Most green-plan activity will take place at the state level, but the states will need both financial help and guidance from the federal government. Such
programs could easily be set up, starting with the creation of a federal
commission on green plans staffed by appointed members of the House and Senate,
the president's cabinet and the Department of Justice, among others. This
commission would distribute funds to the states for green-plan development. Each
state would create a green-plan commission to receive the seed money, define the
state's environmental problems and outline priorities.<P>

When green planning is taken up by leaders around the world, it will be immensely successful. The idea
is gaining momentum and, as it does, it will find leaders to champion it.<P>

<HR>

Adapted from <CITE>Green Plans: Greenprint for Sustainability</CITE>, by Huey D. Johnson
(University of Nebraska Press, 312 North 14th Street, Lincoln, NE 68588-0484;
(402) 472-3581).

<HR>

