<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: The High Cost of Dominion</TITLE>

<H1>The High Cost of Dominion</H1>

<H2>by Jim Mason</H2>

In March 1992, Vaclav Havel, president of the  Czech Republic, wrote in <CITE>The New
York Times</CITE> about social turmoil in the modern era and of impending environmental
disaster. "Man's attitude to the world must be radically changed," wrote Havel.
He also urged that "human uniqueness, human action and the human spirit must be
rehabilitated."<P>

While I respect Havel's views, I think he should have said: "The notion of human uniqueness is a big part of our problems. The human spirit must
be reconstructed, and then humane action can move us in better directions."<P>

Our idea of human uniqueness is biologically bogus. Every species is unique -- by
definition. The idea of "uniqueness" gives a false basis for our place in the
universe, which feeds all of our environmental and spiritual problems. To solve
them, we need to come to terms with nature.<P>

Psychologist Paul Chance explored this obsession with human uniqueness in a 1988 essay for <CITE>Psychology Today</CITE>. We
seem to be driven to find something, he wrote, that "sets us apart from the
beasts of the field, the slimy things that swim in the seas and the creepy things
that hide under rocks."<P>

The obsession has a long history. It began with the ancient Greeks, who said that reason separated us from brute beasts. Then,
approximately 100 years ago, psychologists found that some animals, notably
chimpanzees, can perform simple reasoning, too.<P>

So the human community switched horses and said that creativity separated us from beasts. Then, in the '60s,
psychologists found that <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">porpoises</A> (and many other animals) are inventive,
especially in their play behavior.<P>

So we switched again, claiming tool-making as the great separator. But Jane Goodall and others found that primates and other
animals make and use simple tools.<P>

Backs to the wall, human chauvinists said that language makes us unique, whereupon science soon found that primates can also
learn to use sign language. In an eyeblink, language experts redefined language
in such a way that only human beings can have it.<P>

True, we have unique qualities, but so does every other organism. Humans have the ability to understand the inner
workings of the atom, yet many kinds of <A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">animals</A> can find their home territory
from hundreds of miles away without the aid of maps or instruments. We can build
supersonic airplanes, yet birds can fly and cheetahs can run 50 miles an hour. We
can play the violin, yet elephants can either pick flowers or pull up trees with
their noses. If we are going to claim some kind of uniqueness, then we ought to
admit that it is, in the grand scheme of things, pretty relative.<P>

<H3>Unnatural Separation</H3>

Why are we so driven to separate ourselves from nature? Paul Chance hit the nail
on the head: we want to feel superior to animals and nature. We want something,
he wrote, that "proves that we are, somehow, not really animals at all." This is
how we try to prove our humanhood. However, the approach is infantile and
insecure.<P>

Evolutionary kinship is the biological reality here on Earth, yet we deny it and idealize a strict separation from all other animals. Something in our
culture compels us to denigrate our biological kin and to keep ourselves wholly
apart from them. We want to be sure we are in a class by ourselves -- high over
"lower" nature. This puts us all alone -- <I>over</I> the living world, never <I>in</I> it,
never <I>of</I> it. Propped up on high, we cannot come to a sense of belonging, to a
feeling of ease, here on Earth. No wonder we destroy the living world and sink
into a spiritual malaise.<P>

If there is a creeping, mass insanity, it is in our failure to grasp the very deep cultural roots of our current social and
environmental problems. A growing number of philosophers believes that the seeds
of the modern malaise were sown millennia ago when our distant ancestors took up
farming, which broke our primal bonds with the living world and put human beings
above all other life. As we took "dominion" over the living world, we left behind
feelings of kinship and belonging. Nature became an adversary, a thing beneath
us, something to be conquered and kept at bay. Nature-conquest -- so long
glorified in art, literature and song -- has become second nature to us.<P>

We are creatures of nature, yet our "dominionist" culture makes us very uncomfortable
with this fact. It makes people want to be greater than nature -- next to God.
Dominionists are prone to look down on all "others," whom they see as closer to
nature than themselves. The others can be female, people of color, people who are
different and people of other lands and cultures. Dominionists tend to see these
others as inferior, bestial beings and they regard them with much the same hatred
and contempt that they have for nature in general. They treat others as they do
nature: they try to control them and keep them apart.<P>

We see nature in ourselves, too -- in our bodies, our bodily functions and cycles, our sexuality and the
other physical aspects of life -- and it makes us uncomfortable. Because our
dominionist culture gives us mostly negative views about animals and nature, we
tend to have negative views about any traces of animal nature in humanity and in
ourselves. And we treat this beast within as we do the rest of nature: we try to
control it and repress it.<P>

If we want a better sense of humanity, then, we need to reconsider dominionist views of animals and nature. We could start with a
discussion of what animals have meant to human beings during our evolution. We
grew up as a species in the presence of animals, and our budding human mind was
fascinated and informed by them. Animals were nature's most outstanding members
-- lively, noisy and relatively ordered. In a world that was chaotic and
mysterious, animals were the beings most like us -- they were familiar. They
stirred in us a sense of awe for the world and a sense of kinship with it.
Animals have impressed the human mind and shaped culture everywhere. They are the
first beings in tribal peoples' creation stories the world over. They are the
main figures in the earliest art, in fables and myths, and in language. Until we
made them our slaves and marginalized them, animals were very much on our minds.<P>

Humanity has had a long, evolutionary run with animals and it once gave us a
familial bond with nature. If we want to come to terms with nature, we will have
to come to terms with animals.<P>

<HR>

(c) Jim Mason, 1994. Mason is author of <CITE>An Unnatural Order: Uncovering the Roots
of Our Domination of Nature and Each Other</CITE> (Simon & Schuster, 1993; $24). For
copies, write: PO Box 381, Mount Vernon, MO 65712.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


