<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: The Goldman Environmental Prize Winners for 1995</TITLE>

<H1>The Goldman Environmental Prize Winners for 1995</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

On April 17, environmental heroes from each of the six continents were honored at
the sixth annual Goldman Environmental Prize awards ceremony in San Francisco.
Each winner received a $75,000 "no-strings-attached" award from the Goldman
Environmental Foundation.<P>

The winners for 1995 are:<P>

<UL> 

<LI>From North America, <B>Aurora Castillo</B>, an octogenarian activist from the barrios of East Los Angeles.
In 1984, Castillo co-founded the Mothers of East Los Angeles , which has
successfully opposed the siting of waste dumps and incinerators, freeway
expansions and prisons in the largely Latino community.<P>

<LI>From Asia, <B>Yul Choi</B>, secretary-general of the Korean Federation for Environmental Movement. As a
student leader, Choi was arrested in the 1970s for opposing South Korea's rapid
industrialization. In the 1980s, Choi was placed under house arrest after he
launched the Korean Anti-Pollution Movement's (KAPMA) educational campaign
against the dangers of nuclear power. In 1990, 20,000 KAPMA demonstrators halted
plans for a nuclear waste site on Anmyon Island.<P>

<LI>From South/Central America, <B>Ricardo Navarro</B>, founder of El Salvador's Center for Appropriate Technology.
Navarro trains rural and urban residents to create local technologies to serve
local needs. Navarro is also working with youth to plant 75,000 trees as a
"forest of reconciliation" on land scarred during El Salvador's civil war.<P>

<LI>From the Island Nations, <B>Noah Idechong</B>, chief of the Division of Marine
Resources for the country of Palau. Ide-chong revived ancient consevation
principles to protect local reefs from overuse and overfishing. Idechong is now
director of the Palau Conservation Society.<P>

</UL>

Goldman European winner <A HREF="kickcars.html"><B>Emma Must</B></A> and Africa winner <A HREF="ogoni.html"><B>Ken Saro-Wiwa</B></A> are profiled in the following articles.<P>

 
<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


<A HREF="journal.html"><IMG SRC="jhome.gif"></A><P>
