<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: "We Have Begun to Kick Our Car Habit"</TITLE>

<H1>"We Have Begun to Kick Our Car Habit"</H1>

<H2>by Emma Must</H2>

<HR>

In 1989, the British government announced that it would spend #23 billion ($36.34
billion) on the "largest road-building project since the Roman Empire." The
subsequent construction brought devastation to the British countryside and drove
people from their homes (Summer '93 <CITE>EIJ</CITE>). One morning while walking to her job as
a children's librarian in the south of England, Emma Must came across a
road-building site and was appalled by what she saw. Must joined the muddied
bands of protesters facing beatings and arrests at the hands of police and helped
draw world attention to the "road wars" in rural England. She now heads ALARM, a
road-fighting organization involved in 200 local anti-road campaigns. In November
1994, the British government finally heard the ALARM and canceled one-third of
its road-construction plans.

--Gar Smith

<HR>

Emma Must:<P>

British road-building plans promoted in the '80s would have meant a wholesale
reshaping of the country -- from the white cliffs of Dover, through hills of
Arthurian legend, to the tenements of Glasgow and the suburban streets of
Manchester.<P>

These landscapes and communities have been defended from the road-builders by the old, the young, farmers, nannies, bank managers; by
everybody from New Age travelers with beaded hair to the Tory ladies of the Home
Counties. There has been a tremendous collective effort.<P>

In Britain, ordinary people have succeeded in putting the roads program into reverse. The
"supertanker" of transportation policy is slowly turning 'round. What we now have
is an increasingly clear table on which to place our ideas for alternatives --
improved public transport, cycling, walking and traffic-demand-management
measures. Being awarded the Goldman prize will enable us to develop these
alternatives. Receiving this prize places the battle against car culture firmly
on the international agenda.<P>

Not only is <A HREF="ogoni.html">Ken Saro-Wiwa</A> currently in jail in Nigeria, in fear for his life for opposing the destruction of his homeland by
Shell Oil, which produces the gas that we daily put into our cars, but the roads
lobby is increasingly turning to the developing world in search of new markets.<P>

When you realize that there are currently more cars in Los Angeles than in the
whole of China, India and Sub-Saharan Africa put together, it's not hard to see
why the developing world appeals to [the lobby].<P>

Were the whole world to achieve the level of car ownership that the Department of Transport forecasts for
Britain, there would be an 11-fold increase in the number of cars in the world,
plus all the associated pollution, asthma, landscape destruction and <A HREF="../x/atmosph.html">climate
change</A>.<P>

If we can't stomach this, then we in the West have got to stop holding up our model of motorized mobility as an ideal to the developing world. We have to
begin to kick our car habit. Otherwise, we are simply peddling global inequality.<P>

I really do think that the buck stops here.<P>

<HR>

For more information about the Goldman Environmental Prize, contact: Goldman
Environmental Foundation, 1 Lombard St., Suite 303, San Francisco, CA 94111;
(415) 788-9090; fax: (415) 788-7890.

<HR>

