<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: "Stand by Me and the Ogoni People..."</TITLE>

<H1>"Stand by Me and the Ogoni People..."</H1>

<H2>by Ken Saro-Wiwa</H2>

<HR>

Since 1958, when Royal Dutch Shell first struck oil on Ogoni lands in
southeastern Nigeria, an estimated $30 billion-worth of oil has been extracted.
The 500,000 Ogoni farmers and fishers received little except a ravaged
environment. Once-fertile farmland has been laid waste by oil spills and acid
rain. The landscape is dotted with puddles of ooze the size of football fields.
Between 1976-91, 2976 oil spills blackened the Niger Delta, an average of four a
week. Virtually all fish and wildlife in Ogoniland are vanishing.<P>

Nigerian author and television producer Ken Saro-Wiwa founded the Movement for
the Survival of Ogoni People (MOSOP) to nonviolently defend the environmental and
human rights of the Ogoni, one of 250 ethnic groups in Nigeria. In January 1993,
300,000 Ogoni marched peacefully to demand a share of oil revenues, political
autonomy, compensation for past damages and a clean-up by the multinational oil
companies responsible for the spills [Summer '93 <CITE>EIJ</CITE>].<P>

Last May, the Nigerian military occupied Ogoniland, subjecting the residents to
summary execution, mass arrests, rape, and the burning and looting of villages.
On May 22, 1994, Saro-Wiwa, who has been briefly imprisoned numerous times, was
abducted from his home by Nigeria's military government and charged with the
murder of four Ogoni leaders. Amnesty International believes that these
accusations are unfounded and that Saro-Wiwa's detention "is solely because of
his campaign against environmental damage and inadequate compensation by oil
companies operating in Ogoniland." Amnesty has adopted Saro-Wiwa as a prisoner of
conscience, calling for his immediate release.<P>

In February 1995, Saro-Wiwa went on trial for his life before a three-person
"special tribunal" appointed by the Nigerian military. On May 9, he was moved to
a military hospital for treatment of a chronic heart condition. On March 10,
Saro-Wiwa smuggled the following message to Richard and Rhoda Goldman from his
prison cell. It was read at the award ceremonies by his son, Ken Saro-Wiwa,
Jr.<P>

--Gar Smith

<HR>

Ken Saro-Wiwa:<P>

As far back as 1968, I have publicly protested Shell's spoliation of our Ogoni
lands to satisfy the company's needs, and when, in 1990, I founded the Movement
for the Survival of the Ogoni People it was to mobilize the entire 500,000 Ogoni
to campaign against Shell's insensitive devastation of their environment. The
massive and unstinting support that the campaign received from Ogoni youth, the
sacrifice that they made in defense of their patrimony, compel me to dedicate the
prize to the Ogoni youth.<P>

Only recently, 27 years and more after my initial protest, did Shell finally
agree that it has polluted the Ogoni environment, among others. The company has
now launched what it calls a "major environmental survey" of the Niger Delta, of
which the Ogoni strip is part. In launching the survey, Shell condemned "recent
politicized and emotive campaigning" in defense of the region.<P>

I submit that we have every reason to be emotional in our struggle for the
sanctity of our environment. The environment is man's first right. Without a safe
environment, man cannot exist to claim other rights, be they political, social or
economic.<P>

I believe that Shell knows this much and accepts it for the developed world.
Unfortunately, in Africa, Shell and many a Western multinational company have
failed to apply the environmental principle of "best practice" in their
entrepreneurial activities. Using their financial muscle and the political power
they exercise over African governments, they are wont to blackmail, terrorize and
silence those who have the temerity to question their environmental records. This
is not acceptable.<P>

As I write, I stand trial for my life before a special military tribunal against
whose decisions there is no appeal. The tribunal has been set up by Nigeria's
military dictatorship with the full support of Shell, which is represented [by]
counsel. My real crime? Challenging Shell's ecological war on my beloved Ogoni
homeland. I and the Ogoni people draw comfort from the recognition that the
Goldman Environmental Prize has conferred on our struggle. And we feel emboldened
to continue that struggle, come life or death.<P>

I appeal to the international community and environmentalists throughout the
world to stand by me and the Ogoni people as we battle to save our devastated
environment and for our survival as a people with sustainable development. I
thank those who kindly nominated me for the prize and the Goldman Environmental
Foundation for accepting the nomination.<P>

And, if I may adapt William Blake's famous words, I promise that:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>I will not cease from mental fight<BR> Nor shall my pen sleep in my
hand<BR> Till we have built a new Ogoni<BR> In Niger Delta's wealthy
land.</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

I hope to prove deserving of this prize.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


