<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: A Bad Week for Whalers</TITLE>

<H2>Report From the IWC</H2>

<H1>A Bad Week for Whalers</H1>

by <A HREF="../immp/oasf9501.html">David Phillips</A><P>

Commercial whalers will not fondly remember this year's annual meeting of the
International Whaling Commission (IWC) in Dublin, Ireland, May 29-June 2, because
both Norway and Japan were severely criticized for their <A HREF="../immp/immp3.html">outlaw whaling</A>.<P>

Norway has openly defied the IWC commercial-whaling ban for the past three years. The
<A HREF="../immp/whlclaim.html">Norwegian government claimed</A> that there were more than 86,700 minke whales in the
northeastern Atlantic Ocean and that a kill of 301 minke whales annually  was in
line with "sound science." At this year's meetings, however, the IWC's Scientific
Committee stripped away any scientific rationale for Norway's continued whaling
when it rejected the population model and data used by the Norwegians, whose own
scientists admitted that gross errors had been made.<P>

The Scientific Committee determined that there was no valid estimate for the minke population number and
that no level of kill was scientifically justifiable. On the committee's
recommendation, the full commission then demanded that Norway halt its whaling.<P>

Despite this condemnation, the Norwegian government has refused to call in its
whaling fleet. Norwegian whalers are at sea right now and 82 minke have been
killed so far this year.<P>

Domestic support for Norway's whaling also continues to wane. The <CITE>Oslo Arbeiderbladet</CITE>, the newspaper of Norwegian Prime Minister Gro
Harlem Brundtland's Labor Party,  blasted the continuation of Norway's whaling:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>"The Norwegian battle to gain international acceptance for whaling is already
lost. The sooner we realize this, the better... . Norway has now started with a
kind of politics where we demand that other countries preserve their rainforests,
or their threatened species, but we are not willing to do so ourselves.
Environmental work costs. If Norway wants to be taken seriously, and especially
Gro Harlem Brundtland as the "environmental minister" of the world, we cannot
continue to act as if there are special rules for Norway in the 'game' of the
environment."</BLOCKQUOTE><P>

Twenty-one IWC member nations, including the US, joined in the condemnation of Norway's whaling. The Norwegian's outlaw whaling has provided
ample justification for the Clinton Administration to impose economic sanctions.
Under US law, the president can embargo products from countries violating
international conservation agreements. Such sanctions could cost Norway up to
$100 million per year in lost revenues, far exceeding the value of the whale meat
taken by hunters. By imposing trade sanctions, the US would send a strong signal
that countries must honor their obligations to international agreements.
Conversely, if Norway is permitted to violate the commercial whaling ban and base
its whaling on wildly inaccurate whale-population data, there will be little to
prevent Japan, Iceland and a host of other countries from doing the same.<P>

Last year, President Clinton refrained from imposing sanctions, because the US
accepted Norway's scientific estimates. Now there is no longer any credible
rationale for failing to use economic leverage to convince Norway to end the
whale slaughter.<P>

<H3>Japan Violates Sanctuary</H3>

Japan also came under intense pressure at the IWC meeting for its failure to
honor the newly created Antarctic Sanctuary. Japan sent out its whaling fleets
and took 330 minke whales in the Southern Ocean earlier this year, most from
within the sanctuary boundaries. Japan conducted this whaling under self-granted
"scientific permits." This year, the IWC again called for Japan to abandon its
"research" whaling, citing the lack of any viable scientific rationale.<P>

Japan was further embarrassed by several new investigative reports uncovering widespread
trade in illegal whale meat entering Japan from Taiwan, South Korea and Russia.
EarthTrust and the Endangered Species Project conducted DNA analyses proving that
protected whale species, such as humpback, fin and Bryde's whales, can be found
for sale in Japanese markets.<P>

The IWC responded by passing a resolution to improve mechanisms to prevent illegal trade in whale meat. The resolution calls
on Japan, Norway and any other country with stockpiles of whale meat to generate
annual reports for the IWC on the volume of their stocks and to report on
enforcement actions taken to control sales of illegal whale meat. The resolution
further encourages the use of DNA testing to identify <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">whale</A> meat from endangered
species and calls for the disposal of this meat in the near future.<P>

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Write to Vice President Al Gore [c/o The White House, 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20500] and urge that, in light of
Norway's violation of the IWC and "sound science," that the US impose sanctions
on Norwegian products. Write to Gro Harlem Brundtland [c/o Prime Minister of
<A HREF="../immp/immp3.html">Norway</A>, Norwegian Embassy, 2720 34th St. NW, Washington, DC 20008] and demand
that Norway recall its whaling fleets immediately.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


