<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: DNA Testing Exposes Whale Trade</TITLE>

<H1>DNA Testing Exposes Whale Trade</H1>

<H2>by Don White</H2>

DNA, one of the principal building blocks of life, is an incredible storehouse of
information. While scientists will probably never be able to resurrect extinct
species like those in <CITE>Jurassic Park</CITE>, they can use forensic DNA techniques to help
keep other giants from following the dinosaurs into extinction.<P>

These behemoths -- the great <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">whales</A> -- have benefited from the "protection" of the <A HREF="../immp/immp3.html">International
Whaling Commission (IWC)</A> for many years. Right whales were protected in 1946;
humpbacks in 1966; and there has been an international moratorium on commercial
whaling since 1986. Last year, a huge Southern-Ocean sanctuary was designated to
safeguard most of the surviving whales in their southern feeding grounds near
Antarctica.<P>

The problem with IWC "protection" is that it has historically been passive and frequently unenforced. Whalers have been on the honor system to kill
only IWC-approved numbers and species of whales, mainly for <A HREF="../immp/whlclaim.html">"research" purposes</A>.
With the price of whale meat often exceeding $200 per pound, however, Japan has
become the end-market for the illegal global commerce in smuggled whale meat.
This trade was exposed in 1994 and again in 1995 when EarthTrust used
DNA-sampling techniques to prove that fresh humpback whale steak was being sold
in a major Hiroshima supermarket.<P>

EarthTrust's investigation revealed that Japan has effectively kept "two sets of books" on the number and kinds of whales it has
hunted. Officially, Japan has complied with the IWC's kill limits. In reality,
however, Japan's whaling industry has shamelessly traded in protected and
endangered whale flesh. (Revelations from the former USSR detailed complicity
with Japan from the '50s to the '70s. The Soviets killed more than 48,000
humpback whales -- the majority of the species -- in that period, and Japan
consumed them.)<P>

For years, EarthTrust had hoped to do a DNA analysis of Japan's whale-meat market and by 1993 the testing technology was available. However,
Japan can stall any scientific tissue-export requests under CITES, the
international treaty that protects endangered species.<P>

EarthTrust devised a strategy to use a portable DNA-testing lab in a Tokyo hotel room to do the
analysis. C. Scott Baker, a leading molecular ecologist, traveled to Japan with a
donated MJ Research "minicycler" and amplified the DNA of whale meat samples
collected by an EarthTrust advance team. Once "cloned," the synthetic DNA was
legal for export without permits.<P>

The analysis showed not only humpback, but many fin whale samples, one North Atlantic minke, and a number of ill-fated dolphins
sold as whale (at whale prices). Japan's whalers condemned the study, which
appeared in the prestigious journal <CITE>Science</CITE> in September, 1994. But there are few
areas of science as well-established as DNA testing. A 1995 study of Korea's
whale-meat markets (by Endangered Species Project and EarthTrust) has validated
the original study and put whale smugglers on notice.<P>

DNA can be used as a tool to <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">end illegal whaling</A>, destroy the rationale for "research" whaling and
indefinitely delay "commercial" whaling while illegal commerce is brought under
control. From now on, even after it has been harpooned, flensed, filleted and
marinated, a whale can tell its story.<P>

<HR> 		  

Don White is President of EarthTrust. To support EarthTrust's ongoing use of
DNA to end whaling, contact: EarthTrust, 25 Kaneohe Bay Drive, Kailua, HI 96734,
or e-mail: Earthtrust@mcimail.com.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


