<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Dolphin Defender Threatened</TITLE>

<H1>Dolphin Defender Threatened</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

In February, 1993, Venezuelan biologist Aldemaro Romero, PhD., and Prof. Ignacio
Agudo videotaped a group of fishermen harpooning and butchering a female <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">dolphin</A>
for shark bait -- a common practice along the Venezuelan coast. The biologists
brought the tape and reams of documentation to the attention of government
officials, but their pleas for action to halt the killings went unheeded.<P>

Romero, the author of hundreds of scientific papers, was formerly the executive director
of the Venezuelan Foundation for the Conservation of Biological Diversity and is
a past president of the Hemispheric Conference on Economics and the Environment.
Agudo is the president of Venezuela's Fudacetacea (The Whale Fund).<P>

In November 1993, CNN obtained a copy of the biologists' videotape. When the dolphin killing
was televised in the US, the Venezuelan Consulate in Miami received 20,000
outraged protest letters.<P>

The publicity spurred Venezuelan officials to take action: they charged Romero and Agudo with killing the dolphin. "The government
announced [it was] going to try both of us for 'treason to the motherland',"
Romero stated. "Our telephones were tapped. The fishermen who killed the dolphins
were arrested seven times in five days... and made to sign a confession in which
they claimed we had tricked them."<P>

The Venezuelan government, already smarting from a 1991 US trade embargo because of its <A HREF="../immp/hr2179.html">dolphin-unsafe</A> tuna-fishing
practices, declared that Romero and Agudo were paid provocateurs working for <A HREF="../immp/immp6.html">US
tuna companies</A>. Venezuela accused HJ Heinz Co. (producers of Starkist-brand tuna)
of paying the biologists $10,000 and claimed that the payoff had been laundered
through Earth Island Institute.<P>

In April 1994, a judge issued a warrant for the arrest of Romero and Agudo, and vowed on television that, once arrested, the
scientists "would never be released from jail." Ramon Martinez, the governor of
Sucre state, where the incident occurred, was even more blunt. "If it were up to
me," he told <CITE>The Wall Street Journal</CITE>, "I'd have them shot." When Romero began
receiving death threats from people who pointedly recited his daughter's school
schedule, he and his family fled to the US.<P>

"Professor Agudo is still hiding in Venezuela and I am very concerned about his situation," Romero told the animal
rights newspaper, <CITE>Animal People</CITE>. Amnesty International and the US State
Department have both faulted Venezuela in the past for its abysmal human rights
record.<P>

Even in the US, Romero is not safe. On November 30, 1994, he was invited to meet Eduardo Vetencourt, who identified himself as the Venezuelan vice-consul
in Miami. During a two-hour meeting at a local Burger King, Vetencourt informed
Romero that he was armed and that his "real job" involved "security." He said
that a military plane was waiting to fly Romero to Venezuela for a "fair trial."<P>

Vetencourt told him that Venezuelan authorities had "temporarily" abandoned the
idea of kidnapping him because of fears of bad publicity.<P>

In January, the Venezuelan press reported that the government was considering a request to
extradite Romero. The US State Department, however, has indicated that such a
request will not be honored.<P>

On March 1,  Romero was invited to be "interviewed" by Ricardo Zurita, reporter for Venezuela's <CITE>El Nacional</CITE>. A check of Venezuelan
and US news agencies failed to locate any reporter by that name. Fearing a
kidnapping attempt, Romero called the FBI.<P>

"Given the level of <A HREF="activrisk.html">political [persecution]</A> that I have been subjected to in Venezuela," Romero informed the
FBI, "I believe that once the extradition is not granted, the Venezuelan
authorities will take illegal forceful action to take me back to Venezuela." In
an interview in the March 10 issue of <CITE>Science</CITE>, Romero declared, "I feel like I'm
in a Hitchcock movie. I'm afraid for my life."	

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


