<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Appropriate Technology in Central America</TITLE>

<H1>Appropriate Technology in Central America</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

AT Work is an all-volunteer Earth Island project that assists grassroots
development projects by providing skilled volunteers; educational resources,
technical and material resources; and funding and publicity assistance. AT Work
strives to break the cycle of poverty and environmental degradation by empowering
poor communities in the US and Latin America to develop ecologically sustainable
and socially just living conditions.<P>

AT Work's Alternative Development Exchange (ADE) program helps impoverished communities by connecting them with skilled
volunteers. Volunteers can review AT Work's database of eligible communities and
find projects that meet their specific skills, abilities and interests. AT Work
also provides books, tools and computers to recipient communities and projects.
Recent donations have included a computer for a non-violence training center in
Nicaragua and seeds for Indigenous farming projects in the US and Central
America.<P>

In 1995, AT Work is supporting two new projects in Central America -- the Organic Agriculture Project in Chiapas, Mexico, and the Monteverde
Conservation League in <A HREF="../gsc/costa.html">Costa Rica</A>.<P>

Chiapas is the poorest state in Mexico, and half its population is Indigenous. Since the 1994 rise of the Zapatista movement,
a rebel group fighting for freedom, democracy and human rights, Chiapas has been
subjected to military occupation, bombings, kidnappings and violence.<P>

The Organic Agriculture Project has been a bright light in this troubled region. Neusa
Hidalgo Monroy, a graduate student at the University of California at Berkeley,
has put AT Work in touch with small, organic coffeegrowers in the highlands and
on the coast of Chiapas. These growers have formed a farming cooperative to
improve living and economic conditions by teaching organic farming methods and
marketing skills. In addition to growing coffee for commercial use, the farmers
raise corn, beans, squash and potatoes. In the highlands, they also herd cattle
and sheep. Coop members are developing new projects in sustainable forestry,
building construction and the use of alternative energy resources.<P>

The project still needs volunteers skilled in animal husbandry, bio-intensive farming,
economics and integrated pest management. The broader goal of the Chiapas project
is to help grassroots organizations throughout Mexico get the necessary skills to
run similar agricultural enterprises.<P>

The Monteverde Conservation League (MCL) is located in the Tilaran Mountains of Costa Rica. MCL's aim is to preserve,
conserve and rehabilitate tropical ecosystems and to safeguard biodiversity in
Monteverde National Park. There are some long-term research positions being
offered by MCL, but the majority of workers needed are manual laborers, education
specialists, cartographers and biologists.

<HR>

