<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: AT Work Supports the Mixtecs of Oaxaca</TITLE>

<H1>AT Work Supports the Mixtecs of Oaxaca</H1>

<H2>by Tracey Silberman</H2>

In April, AT Work members gathered in Oakland, California, to meet with Rufino
Dominguez, the lead organizer for Frente Indigena Oaxaqueno Binacional (FIOB).
Dominguez, who maintains an FIOB office at his home in Livingston, California, is
the main conduit for the exchange of information between Mixtecs living in
California and their family members in Oaxaca.<P>

Dominguez reported some promising developments for the Mixtecs and other Indigenous groups living south of the
border. After years of demands from FIOB, the Mexican federal and Oaxacan state
governments have agreed to begin a revolving loan institution for the
organization. Just how much money will be loaned initially and how it will be
dispersed is still to be arranged, but this is seen as a great success for the
Oaxacans.<P>

Dominguez said that the money will be used to begin small agricultural projects in the villages. The project will grow food for the villagers, but the
majority of the produce will be exported, providing a steady income for Mixtecs
so that they do not have to migrate hundreds of miles to the US to find work. In
California, he noted, finding employment often means living in squalor, suffering
exposure to pesticides and being subjected to discrimination.<P>

There is still much assistance that AT Work can provide in Oaxaca. The FIOB needs volunteers to help
organize its business. Because of deforestation and erosion in Oaxaca, research
must be done to determine which crops will thrive in the depleted soil before
planting can begin. Soil surveyors, organic agriculture experts and organizers
are needed. Marketing and management talents are also needed to help Oaxacan
farmers determine which crops are the most profitable, and which markets they
should pursue.<P>

Dominguez confided that, just by listening and being supportive, AT Work had already helped FIOB. In addition, AT Work's material support has
included the donation of several computers and assistance in setting up an e-mail
communication system for FIOB.<P>


<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

To become an ADE volunteer or send donations to support appropriate technology projects, contact: AT Work, Earth Island Institute, 300
Broadway #28, San Francisco, CA 94133; (415) 788- 3666, ext. 128. E-mail:
"atwork@igc.apc.org." 

<HR>

