<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: The Cod Squad vs.the God Squad</TITLE>

<H1>The Cod Squad vs.the God Squad</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

In 1991, former Bush Administration Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan, Jr.,
designated a special committee, chaired by Vice President Dan Quayle, that had
the power to overrule the Endangered Species Act (ESA). This so-called "God
Squad" had the power to decree which threatened species should be denied ESA
protection to accommodate regional and national economic interests. It could, for
example, approve the commercial logging of old-growth forests, even if it meant
the extinction of the northern spotted owl.<P>

The God Squad concept originated in1978 as a compromise amendment to the
Endangered Species Act. The committee included the secretaries of Agriculture,
Defense and Interior, the heads of the EPA and National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration, and the chair of the Council of Economic Advisors.<P>

As the Republican Contract With America threatens the wholesale demolition of the
ESA, the <CITE>Journal</CITE> believes that it is time to counter the pro-growth
notion of the "God Squad" with a pro-species concept -- the "Cod Squad."<P>

Where the God Squad assumed the power to decide which species should become
extinct to protect industry, the Cod Squad  (named in honor of the North Atlantic
Ocean's depleted cod) would identify the <B>industries</B> that must become
extinct to assure the survival of life on Earth.

<H2>The Cod Squad List of Lethal Industries</H2>

<UL><LI><A HREF="../immp/immp.html">Driftnet Fishing</A> -- and all over-fishing technologies that "stripmine the
seas," removing cod and other creatures from the world's oceans.<P>

<LI>Nuclear Technology -- which still has not learned basic table manners -- i.e.,
"Clean up your leftovers before leaving the table."<P>

<LI>Gas-powered Vehicles -- making oil-burning autos "more efficient" makes about as
much sense as trying to design a more-efficient plague virus. More
miles-per-gallon means more people can drive further, spreading pollution and
suburban sprawl.<P>

<LI>Fossil-fuel-burning Power Plants -- smoke clouds and acid rain make each of these
technological dinosaurs a site-for-sore-eyes.<P>

<LI>Petroleum -- the life-blood of the "Combustion Economy." Oil burned heats the
planet. Oil spilled defaces the planet.<P>

<LI><A HREF="../paper/woodfact.html">Non-sustainable Logging</A> -- the timber industry has grown rich from cutting down
irreplaceable, complex forest systems and substituting tree plantations. This
kind of forestry has the same sort of impact on native wildlife that urban
renewal has on the inner-city poor.<P>

<LI>Chemically Intensive Agriculture -- formulating molecules into herbicides,
pesticides and insecticides employs biocide against the environment -- for
profit.<P>

<LI><A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">Pulp Mills</A>-- while paper makers are busy turning pine trees into toilet paper,
they also pour deadly chlorine-based chemicals into adjacent lakes and rivers.<P>

<LI><A HREF="bigmil.html">Military Activities</A> -- whether it is "military exercises" or all-out-war, jets,
tanks and soldiers can mash the most pristine meadow and degrade the most
desolate desert. Even in peacetime, the global military machine is the world's
worst polluter.<P>

</UL>

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


