<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Who Wants to Kill the Endangered Species Act?</TITLE>

<H1>Who Wants to Kill the Endangered Species Act?</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

On April 13, Senator Slade Gorton (R-WA) uncorked a noxious piece of legislation
designed to clearcut, bulldoze and blast the Endangered Species Act onto the
scrap heap of US environmental history. <CITE>New York Times</CITE> reporter
Timothy Egan observed that Gorton could not take full credit, however, since his
bill "was written largely by the industries that will be most affected by its
outcome" -- timber, mining, ranching and utility interests.<P>

Unveiling his handiwork before an enthusiastic crowd of timber executives at a river resort in
Washington state, Gorton explained that, under his plan, the fate of <A HREF="../strp/strpindx.html">endangered animals</A>
and plants would be determined not by law, but by a political appointee
in the Department of the Interior. (Curiously, an identical plan has surfaced in
New Zealand. See "Around the World" in this issue.)<P>

The Gorton bill was drafted with the legal assistance of the National Endangered Species Act Reform Coalition
(NESARC), an industry lobby representing 185 members, including electric-power
companies, scores of state water districts, Kaiser Aluminum & Chemical Corp.,
Chevron USA and Ringling Brothers, Barnum & Bailey.<P>

When Egan asked if NESARC's role constituted a conflict of interest, Gorton admitted that this was not "how
good public policy should be made," but insisted that he was "perfectly willing
to get the free services of good lawyers in drafting my views." (NESARC also
poured $34,000 into Gorton's 1994 senatorial campaign.) "The task of rewriting
our nation's most important environmental laws is being done by major corporate
interests, whose practices created much of the problem in the first place,"
Environmental Defense Fund official Michael Bean told the <CITE>Times</CITE>.

<HR>

<H2>Meet the National Endangered Species Act Reform Coalition</H2>

The NESARC membership list (as of September 1994) included the following
organizations:

American Farm Bureau Federation; American Public Power Assn.; Boise Cascade
Corp.; California Assn. of Winegrape Growers; California Grain and Feed Assn.;
Coalition of Counties/Stable Economic Growth; Coalition of Oil & Gas Industry
Associations; Farm Credit Bank of Texas; Greater Westside California Women for
Agriculture; Interstate Natural Gas Assn. of America; International Council of
Shopping Centers; Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical Corp.; National Assn. of Home
Builders; National Assn. of State Depts. of Agriculture; National Rural Electric
Coop. Assn.; National Stone Assn.; San Joaquin County Citizens Land Alliance
(CA); South Central Nebraska Bankers Assn.; Texas Aggregate & Concrete Assn.;
Texas Farm Bureau; Western States Petroleum Assn.<P>

The membership roll also includes 53 electric-power companies (mostly in the Midwest), 46 irrigation
districts (predominately in California), nine large farms and cattle operations,
and nine county governments (in Arizona, Nevada, New Mexico, Texas, Washington
and Wyoming).

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


