<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Easterbrook's Optimism Flagging</TITLE>

<H1>A Moment for Reflection: Easterbrook's Optimism Flagging</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

Greg Easterbrook's  744-page book, <CITE>A Moment on the Earth</CITE>, has drawn
fire for arguing that most environmental problems have been solved -- the ozone
layer is not vanishing; air pollution is under control; drinking water is cleaner
than ever.<P>

Vermont author Michael Perlman caustically characterized Easterbrook's book as "a
rousing call to inaction."<P>

It seems even Easterbrook is having second thoughts. Appearing on National Public
Radio's "Talk of the Nation" on May 5, he explained that he delivered the
manuscript to his publishers before the Republican victory in the November
elections.  The <A HREF="greengop.html">GOP</A>, Easterbrook now warned, "would repeal large sections of the
Clean Air Act. The Republicans couldn't get away with it if the public knew how
spectacularly successful these laws have been." Easterbrook said that the GOP's
Contract With America was designed to create legislative "gridlock" that could
"eviscerate" environmental laws.<P>

In the interview, Easterbrook admitted to three significant "errors of fact. And
for these," he added, "I apologize."<P>

In fairness, Easterbrook was not the first "ecorealist" to appear on the media
horizon. The <CITE>Columbia Journalism Review</CITE> gives this honor to <CITE>New York Times</CITE>
reporter Keith Schneider who, in 1991, suggested that exposure to dioxin was "no
more risky than spending a week sunbathing" and argued that regulating hazardous
chemicals placed a needless drain on US productivity.<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2> 

A 52-page, point-by-point factual analysis of Easterbrook's claims about endangered species, the spotted owl, ozone depletion and climate
change in <CITE>A Moment on the Earth</CITE> has been prepared by the Environmental Defense
Fund. The report consists of corrections to Easterbrook's information drawn from
the scientific literature. The paper is available from Environmental Defense
Fund, Public Information, 257 Park Avenue  South, New York, NY 10010; (212)
505-2100.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


