<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Progress on National Sustainability</TITLE>

<H1>Progress on National Sustainability</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

<HR>

<H2>Can the US Become Sustainable?:</H2> 

According to the founders of The Sustainability Project (TSP), "America is entering an extraordinary time of uncertainty and
challenge.... Our democratic institutions are failing in multiple ways to ensure
our own security, our children's future and the future of the planet itself."<P>

Countering the rising tide of anti-government rhetoric, TSP President Stan Euston
sees a "sustainability ethic" as the antidote to "current efforts to dismantle
government in the name of narrow individualism."<P>

Instead of the specter of paranoid paramilitary militias, TSP offers a vision of "a citizen-led redirection
of public life toward a political economy that supports community health,
environmental stewardship and social justice." [To get involved, request a free
copy of Gathering Hope: A Citizens' Call to a Sustainable Ethic for Guiding
Public Life, from TSP, 4 Gavilan Road, Santa Fe, NM 87505; phone/fax (505)
466-2052.]

<H2>Sustainable Ashland:</H2> 

On March 21, 1995, the Ashland, Oregon city council passed Resolution No. 95-08, a historic document that calls on the federal government to
establish a National Optimum Population Commission (NOPC) "to analyze and debate
the question: 'What is our optimum population?' " After three-to-five years of
study, the NOPC would "propose non-coercive educational, legislative and
public-policy initiatives to place the United States on the path -- during a
transition period lasting from 100 to 125 years -- toward achieving an optimum
sustainable population." [Contact: City Councillor Brent Thompson, City Hall,
Ashland, OR 97520; (503) 488-0407.]

<H2>The Greening of <CITE>Newsweek</CITE>:</H2>

Covertly cloaked behind the headline, "Bye-Bye, Suburban Dream," the cover story in the May 15 issue of <CITE>Newsweek</CITE> could have read:
"Hello, Eco-Cities!" A rousing paean to the work of the "new urbanists" who are
"going back to the future to take the edge off edge cities," <CITE>Newsweek</CITE> lamented
how the tranquillity of small-town communities has been destroyed by over-paving,
overpopulation and predatory development. Instead of six-lane highways and strip
malls, <CITE>Newsweek</CITE> offered a list of "15 Ways to Fix the Suburbs" that included
"give up big lawns," "bring back the corner store," "make the streets skinny,"
"mix housing types," "plant trees," "plan for mass transit," "link work to home,"
"make a town center," "shrink parking lots," "turn down the lights" and, finally,
"think green."

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


