<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: A Call to Cut Wood Use</TITLE>

<H1>A Call to Cut Wood Use</H1>

<H2>by Peter Bahouth, Director, Turner Foundation<P></H2>

Only ten percent of the inhabited Earth -- regions occupied by forest dwellers, nomads and
land-based native communities -- remains in a roadless condition. The other 90 percent is cut up
into segments of less than 8000 acres by roads. In the US alone, there are more than 350,000
miles of logging roads on public lands -- nine times the length of the entire interstate highway
system. This figure is startling considering that we have not yet reached the 100th anniversary of
the automobile.<P>

The US is the world's leading consumer of <A HREF="../paper/woodfact.html">wood products</A>: with five percent of the population, the US
consumes more than 17 percent of the world's wood. <P>

Current forest industry projections call for a 50-percent increase in US timber demand by the
year 2040. We are cutting down more and more forests that have never been cut before. Whenever
conservationists save a forest, the industry simply moves its logging elsewhere. We must have an
alternative plan.<P>

It is obvious that saving the forests means reducing the amount of wood used in our society. In
October, 1994, at the invitation of the Rainforest Action Network (RAN), 36 environmentalists and
policymakers met in Tomales Bay, California to map out a strategy for saving the world's remaining
forests. They issued the following Tomales Bay Declaration: "We call for a 75-percent reduction of
wood and wood-based <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">paper</A> use in the US within ten years, with the expressed purpose of
increasing meaningful employment, creating a healthy society and restoring natural habitats." <P>

The campaign's ten-point plan recommends the following actions: buy certified, sustainably
harvested lumber; use wood efficiently; shift from timber- to earth-based architecture; use
salvaged lumber and used furniture; use building materials made from recycled wood or
agricultural fibers; use less paper; choose products with the least packaging; shun disposable
products; buy maximum-content recycled and chlorine-free paper; buy <A HREF="../paper/ecosources.html">tree-free paper products</A> made from <A HREF="../paper/kenaf.html">kenaf</A>, hemp, straw or
agricultural wastes. This unprecedented plan is about changing how things are made. It is a
practical plan as well as an idealistic one. The actions of millions of people took the lead out of
paint, <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">whale</A> oil out of machines and horses out of glue. Now it is time
to see the forest for the trees.

<HR>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

RAN, with support from the Turner Foundation, has published a 72-page action guide, <CITE>Cut
Waste, Not Trees: How to Use Less Wood, Cut Pollution & Create Jobs</CITE>. The book, published
entirely on tree-free, kenaf-plant paper, is available for $10 from RAN, 450 Sansome Street,
Suite 700, San Francisco, CA 94111. 
<HR>

