<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: ReThink Paper Update</TITLE>

<H1>ReThink Paper Update</H1>

<H2>by Emily Miggins</H2>

Earth Island's <A HREF="../paper/rtp.html">ReThink Paper</A> (RTP) is conducting research for its <CITE>ReThink Paper Guide</CITE>, to be released in 1996. Project director Emily Miggins has been collecting
data on "forest-friendly" papers currently available on the market. <P>

<A HREF="../paper/kenaf.html">Kenaf</A>, one of the most promising and economical alternative fiber papers available, continues to win friends. Esprit
International used the forest-saving paper to produce a lavish issue of <CITE>Perspectives</CITE> the company's
16-page, full-color house newsletter.<P>

 Gap International recently published its French-English in-house newsletter on tree-free kenaf, Apple Computers Inc. printed a widely circulated
promotional brochure on the paper and <CITE>Understory</CITE>, the journal of the Woodworkers Alliance for
Rainforest Protection, was also printed entirely on tree-free sheets.<P>

 Kenaf has a cost-competitive, tree-saving, landfill-waste-reducing competitor on the horizon. Arbokem of Canada is now
producing beautiful 100-percent tree-free paper made from 45 percent agricultural waste (wheat
straw), 40 percent recycled corrugated cardboard and 15 percent calcium carbonate filler.
Patagonia Corp. has used forest-friendly Arbokem paper in printing its company newsletter.<P>

--Emily Miggins
