<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: How Right-Wing Militias Target Environmentalists</TITLE>

<H1>How Right-Wing Militias Target Environmentalists</H1>

<H2>by David Helvarg</H2>

On November 14, 1994, Ellen Gray, an organizer with the Pilchuck Audubon Society in Everett,
Washington, testified at a county council hearing in favor of a land-use ordinance to protect local
streams and wetlands. As she finished speaking, a man with a noose stood up and said, "This is for
you." Another man told her, "We have a militia of 10,000, and if we can't beat you at the ballot box,
we'll beat you with a bullet."<P>

 Although they do not agree on everything, militant members of the Wise Use movement, property rights advocates and members of armed militias are increasingly
staking out common ground. In the West, the militias are using the existing Wise Use network as
one of their primary recruiting bases, arguing for military resistance to the government and its
"preservationist" backers. As of late winter, 1994, local environmental activists in Washington
state, New Mexico, Texas and Montana reported receiving death threats from militia members. <P>

The hotbed for militia organizing within the Wise Use movement is the Counties Movement, which
insists that county sheriffs have the right to arrest federal land managers who fail to respect the
"customs and culture" of logging, mining and grazing on public lands.<P>

"They think ecosystem management is part of the New World Order," that will overrun the US, says Jere Payton, an
environmentalist in eastern Washington. Among some right-wing activists in the West, the guiding
belief is that land-use planning is a form of socialism. This assumption has resulted in the
targeting of unarmed environmentalists, land-use planners and federal employees of natural
resource agencies. The majority of militia-related incidents has involved people who, one way or
another, are associated with the environment.<P>

In Montana, where land-use planning has become the target of anti-environmental Wise Use activists, an opponent of a building-permit program told a
militia meeting, "When the hour strikes, there will be public officials dead in the street." <P>

In March, the US Forest Service office in Catron County, New Mexico, was painted with hammers and
sickles and the forest service office in Carson City was pipe-bombed. Seventeen months earlier, the
BLM offices in Reno were bombed during the Senate debate over grazing on public lands.<P>
		 
<HR>

<I>Excerpted, with permission, from <CITE>The Nation</CITE> (72 Fifth Avenue, New York, New York 10011;
(212) 242-8400).</I>

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


