<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: The Media Militia: Behind the PR Curtain</TITLE>

<H1>The Media Militia: Behind the PR Curtain</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

The Earth Day edition of <CITE>PR Watch</CITE> [<I>Center for Media and Democracy, 3318 Gregory St., Madison,
WI 53711; (608) 233-3346</I>], which regularly features public-interest reporting on the public
relations industry, served up some tasty excerpts from the February 1995 edition of <CITE>O'Dwyer's PR
Services</CITE>, an influential industry newsletter.<P>

 "Relief is on the way for PR clients on the environmental front...." <CITE>O'Dwyer's</CITE> opined. "Green PR people are advised to ride the
Republican-fueled anti-environmental backlash wave as far as possible. But they should not be
greedy, because overreaching may come back to haunt them once the sun sets on the pro-business
Republicans and greenies are again on the rise." <P>

Michael Kehs, PR firm Burson-Marsteller's "environmental" chief, told <CITE>O'Dwyer's</CITE>: "[Following the Republican victory in the last election] the
business community enjoys the upper hand.... There is a new contract on the street. And although
the word 'environment' is never mentioned, many observers believe it's less a contract with
America than a 'contract on environmental busybodies'...." <CITE>O'Dwyer's</CITE> also echoed Kehs' caveat:
"Don't get your hopes up and don't appear greedy by complaining how much compliance with green
laws costs.... That could jeopardize years of good works and careful corporate positioning."<P>

According to <CITE>PR Watch</CITE>, market researchers have found that 75-95 percent of US citizens consider
themselves to be "green" and more than 20 million green Americans contribute time and money to
environmental organizations. However, when one leading PR firm asked business leaders to respond
to the statement "Overall, the quality of the environment in your country is improving," 99.9
percent of them agreed.<P>

In 1990 alone, US businesses spent an estimated $500 million on anti-environmental PR professionals and on "greenwashing" their corporate images. <CITE>O'Dwyers</CITE>
termed the environmental struggle "the life-and-death PR battle of the 1990s." <P>

According to <CITE>PR Watch</CITE>, the top ten corporate public-relations "greenwashers" are Burson-Marsteller (heading the
list with $17.9 million in income for 1993), Ketchum PR, Hill & Knowlton, Fleishman-Hillard,
Shandwick, E. Bruce Harrison Co., Edelman PR Worldwide, The Rowland Company, Pacific/West
Communications and Ruder Finn.<P> 			

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


