<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Activists at Risk in US and Abroad</TITLE>

<H1>Activists at Risk in US and Abroad</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

<H3>"If the troubles from environmentalists cannot be solved in the jury box or at the ballot box, perhaps the cartridge box should be used."<BR>
--Former Reagan Administration Interior Secretary James Watt (currently under federal indictment on corruption charges)</H3>

Twenty years after the mysterious murder of anti-nuclear whistleblower Karen Silkwood, attacks
on US environmentalists are on the rise. In addition to physical assaults, phone harassment and
death threats, eco-activists have also been shot at, raped, knifed and fire-bombed.<P>

 In his book, <CITE>The War Against the Greens</CITE> (Sierra Club Books, 1994), David Helvarg assembled a chilling list of
attacks on grassroots victims. Helvarg believes that anti-green violence "is much more serious in
the '90s than ever before," owing to the growing desperation of American workers who are losing
jobs and the promise of secure futures.<P>

 Helvarg's book records instances of drive-by shootings, firebombings and pet poisonings. Greens have been attacked by speeding autos, chainsaws, pistols
and, in the case of redwood defender Judi Bari, a car bomb that nearly killed her. <P>

Last September, Oregon Natural Resources Council executive director Andy Kerr and Hells Canyon Preservation
Council executive director Ric Bailey were hung in effigy in Joseph, Oregon. A sign attach-ed to the
tarred-and-feathered figures declared: "Enviros can learn a lot from a couple of dummies." The
public "hanging" was staged the day before a conference hosted by Wise Use movement co-founder
Ron Arnold. <P>

And it is no longer just green activists who are at risk. On May 9, Rep. George Miller (D-CA) accused Republican members of Congress of encouraging acts of violence against US Forest
Service (USFS) and Bureau of Land Management (BLM) employees who are paid to "enforce laws
against resource abuse." Miller cited both House Speaker Newt Gingrich's claim that many people
have a "genuine fear" of government and Rep. Barbara Vuvanovich's (R-NV) warning to federal
officials: "This is Nevada -- people are armed."<P>

 "Offices of the BLM have been bombed, guns have been drawn on park rangers and agents of the Fish and Wildlife Ser-vice (FWS), and there have
been multiple direct threats of bloodshed against other public officials," Rep. Miller charged.<P>

 In response to Sen. Larry Craig's (R-ID) call to disarm federal enforcement officials, Miller pointed
out that these were the employees who were most at risk.<P>

 In October, 1994, Miller reported, a bomb exploded at the BLM office in Reno, Nevada, and in March, 1995, another bomb exploded at
the Carson City, Nevada forest service office. The manager of the Mal-heur National Wildlife Refuge
was threatened with death and his family harassed by anti-federal activists. In June 1994, bomb
threats and drawn guns halted a groundwater-assessment program on federal land in New Mexico.
An FWS employee in Reserve, New Mexico, was told his head "would be blown off" if he kept doing
his job. Road-building crews in the Toiyabe National Forest have ceased work because of threats
against their lives.<P>

 In Nevada, Richard Carver, a Nye County commissioner opposed to the regulation of grazing, mining and logging on public lands, personally bulldozed an illegal road
through public lands, as forest service personnel were held at bay by an armed posse of Carver's
supporters. <P>

Jeff DeBonis, a former forest ranger and founder of the Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility says "one top forest service official recently told me he thought there
was a 50 percent chance of a forest service employee getting murdered this summer in either Idaho
or Nevada."<P>

 The situation for environmental workers outside the US serves as a warning of the direction this trend could take.<P>
 
 <UL>
 
 <LI>In Honduras, Jeannette Kawas' campaign against illegal logging in the Punta Sal National Park was cut short when she was murdered. Her killer remains at
large.
 
 <P><LI>In<A HREF="../gsc/costa.html"> Costa Rica</A>, ecologists Jaime Bustamante, Maria del Mar Cordero and Oscar Fallas-Baldi tried to stop construction of an industrial complex in the Golfo Dulce. They died when
their home went up in flames.

 <P><LI>In Cambodia, military police warned reporter Chan Dara to halt his investigations into the military's involvement in the timber trade. Two days later he was
found dead. 

<P><LI>In Nigeria, Ogoni land-rights activist Ken Saro-Wiwa, appearing physically battered, was transferred from prison to a military hospital to await a secret court hearing that
could hand down a death sentence (see story page 35.

<P><LI>In Mexico, dozens of Tarahumara Indians have been murdered by loggers and drug barons. Environmentalists helping the Tarahumara
fight to save their forests have been kidnapped, tortured and shot (Spring '95 <CITE>EIJ</CITE>).<P>

</UL>			

<HR>

<H2> What You Can Do:</H2>

 Global Response, an international environmental action network, has established a computer-based "Quick Response Network" to publicize and counter threats against activists. To
receive e-mail alerts with the names of endangered activists and the names, addresses and fax
numbers of critical officials "who can make a difference in the case," contact
"majordomo@igc.apc.org" and send the e-mail message: "subscribe globesmembers". Global
Response, PO Box 7490, Boulder, CO 80306-7490; phone/fax: (303) 444-0306.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


