<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Millions Spent to Gas Rats, Dogs, Horses</TITLE>

<H1>Millions Spent to Gas Rats, Dogs, Horses</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

USA -- On April 20, a group of New Mexico environmentalists released a 14-page report,
<CITE>Inhalation Toxicology Research Institute: Hazardous to Your Health</CITE>, criticizing animal experiments
conducted at the ITRI facility at Kirtland Air Force Base near Albuquerque. <P>

"Millions of tax dollars are squandered at ITRI every year on gruesome experiments that take the lives of thousands of
animals," charged Pat Wolff, author of the Coalition for Research Ethics and Accountability's report
[<I>CREA, PO Box 11395, Albuquerque, NM 87192; (505) 281-0032</I>]. Wolff claimed that
"radioactive and toxic byproducts of those experiments have contaminated the air and water"
surrounding Albuquerque and have exposed workers to "hazardous substances and dangerous
working conditions."<P>

 Since 1951, ITRI has received $300 million for experiments that forced animals to inhale radioactive particles in a search for guidelines on human exposure risks. But,
according to veterinarian Stephen R. Kaufman, co-chair of the Medical Research Modernization
Committee [<I>MRMC, PO Box 2751, Grand Central Station, New York, NY 10163-2751</I>], "Studying
relatively high-dose radiation exposure on laboratory-bound, non-human animals cannot address
issues related to human radiation exposure." If the government were interested in determining the
impact of radiation on human health, Kaufman suggested, research funds should be spent to study
the "millions of people [who] have received (and continue to receive) low-level radiation exposure
from diagnostic and therapeutic medical devices. What we need," Kaufman stated, "is good public
health research, not ill-conceived animal 'model' studies."<P>

 CREA noted that ITRI subjected 10,000 dogs, guinea pigs, rats and primates to "inhalation" experiments in 1993 and received a $17
million government subsidy for continued research in fiscal year 1994. Citing "conflicts of
interest," CREA's investigations concluded that "certain individuals involved in directing and
funding work done at the Lovelace/ITRI facility may have a financial interest in industries that
produce or promote the toxic and radioactive materials being tested at ITRI."<P>

CREA has called for a Congressional investigation into the alleged conflicts of interest, as well as health and safety issues.<P>

-- Gar Smith

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


