<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Trees Cut to Fund Military</TITLE>

<H1>Trees Cut to Fund Military</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

Between the first Earth Day in 1970 and the event's 25th anniversary, timber companies turned
20 million acres of pristine forests into timber and woodpulp.<P>

 Less than 30 million acres of the USA's original 1.04 billion forested acres survive today -- more than 97 percent of the forests
have been lost to human expansion.<P>

 Save America's Forests [<I>4 Liberty Court, SW, Washington, DC 20003; (202) 544-9219</I>] notes that more than 60 percent of the US Forest Service's annual
budget is used to liquidate national forests -- at the rate of 800,000 acres a year. At that rate of
timber-cutting, all remaining US forests would be gone in 38 years.<P>

 The one branch of the government that was successfully putting more trees into the ground was lopped off by the
Republican budget axe. The Office of Natural Resources Sales Assistance, with a budget of only $15
million a year and a team consisting of a half-dozen part-time employees in the Small Business
Administration, has managed to plant more than 23 million trees during the past several years.<P>

According to the Washington Post, the $15 million saved "will go to the Pentagon "for military
readiness."

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


