<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Militarizing the US Budget</TITLE>

<H1>Militarizing the US Budget</H1>

<H2>by Gar Smith</H2>

USA -- The NRA and the militia movement may get hot-collared and hysterical at the mere mention
of "gun control," but that is nothing compared to the heat the Pentagon can bring to bear on
politicians who want to control military spending.<P>

 "They want to take away our weapons!" is a rallying cry shared by the Pentagon, the NRA and the militias. However, according to the Campaign
for New Priorities [<I>CNP, 1601 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20015</I>], if the defense
budget were cut in half over the next five years, the US could still "sustain a military larger than
the armies of Britain, Germany, Japan and France combined... and maintain the most lethal nuclear
force in the world."In 1992, the combined military budgets of all the nations on the Pentagon's list
of "potential adversaries" (Russia, Iraq, China, Iran, North Korea, Libya, Cuba and Panama) was
$77.8 billion. The Pentagon's budget for 1992 totaled $270.9 billion. <P>

Last December, when President Clinton requested an additional $27.6 billion boost to the military budget to assure the
Pentagon's "readiness," the retired military officers at the Center for Defense Information [<I>1500
Massachusetts Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20005</I>] asked incredulously, "Ready for what?" CDI
director Vice Admiral Jack Shanahan (USN-ret.) has warned that "US military spending is out of
control." According to Shanahan, Washington is spending $5 billion a week on military expenses at
a time when "there are no real military threats to America's safety." <P>

While budgets for nutrition, health care, education and environmental protection are being savaged, CDI notes, "President
Clinton and the Congress have declared the military budget to be exempt from any cuts." CDI's
analysts have responded with a plan to maintain "a strong and adequate" US defense with a military
budget of $175 billion -- an annual savings of almost $96 billion.<P>

 The Pentagon's case was not helped by the revelation in late May that the Department of Defense was unable to explain an
"accounting gap" of $28.8 billion.<P>

<H2>Write Your own Budget</H2>

If you were president, what kind of a budget would you propose? Thanks to the Center for
Defense Information, anyone can now play Chief Executive. CDI has produced a two-page version of
the federal budget with the president's proposed spending, actual budget amounts for 1994, and a
blank column to be filled in by citizens. Clinton's proposed budget, devotes $264 billion to the
Pentagon $54 billion to education and $7 billion to pollution control. After filling out your budget,
CDI suggests that you mail copies to the House, Senate and the Oval Office.

<HR>

