<TITLE>EIJ Summer 95: Campaign Against Methyl Bromide</TITLE>

<H2>Campaign Against Methyl Bromide</H2>

<H1>Ozone-Killing Pesticide Opposed</H1>

Methyl bromide is a pesticide that is at least 50 times more destructive to the ozone layer, atom for
atom, than chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs). In 1992, the United Nations estimated that the bromine
atoms released into the upper atmosphere by methyl bromide are responsible for five-to-ten
percent of global ozone depletion, a share that is expected to increase to 15 percent by the year
2000.<P>

 In 1994, the UN listed elimination of methyl bromide (MB) as the most significant remaining approach (after phase-out of CFCs and halons) to reducing ozone depletion. While CFCs
and halons can continue destroying ozone for decades, bromine atoms remain in the atmosphere for
less than two years. UN scientists conclude that eliminating MB emissions from agricultural,
structural and industrial activities by the year 2001 would achieve a 13 percent reduction in
ozone-depleting chemicals reaching the stratosphere over the next 50 years.<P>

 MB is extremely toxic and can cause acute and chronic health effects. Farmworkers, pesticide applicators and people living
or working  where MB is used can suffer poisoning, neurological damage and reproductive harm.
The chemical is so toxic to humans and animals that the Environmental Protection Agency (EPA)
classifies it as a Category I acute toxin, the most deadly group of substances.<P>

 For 60 years, MB has been used to kill pests in soils and buildings, and on agricultural products. In 1991, the US
accounted for nearly 40 percent of the pesticide's worldwide use. Soil fumigation to sterilize soil
before planting crops is by far the largest use of MB in the US.<P>

 Worldwide, most MB is used for luxury and export crops, like tomatoes, strawberries, peppers, tobacco and nursery crops.<P>

<H3>Health Effects of Exposure</H3>

MB affects the central nervous system and damages lungs, kidneys, eyes and skin. Recovery from
the more severe symptoms of MB toxicity, such as pneumonia, severe weakness, paralysis and
heart problems, can take days to several months. Studies show that MB concentrations can drift
several miles from a site of fumigation, posing a threat to residents and workers who may be
exposed to the gas. But unlike some other pesticides, MB is believed to leave little or no residue on
most foods.<P>

Under the Clean Air Act the EPA has mandated a halt to MB production in and import to the US in 2001, but manufacturers and agricultural users have mounted a formidable campaign to
delay the ban. Because no gradual phaseout is required, methyl bromide can be used without major
restrictions until 2001. Since the act does not prohibit the use of existing stocks after 2001,
application of the pesticide can continue as long as stockpiled supplies last.<P>

 An MB tax -- like that imposed on other ozone-depleting chemicals -- should be required to pressure users and producers
to reduce their dependence on the compound and to stimulate the  shift to available alternatives
before the phaseout date. The Congressional Budget Office estimates that an MB tax could generate
nearly $1 billion over five years.<P>

 The Montreal Protocol, the principal international treaty on ozone-depleting substances, officially recognized MB as an ozone-depleting chemical in 1992, but
will not decide on an international phaseout until December, 1995. Resistance stems primarily
from countries with large MB producers and users, including the US, Israel, Japan and France.<P>

<H3>Methyl Bromide Alternatives</H3>

Numerous alternatives to MB exist, including organic soil additives, soil solarization, crop rotation
and biological pest control in farming. Controlled atmosphere techniques (using pest-suppressing
levels of nitrogen and CO2) and heat/cold treatments are proven alternatives on harvested crops
and in structures. In 1992, the US Defense Logistics Agency saved $2.8 million by using controlled
atmosphere to ship produce to troops.<P>

Several of the key pesticides proposed as MB replacements by the chemical industry pose known health risks. The soil fumigant 1,3-D (Telone) is considered a
probable human carcinogen by the EPA, while metam-sodium has been found to cause birth defects
in laboratory animals.<P>

 The Methyl Bromide Global Coalition (MBGC) -- a group of eight international MB users and producers -- has launched a multimillion-dollar lobbying campaign to
keep the product on the market. In early 1994, members of the MBGC, along with the agribusiness
and chemical industries, sued EPA to stop the MB phaseout.<P>

 While some nations are actively fighting a phaseout, other countries have already banned or vigorously regulated MB. In 1992, the
Netherlands eliminated all soil fumigation using MB, and other countries, including Denmark,
Germany and Switzerland, are planning similar actions.<P>

 The Methyl Bromide Alternatives Network (MBAN), formed in 1993, is a coalition of 17 US environmental, agricultural and labor
organizations working to phase out and replace MB with affordable, environmentally sound
alternatives. MBAN is asking food manufacturers to switch to alternatives that do not deplete the
ozone layer, pressing the EPA to accelerate the MB phaseout and demanding that the Department of
Agriculture work to develop and promote alternatives. MBAN is also urging delegates to the
Montreal Protocol to sign a global MB phaseout agreement in December. <P>

-- Anne Schonfield, MBAN<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2> Ask the EPA to require labeling of all products using MB; ask stores to stock
organic produce; demand non-chemical treatments from pest-control companies. Contact MBAN,
116 New Montgomery Street, #810, San Francisco CA 94105; (415) 541-9140; fax (415)
541-9253. Contact Ozone Action, 1621 Connecticut Avenue, NW, Washington, DC 20009; (202)
265-6738.<P>

<HR>

<H2>Bromicidal Maniacs</H2>

A leaked document from the US chemical industry's Methyl Bromide Working Group (including
Ethyl Corp. and Great Lakes Chemical Corp., the country's major MB producers) has
environmentalists steamed. Unfazed by reports of record ozone depletion and the appearance of an
ozone hole over the North Pole, the MBWG's letter states: "If we continue to work together, we stand
an increasingly good chance of being able to use methyl bromide well beyond the year 2001." To do
so would violate the Clean Air Act. With MB bans likely in industrialized countries, there is intense
pressure to expand MB sales in Third World nations. <P>	         

-- Gar Smith

<HR>

