<TITLE>EIJ Summer 94: GATT threatens US environment.</TITLE>

<H1>GATT threatens US environment.</H1>

<HR> Earth Island Journal.<BR> Summer 94<BR> Vol. 9 Issue 3<BR> p26+ <HR>

<H2><I>Congress Considers Critical Vote</I></H2>

The foremost test of any proposed international 
agreement should be whether it 
damages democracy or unduly limits legitimate 
sovereignty. The World Trade Organization 
(WTO), established during the 
Uruguay Round of the General Agreement 
on Tariffs and Trade (GATT) negotiations, 
fails these two tests. The WTO is an international 
autocratic regime that subordinates 
non-commercial standards and policies 
such as health, safety and workplace conditions 
to the dictates of international trade 
priorities.<P>

This transnational agenda suits global 
corporations because it transfers power 
away from accountable democratic constituencies
 and procedures. To corporations acting 
 on the global level, citizens acting at the 
 local, state and national levels have become 
 too much of a hindrance. The WTO would 
 greatly reduce citizen involvement in matters 
 of commerce. Large corporations can 
 deeply influence the WTO, its tribunals 
 and committees; citizens cannot.<P>

In the US, citizen advocacy to protect public 
health, safety and the environment 
has made considerable progress in recent 
decades despite the opposition of multinational 
companies. This achievement has 
been possible due to a number of democratic 
tools, such as the right to information, the 
right to petition, the right to appeal rulings 
and to elect or defeat lawmakers.<P>

The WTO hurls autocracy against this 
democracy. If this trade agreement is approved, 
the WTO's bureaucrats would have 
the power to force the US Congress, 
and state or local governments, to change laws 
or else to face economic sanctions.<P>

Laws at risk because of the finalization of 
GATT include such vital consumer and environmental 
provisions as state recycling 
programs, the US asbestos ban, the US 
Delaney clause prohibiting cancer-causing 
additives in food, US efforts to restrict the 
export of raw logs, US fuel-economy standards 
for cars, food-labeling rules, US laws 
designed to protect <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">dolphins</A>, and state bans 
on the controversial bovine growth hormone 
(BGH) used on dairy cows. Workplace 
safety standards would also be at risk.<P>

Under the WTO's rules, these protective 
measures could be defined as "non-tariff 
trade barriers." The rationale is that anything 
that interferes with a corporation's 
ability to sell products -- even dangerous 
products -- to consumers in nations with 
strong health, safety and environmental laws 
could be considered a barrier to trade.<P>

<H2>How the WTO Would Work</H2>

Proposition 65 is a California law passed in 
1986 by popular referendum that mandates 
the labeling of consumer products containing 
cancer-causing chemicals. As a result of 
GATT, any nation wanting to export products 
containing these dangerous chemicals 
to California without such labeling could 
appeal to the WTO.<P>

An official from the US Trade Representative's 
Office in Washington, DC, would 
then have to travel to Geneva to defend the 
state's law before a tribunal of three unelected 
trade specialists. These tribunal judges 
would be nominated by the 119 GATT signatory 
nations, but chosen by the WTO. The 
judges would likely be from other nations 
and would need no knowledge of California 
law or food safety to be appointed to the 
case. The WTO's tribunal has no conflict-of-interest 
provisions, so panelists could have 
an interest in the cases that they review.<P>

The tribunal would hear cases in secret. 
No one from the press, public or state government 
would be allowed to hear the 
tribunal's proceedings or to participate -- 
even as a friend of the court. Records from 
the tribunal would not be made public. US 
citizens would never know what the trade 
representative said to this court, or the 
questions raised by the judges. Thus, US 
officials and those of other countries would 
remain publicly unaccountable.<P>

If the WTO decided against a state's law, 
the US federal government would then be 
required to do everything in its authority -- 
including, for example, cutting off highway 
funds -- to force the state to comply. If a 
state did not change its law, the US would 
have to pay perpetual economic sanctions to 
the WTO. There would be no appeal to any 
outside body or higher court.<P>

Under the WTO, new international food-safety 
and agricultural standards would be 
set by the Codex Alimentarius Commission, 
a Rome-based subgroup of the United Nations 
Food and Agriculture Organization 
that is heavily influenced by the food and 
agribusiness industries. A recent study of 
the National Food Alliance in the United 
Kingdom found that 660 industry representatives 
participated on Codex committees, 
compared to 26 representatives of the public-interest 
community. Many Codex standards 
are weaker than those of the US. A 
1992 study by the US Government Accounting 
Office found that Codex standards for 
cancer-causing residues in foods were 
weaker than US standards in more than 50 
percent of the instances.<P>

The WTO also demands that all food 
safety, environmental, workplace and consumer 
standards be the "least trade restrictive." 
This would inherently threaten 
bans on dangerous products because any 
ban is automatically "trade restrictive."<P>

<H2>The World According to GATT</H2>

In its first 40 years, GATT concerned itself 
primarily with trade tariffs and related 
matters. In 1986, when the so-called "Uruguay 
Round" of GATT negotiations began, 
the scope of the agreement changed.<P>

During the "Uruguay Round," multinational 
corporations asserted their goal of 
investing anywhere in the world without 
restrictions. Environmental and safety 
standards were "harmonized" to facilitate 
international trade. Monopoly rights governing 
global ownership of intellectual 
property (patents, copyrights and trademarks) 
became entrenched. Transnational 
and government representatives also asked 
that food, agriculture and services (banking, 
insurance, shipping, etc.) be included 
under GATT. Finally, they created the WTO 
to enhance GATT's power over each participating 
country.<P>

While citizens were excluded during the 
past several years of GATT negotiations, 
corporate lobbyists cruising the halls outside 
the negotiating rooms in Geneva were 
able to exert tremendous influence over the 
negotiations. Citizen groups, lacking the 
resources or contacts to post lobbyists in Geneva, 
have not been able to play a parallel role.<P>

In a March 1994 speech in New York 
City, then-Director General of GATT, 
Irishman Peter Sutherland, declared that 
"Governments should interfere in the conduct 
of trade as little as possible" -- a sentiment 
shared by officials of the largest multinational 
corporations.<P>

Unfortunately for Americans, the "conduct 
of trade" issue includes concerns like:<P>

<UL>

<LI> Can the US ban asbestos? <BR>(Foreign asbestos 
exporters see such a ban as a "trade barrier.")<P>

<LI> Can the US maintain fuel-economy standards 
for cars sold in this country? <BR>(Makers 
of some European gas-guzzlers, like Mercedes 
Benz and BMW, call this an "unfair trade barrier.")<P>

<LI> Can the US defend the part of the Marine 
Mammal Protection Act that protects dolphins ? <BR>(Foreign tuna producers whose fishing 
methods kill large numbers of dolphins 
claim the US <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">"dolphin-safe" conservation</A> laws discriminate 
against their imports.)

</UL>

The WTO would create a regulatory climate 
that would inhibit future progress in 
environmental and consumer protection. 
Under the WTO, such protections would be 
diminished towards an internationally lower 
common denominator. Domestic standards 
deemed "too strong" could be challenged 
as trade restrictions. Standards deemed "too 
low," however, could not be challenged.<P>

Consumer groups already have enough 
problems dealing with wealthy corporate 
lobbyists and their politicians in Washington 
without being told that decisions are 
increasingly going to be made by other countries, 
other officials and other lobbies that 
have no accountability or disclosure requirements 
in the US. The WTO would establish 
an international autocratic structure over 
the US federal and constitutional systems 
that could make a mockery out of self-determination 
and legitimate sovereignty.<P>

If Congress approves the GATT, people in 
Los Angeles or Chicago who want to push 
for safer food, pollution controls and safer 
cars will hear from their Washington representatives 
and from corporate lobbyists, 
"Sorry, but the Japanese won't stand for it. 
The French won't stand for it."<P>

Both the US House of Representatives 
and the Senate must approve the Uruguay 
Round of GATT before it takes effect. The 
vote could come as early as this summer. 
Congress can only vote it up or down -- no 
amendments are permitted under the trade 
agreement procedures. Fortunately, Congress 
can still decide to keep the US out of 
the proposed WTO. The power to move 
Congress to reject this harmful trade agreement 
is in the hands of citizens. With most 
Fortune 500 companies poised to spend 
millions of dollars to lobby for passage of 
this agreement, citizens need to flood congressional 
offices by phone, fax, mail and 
telegram. Congress must know that we will 
not give up our right to set our own laws, 
nor will we tolerate having to pay a ransom 
to keep our laws.<P>

<H2>What You Can Do:</H2>

Contact Senator Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-NY) and your state's Representative and Senators [House of Representatives, Washington, DC 20515; US Senate, Washington, DC 20510; Capitol switchboard: (202) 224-3121] to express you r concern over the upcoming WTO vote. For more assistance, contact Public Citizen's Trade Campaign, 215 Pennsylvania Avenue, SE, Washington, DC 20003; (202) 546-4996; fax: (202) 547-7392.<P>

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


