<TITLE>EIJ Summer 94: The constitution's 'green' secret.</TITLE>

<H1>The constitution's 'green' secret.<I>By Michael Diamond.</I></H1>

<HR> Earth Island Journal.<BR> Summer 94<BR> Vol. 9 Issue 3<BR> p26+ <HR>

At the Constitutional Convention held in
Philadelphia during the summer of 1787,
 few delegates disagreed with Alexander
  Hamilton's assessment that' "men were
   ambitious, vindictive and rapacious." Del
egates considered domestic dangers to be
 "more alarming than the arms and arts of
  foreign nations." In the intervening centu
 ries, environmental shortsightedness and
  misplaced self-interest have joined to cre
  ate unprecedented threats of harm to the human species.<P>

The framers of the Constitution not only
 foresaw the root cause of our problem, but
  also provided an effective means for its
   cure: Article IV, Section 4 of the Constitu
   tion, which states: <I>"The United States shall
 guarantee to every State in this Union a Repub
 lican form of government, and shall protect each
  of them against invasion; and on application of
   the Legislature, or of the Executive (when the
    Legislature cannot be convened), against do
    mestic violence."</I><P>

The harm that we have done and are
 doing to ourselves by carelessness and in
 difference to the environment has brought
  about a condition of "domestic violence."<P>

Environmental contamination has poi
soned air, water, soil and food supplies in
ways that are analogous to acts of sabotage
or war. These incidents have resulted in
loss of long-term resources (e.g., aquifers 
and  forest ecosystems) and damage to private property. People have died as a result
of exposure to toxic and carcinogenic com
pounds in their environments. Individual
health, well-being, human potential and
even intellectual capacity have been put at
risk by those exposures. (The US Supreme Court
has deemed the phrase "each of them"
in Section 4 to include citizens of the various
states.)<P>

The framers clearly intended the term
 "domestic violence" to refer generally to
the infliction of harm or injury to persons
or property on a broad-enough scale to
threaten survival. On August 30, 1787, a motion 
was made to strike out "domestic
violence" and insert in its place the term
"insurrections." That motion was defeated.
"Violence" was clearly intended to mean
more than just rebellions or forms of physical 
challenge to government.<P>

<H2>"...To Assure Survival..."</H2>

Our danger is both extreme and immediate. 
Assuring survival has always
been the first duty of government. It was for that
purpose that we formed governments and
gave up great measures of personal sovereignty.<P>

Can the federal government afford to
spend $10 trillion to begin dealing with the
widespread health effects of pollution, 
accomplish the clean-ups and eliminate the
discharge of toxins? The question has little
to do with economics and everything to do
with the definition of national security. We
spent more than that sum on a <I>perceived</I>
military threat. Can we spend less on an
actual, physical one?<P>

At the Constitutional Convention, James
Madison observed that "A standing military 
force with an overgrown executive will
not long be safe companions to liberty. The
means of defense against foreign danger,
have been always the instruments of tyranny 
at home."<P>

The domestic violence clause is the 
necessary constitutional counterweight that can 
accomplish a rapid changeover from supporting 
a standing army to spending for 
survival.<P>

Because the threat to human survival is 
no less real from environmental domestic 
violence, the same federal mobilization that 
was occasioned by World War II ought to
take place under the "domestic violence" 
clause of the Constitution.<P>

When survival is at stake, the federal government 
must push lesser endeavors aside, 
curtail competing interests both public and 
private, gather the money and the talent 
necessary to solve the problem, and keep at 
the task long enough to assure survival. 
Isn't that why we have governments?<P>

Large-scale social changes occur rapidly 
when they are simultaneously embraced by 
a number of differing constituencies. 
The domestic violence solution can appeal 
equally to businesses, environmentalists, 
public health professionals, insurance companies, 
banks and religious organizations. 
This solution could be in place and working 
in a matter of just a few years. There would 
finally be enough meaningful jobs for everyone -- 
doing stewardship work and getting 
paid for it.<P>

Because invoking the "domestic violence" 
clause places so much power in the 
hands of the federal government, only full, 
public discussions leading to consensus can 
put that step on a firm footing.<P>

Only a constitutional mandate, understood 
by the people, can bring all of that about. 
That mandate exists at present in Article 
IV, Section 4. The clause is nothing less than 
a road map in a time capsule left for us by 
the founding fathers who, in their wisdom, 
knew that we would, in the end, be the 
authors of our own demise.<P>

If the "guarantee" portion of Section 4 is 
-- as Sen. Charles Sumner put it in 1867 -- 
the "sleeping giant in the Constitution," the 
domestic violence clause of Section 4 is 
even more momentous. In short, the framers 
harnessed a colossus for our use.<P>

<HR>

<H1>An Emergency Green Government?</H1>

Here is a partial list of what an "Emergency Green Government" could accomplish.<P>

<UL><P>

<LI> Require toxic screenings for all children, immediately.<P>

<LI> Remove lead from all homes and schools.<P>

<LI> Ban the use of lead, mercury, cadmium and other heavy metals.<P>

<LI> Require the closure of polluting industries and the seizure of corporate assets to finance clean-up and restoration work.<P>

<LI> Use seized corporate assets to fund retraining of workers for sustainable jobs.<P>

<LI> Void clauses in loan documents requiring farmers to use synthetic chemicals.<P>

<LI> Require changeover from synthetic to organic farming.<P>

<LI> Resurrect abandoned mass-transit systems.<P>

<LI> Institute a "Manhattan Project" to stabilize the ozone layer.<P>

<LI> Elevate the EPA to a cabinet position.<P>

<LI> Turn the Pentagon into a national archive housing cultural treasures. (At the time of its construction, it was promised that the Pentagon would be turned over to civilian use upon the conclusion of WWII.)<P>

</UL><P>

Please send further suggestions to "Green Government" c/o Earth Island Journal.<P> 

<HR>

