<TITLE>EIJ Summer 94: Randy Borman: Cofan Chief</TITLE>

<H1>Randy Borman: Cofan Chief<I> by Mike Tidwell</I></H1>


<HR> Earth Island Journal.<BR> Summer 94<BR> Vol. 9 Issue 3<BR> p26+ <HR>


Ecuador's multi-billion dollar Amazon petroleum 
industry has been dominated for 
more than 20 years by such US companies 
as Texaco, Arco, Maxus, Occidental and 
Oryx. After years of sloppy operations, the 
industry is being characterized by American 
and Ecuadorian environmentalists as a 
direct threat to the well-being, and perhaps 
survival, of Ecuador's</A> rainforest</A> and its 
peoples.<P>

Last November, Randy Borman, the 38-year-old 
son of American missionaries and 
chief of a community of Cofan Indians, 
slipped into his Indian tunic and applied 
streaks of red ceremonial paint to his face. 
He then led his band of 35 Cofan followers 
on an armed visit to an oil well illegally 
constructed on their land deep inside 
Ecuador's Amazon rainforest.<P>

With spears and shotguns, the Cofan encircled 
the well and its crew of startled 
workers. Thirty-six hours later, following a 
tense standoff and extensive negotiations, 
Borman had what he wanted: the promise 
of an environmental impact study (EIS) for 
the area and a compensatory batch of 60 
solar panels to go atop the Cofan's thatch-roof 
village huts.<P>

Born and raised among the Cofan, 
Borman could use a blowgun at age four 
and spear an Amazon pig at age ten. When 
his Bible-translating parents retired from 
the forest 13 years ago, he stayed behind, 
marrying a Cofan wife and eventually rising 
to power as an elected Cofan chief. 
Now, in a campaign that has captured international 
attention, Borman and the Cofan 
have become the vanguard of a battle to 
preserve Ecuador's</A> 32-million-acre Amazon 
rainforest</A> from ongoing oil exploitation.<P>

<H2>Defending Native Territory</H2>

"We were forced into this action by direct 
threats to our survival," said Borman of the 
November 1, 1993 shutdown at the oil well 
belonging to Petroecuador, the national oil 
comp any. "Unless we take direct action like 
this, we know our forest and way of life will 
be destroyed by oil companies. It has happened 
elsewhere and it will happen here."<P>

Borman and the Cofan, fearing 
the destruction of 
their still-pristine 
expanse of forest 
in eastern-most 
Ecuador by Petroecuador and multinational 
oil companies, have been prompted to take 
matters into their own hands. Last September, 
after numerous protest letters went 
unanswered by Petroecuador, Borman led 
the Indians in setting fire to another of the 
company's drilling platforms, built without 
permission on Cofan land, and destroyed 
the unmanned rig. Two years earlier, 
the Cofan kidnapped for 24 hours and 
then expelled from their land a 23-man 
crew of trespassing seismic-testing oil technicians.<P>

All of these events took place on or near 
Cofan territory and within Ecuador's</A> 
Cuyabeno Wildlife Reserve, some of the 
most biologically diverse rainforest in the 
world. The Cofan's protest efforts have 
helped galvanize an unusual coalition of 
environmentalists, tourism companies and 
other Indigenous tribes determined to protect 
Cuyabeno from the oil spills and large-scale 
deforestation that have followed the 
activities of oil companies elsewhere in Ecuador.<P>

Borman wryly defends the Cofan's actions 
with his so-called "three-point explanation."<P>

"One," he said, "all the acts were unavoidable. 
Two, we pursued every possible 
alternative means before acting. Three, all 
the acts were unavoidable." Borman 
stressed that the Cofan policy is to never 
shoot first, but to defend themselves if fired 
upon during any armed visit to a well site.<P>

To date, none of the Cofan attacks have 
resulted in physical violence or government 
retaliation. Most Ecuadorian conservationists, 
in fact, defend the acts as measures 
of self defense. Jose Delgado, a leading 
rainforest</A> preservationist within 
Ecuador's</A> Ministry of Agriculture, described 
the Cofan's activism as nothing 
short of "historic."<P>

"For the first time, thanks largely to the 
Cofan, oil companies in Ecuador are being 
forced to admit that the rainforest is not a 
vacant land where they can do whatever 
they want," said Delgado. "People live there 
with rights</A> and aspirations just as valid as 
any company wanting a profit."<P>

In the past, with government complicity, 
oil companies have routinely entered and 
significantly degraded Ecuadorian rain-forest 
areas without consulting or compensating 
Indigenous peoples. But with 
Petroecuador's agreement to an EIS, environmentalists 
in Ecuador and the US increasingly 
point to the country as a place 
where the fear of "green castigation" has oil 
companies behaving more cautiously.<P>

<H2>A Multinational Malefactor</H2>

"No one wants to be the next Texaco," said 
Yolanda Kakabadse, former president of 
Fundacion Natura, Ecuador's</A> largest 
environmental organization. Last year, lawyers 
representing Amazon farmers and several 
tribes, including the Cofan, filed a record 
$1.5 billion class-action suit in New York 
and Texas against Texaco for allegedly "negligent, 
reckless, intentional and outrageous 
acts" of environmental damage connected 
to its extensive rainforest</A> drilling operations 
between 1964 and 1992. The Cofan
 contend that Texaco dumped drilling wastes 
 and oil into the region's rivers, contaminating 
 the water, jeopardizing the health of 
 native peoples, and killing plants and animals. 
 Over Texaco's objections, the New 
 York court has agreed to decide whether 
 the case should be tried in the US.<P>

While Texaco strongly denies any pattern 
of environmental wrongdoing in its 
past Ecuador operations, a March, 1994 
study of several drinking-water sources scattered 
across the company's old Amazon 
concession area in northeastern Ecuador 
shows signs of widespread contamination, 
according to Sarah Zaidi, coordinator of the 
study. Commissioned by the New York-based
 Center for Economic and Social 
 Rights, the investigation found substances 
 associated with the presence of oil in areas 
 adjacent to former Texaco facilities at 2-500 
 times the maximum level accepted by the 
 US Environmental Protection Agency.<P>

Government records show that spills 
from the trans-Ecuadorian pipeline, 
which Texaco built in 1972, totaled 500,000 
barrels (16.8 million gallons) of crude oil 
over 17 years, 50 percent more oil than was 
spilled by the <I>Exxon Valdez</I>.<P>

However, Ecuador has no plans to slow 
the pace of oil production, now running at 
approximately 360,000 barrels a day. Oil 
exports account for 14 percent of the 
country's gross national product and 50 
percent of foreign-export earnings. But the 
nation's Ministry of Energy and Mines reports 
that this year the government will 
begin requiring oil companies with major 
concessions in Ecuador to carry $1 billion-worth 
of environmental "clean-up insurance" 
to cover any spills or other contamination.<P>

Meanwhile, the Cofan have demanded 
and received assurances from the government 
that extensive environmental impact 
studies will be conducted in areas targeted 
for exploratory drilling on or near Cofan 
territory. The Cofan will also receive a list of 
chemicals and machinery slated for use in 
oil exploration before such materials are 
used, thus giving the Indians the theoretical 
right to veto some aspects of oil activities. 
Indian-rights</A> proponents now vow to 
press for similar rights for other Indigenous 
Ecuadorian groups affected by oil 
development, amplifying the Cofan gains.<P>

Officially, the Cofan say they are not 
opposed to oil exploitation on their land, as 
long as environmental precautions are 
strictly adhered to. But privately, conservation 
activists working with the Cofan admit 
that the strategy is to entangle Petroecuador 
in environmental studies and potential lawsuits 
until the company abandons the 
Cuyabeno Wildlife Reserve entirely. Environmentalists 
fear that even if exploratory 
wells are made safer, any oil discovery necessarily 
will require the construction of 
roads and pipelines through the reserve.<P>

During two decades of oil production, 
hundreds of miles of roads have brought 
thousands of settlers into the region from 
the land-scarce Andean highlands. Already 
more than 2.5 million acres of jungle 
have been deforested as a consequence of 
oil operations, according to attorney Judith 
Kimmerling, author of the report, <I>Amazon 
Crude</I>.<P>

Most observers in Ecuador agree that, 
despite the recent successes of the Cofan 
and the growing clout of environmental 
groups, the Ecuadorian Indigenous and 
ecology movements face a stiff uphill battle 
against a national government firmly committed 
to continued exploitation of its oil 
reserves, almost all of which lie in the 
country's Amazon forest region.<P>

In January, the Ecuadorian government 
announced its plans to lease five million 
acres of Amazonian rainforest</A> to multinational 
companies for oil exploration, which 
will require the construction of a new oil 
pipeline and hundreds of miles of new 
roads. The area covers 85 percent of Indigenous 
land in Ecuador (although no Cofan 
territory), according to Rainforest Action 
Network, as well as national parks and 
protected wetlands, where subsurface rights</A> 
are not protected by the government.<P>

In response, environmental and Indigenous 
groups are petitioning the Ecuadorian 
government, and appealing to the US 
Congress, for a 15-year moratorium on new 
oil development in the Amazon in order to 
provide time to fully assess environmental 
damage and implement ecological and cultural 
safeguards.<P>

<H2>The Promise of Ecotourism</H2>

Environmentalists contend that revenues 
earned from tourism in the Amazon 
rainforest</A> could eventually outstrip oil 
earnings. The number of visitors to the 
Cuyabeno Wildlife Reserve, for example, 
has doubled to 10,000 people in the past five 
years alone, according to park officials.<P>

"Unlike oil, tourism is sustainable," said 
Pedro Proano, president of Transturri, S.A., 
Ecuador's</A> largest ecotourism company, 
with operations centered in the Cuyabeno 
reserve. "If the oil companies have their 
way, in 20 years [when Ecuador's oil reserves 
are expected to run out] there won't 
be any oil <I>or</I> a rainforest. But tourism is 
forever. It preserves the forest and brings 
money into the country year after year."<P>

Indeed, the Cofan Indians themselves in 
recent years have begun offering guided 
tours to backpackers and scientists wanting 
to see the splendor of the Cuyabeno forest. 
The extra income has helped finance the 
group's protest efforts within the park, as 
well as trips to Quito to testify before various 
government oversight agencies. Chief 
Borman, meanwhile, has said he may visit 
Washington later this year to testify before 
Congress on the Cofan's situation.<P>

Ecuadorian land laws are ambiguous and 
contradictory in this region of the country, 
though they appear more favorable to the 
Cofan than the oil companies in terms of 
rainforest</A> use. For this reason, Petroecuador 
has avoided requesting that the government 
provide military intervention as a response 
to the Cofan protest actions.<P>
 "We all want the same thing anyway," 
 said Fabiola Gomez, spokesperson for 
 Petroecuador. "Our company wants to reach 
 an agreement that's good for the forest just 
 as much as Borman and the Cofan do."<P>

Borman and the Cofan are wary, however, 
watching the oil companies that are 
rapidly approaching their settlement area 
near the Peruvian border as the companies 
move progressively through the forest. The 
Indians' backs are against the border. Escape 
is impossible. So chief Borman, with 
his silver-blond hair and blue eyes, has 
taken to streaking his cheeks with red paint. 
He has decided to resist the oil companies.<P>

"We will never accept all the oil spills 
and environmental calamity that have come 
with oil elsewhere," he said. "The only way 
that will happen here is if the companies or 
the government remove us. And I have no 
intention of leaving," he said, pausing, then 
adding, "not willingly, at least."<P>

<H2>What You Can Do</H2> Send letters requesting 
a moratorium on oil development in the Ecuadorian Amazon to<P>

Alfred C. DeCrane, Jr.<BR> Chairman and CEO, Texaco Inc.<BR> 2000 Westchester Ave.,<BR> White Plains, NY 10650;<BR> fax: (914) 253-7753<P>

Dr. Francisco Acosta<BR> Minister of Energy and Mines<BR> Sant Prisca 223 y 215<BR> Quito, Ecuador.<P>

For more information, contact:<BR> Rainforest Action Network<BR> 450 Sansome St.,Suite 700<BR> San Francisco, CA 94111<BR> (415) 398-4404.

<HR>

