<TITLE>EIJ Winter 94: Organic Farmers VS. Malathion</TITLE>
<H1>Organic Farmers VS. Malathion<I>by John Sterling</I></H1>

<HR> Earth Island Journal.<BR> Winter 94<BR> Vol. 10 Issue 1<BR> p20 <HR>

Last October, as the California Department 
of Food and Agriculture (CDFA) began its 
annual ritual of aerial spraying to eradicate 
the Mediterranean fruit fly from Southern 
California, environmentalists renewed the 
call for an end to the spraying program, 
claiming that it discriminates against organic 
farmers and that it does not work.<P>

	Spraying of the pesticide malathion began 
in Ventura County after more than 60 
pregnant "medflies" were found, signaling 
a threat to the region's citrus and avocado 
crops. There are at least two organic farms 
inside the spraying area. Under the California 
Organic Foods Act, any farm contaminated 
with synthetic chemicals could 
lose its organic certification for three years.<P>

 "We have no recourse against the spraying," 
said Mary Ann Carpenter, one of the 
affected farmers. "It's our misfortune that 
we farm in a designated spray zone."<P>

	Malathion, a product of the Swiss chemical 
giant, Ciba-Geigy, Ltd., can damage 
both the immune and nervous systems. A 
1991 California Department of Health Services 
report claimed that people exposed to 
malathion were more susceptible to infectious 
diseases such as pneumonia. The EPA 
is concerned that malathion may cause 
permanent eye damage. A Los Angeles 
couple is suing the state, claiming that their 
son was blinded in 1990 after being exposed 
to the pesticide.<P>

Because CDFA has ruled the medfly an 
agricultural emergency, the expense of the 
spraying program is borne by state and 
federal funds, not by the program's primary 
beneficiary -- the agribusiness industry. 
Emergency reactions are notoriously 
expensive and rarely result in lasting 
solutions, noted Pesticide Watch, 
a San Francisco-based environmental organization.<P>

	Medflies have been found in the state
 every year since 1986. Pesticide Watch said 
that the state sprayed the LA basin 153 
times in 1989-90, dumping a total of 509,583 
pounds of the pesticide. Two medflies were 
found one week after the CDFA declared 
that the flies had been eradicated.<P>

"Malathion is not a selective pesticide," said Michael Abelman, an organic
farmer in Goleta. "It may also kill some of the many beneficial insects that
[organic farmers] depend on." Malathion is known to kill ladybugs, which
control aphids.<P>

	California spent roughly $63 million on 
aerial spraying in 1990, while committing 
only $750,000 to non-chemical alternatives. 
Both Abelman and Pesticide Watch 
advocate shifting funds from aerial spraying 
to alternative eradication strategies that 
emphasize biological controls, such as the 
release of predatory insects and sterile medflies.<P>

Pesticide Watch director Joan Clayburgh 
contends that alternatives will be developed 
only after the medfly is declared "established" 
in California, thus stripping its presence of 
emergency status. Without emergency 
funds, agribusiness would have to develop 
less expensive and longer-term solutions.<P>

Non-organic farmers, and state and federal 
politicians, oppose listing the medfly 
as "established" because they fear an embargo 
of US crops by Japan and other Asian 
countries.<P>

The US accepts produce from medfly-host 
countries and Clayburgh believes that 
there is no reason the Asian countries could 
not do the same.<P>

"It's an attitude problem more than an 
insect problem," said Abelman. "We need 
to take a more holistic approach to farming; 
one that preserves organic balance."<P>



<H2>What You Can Do</H2> For more information contact:<P>
Pesticide Watch<BR>116 New Montgomery St., Suite 530<BR> San Francisco, CA
94105<BR>(415)543-2627<P>

<HR>

