<TITLE>EIJ Winter 94: Ban the Boats!</TITLE>
<H1>Ban the Boats! <I>by Justin Lowe and Gar Smith</I></H1>
<HR> Earth Island Journal.<BR> Winter 94<BR> Vol. 10 Issue 1<BR> p15
<HR>
In his 1994 book, <I>Polluting for Pleasure</I>,a sailboat 
builder Andre Mele makes a persuasive argument 
for the elimination of motorized boating. According to Mele, oil-burning pleasure boats in
the US create "nearly as much atmospheric 
pollution as all of our automobiles and spill 15 
times more oil into our waters than the <I>Exxon 
Valdez</I> -- every year." Mele's book not only
exposes an overlooked environmental culprit, 
it also devotes some practical solutions -- low-resistance 
boats, clean-fuel alternatives 
(including electric and solar-powered boats) and 
strategies to "take back the waterways."<P>

In October, the Environmental Protection 
Agency announced plans to  require 
outboard-motor manufacturers to modify their engines to 
reduce emissions. Outboards represent approximately 
half of all marine engines sold annually
and can release as much uncombusted, 
smog-producing hydrocarbons in an hour as a car 
equipped with emissions-control devices produces 
in 40 hours. The EPA estimates that 
outboards account for three percent of all 
hydrocarbon and nitrous oxide emissions released 
nationwide. The new regulations will be phased 
in between 1998 and 2006.

<HR>

<I>Copyright 1995, Earth Island Journal. Articles may be freely reprinted with
prior permission. Please credit </I><B>Earth Island Journal</B><I> and send
samples.</I><P>


