<TITLE>Ocean Alert Fall 1995: The Norwegian Whaling Scandal</TITLE>

<H1>The Norwegian Whaling Scandal</H1>


For the past three years, the Norwegian government has claimed that there are more than 
86,700 minke whales in the Northeastern Atlantic Ocean and that a kill quota of 301 per 
year is scientifically justifiable. 
<P>

Meanwhile, Earth Island Institute and a spate of other environmental organizations have 
disputed Norwegian estimates and called on Norway to abide by the global commercial 
whaling ban. Members of the International Whaling Commission (IWC) also questioned 
these whale population estimates because all research and calculations were done by 
Norwegian officials without any review from outside scientists.
<P>

Despite strong public opposition worldwide, Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Brundtland held 
fast to the high estimates and sent out the whalers. For two years, Norwegian whalers have 
killed whales in violation of the global moratorium. And, because the Norwegian whale kill 
was considered "science-based," the Clinton Administration chose not to impose trade 
sanctions on Norway for conducting its outlaw whaling.
<P>

Now, startling new evidence has surfaced that Norway's whale population estimates have, 
in fact, been grossly exaggerated and that its formulas for calculating populations contain 
numerous errors. A special meeting of the IWC's Scientific Committee recently examined the 
data, and even Norway's own scientists have been forced to admit the errors.
<P>

As a result, Norway's whaling program is in disarray. In April, the Norwegian government 
reduced its estimate of the minke population by more than 20 percent, to 69,600. Further 
review may show that even this estimate is far too high. The Fisheries Ministry has also 
reduced this year's whale kill quota from 301 to 232. Lars Walloe, head of Norway's Whale 
Research Program, told Reuters that the error is "a bit embarrassing."
<P>

The repercussions go much further. Norwegian whalers now say that unless they receive full 
financial compensation of $8,500 (1,565 kroner) per whale for the reduction in the planned 
quota, they will kill all 301 whales, in defiance of both the IWC ban and the Norwegian 
government limits. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="whlmeat.gif" ALIGN=Right 
VSPACE=10 
HSPACE=10>

The whalers are also becoming increasingly frustrated with their inability to export whale 
products. Demand for whale meat in Norway is dropping, and there is pressure to resume the 
export of whale meat and blubber to Japan, where the prices paid are far higher. The 
Norwegian government has blocked the sale of 300 tons of whale blubber -- which now sit 
frozen in storage at processing plants. Steiner Bastensen, leader of Norway's whaling 
association, is pushing to have the whale kill quotas raised to 1980 levels of 1,800 per year. 
<P>

These will be hot topics at the June IWC meetings in Dublin, Ireland, during which member 
nations will pressure Norway to stop its outlaw whaling and abide by the international 
whaling ban. 
<P>

Norway's fraudulent minke whale-population estimates also provide ample justification for 
the Clinton Administration to impose sanctions against Norway. Under US law, the president 
can embargo products from countries violating international treaties. Such sanctions could 
cost Norway up to $100 million per year in lost revenues. By taking this action, the US 
would send a strong signal that countries must honor their obligations to international 
agreements. If Norway is permitted to violate the commercial whaling ban and base its 
catch on inaccurate whale-population data, there will be little to prevent Japan, Iceland, 
and a host of other countries from doing the same. This precedent could cause the entire 
IWC moratorium to crumble.
<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="oasf95.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">Ocean Alert - Summer/Fall 1995</A>.<P>

