<TITLE>Ocean Alert Fall 1995: Keiko to Move to Oregon</TITLE>

<H1>Keiko to Move to Oregon</H1>

Finally there is some good news for Keiko!  After nearly a year of planning, Keiko, the orca 
that played Willy in Warner Bros.' hit film, Free Willy, is being prepared to move to a new 
home. President of the newly formed Free Willy Foundation, Dave Phillips, said, "The pieces 
are coming together for the historic relocation, rehabilitation, and possible release of Keiko."
<P>

In 1994, Lauren Shuler-Donner, the producer of Free Willy, asked us to help create a plan 
to move Keiko to a better facility. About 16 years old, Keiko has been living in captivity for 
14 years and performing in marine parks. He now lives at Reino Aventura, a marine park in 
Mexico City in facilities that are too small. Keiko is nearly 20-feet long, weighs about 7,000 
pounds, and has a skin condition called papilloma that needs treatment. His teeth have also 
been worn down from years of gnawing at the side of his tank, and he needs to be in colder, 
natural sea water. People from around the world have demanded that Keiko be moved to a 
better home and eventually returned to the wild.
<P>

<IMG SRC="frepic3.gif" ALIGN=Left 
VSPACE=10 
HSPACE=10>

After an intense search, a site was selected at the Oregon Coast Aquarium in Newport, OR. 
The new center will be a state-of-the-art, deep-water pool 150-feet long, 75-feet wide, and 
25-feet deep filled with two million gallons of cold sea water pumped from adjoining Yaquina 
Bay. The water quality will be regulated by sophisticated sand filters and an ozone filtration 
system to ensure that it is always clean. In addition, there will be underwater viewing 
windows and a "rubbing beach." Keiko will be fed 300 pounds of restaurant-quality fish 
daily, frozen to destroy parasites and supplemented with vitamins. Dr. Lanny Cornell, a 
veterinarian with extensive experience treating orcas, will direct Keiko's medical care and 
supervise his rehabilitation. Also, two of Keiko's trainers from Reino Aventura will stay with 
him for several months to make his transition easier, and the professional staff at the Oregon 
Coast Aquarium will ensure that he has first-rate care. Currently under construction, the 
facility is scheduled to be finished in December 1995, and Keiko will be moved shortly 
thereafter.
<P>

Never before has a captive orca been returned to the ocean. While people are optimistic, 
Keiko has many obstacles to overcome before he can survive in the wild. In addition to his 
health problems, Keiko must relearn behaviors of wild orcas. He must learn to hunt for his 
own food and interact with other orcas. Said Dr. Cornell, "We won't really know if we can 
retrain Keiko to live in the wild until he is in the new facility, and we get a chance to better 
evaluate his health. But, a strong, male orca of his age should have an excellent chance to 
survive in the wild."
<P>

Once at the new facility, Keiko will never perform for the public. The center is designed 
solely to rescue, rehabilitate, and release marine mammals. It is expected to help not only 
Keiko, but a number of other dolphins and whales over the years.
<P>

The project has been made possible by sponsorship from Warner Bros., the Craig McCaw 
Foundation, Earth Island Institute, the Humane Society of the US, and the Oregon Coast 
Aquarium. Nevertheless, it  is a huge task and an additional $3 million must still be raised. 
The response from the public has been overwhelming, with people sending in donations to 
the Free Willy Foundation. The Foundation greatly appreciates people's support.
<P>

A special Keiko Adoption Kit has been prepared so people can get involved. Said Phillips, 
"Our work to help Keiko is far from over, and he faces a long road before he can rejoin his 
family. I know that it can be done and am optimistic about his future." 
<BR>

<A HREF="oasf95.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">Ocean Alert - Summer/Fall 1995</A>.<P>

