<TITLE>Ocean Alert Fall 1995: The Dolphin-Safe Tuna Anniversary</TITLE>

<H1>The Dolphin-Safe Tuna Anniversary</H1>

<B>A Personal Perspective of Five Years of International Tuna Monitoring<BR>
by Director Brenda Killian</B>
<P>

<IMG SRC="brenda.gif" ALIGN=Right 
VSPACE=10 
HSPACE=10>

I will never forget that day -- April 12, 1990. H.J. Heinz Co., the parent company of StarKist 
Seafood, announced that it would become "dolphin-safe." After years of campaigning to 
stop the drowning of dolphins in tuna nets, we had finally reached victory. Support from 
hundreds of thousands of people who wrote letters, boycotted canned tuna, and staged 
demonstrations in front of tuna companies had paid off.
<P>

Amid the celebration, champagne flowed and staff cheered, grateful that Heinz had decided 
to take the lead in putting an end to the dolphin slaughter. Within hours of StarKist's 
announcement, the other two major canned-tuna companies, Chicken of the Sea and 
Bumble Bee Seafoods, announced that they, too, would become dolphin-safe. Documenting 
this momentous decision, the news media responded with headlines and newscasts.
<P>

That night, I went home filled with gratitude. For years, I had wanted to help stop the killing 
of dolphins by tuna fishers. Yet, after the announcement, I knew that our job was far from 
over. We had to ensure that the tuna companies were not just becoming dolphin-safe to 
escape the canned-tuna boycott but were actually committed to ending the killing of marine 
mammals.
<P>

Within months of the StarKist announcement, we convinced the US Congress to implement 
legislation defining dolphin-safe tuna and outlining labeling requirements. More and more 
companies were declaring their tuna dolphin-safe, yet there was no enforcement in place to 
ensure that tuna labeled dolphin-safe was not caught in driftnets or by setting nets on 
dolphins.
<P>

I began research on the sources of the massive amounts of tuna coming into the US. In late 
1990, I conducted the first investigation of the largest tuna exporting nation -- <A HREF="../gsc/thai.html">Thailand</A>. I 
discovered that most of the canneries were purchasing and processing tuna caught by 
driftnets, and some had also purchased tuna caught by setting nets on dolphins. As the 
pressure from US customers increased, the majority of the Thai tuna canneries ceased 
purchasing driftnet-caught tuna and  indicated to us an interest in establishing dolphin-safe 
policies.
<P>

We had to be on guard against companies misrepresenting tuna as dolphin-safe. This meant 
placing observers at tuna-loading sites, in processing factories and warehouses, and even 
aboard some vessels. To accomplish this, the International Monitoring Program (IMP) was 
created in September, 1990. In the ensuing five years, the program has expanded greatly. 
There are currently more than 25 monitors inspecting tuna facilities on every continent and 
on board a sampling of vessels operating in all of the world's oceans.
<P>

Tuna companies in countries that once relied on tuna caught with dolphin-unsafe fishing 
methods, such as Italy, Spain, Taiwan, Ecuador, and <A HREF="../gsc/costa.html">Costa Rica</A>, have been convinced to 
implement dolphin-safe policies. IMP monitors are given unrestricted access to all areas of 
production and all purchase records to ensure compliance with dolphin-safe policies.
<P>

A whole host of new dolphin-safe canneries has been a key part of the 96-percent decrease 
in dolphin mortality in the past five years. More tuna vessels are switching to methods that 
do not involve the intentional chasing and setting of nets on dolphins. Long-held attitudes 
of tuna fishers and tuna-company representatives have also changed. There is a greater 
interest in fishing techniques to ensure that dolphins are not harmed and that the marine 
environment is sustained. Many tuna-company officials who previously had refused entry to 
their companies now invite IMP monitors to inspect their operations.
<P>

But the work is not over. We will not be satisfied until all dolphin-unsafe markets are closed. 
And, unfortunately, there are many other serious threats to dolphins and the marine 
ecosystem, including  human encroachment, pollution, over-fishing, and direct hunts of 
dolphins and whales. Without question, the past five years have shown that positive 
changes can be made and the future for dolphins is brighter. Thanks to the support and 
hard work of people around the world who think the slaughter of dolphins is too high a price 
to pay for a tuna  sandwich, we have come a long way. Together we will continue this fight 
to protect dolphins.
<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="oasf95.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">Ocean Alert - Summer/Fall 1995</A>.<P>

