<TITLE>Ocean Alert Fall 1995: Saving Seals in San Francisco Bay</TITLE>

<H1>Saving Seals in San Francisco Bay</H1>

<B>Dianne Kopec Directs a New Initiative</B>
<P>

Seals, sea lions, and sea otters were once found in great numbers within the fertile estuary 
of San Francisco Bay. Yet, in the 1800s, the European fur market decimated seal 
populations along the west coast of North America. Seal populations dwindled and breeding 
areas were abandoned. By 1900, the harbor seal (Phoca vitulina) was the only marine 
mammal with a resident breeding population in San Francisco Bay. 
<P>

<IMG SRC="seals.gif" ALIGN=Left 
VSPACE=5 
HSPACE=5>

After the 1972 Marine Mammal Protection Act prohibited direct killing of harbor seals, their 
populations increased along the California coast. But, the San Francisco Bay harbor seal 
populations did not change. 
<P>

Evidence suggested that high accumulations of toxic pollutants in the Bay were affecting 
seal populations. These were the same contaminants that had been linked to severe 
reproductive declines and disease in the seal population along Europe's northern coast. In 
the summer of 1988, more than 16,000 harbor seals died from a virus that spread along the 
North Sea shores.  Recent studies have shown that the pinniped immune system, like that of 
other mammals, is damaged by toxic pollutants, reducing the ability to fight off disease.
<P>

In 1989, Dianne Kopec, in collaboration with Dr. James T. Harvey at Moss Landing Marine 
Laboratories, began a wide-ranging study of the bay's resident harbor seal population. 
During the four-year study, Kopec and Harvey  made regular counts and observations at the 
primary "haul-out" sites in the bay, where seals congregate on rocks. The biologists drew 
blood samples from wild seals for pollutant and health analyses and created the first picture 
of contamination in a wide sampling of the bay seal population. Scat was collected from the 
haul-out sites and analyzed to determine the seals' prey. Photo-identification and 
radiotelemetry methods were used to monitor the seals' daily and seasonal movements and 
to locate preferred feeding areas within the vast bay.
<P>

The results of the study will be released this summer. The report documents the seal status 
and their accumulated load of toxic pollutants. As a new member of the Earth Island 
Institute staff, Kopec will use the findings as the basis for further seal population work and 
to develop a campaign to inform the public and policy makers on how to protect the last 
resident marine mammal in San Francisco Bay.
<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="oasf95.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">Ocean Alert - Summer/Fall 1995</A>.<P>

