<TITLE>Ocean Alert Fall 1995: Whales Alive Project Report</TITLE>

<H1>Whales Alive Project Report</H1>

Whales alive, an initiative of the International Marine Mammal Project, hosted nearly 20,000 
visitors during the 1995 humpback whale migration through Hawai'ian waters, including 
6,000 enthusiastic Japanese whale-watchers. Whales Alive's efforts to promote a better 
understanding of cetaceans is helping change Japan's whaling policy.
<P>

Meanwhile, controversy continues to rage about the newly designated Hawai'ian Islands 
Humpback Whale National Marine Sanctuary. Established under federal law in 1992, the 
sanctuary needs approval from Hawai'ian Governor Ben Cayetano to operate in state 
waters. And, a well-financed misinformation campaign against the sanctuary is being 
orchestrated by thrill-craft operators and harbor developers. As a result, many people have 
been confused. To show support for the sanctuary, the January 1995 Whales Alive 
Conference featured presentations by sanctuary staff and began a petition drive.  
<P>

The Fourth Annual Whales Alive Conference is scheduled for January 24 to 28, 1996 at 
Wailea, Maui.
<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="oasf95.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">Ocean Alert - Summer/Fall 1995</A>.<P>

