<TITLE>Answering Your Questions About Keiko</TITLE>

<IMG SRC="fw-keiko.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>

<H1>Answering Your Questions About Keiko</H1>
<I>Last updated November 27, 1996</I>

<H2><B>Q.</B> How has Keiko adapted to his new facility?</H2>

<B>A.</B> Keiko has made great strides at the Oregon Coast Aquarium. He is far
more active, very attentive, and spends considerable time exploring his new tank.<P>

January 7, 1997 will mark the first anniversary of Keiko's relocation to our
new center in Oregon. <P>

<H2><B>Q.</B> I heard he was skinny. How is his appetite now? What does he eat?</H2>

<B>A.</B> Keiko's health continues to dramatically improve.  His weight has
increased by more than one thousand pounds. Keiko is eating approximately 200
pounds of fish per day.<P>

Efforts are just beginning in the experiment to re-teach Keiko to catch live
fish.  In the months ahead this work will continue.  It has been many years
since Keiko ate live fish, but this is an important part of his ongoing
rehabilitation.<P>

He eats a great variety of fish, including salmon, sardines,
herring and squid.
<P>

<H2><B>Q.</B> How long will Keiko be at the Oregon Coast Aquarium?</H2>

<BR CLEAR=ALL><IMG SRC="iceland.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>

<B>A.</B> We remain very optimistic about the chances of bringing Keiko back to full
health, and re-introducting him back to his native habitat in Iceland.<P>

Keiko has been in captivity for fourteen of
the seventeen years of his life. Though we've made great strides in his weight, muscle tone
and skin condition, there are still some hurdles to overcome.<P>

He will need to learn various skills necessary
for surviving in the wild. We expect this to take one to two years. Luckily,
Keiko is now in what we feel is the best marine mammal rehabilitation center in
the world, with the finest veterinary care and water quality available. We'll
keep you posted on his progress.<P>

<H2><B>Q.</B> How is Keiko's skin condition?</H2>

<B>A.</B> His papilloma skin condition is almost entirely
resolved.  Intensive veterinary work continues toward his rehabilitation.
Curing Keiko's
skin condition has been one of the most important tasks.<P>

Keiko's skin condition, called papilloma, causes the areas around his
pectoral fins and tail to become raised and cracked. The
extremely cold, high quality natural sea water coupled with state-of-the-art
ozone water treatment will provide the best chance for curing the papilloma. 
Although it is still much too early to predict a recovery, some of the affected
parts around Keiko's tail and fins already show some improvement. <P>

<BR CLEAR=ALL><IMG SRC="fw-oregon.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=283 HEIGHT=198>

<H2><B>Q.</B> What kind of activities does Keiko take part in?</H2>
 
<I>The photo to the right was shot with a "fish-eye" (extreme wide-angle) lens.</I><P>

<B>A.</B> He is very active,
and staff at the Aquarium are working with him on a variety of mental
stimulation techniques such as shape recognition, and hunting techniques.<P>

Wild orcas often swim 50 to 100 miles a day in the wild. In order to
strengthen his body for long-distance swimming, Keiko needs plenty of exercise.
New exercises and training practices are being employed to develop his muscles
and encourage fast swimming.<P>

Wild orcas often lift the front halves of their
bodies above water in order to spot food and investigate their surroundings.
Keiko will also be encouraged to begin this behavior, called "spyhopping."<BR><BR CLEAR=ALL>

<IMG SRC="aquar.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>

<H2><B>Q.</B> Will Keiko get a companion for his tank?</H2>

<B>A.</B> Orcas are, by nature, very social animals with strong family bonds. 
For years, Keiko shared his tank at Reino Aventura with bottlenose dolphins.
However, the water temperature in Keiko's new pool is too cold for bottlenose
dolphins. We are investigating the possibility of bringing in other marine
mammals. A stranded or captive cold-water dolphin, such as a pacific whitesided
dolphin, would be a good candidate. The new facility was built with enough room
to rehabilitate several stranded dolphins and whales at the same time.<P>

<H2><B>Q.</B> Can people visit Keiko?</H2>

<B>A.</B> Yes. Though his days as a performing orca are over, Keiko is observable
 from a below-water-level viewing area at:<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>Oregon Coast Aquarium<BR> 
2820 SE Ferry Slipp Rd.<BR>
Newport, OR 97365<BR>
(503) 867-3474</BLOCKQUOTE>

<IMG SRC="fw-waves.gif"  WIDTH=552 HEIGHT=60><BR>
              
<BR>

<A HREF="keiko.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif"></A>Go back to <A HREF="keiko.html">Free Willy News</A> table of contents.<P>

<A HREF="immp.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif"></A>Go to <A HREF="immp.html">IMMP</A> table of contents.<P>

