<TITLE>Keiko's Incredible Voyage</TITLE>

<H1>Keiko's Incredible Voyage</H1>

<H2>Successful Move To Oregon Coast Aquarium</H2>

<IMG SRC="fw-hoist.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=331 HEIGHT=232>

In the early morning hours of January 7th, the world's most famous orca whale and
star of the movie <I>Free Willy</I> began the long and historic journey from
Mexico City to Newport, Oregon.<P>
  
After more than two years of planning, the Free Willy - Keiko Foundation brought
together a team of top veterinarians, Reino Aventura staff, and crane, truck, and
airplane operators to oversee the complicated task of successfully moving a
nearly four-ton whale.  Emotions were running high.  More than 27,000 people
silently filed by Keiko's pool in Mexico to say their last good-byes to the whale
they had known and loved for eleven years.<P>
  
At midnight, the maneuvers began.  Directed by Dr. Solarzano and Dr. Cornell, the
veterinary team coaxed Keiko into the sling.  The months of practice, combined
with Keiko's calm disposition, made a big difference.  It was an eerie scene, lit
by powerful floodlights, as the crane lifted Keiko into the water-filled
transport box.<P>
  
Even at two o'clock in the morning, tens of thousands of Keiko fans lined the
processional route from Reino Aventura to the airport to wish Keiko good luck and
"adios."  Free Willy Foundation director David Phillips called it "the most
amazing outpouring of love for an animal ever.  That made it all the more
important that we do the job right."<P>
  
<BR CLEAR=ALL><IMG SRC="fw-express.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=357 HEIGHT=245>

Awaiting Keiko at the Mexico City airport were a C-130 Hercules cargo plane,
donated for the trip by United Parcel Service, and a chase jet arranged by the
Discovery Channel, the producers of the upcoming television documentary on
Keiko's story.  By daybreak, Keiko and the twelve person transport team were
aloft for the nearly three- thousand- mile trip.<P>

Throughout the flights, Keiko was carefully monitored.  Lanolin cream was rubbed
onto his back to prevent drying and cracking.  Drs. Cornell and Solarzano, who
have transported many whales and dolphins, agreed that Keiko traveled extremely
well and remained very calm.<P>

Keiko headed to the new rescue and rehabilitation center at the Oregon Coast
Aquarium, built by the Free Willy - Keiko Foundation.  Contractors worked
virtually around the clock to have the state-of-the-art 2.2-million-gallon pool
ready.  Private donations from thousands of individuals and school classes,
combined with generous grants from the Craig and Wendy McCaw Foundation, Warner
Bros., New Regency Productions, and the Humane Society of the US made the
facility's completion possible.  In contrast to Keiko's pool at the marine park,
the new center features four times more swimming area, acoustically varied
surfaces, inlets and water jets for creating in-tank currents, better temperature
control, and the most advanced ozone treatment and filtration systems available. 
After final adjustments of the pool's water temperature, salinity, and filtration
systems, everything was ready for Keiko.<P>

After flying nearly eighteen hours and braving rain and low cloud ceilings, the
C-130 finally touched down in Newport.  There to greet Keiko were throngs of
media and a big crowd of children holding "Welcome to Oregon" and "We love Keiko"
signs.<P>

<BR CLEAR=ALL><IMG SRC="sling.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>

Now all that was necessary was the twenty minute truck ride to the aquarium and
the final step of lifting Keiko into the new pool.  Rows of satellite trucks
broadcast live as the world watched to see how Keiko would fare.  As he was
hoisted forty feet in the air and carefully lowered into the water, the crowd
cheered and cameras flashed.  Keiko pushed free of his sling, immediately took a
deep dive, and swam several laps of the pool.  Within a half hour, he was
exploring, vocalizing, and eating fish. There was a huge collective sigh of
relief.  Keiko had made it.   Phyllis Bell, President of the Aquarium, stated: 
"We mounted a round-the-clock watch on Keiko for the first three days, but after
just 24 hours it was clear that he was settling in well."  Karla and Renata,
Keiko's trainers from Mexico, relayed the word:  "He's doing great!" <P>
 
Even with this crucial step taken, the Free Willy - Keiko Foundation's work is
still in full swing.  Now the task is to bring Keiko back to full health.  He
needs to gain more than two thousand pounds, and things are off to a very good
start.  His food consumption has risen to 245 pounds per day, 100 pounds per day
more than he was eating in Mexico.  Current priorities are to cure his skin
condition and build up his muscle tone.  All this is in anticipation and hope
that Keiko may be able to be returned to his native waters and family off the
coast of Iceland.  We'll keep you posted on Keiko's progress.<P>

<IMG SRC="fw-waves.gif"  WIDTH=552 HEIGHT=60><BR>
              
<BR>

<A HREF="keiko.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif"></A>Go back to <A HREF="keiko.html">Free Willy News</A> table of contents.<P>

