<TITLE>Support for Keiko Soars</TITLE>

<H1>Support for Keiko Soars</H1>

<IMG SRC="fw-kids.gif"  WIDTH=236 HEIGHT=165 ALIGN=RIGHT>

The Free Willy - Keiko Foundation is grateful to the tens of thousands of people
who have contributed to our efforts to move Keiko to the Oregon Coast Aquarium
and begin his rehabilitation. The creativity and commitment schools and other
organizations have demonstrated in raising money for the cause are impressive.
According to Foundation spokesperson Mark Berman, "Children from all across the
country have amazed us, sending anything from a few cents up to a school project
generating $31,000." Three elementary schools are among the outstanding examples
of devotion to Keiko's well-being.<P>

In 1993, Jean Jakob's third grade class at Northwest Elementary in Tampa, Florida
began working to raise money for Keiko's relocation and release. Upon realizing
that, unlike his Free Willy character, Keiko was still in captivity, the entire
school signed on to the effort to help him. Through bake sales, door-to-door
canvassing, and "dollars for Keiko" collections, Jakob and the schoolchildren
raised over $30,000, which they presented to the Foundation in late 1995. In
January, a Tampa television station, WTVT, flew Ms. Jakob, two students, and two
parents to Newport, Oregon where they received a behind-the-scenes tour and had
the opportunity to wish Keiko well on behalf of their community.<P>

<BR CLEAR=ALL><IMG SRC="in-aqu.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>

In Kodiak, Alaska, near the cold waters where other orcas like Keiko live,
Peterson Elementary School hosted a penny drive to relocate Keiko. Students
placed a Free Willy penny jar in the hallway of the school for fifteen minutes
each morning for approximately one month and spent hours collecting and wrapping
the pennies. Organized by Peterson's student council, the penny drive set and met
a goal of raising 30,000 pennies, for a total of a $3000 donation towards Keiko's
rehabilitation.<P>

Close to Keiko's current home at the Oregon Coast Aquarium, students at Sam Case
Elementary School in Newport, Oregon recently raised $4500 by sending fundraising
letters, selling buttons, and holding a penny drive, and a raffle. Students from
eighteen primary and secondary schools in the Salem/ Keizer School District in
Oregon have also raised more than $4000. Students from the West Chester Area
School District in Pennsylvania, sponsored by environmental education teacher
Elizabeth Anderson, sold T-shirts and raised tips by working at a local
restaurant to donate $1000 for Keiko's rehabilitation.<P>
 
The initiative demonstrated by students throughout the country testifies to
children's concern for protecting wildlife and demonstrates their ability to make
a difference. Please write to us for more information about what you and your
school group can do to get involved!<P>

<IMG SRC="fw-waves.gif"  WIDTH=552 HEIGHT=60><BR>
              
<BR>

