<TITLE>What You Can Do to Help Whales and Dolphins</TITLE>

<H1>What You Can Do</H1>

<IMG SRC="fw-window.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=245 HEIGHT=358>

<H2>How You Can Help Whales and Dolphins</H2>

Keiko's hoped-for return to the wild raises the question of how safe the oceans
are for wild whales. Whales are still in danger from <A HREF="../bw/bw.html">marine pollution</A>, oil
spills, ozone depletion that affects phytoplankton growth, and, once again,
commercial whaling. In 1986, the International Whaling Commission banned all
commercial killing of whales. In 1992, Norway began killing minke whales in
defiance of this ban and Japan continues to kill whales by claiming that it is
for scientific research purposes. Now that Norway has broken the agreement,
Iceland is also pursuing plans to resume commercial whaling.<p>

Information from Earth Island's International Marine Mammal Project concerning commercial killing of whales:
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org/immp/mmumay.html#Whale">Whale Hunting Season Begins in Norway</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org/immp/warwhales.html">Norway, Japan, and Iceland Accelerate War on Whales</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org/immp/whlclaim.html">IMMP responds to Norwegian whaling claims</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org/immp/immp3.html">Norway's Rampant Whale Slaughter</A>
<LI><A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org/immp/s96-1c.html#Update">Update from the IWC</A>
</UL>


Your letters can
make a difference. Write to:<P>


<UL>

<LI>Ambassador Kjeld Vibe<BR>	 
Norwegian Embassy<BR>
2720 34th Steet, NW<BR>
Washington, DC 20008<P>

<LI>Ambassador Kunihiko Saitou<BR>
Japanese Embassy<BR>
2520 Mass. Ave, NW<BR>
Washington, DC 20008

</UL>

Economic pressure can create powerful leverage for policy change. Urge Vice
President Al Gore to ensure that the Clinton Adminstration not only maintain
strong support for the IWC commercial whaling moratorium, but that it also impose
tough sanctions against any countries violating the international whale killing
ban.<P>
 
<UL>                          

<LI>Vice President Al Gore<BR>
Old Executive Office Bldg.<BR>
Washington, DC 20500

</UL>

<h2>U.S. dolphin protection legislation</H2>

<IMG SRC="rep-vw.gif"  WIDTH=333 HEIGHT=207><P>

<A HREF="http://www.earthisland.org/immp/ddstop.html">U.S. dolphin protection legislation</A> and the
embargo against tuna from countries whose tuna fishing methods are not
dolphin-safe have spared the lives of hundreds of thousands of dolphins.
Eastern spinner and northeastern spotted dolphin populations are still severely
depleted because of the deadly practices of the dolphin killing fleets. Even
so, a number of tuna fishing countries claim that the U.S. regulations
requiring that tuna be caught without setting of nets upon dolphins are too
strict.<P>

<IMG SRC="payne.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT  WIDTH=260 HEIGHT=305 VSPACE=2 HSPACE=2>
"More than 90% of the world's canned tuna markets are now 'dolphin safe',
according to figures from the United Nations," stated Phillips.  "The Mexican,
Venezuelan, and Colombian governments must realize that the technique of
setting nets on dolphins to catch tuna is cruel, unnecessary, and will never be
acceptable to the American public."<P>

Earth Island Institute announced the "Dolphin Death Act" has been stopped in
the U.S. Senate and will not become law. "These bills would have crippled
dolphin protection and misled millions of Americans," explained David Phillips,
Director of Earth Island Institute. "Thanks to the public outcry and to the
leadership of Senator Barbara Boxer (D-CA) and the bipartisan group of Senators
and House members, the dolphin-safe label is safe"<p>

We must stop Congress  from passing any "Dolphin Death Act" changing the
definition of dolphin-safe to again allow the chasing, capture, and entanglement
of dolphins. Many of  you have seen the horrific footage of dolphins being chased
and encircled in purse seine nets to catch the tuna beneath them. Even when
dolphins do not die in the nets, they are traumatized, and may suffer physical
injury from which they will later die, unobserved. <P>

Voting for the "Dolphin Death Act" were:  Jim Saxton (R-NJ), Don Young (R-AK),
W.J. (Billy) Tauzin (R-LA), Wayne Gilchrest (R-MD), Peter Torkildsen (R-MA),
Linda Smith (R-WA), Walter Jones (R-NC), Jack Metcalf (R-WA), James Longley
(R-ME), and Solomon Ortiz (D-TX).<P>

Voting NO were:  George Miller (D-CA), Gerry Studds (D-MA),  Sam Farr (D-CA),
Frank Pallone (D-NJ), Sam Gejdenson (D-CT), and Patrick Kennedy (D-RI).<P>

Please write to your representatives to urge that they oppose any change in the
definition of dolphin-safe and any weakening of dolphin protection in the name of
free trade:<P>                              

<UL>

<LI>Senator<BR>
Senate Office Bldg.<BR>
Washington, DC 20510<P>  

<LI>Representative<BR>
House Office Bldg.<BR>
Washington, DC 20515<P>

<LI>Capitol Switchboard:<BR>
(202) 224-3121

</UL>
              

<IMG SRC="fw-waves.gif"  WIDTH=552 HEIGHT=60><BR>
              
For more information contact:<BR>
International Marine Mammal Project<BR>
Earth Island Institute<BR>
300 Broadway, Suite 28<BR>
San Francisco, CA 94133<BR>
(415) 788-3666<P>
     
e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:marinemammal@igc.apc.org">marinemammal@earthisland.org</A><BR> 
