<TITLE>IMMP: Int'l Tuna Com. Fails to Reduce Dolphin Kill Quotas</TITLE>
<IMG SRC="immp1-ii.gif"><P>
<I>A dolphin and yellowfin tuna swim together</I><P>
<H1>International Tuna Commission Fails to Reduce Dolphin Kill Quotas</H1>
INTERNATIONAL MARINE MAMMAL PROJECT<P>

<I>The Winter/Spring 1995 Ocean Alert (formerly the Dolphin Alert) is an Earth Island Institute publication.</I><P>

At a meeting in La Jolla, CA in October 1994, the InterAmerican Tropical
Tuna Commission (IATTC) let stand the international tuna fleet's
dolphin kill level of 9,300 for 1995. The IATTC, an international
commission established to manage tuna populations, has come under
increased scrutiny recently over the tuna fishery's impact on
dolphins.<P>

EII Executive Director David Phillips called the IATTC move, "...a
total cop-out. At a time when the total dolphin kill has been less than
4,000 in each of the past two years, the fact that the IATTC has set a
kill quota of more than twice as high is absurd."<P>

The US delegation to the IATTC wanted a 1995 quota of 4,000 but was
rebuffed primarily by the delegation from Mexico, the largest remaining
dolphin-killing country. All commission decisions must be made by
consensus.<P>

Fortunately, the US tuna fleet adheres to a stronger domestic law, the
International Dolphin Conservation Act (IDCA), which severely limits
the US fleet's dolphin kill. The IDCA calls for a descending quota
eventually reaching zero by 1999 or earlier. Because the US fleet
killed 114 dolphins in 1994, the maximum allowed for 1995 is 113.
Regardless of the IATTC resolutions, the US fleet must comply with the
requirements of the stronger and more effective IDCA. To date, no US
tuna boats have applied to operate in the Eastern Tropical Pacific
Ocean (ETP) in 1995. This represents the first time since the late
1950s that no US tuna vessels are engaged in dolphin-unsafe fishing
techniques.<P>

Whether the international fleet will kill 9,300 dolphins this year is
unknown. Mexico, Venezuela, and Vanuatu continue to use dolphin-unsafe
fishing practices. Yet, of the 40 Mexican tuna purse seiners, 12 have
shown the ability to fish dolphin-safe. Our staff will continue to
press for an end to all encirclement of dolphins and for a reduction of
the IATTC quota to zero.<P>

<BR>

<A HREF="immpws95.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">Ocean Alert - Winter / Spring 1995</A>.<P>

