<H1>Pressing Environmental Issues at Baikal<BR>
What Price to Pay?</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal Currents- Pressing Environmental Issues at Baikal<BR>
What Price to Pay?</TITLE>

<H2>The Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill</H2>

 Those who are concerned about the fate of
Lake Baikal are aware of the problems related to this notorious mill, located
on the Lake's south shore.  A special inserted supplement  provides information
on this issue: chronicles the history of this issue, gives an update on recent
action at Baikalsk, and discusses prospects for the future.  Please see
supplement to learn about the latest developments in the movement to halt the
mill's damaging operations.<P>

<H2>The Level of the Lake</H2>

The change in the level of Lake Baikal has been one of the most serious
problems affecting the environmental well-being of the Baikal region.  The
issue of rising water levels in Baikal is one that has not been openly
discussed for a long time.  In 1994, for the first time, it was brought to the
public's attention by InterBaikal (an independent newspaper, published in
Irkutsk). <P>

The level of the lake was raised about one meter upon the completion of the
Irkutsk power dam in 1958.  Over 1,200 square kilometers of valuable
agricultural and wetlands were flooded. Even today, there is a constant process
of erosion causing the destruction of the lake shores, and threatening
railroads, highways, and harbors.<P>

By the end of the 1960s the omul-fish harvest dropped by up to 10-15 percent,
and the productive quality and weight of each fish dropped by a factor of two.
(Some scientists  regard this as evidence of the impact of the dam). No serious
studies have been done on the impact of this project.  Some are arguing for
raising level of the lake even more. <P>

Dr. A. Sukhodolov of the Research Institute of Regional Economics:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>"If raising the level of the lake even higher by another half meter would
translate into an increase of energy production by the entire Angara power
system (by as much as 1.6 billions kilowatt-hours), then this will result in
saving 1.4 million tons of fossil fuel annually.  It will reduce air emissions
from other power stations in the Irkutsk-Zima industrial region.. In theory it
is possible to restore the original level of the lake, but this will interfere
with the normal work of the Bratsk and Ust-Ilimsk power stations downstream,
and will badly influence the entire water-industrial complex on the Angara and
Yenisey Rivers... It would not be possible to guarantee low energy prices in
this case." </BLOCKQUOTE>

Leonid Bezrukov of the Institute of Geography, Irkutsk:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>"If achieving even higher Lake levels would be prohibited, this would hardly
have much influence on the normal work of the Irkutsk and even less so on the
other power stations of the Angara-Yenisey system.  And, to boot, it will
eliminate the necessity to spend billions and billions for bank reinforcement
works... First and foremost, serious analyses based on good science are
needed--this will allow us to measure with ruble figures all the plusses and
minuses.  What we need is the participation of resource economists, experts who
will provide economic assessment of the damage already done and project
potential costs versus benefits of each scenario."</BLOCKQUOTE>



<H2>Baikal Law</H2>

There have been plans to enact a Baikal Law at the federal level for several
years now.  (It was deemed most appropriate to do this at the national level
because the Baikal watershed encompasses three different states in the Russian
Federation; therefore a special law should be passed in Moscow to better
protect the lake as a whole.)<P>

At the beginning of this year, there were five different drafts of a proposed
Baikal Law in existence, each put forward by different factions.  The latest
draft, entitled "About the Protection of Lake Baikal" was offered on April 26, 
1995 by State Deputies of the Duma (Russian Parliament) Alexeev, Bosholov, and
Bratishev, among others.  This draft was accepted at a first reading, to be
followed by further readings.  In fact the Duma held special hearings in
Irkutsk on the first of June with 15 people attending from the State Duma.  At
this hearing there were many remarks and corrections made on the original
draft.  The main discussion centered around: <OL>

<LI>the role of a future Baikal Commission (its legal status, structure, and
jurisdiction);<P>

<LI>the future use of a Baikal Ecological Fund<P>

<LI>the reconstruction or closing
of ecologically dangerous enterprises around the lake, including the
prohibition of cellulose production on the shores of Baikal<P>

<LI> land use policies in the core zone.  

</OL>

A second reading of this draft was planned for Moscow  in July.  Perhaps
because there were so many corrections in this latest draft, the Duma decided
not to take the time to hear this latest draft of the Baikal Law.  There is
little hope that any version of the Baikal Law will be heard by the Duma 
before next summer.	<P>

<I>The information drawn from reports by Nelli Romanova and
Natasha Zhavoronkova of the environmental and public interest law  groups known
as EPRA and EcoJuris, located in Irkutsk and Moscow respectively.</I><P>


<H2>What Price to Pay?</H2>

The surplus of electric power generated by Irkutsk Hydropower System (which
includes Irkutsk, Bratsk, and Ust-Ilimsk Power Stations) is 15 billion kilowatt
per hour,  that is 3 times higher than the average annual power production of
the Irkutsk Power Station . <P>

The cost of reinforcing the shorelines in order to preserving the Old Baikal
Railroad against higher lake levels will amount to 140 billions rubles (or over
$30 million at 1995 rates).<P>

Residents of the northern towns of Nizhneangarsk and Severobaikalsk, where some
of corollary damage was greatest,  have been unsuccessfully trying to draw
attention to this problem. They have formed a group (Fedor Pilugin, Evgeny
Mariasov, and Pavel Nepomnyaschikh; e-mail: davan@glas.apc.org.  This group
appealed to the government of Buryatia. Their main concern is for Yarki Island
(a long sandy island at the far northern tip of Baikal), as well as for pasture
land around Severobaikalsk and Nizhneangarsk. They have requested that a
special <I>expertisa</I>  (or environmental impact assessment) be held to make
a decision on how to reduce the level of the lake. <P>

Lately,  the impact of the dam has  been showing itself in a more obvious way,
and has forced officials to pay more particular attention to this issue.  A
special commission to investigate the consequences of this situation was formed
recently in Buryatia. <P>

At the same time, a federal working team was formed (chaired by Mr. Mikheev,
the head of <I>Minvodkhos</I>  - Ministry on Water Issues and Management).<P>

<A HREF="supp95p-p.html">The Governmental Commission on Baikal</A> in it's October resolution made a
decision  to estimate the  impact of the fluctuation of the lake level, and to
ask the  Irkutsk Region to allocate funds for this study from it's Ecological
Fund

<H2>The Heavens Will Aid the Island of Yarki</H2>

by Albina Andreeva<BR>

special for Baikal Currents and InterBaikal<BR>

August 1995<P>

The gradual disappearance of the island of Yarki, located on the northern
extremity of Lake Baikal, is only a small part of the more complicated problem
of preventing catastrophic changes on the shores of lake Baikal caused by the
water backup from the Irkutsk Hydrosystem dam.  The negative consequences of
the artificial rise in the lake's water level are intensified by the repeated
forcing of the water level over the norm that was established in the planning
designs.<P>

According to the chairman of the Water Resources Committee of the Republic of
Buryatia, V. Molotov, "From 1980 to 1994, in violation of  existing laws, the
Irkutsk Power Engineering Center (Irkutsk Energo) didn't adhere to established
norms, as a result, the normal backup water level, established at the 457 meter
mark was exceeded no less than 10 times. And each centimeter in excess of this
level reflects meters of ruined area primarily on the eastern side.  On the
Irkutsk side the  problems are not so obvious and not as severe as in Buryatia.
<P>

A year ago representatives of the government of the Republic of Buryatia
intended to sign an agreement with the administration of the Irkutsk Oblast for
an increase in the normal backup water level (up to the 457.20 meter mark) in
exchange for a decrease in the tariffs on electricity supplied to Buryatia.  If
this decision had been implemented, it is possible Yarki Island would now only
be a memory.  <P>

Under the pressure of public opinion and realizing it had made a mistake, the
government revoked its decision and went further in a different direction,
changing its color somewhat green.  On the 7th of December, 1994, at the
meeting of the Governmental Commission on Baikal, the First Deputy Chairman of
the government of the Republic of Buryatia, M.A. Spasov informed about the
catastrophic events on the shores of Lake Baikal and called for preventive
measures.<P>

The most important among these measures is strict regulation of the water level
of Lake Baikal.  A working group was formed with the participation of the
representatives of the Administration of the Krasnoyarsk region, the Irkutsk
Oblast, the government of Buryatia, and also interested ministries and
departments. At the meeting of this group, which took place on the 28th of July
in Ulan-Ude, the parties agreed not to exceed the back- up water level,
established at the 457 meter mark.  A system of control over the rate of the
work of the Hydro Electric Station was also planned.  Should these agreements
be fulfilled, the further destruction and flooding of significant parts of the
shore zone, including the island of Yarki, will be prevented.<P>

However, everything is dependent upon money. At this point in Buryatia and
Irkutsk, there is no hope of raising this money except for profits from the
exploitation of hydro- resources. But it is still not certain when all the
necessary normative documents and working plans  will be worked out.  In the
meantime, trust must be placed in Her Majesty, Nature.  According to the
prognosis of scientists from the hydro-meteorological service, after 1995 a dry
period is expected with a subsequent decrease in the inflow of water to the
Lake.  Thus, it is possible that the water-horizon of the Siberian Sea will
fall to an acceptable level by natural methods. And this may cause problems of
an opposite character, no less and perhaps more severe and complicated.  Nature
does not like to be subjugated.<P>

<H2>The Boguchansk Power Station.</H2>

The completion of construction on the Boguchansk hydro-electric station (BoGES
is a Russian abbreviation) will have an immediate effect on the region known as
Nizhnee Priangarie (in the north-eastern part of the Irkutsk Oblast').<P>

BoGES represents the 4th step - i.e., it is the 4th hydro-power station--along
the Angara-Yenisey river system.  Construction started in 1976. The projected
capacity at BoGES will be 4,000 megawatts, although initially it will produce
some 3,000 megawatts. This project was started to help develop a complete
energy infrastructure for industrial activity on the western side of Baikal.  It is
also intended to provide for the growing demand for energy in all of eastern
Siberia, including the Irkutsk region.<P>

Construction site of this dam was selected in 1984 but was not confirmed with
the Baikal Bureau of Reclamation, or with the Fish and Game  Department.<P>

The Irkutsk Regional Government issued a resolution allocating 34,365 hectares
of land for the operation of the Boguchansk Power Station.  In August of 1989,
the Ust-Ilimsk county government issued a resolution which prohibited the
cutting of forests in that area which would be flooded for BoGES, at least
until the results of an official Environmental Impact Assessment (EIA) would be
known.  In 1992-1993, all work was stopped due to an EIA performed by the
Krasnoyarsk Regional Committee on Nature Protection.  The findings of this EIA
were negative, since the project is not in compliance with nature protection
laws.

<H2>A 208 meter dam would drown:</H2>

An EIA on the dam done by the Krasnoyarsk Science Center in 1993 indicated a
208 meter dam would drown:<UL>

<LI>107,400 hectares (268,500 acres) of land, of which 85,700 (214,250 acres) is
forested.<P>

<LI>2 million cubic meters of (timber) wood<P>

<LI>3,5 million tons of other, non-timber plant matter, such as plants and dead wood<P>

<LI>120 archeological sites (some dating back to 30-40 thousand B.C..)<P>

<LI>100 monuments of wooden architecture <P>

<LI>31 villages<P>

</UL>

What is more, the land that will be inundated contains the burial places of
many animals who died from Siberian anthrax!  In all, estimated damage from the
dam (for Nizhneilimsk County alone) will amount to 126 billion rubles (28
million dollars) annually, to be incurred for at least the next 100 years
(using January 1995 price levels).</I><P>

<H2>Citizens of Nizhneilimsk County's letter to Boris Yeltsyn</H2>

<I>A local group recently prepared a letter to the Russian government to inform
them of this issue and to seek support from other activists who understand the
problem and the probable impact of the Boguchansk Project.  Their letter
follows:</I><P>

To: President of the Russian Federation Boris Yeltsyn<P>

Prime-Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin<P>

On March 26 of 1994, Resolution #236--entitled "On the Completion of
Construction of the Boguchansk Power Station"-- was issued by the Russian
Federal Government. The decision to finish this project poses ecological
threats to a vast area, including the Ust-Ilimsk and Kezhemsk Counties in the
Irkutsk and Krasnoyarsk regions.  <P>

Up and down the Angara River a huge industrial complex of chemical, micro
biological, metallurgic, forestry, and cellulose enterprises is located. 
Wastes from all these enterprises are discharged into the Angara and its
artificial reservoirs.<P>

The construction of three reservoirs along the Angara has caused flooding of a
massive part of the Angara valley and adjacent lands.  This flooding was done
without any precaution to clear reservoir beds, nor to counter the decrease in
the river's ability for self purification.  What is more, there ... has been a marked increase in soil erosion and the destruction of the river
banks.  This has all resulted in a worsening of water quality in those
reservoirs that are used as a principal source of drinking water. <P>

(At present the quality of drinking water at the proposed site for the
Boguchanskaya power station is classified as "dirty" and "extremely dirty".)<P>

It is commonly recognized that many valley hydro stations are inexpedient,
since the damage caused by their construction is far greater than the resulting
economic benefits.  At present there are numerous examples of smaller hydro
stations, which are ecologically safe and, collectively, of greater
capacity.<P>

Governmental Resolution was not confirmed with the local administrations, which
is a violation of the Russian Constitution and contradicts the current laws on
nature protection.<P>

We appeal to you with a request to stop the enactment of Resolution #236, at
least until the results of an Ecological Impact Assessment are received by the
Russian Ministry of Nature Protection.<P>

Signed by citizens of Nizhneilimsk County.<P>

<HR>

A citizen organization called "Save the Angara" was formed in Ust-Ilimsk in
1994 (this group can be reached through the <A HREF="bcci.html">Baikal Center</A>, or, more directly,
at 665770 Ust-Ilimsk, P.O. Box 1326, tel: 51-438)  Also  Association for the
Rehabilitation of Angara-Yenisey, Krasnoyarsk Ecological Movement and Friends
of Siberian Forests are publicly opposing the completion of the BoGES
project.<P>

<HR>


