<H1>Environmental Activism</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal Currents- Environmental Activism</TITLE>

Environmental Activism in the Baikal Region is the principal program of the
<A HREF="bcci.html">Baikal Center For Ecological and Citizen Initiatives</A> for 1995. The aim
of this project  is  to widen the circle of "green" activists in the region by
helping them establish contacts both intra- and inter-regionally, providing
them with informational and organizational support, helping them with the
development and implementation of projects which improve the region's ecology,
and by promoting feelings of personal worth and significance among local
people. The work of the Center has been made possible with the support of
<I>Eurasia Foundation</I>. <P>

<H2>Preliminary Results on a Irkutsk Survey</H2>

A Survey on Environmental Activism in the Baikal region.  (conducted by the
Baikal Center) should be completed by spring 1996, but some preliminary results
on a survey in Irkutsk follow:<P>

According to the results of a survey conducted in the city of Irkutsk, there
are 17 NGOs (non-governmental groups) which are engaged in environmental
issues.  Most of them were established in the  early 90s. The focus of interest
for most of these groups is  ecological education and the development of
eco-tourism.  Some groups are involved in helping local protected areas,
cataloging natural monuments, or publicly monitoring the use of local natural
resources.<P>

Many groups are trying to strengthen information networks.  Everyone is for
closer ties between NGOs and for more cooperation in general.  According to
this survey, the lack of information or the difficulty of access to information
is viewed as one of the most serious obstacles to effective work.  Information
on the following subjects is considered the NGO's  most useful (in order of
preferences stated): <OL>

<LI>ecological education

<LI>ecotourism

<LI>foreign experience in the sphere of nature protection, education, and
tourism development

<LI>financial possibilities for funding NGO programs

<LI>data (statistics) on ecological issues

<LI>evaluation of the overall ecological situation in the Irkutsk region.

</OL>

The main ecological problems in the region which need urgent attention are,
according to this survey of Irkutsk groups:<OL>

<LI>the Baikal Law

<LI>the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant

<LI>Forest Protection

<LI>the Level of Baikal

<LI>Ecological Education

<LI> Air Emissions and Water Discharges

<LI>Industrial Waste Management

<LI>Reduction of Anthropogenic Impact on Baikal itself

<LI>Sewage Treatment Facilities in Urban Areas

<LI>Poaching

<LI>Establishment of Independent Environmental Information Network

</OL>

NGOs presently are interacting well with each other, as well as with the
Irkutsk Regional Committee and with the Society for Nature Protection.  Most
Irkutsk NGOs are interested in cooperation with foreign NGOs, but mainly expect
financial support from local and federal governmental agencies.  Once again
they see the main obstacle in the way of solving ecological problems as being
the lack of cooperation and coordination between various governmental agencies,
private enterprises, industries, and NGOs.<P>

<H2>Baikal Ecoforum</H2>

The Baikal Center began the first stages of planning for the Baikal
Ecoforum, a meeting among  environmental organizations and for
environmental activists of the region.  The meeting hopes to address two main
questions:<OL>

<LI>How to facilitate/include meaningful citizen participation in
those decision-making processes which directly affect the environment and/or
the implementation of conservation programs.<P>

<LI>How to make work and
cooperation among NGO's more effective.<P>

</OL>

 The agenda will include discussion on
the following current ecological programs and problems:<UL>

<LI>Baikalsk Paper & Pulp/Selenginsk Paper & Cardboard Plants

<LI>Changes in Lake Baikal's water level

<LI>Boguchansk Hydro-Electrical Dam

<LI>Atmospheric pollution in the Angara Valley

<LI>Water quality in the Angara region

<LI>Regional mineral extraction, e.g: the Udokan copper mines

<LI>Environmental Education

</UL>

The proposed dates for the conference are April or November of 1996. Neighbors
from nearby regions and foreign colleagues working on Lake Baikal are invited
to participate in this forum.  The local government <I>Committees on Nature
Protection</I> will be taking part in the conference as well.   The first funding
for this event have come from <A HREF="baikal.html">Baikal Watch</A> and from the <I>Ecological Fund
of the Irkutsk Region</I>.  The Baikal Center is also applying to the Ecological
Funds of the Chita Region and the Buryat Republic, as well as to other funding
sources, in order to make this conference possible. <P>

In November, the Center began work on a new program, known as: "Public Rights
for Healthy Environments in the Baikal Region and Zabaikal'e: Enhancing the
Role of Citizen and Public Participation in Environmental Decision-making and
Policy Implementation (<I>Baikal Paper and Pulp Plant and Baley</I>)." These
programs, made possible with the support of the <I>US Agency for International
Development</I> through the American organization <I>Save the Children</I>, are
described more  in a special supplement.<P>

<H2>The first regional NGO convention</H2>

took place in Ulan-Ude and was devoted to a discussion of NGO participation in
the implementation of "The Program for Preservation of Biodiversity in Russia,"
which has been developing under World Bank auspices, and includes a Baikal
component.  The idea of this program is "to demonstrate the possibility for
regional interdisciplinary and intergovernmental coordination in the sphere of
regional biodiversity protection" and "to promote initiatives for strengthening
schemes of natural resource management." <P>

There are three so-called model projects developed as a part of the Baikal
component program.  These projects--each to take place in one of the watersheds
of three small rivers (the Bolshoe Goloustnoe, the Tugnui and the Khilok)--are
as a whole viewed as tools for the implementation of proposed strategies.<P>

It is proposed by the program to established Supervisory Council (SC) which
will be in charge of implementing the projects. This SC shall include, along
with the heads of the regional Committees on Ecology, three representatives of
NGO groups and the  scientific community.<P>

The various Baikal NGOs, although deeply dissatisfied with the outcome of this
larger project (they consider that the proposed model projects do <I>not</I>
suggest a strategy for biodiversity preservation in the region), nevertheless
have decided to take a pro-active role, and in order to help prevent a
potential useless waste of money and time, they have elected their
representatives to the SC. <P>

A resolution from this convention was delivered to the heads of regional
administrations, as well to representatives of the World Bank and the Russian
Ministry of Nature Protection.  Also, a number of proposals for organizational
management of the project were suggested.<P>

<H3>Resolution from Representatives of Ecological NGOs at Baikal</H3>
Sept. 30, 1995, Ulan-Ude.<P>

Conference participants support the decision by the GEF to provide a grant of
$20,000,000 to Russia for the purpose of preserving biodiversity.  We realize
that it has been necessary to deal with all sorts of bureaucratic problems
while preparing this stage of the project, and do hope that organizational
mistakes made so far will not re-occur during the implementation phase of this
project.  In part, it is necessary to point out that, in Irkutsk and Buryatia,
work on the preparatory phase (from Oct., 1994 to April, 1995) of the project
was conducted in a somewhat secretive manner, and without appropriate
publicity.  The selection of working group leaders was not done on a
competitive basis, and this is reflected by the fact that not the best choice
was made in selecting model projects.  This fact without doubt will be
reflected also in the quality of the program and its significance.<P>

We do not have any doubt that broad publicity and discussion of this project
throughout the Baikal region will not only help to improve its implementation
prospects, but also will secure the support of the local population. There is
no possibility for success of this project if the people of the region will not
take part in it.<P>

Proposals for structuring the Supervisory Council for the project:<OL>

<LI>The Director of the executive group for model projects shall be approved by
the Supervisory Council.<P>

<LI> All local projects shall be selected in open competition, with preliminary
publication of all submitted project proposals. Projects with the potential for
the most serious impact shall be considered for independent public
assessment.<P>

<LI>Representatives of regional NGOs shall be elected and are accountable to a
Regional NGO Conference.<P>

<LI>It is recommended to consider  a decision  passed only if it receives
two-thirds of the Council 's votes.<P>

<LI>Simultaneous service in the Project Management Group, the  Supervisory
Council and the Baikal Commission shall not be permitted.<P>

</OL>

<HR>


