<TITLE>Baikal Currents- Regional NGO's Projects</TITLE>

<H1>Regional NGO's Projects</H1>

<H2>Save The Baikal Seal!</H2>

As many of you may know, the grassroots group <I>The Baikal
Ecological Wave</I> has been a leader in efforts to save
the Baikal seal (the famous fresh-water <I>nerpa)</I>. 
Over the last year, the Wave has been working with
scientists to investigate the <I>nerpa's</I> status.  The
Wave is trying to determine the  effects of legal culling,
of poaching, and of pollution on the seal.  It is using the
results of this research to lobby for better protection for
the <I>nerpa</I> and its habitat.  It is also producing
video-documentaries for Russian television, and preparing
materials for its environmental education programs in local
schools.  The Wave has been collaborating closely with
Earth Island Institute's <A HREF="baikal.html">Baikal
Watch</A> and <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">International
Marine Mammal Project</A> (whose seal specialist, Dianne
Kopec visited with colleagues at  Baikal).  Final
assessments on the general health of  the seal, and of
Baikal itself, will be available in report form by late
spring of 1996.<P>

<H3>Nerpa and their Environment threatened</H3>

Lake Baikal, magnificent and incredibly beautiful, is known
throughout the world.  More and more people are drawn here
to enjoy its severe beauty and to experience for themselves
the uniqueness and preciousness of this natural creation. 
And all visitors dream of catching a glimpse of its only
mammal, the Baikal seal, locally called nerpa, an endemic
that inhabits the expanses of this inland sea.<P>

The Baikal nerpa (Phoca sibirica) is a representative of
the order of pininpeds and the family of real (earless)
seals.  Nerpa spend most of their life in the water,
surfacing periodically to breathe. Thanks to the capacity
of their blood to hold oxygen, nerpa can remain under water
for up to 45-60 minutes.  In winter, when Baikal is frozen
over, nerpa makes escape holes in the ice.  <P>

In mid-March nerpa give birth to one or, very occasionally,
2 pups, in snow dens on the ice.  At first the pups are
yellow-green in color, but in two weeks turn white.  This
white fur is the pup's camouflage, enabling it, in the
first weeks of life, while it is still feeding on its
mother's milk, to be practically unnoticeable on the ice.
By the time it switches on to independent feeding on fish
its fur turns a silvery-gray.  On the market, this fur is
considered the most beautiful and expensive, and for this
reason such pups are the main object of hunting. <P>

Nerpa remain today the object of both official and
unofficial hunting. The main hunt takes place on the ice on
sleds, but since 1970, two other forms of hunting have been
introduced to Baikal--from boats with rifles, and using
nets. Shooting the animal usually result in the nerpa's
managing to escape into the water, later to die, to no
purpose, of its wounds.  The most effective method is with
nets set at the bottom.  Nerpa, caught in the netting, are
usually brought out of the water dead from drowning.<P>

Hunting for nerpa's meat, fat and fur, has been carried on
since ancient times, but in the 20th century, because of
more intensive development on the shores of Baikal and
higher prices for nerpa products, hunting increased
dramatically.  Clearly, if we want to maintain the numbers
at least at today's (decreased) level, official hunting
should be reduced, or better still, in our opinion, banned
altogether. <P>

In addition to the problems of hunting, there is industrial
pollution around the lake which weakens the animals ability
to combat infection.  Another stress factor for the nerpa
population is the impact of global warming on the lake's
ice conditions, on which nerpa are closely dependent. <P>

In order to properly understand the problem and come to a
well considered policy,  the participants of the joint
Russian-American  project "Nerpa" (financed by ISAR, the
Institute of Soviet-American Relations) are undertaking a
survey among local people, hunters, tourist firms, park
rangers, and scientists in order to assess the state of the
nerpa population, the significance of the hunting, and what
is necessary for it to be cut or stopped without causing
social or economic conflict.<P>

A very important part of the Nerpa project is its emphasis
on information and education.  One of the aims of the
project is to bring nerpa closer to the attention and
hearts of the people of the Baikal region through video,
films, information, and exhibitions for adults and
children. It should help all of us to better understand
nerpa and their habitat, and develop in us the desire to
care for both. In our industrial society, constant efforts
are required to heighten people's perception of the natural
world and to help us feel its wonder and fragility.  We
hope the project "Nerpa" will help us in this task.

<H3>How to contact "Save the Nerpa" project</H3>

For more information on the Save the Nerpa project, contact
Jennie Sutton, Director of the <I>Baikal Ecological
Wave</I> (e-mail: sutton@wave.irkutsk.su) one of the
leading independent environmental groups in the region. The
group was formed in 1991 with the goals of facilitating the
development of a grassroots environmental movement,
providing environmental education and awareness, publishing
environmental education materials, and completing
conservation projects. One of the most important tasks of
the Baikal Wave is to inform the public about the condition
of the environment and the facts about violations of
environmental laws and regulations.   Currently, the Baikal
Wave is working on creating a video studio, and a
grassroots network of environmental educators to distribute
informational newsletters.  <P>

<HR>

<H2>The Green Zone Program</H2>

The Green Zone Program was started in 1995 in the Irkutsk
Region by the <I>Irkutsk Branch of the All-Russian Society
for Nature Protection</I>. (Vera Shelenova or Peter
Khrenov. <P>

The violation of existing regulations on using so-called
"green" (water protective and primary forest land) zones
has become a common-place occurrence in the Irkutsk region.
Lands once allocated and zoned according to their special
natural importance have been withdrawn from protection for
the purpose of establishing gardening coops, private
dachas, and other developments. <P>

This turn of events has met with the vocal protests of the
public.  Beginning in 1990 the public was questioning  the
continued vitality of green zones in Irkutsk, and
surrounding cities such as Shelekhov, Angarsk and
Usolie-Sibirskoe.  In 1991, an official resolution
entitled: "On the Status of Green Zones in Urban Areas and
Settlements of the Irkutsk Region" was adopted, but it
didn't have any positive impact--green zones are still
being withdrawn for improper uses.  The local mass media
has paid a great deal of attention to this very issue, and
has published various documentation of these violations.  A
protest by 8 NGOs at the Federal Prosecutor's Office did
not meet with an adequate official response.  Attempts (by
the Irkutsk Regional and County Committees on Nature
Protection, as well as by local NGOs) to oppose the
destruction of these green zones have not been very
successful so far.<P>

The most "famous" case has to do with the construction of
condominiums on the outskirts of the city on lands  located
within a water protection zone with the special status  of
lands designated for study purposes only. Among the owners
of the new dachas and condominiums are representatives from
the Irkutsk Regional and County Governments and the
Committees on  Ecology and  Land Use.<P>

One of the latest examples is the construction of eight
stores right on the banks of the Angara and Ushakovka
Rivers, some 20-30 meters from the water and in the one of
the most picturesque areas.  City authorities "blessed" the
construction and did not even bother to comply with the
existing regulations, claiming that these are, in fact,
just temporary structures.  For, despite the fact that
these buildings not only obscure scenic views and cause
traffic problems on the roads that parallel these
serpentine rivers (not to mention the impending ecological
damage), the projects are going full speed ahead. <P>

While the Irkutsk Committee on Nature Protection was filing
their protest with the General Prosecutor of the region,
the owners of these stores (well-to-do private car trading
enterprises) are making these "temporary" structures look
more permanent: they have constructed a parking lot right
on the edge of the water, hoping to make the stores look
more inviting to customers. <P>

As time is goes by, the public's attention span on this
issue has shortened. The public's common response has been:
"What can we do? Fortuna (the name of the culprit
enterprise, that means "fortune, luck and fate" in Russian)
is not there to look after us!"  And the destruction of
green zones goes onward. <P>

But there are ways to address this issue and to make a
change, or so believes Vera Shelenova, the Co-Chair of the
Irkutsk Branch of the All Russian Society for Nature
Protection.  Her task has been to draw broader attention to
this problem.  So her organization has initiated a "Program
for Public Participation in the Protection of Green Zones
in the Urban Areas of Irkutsk."<P>

This Program is targeted to provide complete and adequate
information to the general public regarding green zones,
and in so doing, help them lobby for their protection.
Their plan is:<OL>

<LI>To establish a data base  which will include all
existing resolutions, legal acts, scientific data, and
other information collected while monitoring all the
existing green zones.<P>

<LI>To conduct a survey among inhabitants of the Irkutsk
Oblast re.: the problems facing green zones.<P>

<LI>To publish maps of all  the green zones in Irkutsk,
Angarsk, Shelikhov and Usolie.<P>

<LI>To organize public monitoring programs, and appoint
public "guardians" for these green zones.<P>

<LI>To conduct public programs for "adopting" and cleaning
these zones.<P>

<LI>To develop drafts and initiatives for consideration by
local legislative and executive authorities. <P>

</OL>

Under item number 6 above, the following requests have
already been submitted to:<OL>

<LI>the Irkutsk Regional Land Use Committee (to provide the
public with open access to information concerning the
so-called "Plan of Land Allocation for Garden Coops and
Dachas, and other Proposed Private and Public Lands")<P>

<LI>the Legislative Committee (to inform the public of cases of
non-compliance with the 1991 Resolution on Green Zones)<P>

<LI>the Regional Committee on Nature Protection (to have them
hold public hearings on the status of green zones, where
results of environmental impact assessments related to
green zones will be shared)<P>

<LI>the Department of Forest Management (asking them to
provide information on the general scheme of forest
restoration and forest management in green zones). <P>
</OL>

<H3>How to contact "The Green Zone Program" project</H3>


E-mail: irkutsk@glas.apc.org, 664003 Irkutsk, Sukhe-Batora,
15).<P>

<HR>


