<H1>Even One Dollar Or One Helping Hand Can Make A
Difference</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal Currents- Even One Dollar Or One Helping Hand Can Make A
Difference</TITLE>


Direct, "on the ground" financial support has made a world
of difference to a number of groups at Baikal.  In 1995, a
number of American foundations and other groups (often with
assistance from the US Agency for International
Development) contributed to environmental projects.  Among
them Eurasia Foundation, ISAR, German environmental groups,
and the World Wildlife Federation.<P>

<H2>First grants from a private foundation awarded at
Baikal.</H2>

The American <I>Global Greengrants Fund</I> (in association
with the <I>Pacific Environmental Resources Center</I>, and
with the participation of members of Siberian and Far
Eastern independent organizations), is continuing its small
grants program for Siberia and the Russian Far East.  The
first grants were allotted in July of 1995.  Seventeen
organizations and individual activists received support,
including four from the Baikal region. For example, it made
funded the following restoration project in the village of
Shumak.<P>

<H2>Case study: Cleaning up in Shumak.</H2>

The  famous Buryat Shumak (hot springs) has  become
cleaner.  Last year, 28 large garbage dumpsites were
discovered along the Shumak. This summer about one ton of
non-combustible debris was removed with the help of a
helicopter.  Now only about 50% of the garbage remains near
the Shumak, debris which is more difficult to salvage as it
is in a liquid, kasha-like state.  This work was carried
out by around 70 volunteer participants, including a number
of Buryat teens.<P>

In the summer of 1996, work will continue on eliminating
the remaining garbage piles and on monitoring the water
sources feeding the Shumak.<P>

Liya Sandanova says:  "We are conducting a search for
transferable technology which can utilize wastes for other
purposes in regions far from civilization.  We are working
on the issue of biotoilets.  We are studying the experience
of people living in nature preserve areas, people who have
created an exemplary model, where a natural equilibrium
with the environment is maintained, the same as we would
like to see in Shumak.<P>

We request those with experience in utilizing waste
products to help with advice on how to accelerate
composting of organic waste, of which there is quite a bit
along the water sources."  For more information contact
Liya Sandanova, FIRN Project Director, at
<a href="mailto:baikaluu@glas.apc.org">baikaluu@glas.apc.org</A>.<P>

<H2>Volunteer for a Siberian Nature Reserve this Summer!</H2>

The Baikalo-Lenski Nature Reserve (or zapovednik, in
Russian) is looking for hardy and adventurous volunteers
for trailbuilding this summer season.  It is one of the
largest in Russia;  it comprises 660,000 hectares, and is
situated in the Irkutsk Region,  one of the most wild and
inaccessible parts of Lake Baikal.  The zapovednik boasts
110 km of shoreline, the Baikal mountain range, and the
headwaters for the Lena, the Kirenga, and other Baikal
tributaries.  About 90% of the zapovednik is forested,
providing habitat for over 250 species of birds and 50
species of wild animals.  About 200 bears live in the
zapovednik, the largest concentration around Baikal.  No
wonder that one of the zapovednik's areas is called "Shore
of the Brown Bear". <P>

The zapovednik is relatively young, only 8 years old, and
lacks any amenities for visitors.  Work will begin this
summer on construction of an educational, interpretive
trail, and we need your help!  Volunteers will be needed
during the first part of July, the best time to be at
Baikal, and will last two or three weeks.  Volunteers must
be physically strong and healthy, able to do strenuous work
and willing to live in primitive conditions (i.e.: sleep in
tents or cabins).  Work groups will consist of 7 or 8
people.  <P>

Volunteers are responsible for transportation to the
zapovednik (a round trip San Francisco-Irkutsk will cost
about $1,200), as well as for living expenses while there
(about $100-200 a month).  Volunteers must also bring their
own sleeping bag, warm clothing, rain gear, and rain boots.
The zapovednik will provide all necessary work tools and a
guide-instructor.  <P>

All visas, invitations, and other logistics will be
arranged through the <A HREF="baikal.html">Baikal
Watch</A>.  We can help with your trip planning.  Start
planning now for this exciting opportunity!  	<P>

For more information, please contact the <A
HREF="baikal.html">Baikal Watch</A> Program  (Earth Island
Institute, 300 Broadway, Suite 28, San Francisco, CA 94133
USA, tel. (415)788-3666, fax:(415)788-7324,  e-mail:
baikalwatch@igc.apc.org), or the Baikal Center for
Ecological and Citizen Initiatives in Irkutsk (e-mail:
irkutsk@glas.apc.org).<P>

<HR>


