<H1>Environmental Education at Baikal</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal Currents- Environmental Education at Baikal</TITLE>

<H2>Local Groups</H2>

<B>The Ecological Organization of Angarsk</B>--or
<B>GEO</B>--(664816 Angarsk, 179-11-41, e-mail:
irkutsk@glas.apc.org. Contacts: Larissa Chikalina and
Larissa Lobkova) was established by several children's and
youth environmental groups, as well as by middle school
teachers in Angarsk.  The Angarsk city administration also
supports the activities of GEO, which features
environmental education for school children and the
creation or expansion of summer nature camps.  Besides
these school programs, GEO is forming an Angarsk
environmental information center, as well as renewing work
in the Ptichii Nature Preserve.  <P>

<B>The Ecological Center (NMETS)</B> (665914 Baikalsk, Irkutsk
Oblast, Yuzhnii Way, Kvartal 1, apt. 6, e-mail:
ceei@cetin.irkutsk.su, contact: Alexey Gulin)was created in
1995 with the help of the municipal government.  Their
purpose: to develop visual aids and practical tools from
local materials for use by school children in a local
environmental monitoring laboratory.<P>

<B>The Center for Ecological Education and Information</B>
(665914 Baikalsk,  Irkutsk Oblast, Gagarin post office, box
74, e-mail: ceei@cetin.irkutsk.su, contact: Victor
Khotilovich,) has already been in existence for eight years
(though only three as an "official" organization).  This
independent group conducts studies on environmental
protection and conservation, making use of modern
technology, computer-generated ecological games, excursions
and field work (such as the clean-up of recreational areas
along the lake shore).  They have published an "Ecological
List," replete with independent research products done by
local children on the flora and fauna of Lake Baikal, with
the children themselves acting as the designers and
editors.<P>

<B>Davan and The Youth Tourist Club</B> (671717 Severobaikalsk,
Buryatia, Taezhik, tel.30139-20323, e-mail:
davan@glas.apc.org, contact: Maria Moshkina, Evgeny
Mariasov). This group is preparing an ecotourism guidebook
showing prime routes for tourists.  They are also studying
environmental conditions in public recreational areas at
Lake Baikal and Lake Sludyanskii.<P>

<B>Ekos Ecological School</B> (670002 Ulan-Ude, Babushkina 2 ,
tel.3-32-00).  Headed by Antonina Derevtsova, this school
was founded in 1992 and is for children between the ages of
13-17.  The school's mission is to provide an in-depth
understanding about ecology and the world as a whole.<P>

<B>The Republic of Buryatia Student Ecology-Biology Center</B>
(640038 Ulan-Ude, Oreshkovo, box 3076, tel. 4-59-41,
contact: Oleg Selyaev, and Sergei Tararin).  This Center
was opened in 1991 on the model of the former Republic
Group for Young Naturalists (founded in 1954).  The center
is a sort of "island" where urban children can experience
nature.  Here children are given the opportunity to work in
gardens and other natural settings.  They prepare flower
beds, plant seeds, and take care of their seedlings, look
after farm animals.  Before all else, this center seeks to
deepen the knowledge and basic understanding of natural
science through special study group programs.  They offer
organized programs on ecology, bee keeping, hydro-biology
and other topics.  In all, some 22 study groups are at
work.  The center cooperates with practically all schools
in Buryatia.  At present, this group is helping set up a
series of Republic-wide school ecocenters, where the unique
aspects of local natural habitat, as well as elements of
applied biology can be observed.<P>

<B>Window to the World</B> (672090, Chita, box 1041,e-mail:
chita@glas.apc.org, contact:Inga Zinovieva). This is a
joint project of the  Chita Chapter of the Baikal Fund, the
<A HREF="bcci.html">Baikal Center</A>, the Baikal Division of the Ecological
Academy, and the Zabaikalsk Center for Biodiversity
Preservation.  Together these groups organize seminars for
educators and environmental activists, develop school
programs for river monitoring (the so-called GREEN
project), and help schools prepare academic programs and
special ecology courses.  Two seminars have already been
held for teachers of the Baikal region on interactive
methods of ecological education.  This group also publishes
a news bulletin called "The Future Starts Today."<P>

The <B>All-Russian Society for the Protection of Nature</B>
(Irkutsk, Sukhe-Batora, 15, Vera Shlenova) is one of the
most active groups in helping coordinate the activities of
those occupied with issues of environmental education in
the Irkutsk region.<P>

<H2>Spanish Connections</H2>

The Buryat Regional Department for Lake Baikal and two
Spanish ecological associations: The Natural Heritage
Preservation League IPCENA (of Barcelona, Catalonia) and
The Institute for the Preservation and Study of Environment
DEPANA (from Laeida, Catalonia)---have set up a joint
program called Help Baikal.  In July of 1994, an agreement
on cooperation was signed in Ulan-Ude.  The basic task of
the project is to create an environmental education center,
whose purpose will be to facilitate sustainable development
and rational use of the region's natural resources.  The
project initiators have held two public meetings and have
prepared a brochure about Baikal for the Spanish public.
<P>

The Spanish ecologists took on the responsibility of
procuring financial support for creating this educational
center, which will:<UL>

<LI>Work with local peoples and help raise their ecological
consciousness;<P>

<LI>Develop concrete environmental education programs for
schools;<P>

<LI>Work on ecotourism projects;<P>

<LI>Develop student and scientific exchange programs.<P>

</UL>

Additional information about this program can be received
from Sergey Shapkhaev, <P>

e-mail:  shap@techn.buriatia.su<P>

or DEPANA (apartat de Correus 2809 08080 Barcelona,
Spain)/IPCENA (Placa Mercadal, 45, 2n.2a, 25600 Balaguer,
Spain) tel. (973) 448870/fax (973) 448856.<P>

<H2>Baikal Center Seminars:</H2>

 Together with the Chita Division
of the <B>Baikal Fund</B>, the <B>Window on the World</B> program,
and with the collaboration and financial support of the
<B>Pacific Environment and Resources Center</B>, the second
regional teachers' seminar was held in Chita this last
July. The seminar focused on the subject of "Interactive
Methods of Environmental Education, Including Environmental
Games".  Seminar participants worked on the development of
a local chapter of <B>Project GREEN</B> (Global Rivers
Environmental Education Network), which teaches
schoolchildren to monitor water quality in small rivers. 
At least three schools from the Baikal region will take
part in this program.  <P>

The teaching materials and lesson plans are being prepared
by "Windows on the World." (See above.)<P>

The Baikal Center is continuing to compile a database to
widen the network of connections between environmental
education teachers.  The Center provides regular
consultations concerning existing eco-education programs,
organizations, and information sources.  Curricular support
and environmental literature has been provided to 11
regional schools.  In the Irkutsk region, the Center
collaborates with Larissa Slatina of the Irkutsk In-Service
Training Teacher's School and Larissa Chikalina.<P>

<HR>


