<H1>From local media and official sources</H1> 

<TITLE>Baikal Currents-From local media and official sources</TITLE>

<H2>From local Baikal newspapers (July- September)</H2>

<H3>Natural gas of Kovykhta</H3>

Four American Banks have expressed an interest in helping develop this natural resource deposit.  Among the
first stock holders are the Irkutskenergo Enterprise, which intends to use the Kovykhta natural gas deposits
to increase local power capacities.  Other groups such as Bransvik and the American First Boston Bank, as
well as Japanese and Korean businessmen, have expressed serious interest in the Kovykhta deposits. Starting
in 1996 a Kovykhta development project will become part of the larger federal program, known simply as "Power
and Energy".<P>

<H3>New Laws and Regulations at Baikal</H3>

In July, a new  Law on Fees for Land was enacted in Irkutsk.  A Law on Tourism was adopted in Buryatia in
November. At the same time, a Tourism Law for the Irkutsk Region is being developed by the Irkutsk Regional
Law Institute.<P>

<H3>Sykhoy Log gold mine</H3>

On September 20,1994 the Government of the Russian Federation issued a resolution for the development of the
Sykhoy Log gold mine in the Irkutsk Oblast'.  Among the stock holders of the Lenzoloto (Lenagold) company is
the Australian Firm STAR.  Ten percent of the stock belongs to the Irkutsk Region itself, and 69 percent of
the stock holders are various private Russian companies.<P>

<H3>Lake shore terrain in danger</H3>

In February, 1995 the Irkutsk Regional <B>Comprehensive Ecological-Economic Program "Baikal"</B> was approved
by the administration of the Irkutsk region. According to a decree issued by the Irkutsk Governor, in 1995
alone, some 1,868 million rubles will have been allocated for the scheduled implementation of this program.
In August, 1995, a federal ordinance sent additional funding from the federal budget for this very program in
the Irkutsk region.  Thus, a total of 3,787 million rubles is to be spent on this program in 1995. All funds
will be used for <A HREF="fall95pr-en.html">re-enforcement of lake-shore terrain</A> in the southern part of
the lake.  (Another 2 billion rubles has been assigned from the regional Ecological Fund for the
implementation of a joint Russian-German landscape zoning program, and for the improvement of municipal
sewage treatment facilities in Sludyanka. <P>

<H3>Buryatia air emissions decreased</H3>

In Buryatia, due to a reduction in industrial development, air emissions decreased by 12.6 percent in
comparison with 1994. The main air polluters are Gusinoozersk power station, the Ulan-Ude Power Station, and
industry in the Kyakhta Region.<P>

<HR>

<H2>Forestry Issues In Siberia.</H2>

by  Georgiy Kuznetsov<P>

"The fact that our region is the richest in forest resources in this country is a common knowledge,"  stated
Mr. V. Mironov, one of the leading foresters of the Irkutsk region.  This quote appeared in the "Eastern
Siberia Pravda" newspaper several years ago.  And at that time he meant not only Russia, but the entirety of
the Soviet Union.  To prove his point, one need only compare the total territory of the Irkutsk region, some
767,900 sq. km (or 285 thousand sq. miles) and its total forest area (714,450 sq. km.), and one accounts for
more than 92 per cent of the Oblast'. (figures are from the official state forest registration dated January
1, 1993).  <P>

Mr. Mironov goes on to say:

<BLOCKQUOTE> If one considers that about nine billion cubic meters of wood is concentrated in this region of
Russia, 80% of which is coniferous, then there should be no doubt that we are incredibly and fantastically
rich.  We can fell trees forever, and there will be still more. There will be more than enough left for our
children and grandchildren.  And when the time of our great grandchildren comes, new forests will grow where
we are felling trees today.  So it seems there is nothing to worry about.  Just fell, sell, and live
rich.</BLOCKQUOTE>

However, Vladimir Bulygin, who recently served as chief government nature protection inspector for the
region, and now is a lawyer for the regional government, offers a different point of view on the subject.  In
the "Eastern Siberia Pravda" newspaper he states: "Have a look at the forest, not through the reports of the
Forestry Department, but through an airplane window.  Half of our Siberia is as clean shaved as the head of
an old-time Siberian exiled prisoner."<P>

Annually, more that 150,000 square kilometers (or 55,000 square miles) of forest are logged in the Irkutsk
region, mostly without any foreign "participation".  According to Mironov, up to 30-40 percent of logged
trees remain unremoved from the forest. Lots of timber is wasted or lost in transport, and even more is
wasted in processing wood.  In Russia, on average, 1,000 cubic meters of timber are used to produce only 30
tons of paper.  For comparison's sake, the same amount of timber could produce up to 140 tons of paper in the
USA and more than 160 tons in Finland.<P>

Added to all this is the fact that, between 1981 and 1990, more than 1,435,000 hectares of forest in the
Irkutsk region were lost to forest fires.<P>

According to Deputy Governor Mr. Nosyrev, representatives of foreign timber companies that have approached
the government of the Irkutsk region so far are interested only in the export of raw, unprocessed timber. Not
one company has expressed any interest in creating a joint-venture for processing timber in the region. On a
more positive note, in recent years it has been noted that timber harvests in Irkutsk have decreased by more
than half.  But this reduction is not due to a wiser or more caring treatment of the forests, but to the
general economic crises that is slowing down Russia.<P>

<I>Facts and quotes provided by  Georgiy Kuznetsov, an environmental journalist living in Irkutsk.)</I><P>

<H2>Land Use Issues</H2>

Implementation of the joint Russian-American land use program for the Baikal watershed continues in 1995. The
Governmental Commission on Baikal recommended that it's findings be taken into consideration for any future
land use plans.<P>

(also see special supplement, p. 7 )<P>

<H3>Ecologically Sustainable Development's</H3>

In  1994-1995 (through May), the <A HREF="bcci.html">Baikal Center</A> assisted in implementing Ecologically Sustainable
Development's (ESD's) Comprehensive Land-Use Plan for the Baikal Region.  Baikal Center employees coordinated
all preparations for a summer of field projects in the town of Bolshoe Goloustnoe and on the island of
Olkhon.  Special task forces completed a church renovation project, restored and re cultivated a kilometer
long section of lake shore, and assembled a solar-panel system for the Bolshoe Goloustnoe school.  At Olkhon
a support center for local farmers was opened with the help of the <B>Schumacher Society</B> and ESD.  The
ESD contract was completed in May. Starting  in May of 1994, the  Irkutsk Regional Administration, Irkutsk
Institute of Geography, Irkutsk Committee on Nature protection, County Administrations of Irkutsk and Olkhon
started a joint project with a Land Use Bureau (GMBH) from Germany.  An official agreement was signed,
targeting the development of legal acts and norms for landscape zoning.<P>

Irkutsk governmental officials and specialists from the Institute of Geography got acquainted with land use
planning strategy from Germany. Field work took place in Bolshoe Goloustnoe and Olkhon.<P>

The fact that the question on other land use program was on the agenda of the Baikal Government Commission
(see  Special  Supplement, pp.5-6) gives us hope that governmental officials in the Irkutsk region will
coordinate their efforts with all parties involved.<P>

