<LI>Buryat Republican Library<P>

</UL>

</UL>

This program is being implemented with the support (financial, consultative) and friendship of our colleagues
from the <B>Sacred Earth Network</B>. With the support of the <B>Eurasia Foundation</B> through <B>Omni</B>.<P>

<HR>

<H2>Sister-Cities</H2>

The <A HREF="bcci.html">Baikal Center</A> has been helping to develop sister-city projects by providing e-mail capabilities to
others.  Having assisted the Irkutsk-Eugene project for several years, now the Center is linking Baikalsk and
its new sister-city at South Lake Tahoe.  The Center is also distributing information about potential
contacts for other grassroots groups and also helping to facilitate correspondence between groups and
individuals. <P>

At the present, there are four cities from the Baikal region with American sister-cities.<P>

<B>Irkutsk-Eugene, Oregon</B> (Chairpersons--Ludmila Kurbatova in Russia/Gail Groza in Oregon)  The most open and
accessible program, "Families to Friends through Correspondence" was organized by Zhanna Nelson (e-mail:
71564.170@compuserve.com), and helps put interested families in contact with one another.  (For more info on
these cities, see previous newsletters.)<P>

<B>Chita-Boise, Idaho</B> (Committee Chairpersons, Rima Kim, and Dr. Robert Smith; e-mail: root@kim.chita.su).  
Ludmila Lanskaya, a schoolteacher, initiated this exchange and was supported by Dr. Robster from Boise. 
Three delegations have already traveled between the two cities and a Rotary Club was created in Chita.  An
intensive exchange continues between doctors who are conducting a seminar entitled "A Healthy Way of Life".
In Boise, ways of helping provide medical equipment to hospitals in the Chita region are being discussed. 
<P>

<B>Ulan-Ude--Berkeley, California</B>.  (Co-Chairpersons, Larissa Kovaleva and Chimita Garmaeva; Berkeley
committee-, Gary Cook: e-mail: <A HREF="mailto:baikalwatch@igc.apc.org">baikalwatch@igc.apc.org</A>).  The Ulan-Ude committee was created in January
1995.  Sub-committees on ecology, education, culture, and citizen exchange programs were set up.  A group of
10 "city representatives" has been formed for the first visit to Berkeley to come in 1996.  In Berkeley,
Michelle Kellman undertook the organization of a pen-pal program and the students of Ulan-Ude's schools
numbers 3 and 49 have already received their first answer from the 4th graders of Malcolm X elementary
school.  With the assistance from the Asia Foundation and Berkeley families, the first shipment of books for
the National Library was received.  <P>

<B>Baikalsk-South Lake Tahoe, California</B> (e-mail: ceei@cetin.irkutsk.su, erterlich@aol.com, contacts: Andrey
Durnykh and Gabe Litvin, Robert Erlich). In the spring of 1994 the first Baikalsk delegation visited
California.  Discussions were held about environmental educational programs and summer camps for school
children.  At the end of September, Robert Erlich, Joy Pepper, Gabe Litvin, and Virginia Esperanza came to
Baikalsk to become better acquainted with their friends, the surrounding environs, and the environmental
situation.  This American delegation, as representatives of the <I>Tahoe Regional Planning Agency</I> and the
<I>Lake Tahoe Conservancy</I>, have agreed with Baikalsk colleagues and the Baikal Center to prepare for joint
actions on environmental issues.<P>

<H3>Severobaikalsk City hopes to find partner</H3>

The city of Severobaikalsk(e-mail: davan@glas.apc.org) also hopes to find a sister-city project with an
American city as partner, and has already submitted its request to the international committee for
Sister-City Programs.  Some possible matches are Sandpoint, Idaho and Reno, Nevada.  <P>

Anybody  willing to help to find a match?<P>

