<H1>About The Baikal Center</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal Currents- About The Baikal Center</TITLE>

The fundamental goal of the <A HREF="bcci.html">Center</A>'s work is to offer informational and logistical help to the environmental
movement and to the citizens of Baikal.  It is to support citizen initiatives for change, and to help with
the development and implementation of independent environmental programs.  For these purposes, a substantial
part of the Center's time is dedicated to developing structures for processing information for other groups
or individuals.<P>

A significant part of the Center's work consists of providing consultative help to the region's visitors and
residents.  The Center often plays the role of "Tourist Information Center," providing information and advice
(for example, on whom to contact, where to find needed information, or who is working on this or that
project).  The Center makes arrangements for visiting scientists, activists, and journalists.  Consultative
services are <P>

also provided to help to find reliable sources of funding.<P>

<H2>Update</H2>

While the Center's work is headquarters in Irkutsk, it continues to serve and establish contact with groups
on both sides of the lake.  Following the closure of temporary offices in Ulan-Ude, the Buryat capital, and
Chita, all the Center's informational and coordinating work has been transferred to one office in Irkutsk. 
Happily, the number of volunteer helpers has grown.  (We are especially grateful for the help of Mikhail
Rybalko and Ariadna Reida, students at <B>Irkutsk State University</B>.)  The Center is also happy to welcome
aboard newcomers Yulia Bogomolova, Anna Maryasova, and Michael Agrafonov. We also grateful to Debra Sharky of
TBI, who spent 3 months in Irkutsk assisting  our work and  glad to admit a more close collaboration with
PERC and TBI.<P>

In Chita, as before, the BC's primary partner remains the <B>Baikal Fund</B>.  Questions regarding the activities
of Chita eco-groups may be directed to us in Irkutsk, or to Inga Zinovieva and Tatiana Strizhova in Chita.
Tel: (3022 2) 2-19-62;  e-mail: chita@glas.apc.org.  In Buryatia, the Center has established an
<B>Environmental NGO Support Station</B> which provides computers and e-mail access to 8 groups (see page 16 for
a list).  This station is located in the <B>National Library of the Buryat Republic</B> in Ulan-Ude<P>

 <H2>Baikal Center Club</H2>

The Baikal Center Club  began work in Ulan-Ude and Irkutsk, producing a calendar full of events such as
films, lectures, and TV-video screenings, meetings with visiting environmentalists and colleagues.  These
meetings are intended for guests visiting the region, people who work in the field of environmental
protection and/or sustainable development, and other NGO representatives. <P>

We encourage those who have travel plans to Baikal to let us know in advance of your visit:  The Baikal
Center Club is interested in arranging lectures and presentations for and by visiting NGO representatives,
scientists, scholars, and activists.<P>

<HR>


