<H1>Baikalsk Pulp And Paper Plant (BPPP)</H1><P>

<TITLE>Baikal CurrentsSupplement- Baikalsk Pulp And Paper Plant (BPPP)</TITLE><P>

Those who are concerned about Lake Baikal are aware of the problems
related to notorious Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant.  For over 30 years
this very iussue has been the centerpiece of discussions and arguments
between scientists, environmentalists, developers, industrialists and
governmental officials.  The environmentalists lost the battle to stop
construction of this huge factory on the shores of Baikal in the
1960's.  Since then, there have been various efforts to use common
sense and find an alternative to the existence of the Pulp and Paper
Plant at the southernmost point of Baikal. Some of these efforts have
been more obvious, but mostly they have consisted of  "routine" work by
researchers, scientists, and those who cared. <P>

Only when very obvious threats are posed (such as the  plan to
discharge Baikalsk Pulp And Paper Plant (<B>BPPP</B>) waste into Irkut
river) does the public pay attention  and become actively  and
effectively involved.  <P>

Over the last ten years, public attention to the Plant itself, as well
as to other ecological threats to Baikal, has subsided.  Only a few
activists have been trying to keep attention focused on this issue. 
Even the  development of a special Law on Baikal doesn't change the
situation with the BPPP very much: after many talks, none of the many
variants of this law have been adopted, and with each passage through
the legislative bodies the Law  becomes weaker and weaker (see page 3
of Baikal Currents).<P>

This fall, however, the Baikalsk Plant again became the center of
attention of various environmental activists and scientists throughout
the region and Russia. Even Greenpeace Russia has developed a Baikalsk
Plant campaign.  We hope that this latest wave of interest, action, and
legislation will finally lead to a permanent resolution of the problem
that will protect the lake, its environment, and its people.<P>

Please check here for <A HREF="supp95f-f.html">Facts And Figures On The
BPPP</A><P>

<H2>History of Official (In-)Action at BPPP</H2>

In 1987 the Soviets decided to reprofilie the mill within five years -
by 1993 at the latest. The decision was passed by the Central Committee
of CPSU and by the Council of Ministers as No. 433 dated 13.04.87.<P>

The Russian Federation Government reconfirmed the reprofiling decision 
by issuing decree No. 925 dated 2.12.92 , titled: " On Reprofiling the
Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill and Creating Compensating Industry to
Replace Pulp Production". <P>

A Comprehensive Federal Program to ensure the protection of the lake
was approved as No. 1306 dated 25.11.94. This program states:<UL>

<LI>The Baikalsk  Pulp and Paper Mill is the leading  industrial
enterprise causing irreparable damage to the environment and to the
health of the people, being the only one to be  situated on the shore
of the lake and discharging its waters into the lake.<P>

<LI>The Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Mill hasn't begun to fulfill the
Government's resolution on reprofiling; indeed, the Plant has been
investing in technological improvements for pulp production, thus
demonstrating that they does not intend to change the production
process, only make it more efficient. <P>

</UL>

In 1993, the Government of the Russian Federation, along with the
Ministry of Ecology, resolved to hold an international call for
proposals on potential remodeling of the Baikalsk Plant. The
competition never took place,. However, 8 variants for remodeling the
plant were considered by the Administration of the Irkutsk Region. The
so called "variant No. 8" was chosen as the most appropriate. <P>

According to the Head of Environmental Impact Assessments (EIA) for the
Irkutsk Committee on Nature Protection, Natalia Ryabukhina, all 8
variants have undergone an EIA. The approved 8th variant still doesn't
comply with all existing environmental regulations: it's EIA showed 15
points that need to be taken into consideration.<P>

Variant No. 8 calls for the diversification of the Baikalsk Plant by
establishing a mechanical timber processing enterprise and paper
production from imported materials.  The following production is
planned: lumber, prefabricated wooden houses, furniture, mattresses,
technological-mechanical pulp, paper for packaging, and wallpaper.  
The converted enterprise should provide employment for 1,700 people.
<P>

Variant No.8 was adopted by the Administration of the Irkutsk Region in
Resolution # 385 of December 29, 1993 and submitted to Goscomimushestvo
(The Federal Committee of the Russian Federation on Property) and
approved on August 25,  1994.  But this program was not introduced to
potential investors, and no bidding was announced. <P>

In September , 1994 another variant was introduced by the  Limnological
Institute of the Siberian Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences by
M. Grachev, A. Suturin, N. Aldokhin, and A. Sukhodolov.  It was called
"rokirovka", or castling. It calls for converting the Baikalsk Plant
into a bottling plant for Baikal drinking water and for the production
of soft drinks  and liquor using Baikal water.  Also food and furniture
would be produced at the plant.  Simultaneously, it calls for the
modernization of the Selenginsk Plant and the construction of
facilities for producing bleached Kraft there.  It was calculated that 
this variant would require an investment of $150 million USD.  <P>

A task force to study this proposal was established under the umbrella
of the Administration of the Irkutsk region in May, 1995.  The European
Community has expressed interest in the idea, but it is still an idea
rather than a developed program or a project.  Still, it is the only
option that halts the production of pulp, with all of its attendant
ecological degradation, at the lake.<P>


<H2>Local  NGOs to UNIDO: "Say  What?"</H2>

Here is the response of local environmentalists regarding the findings
of the United Nations Economic Development Organization (<B>UNIDO</B>) experts:<P>

Environmentalists have been struggling for over 30 years against the
production of pulp at Lake Baikal.  It is clear that our Government,
while publicly supporting the remodeling of the mill, aims instead to
modernize the mill's pulp production.  They did not even mention
remodeling.  The <A HREF="supp95un.html">UNIDO recommendations</A> for modernization both shocked
and caused protest among specialists and researchers who are engaged in
ecological and technical issues concerning the Baikalsk Mill.  These
recommendations are self-serving and many of the statements were
contradictory.  Furthermore, many of the economic calculations didn't
seem to be right.[<I>See also</I> <A HREF="mccubbin.html">Neil McCubbin, formerly of UNIDO team,
comments.</A>]<P>

Ecological reasoning proves the fact that the UNIDO experts lacked
competence, although they sounded professional in their
press-release.<P>

Here's the proof :<OL>

<LI>The group, excluding the coordinator, consisted of 8 experts from
Finland (those who were ready to supply the modernization equipment),
Germany, Scotland, Holland, Russia and Canada.  The group included an
analyst on finance from Finland, a sociologist from Holland, and a
Russian researcher (Mr. Grachev, Russian Academy of Science
corresponding member ).  Dr. Grachev had difficulty finding a common
language with the othercommittee members ("differences in approaches" as we were informed by
the participants of the conference).<P>

The experts visited the mill for 1-8 weeks, and in their final report, 
they stated:<P><UL>

<LI>The Pulp and Paper Mill doesn't cause any damage to the environment
and to the health of the people<P>

<LI>The harmful substance emission regulations are too strict: they
should be liberalized and adapted to the production capacity  of the
mill (we ask: why not to the possible reaction of the environment and
the health of the people?) <P>

<LI>Despite this, the mill should be modernized (why, if everything is so
good already?) <P>

</UL>

Modernization would be going on for 5 years at all stages of the
production process, putting new equipment units into operation (that
means practically building a new mill within the premises of the old
one!) Remodeling the mill is unreasonable and would cost $600 million,
just modernizing the first production line would cost $118 million. 
These calculations are indisputably tricky:  if the mill were closed,
the cost of dismantling would amount to $230 million, including
financial support and social benefits for those who would lose their
jobs ($100 million), while if modernization were carried out, the work
force would be reduced (regarded as a positive argument), though social
benefits for them are not considered here. The report contains many
more such contradictory details.<P>

<LI> The <A HREF="supp95un.html">UNIDO expert recommendations</A> are
ecologically dangerous.  The experts propose burning old, accumulated sludge,  but they are surely
aware that dioxides (with a reputation for being terrible and toxic
substances) would be emitted into the air.  The experts also offered to
establish the standards for atmospheric emissions in kg/ton (they claim
it is a common practice everywhere in the world), instead of mg/cubic
meter for air and mg/l for water. The unit of kg/ton could be an index
of advanced technology and ecology only. If such units are accepted,
the mill is practically given Carte-Blanche for producing
100,000-300,000 tons of pulp.  The requirements on the emission norms
will be met, while  total environmental emissions will increase  2 or 3
times.  When referring to the accepted world norms for methylmercaptan emissions (
0.05 kg/ton ), the committee never tells us how much pulp those mills
are producing or how their environment differs from that of Siberia. [<I>See
also</I> <A HREF="mccubbin.html">Neil McCubbin, formerly of UNIDO team,
comments.</A>]<P>

<LI> It is unacceptable  to claim the necessity of adapting ecological
norms to meet  technical capacity.  We claim the norms should be
oriented toward protecting people and the environment from irrevocable
and harmful influences caused by pollutants. <P>

<LI> The experts fully ignore the unique quality of water in Lake Baikal 
and its chemical and hydro-biological parameters.  They don't have any
idea of the climate: Lake Baikal is situated in the center of the Asian
continent, the biggest in the world according to its latitude extent. 
It experiences anticyclones and calm winds nearly eight months a year,
while the Lake Baikal shoreline is noted for mountain and valley winds
and breezes.  Here the air emissions  hoveri over the mill zone for
7-10 days and then accumulating and whirling together with the
shoreline circulation.<P>

</OL>

Therefore, it seems strange that it was the city of Irkutsk, located 70
km away from Baikal, and not the Baikalsk Mill that was named as the
main source of pollution around the lake.  It is ridiculous to compare
the toxicity of the mill with that of Irkutsk, considering that Irkutsk
waste-waters cannot flow into Baikal, because Irkutsk is located
downstream of the lake, on the banks of Baikal's only outflowing river,
the Angara.<P>

The character of this document not only undermines United Nations Economic Development Organization (<B>UNIDO</B>)'s reputation
among Russian people, but it also makes us question the role of our
authorities, especially the Ministry of  Foreign Affairs.  It is quite
clear that the UNIDO initiative coincides very much with the intention
of developed countries to encourage the primary processing of raw
materials in developing countries, thus protecting their countries
against ecological crisis and expanding the equipment supply market.<P>

The Pulp and Paper Mill Management are well-known for their greediness
and use of any means to achieve their goals.  They demonstrated it in
the 1960s when they fooled the Government, stating that the Baikalsk
Mill would be emitting nothing but water and oxygen! They inspire fear
among their employees by predicting unemployment, thus making them
dependent on the mill.  They never mentioned the fact that, after the
modernization program they support, some workers will be thrown out.<P>

History is returning to the point where we are in danger of  losing our
Russian national heritage.  (Prepared by Vera Shlenova and Bella
Chebanenko on behalf of the Irkutsk Branch of the Society for Nature
Protection).<P>

<H2>RESOLUTION</H2>

Resolution of the Government Commission on Baikal, October 18, 1995,
Irkutsk<P>

The resolution of the Government of the Russian Federation of December
2nd, 1992,  No.925, envisaged the implementation of conversion of the
Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant over the period 1993-1995.  Neither the
Ministry of Economics nor Goskomprom (the State Committee for Industry)
saw to the implementation of  that resolution.<P>

In this situation, bearing in mind the necessity to solve the
environmental problems connected with the work of the Baikalsk Pulp and
Paper Plant,  and also the significance of the plant as fundamental to
the existence of the town of Baikalsk,  the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper
Plant worked out and coordinated an investment plan for the  Plant's
conversion together with the Irkutsk Regional Administration.   This
program was  sent  to Goskomimushestvo (the State Committee for
Property) but to date has not been confirmed. In 1995, an international
assessment of the situation at the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant and
options for conversion was undertaken with participation of  UNIDO
specialists.<P>

Bearing in mind the above, the Commission resolved:<P><OL>

<LI>To  ask the Government of the Russian Federation to change the<P>

period for the conversion of the Baikalsk Plant.<P>

<LI>To  ask the Government of the Russian Federation to make changes in
the "Complex Federal Program for ensuring the  protection of Lake
Baikal and rational use of the natural resources of its basin"
stipulating conversion of the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant and a
solution to the social problems connected with this in the town of
Baikalsk.<P>

<LI>To recognize the necessity of conversion of the Plant based on the
principles of the investment program agreed on by resolution No.385 of
the Head of the Irkutsk Oblast Administration, dated 29.12.93.<P>

<LI>To propose to the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant and
Goskomimushestvo that, together with Roslesprom (the Russian Ministry
of Forestry) and the Siberian Branch of the Academy of Sciences, they
complete the above mentioned program, have it confirmed by the
respective Ministries and Departments and the Irkutsk Regional
Administration, and submit it to the Government Commission on Baikal by
the 1st of January 1996 for further confirmation by the Government of
the Russian Federation.  And while completing work on  the program, to
take into consideration the following:<P><UL>

<LI>provision for the protection of Lake Baikal as a World Heritage
Site;<P>

<LI>minimization of the impact of the plant on the region's natural
environment, including the exclusion of elemental chlorine from the
production process and the reduction of gaseous emissions;<P>

<LI>diversification of the plant's production.<P>

</UL>

<LI>To accept the proposal of the Russian Academy of  Sciences to
develop a model for the sustainable development of the south Baikal
region through 2005, together with the appropriate  Ministries and
Departments,  financed from the budget stipulated in the Baikal Program
and from other sources.<P>

</OL>

<H2>"In the Clutches of the Beaurocrazy" (sic) </H2> <P>

by Sergey Shapkhaev, Head of Buryat Department  on Baikal*<P>

At a meeting of the Governmental Commission on Baikal, held in Irkutsk
on October 18, 1995, it was confirmed that the situation surrounding
the problems of the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant (BPPP), as well as
the regulation of the lake level had come to a dead end with no
solution in sight.  <P>

As the BPPP problem was being discussed in front of this Commission, it
was becoming obvious that a bizarre "love quadrangle" had come into
play among the Irkutsk Oblast' administration, the State Forestry
Service, various federal agencies, and representatives from academic
science.  Each of these parties advanced their own rather convincing
and resounding arguments, shifting responsibility for solving these
problems onto the shoulders of their opponents. Industry
representatives strongly advocated the idea of modernizing the mill,
upholding the results of an international study recently performed by
UNIDO (the UN Commission on Industrial Development- see p. 4).  They
comcluded that, thanks to the technological progress of the last 10
years, the continued production of cellulose by the BPPP was by far the
most environmentally pure and harmless option for Baikal's ecosystem. 
<P>

The Director of the Limnological Institute for the Siberian Division of
the Russian Academy of Science, Dr. Grachev, criticized the results of
the UNIDO study.  After analyzing trends in the world cellulose market,
he came to the conclusion that, even with the transition to the latest
modern technology for processing cellulose, the mill's production will
soon become non-competitive due to rising costs for raw materials and
the use of water.  Moreover, the transition to modern technology will
result in a sharp cut in the number of mill workers, increasing the
social tension in Baikalsk and the Slyudyanka regions of southern
Baikal. "Improving a mega-industry in the region contradicts the idea
of sustainable development," added the scientist.  As a way out of this
situation, he suggested reprofiling the factory into a bottling plant
for producing Baikal drinking water and similar beverages and other
products.  He proposed transferring the production of bleached
cellulose to the Selenga Cellulose and Cardboard Plant, adding that the
economic assessment for this "castling" maneuver has found support from
the President and the Government of the Buryat Republic.<P>

The Chairman of the State Committee on Ecology for the Irkutsk Oblast',
Y. H. Udodov, expressed doubts about the introduction of absolutely
harmless cellulose production technologies in the foreseeable future,
considering current economic realities.  He called on the Government
Commission on Baikal to demonstrate their principals and order the BPPP
shareholders, the government of the Russian Federation, and the plant
administration to develop a timetable for reprofiling the BPPP, to the
exclusion of any cellulose or paper production.<P>

The Deputy Head of the Irkutsk Oblast' administration accused the
federal agencies of inaction and unwillingness to solve the BPPP
problem.  In part, he referred to the fact that the government of the
Russian Federation had in fact obstructed plans for an international
competition-convention for the reprofiling of the plant (they had done
this by not allocating sufficient funds to organize this convention). 
In his turn, the conference chair, Deputy Minister for Environment and
Natural Resources of the Russian Federation, A.A... Averchenkov,
shifted all responsibility for the present situation to the Ministry of
Economy and the Government Committee on Industry of the Russian
Federation, neither of whom had representatives present at the
conference.<P>

Finally, all interested parties, including the Siberian Division of the
Academy of Sciences, agreed to form a group which would, on the basis
of the Irkutsk Oblast' investment program (see page X), prepare a
proposal for the long-term future of the BPPP and present it to the
Government Commission on Baikal. Perhaps this decision only satisfied
the Academy of Science representatives, who usually receive special
funding in these cases for additional research.   (For a description of
what the Baikal Center's program intends to do about this situation,
see below)**<P>

The Buryat delegation, who in the first stages had maintained a
diplomatic silence, became much more lively after lunch, especially
when discussion turned to the regulation of the lake level.  The
Director of Irkutsk Energy, B. I. Syutkin, poured oil on a smoldering
fire when he predicted an impending ecological catastrophe in Irkutsk. 
He announced that the downtown section of the city would be inundated
following increased releases through the dam at the Irkutsk
hydroelectric station following an unusually wet summer.  The high
inflow-rate of rivers between June and August raised the level of
Baikal.  And in order to meet the requirements set by the Government
Committee on Baikal (in an agreement between the Irkutsk Oblast' and
Buryatia on the inadmissibility of letting the level of Baikal rise
above the 457.0 meter mark), workers at the power plant had begun
increasing the outflow of water through the dam.  This would lead to a
rise in the water level beyond the dam, in the tail waters below.
If--before the construction of the dam--these floods would last several
days, then now they would last a month or more.  In principle this
could lead to unwanted consequences for the large population of Irkutsk
(e.g., washing away buildings, destroying lines of communication,
etc.).  <P>

In the animated discussion that this touched off, more attention was
paid to possible methodologies for determining any damage that would be
caused by the artificial fluctuations in the level of Baikal.  A
decision was taken to finance a study of these methodologies by the
Ecological Fund of Irkutsk Oblast'.  For some reason, problems
concerning  damage and the calculation of compensation were mainly
discussed. However, the idea of solving the problems by minimizing them
 was practically not discussed at all. Somehow, everyone had earlier
resigned themselves to its inevitability, and concentrated on potential
liability claims.  This strategy could hardly be seen as
constructive.<P>

(In the end, the conference participants, having "let off steam" on the
previous questions, calmly and without emotion listened to short
presentations by A. Malevskiy, S. G. Shapkhaev, and I. P. Glazyrina. 
They reported on the implementation of the Comprehensive Program of
Land Use Policy for the Russian Portion of the Lake Baikal Basin, as it
was evolving on the territories of the Irkutsk Oblast', Buryatia, and
the Chita, respectively. It was taken under advisement to use the
experience and results of this work in implementing other programs that
affect the use of natural resources or the protection of biodiversity
in the Baikal Region.) <P>

<H3>Notes</H3>

* Buryat Department on Baikal (e-mail: shap@techn.buriatia.su) deals
with issues of  comprehensive use of land, was established  in 1993
with an American assistance for implementation of the land use program
and works with ESD (Ecologically Sustainable Development,
e-mail:esd@igc.apc.org, tel. 518-873-3200)<P>

** As part of the Citizen's Rights to a Healthy Environment Program,
the following steps will be taken to resolve the Baikalsk problem: <P>

1) organizing a database of all concerned parties and interpreting the
data for public consideration; <P>

2) engaging in active outreach and education campaigns in order to
promote public involvement;<P>

3) discovering why, after so many studies , proposals, and resolutions,
 nothing has been done to change the plant;  and holding accountable
those who are responsible for decisions not being implemented;<P>

4) advocating for an international competition for companies wishing to
invest in and reprofile the plant;<P>

5) organizing an international boycott of pulp products from Baikalsk
in order to reduce the plant's economic feasibility;<P>

6) organizing public hearing on the Baikalsk Plant as a case study for
public participation.<P>

<HR>

Financial support for this program was provided by <B>United States
Agency for International Development</B>through the <B>Save the
Children Foundation</B>.<P>

This issue  was prepared by Jonathan Burstein, I.
Dyatlovskaya-Birnbaum.<P>

Special thanks to Lev Khodyrev, Valentina Dudareva, Tatiana Strizhova,
Michael Grachev, Sergey Shapkhaev, Arkady Kalikhman, Vera Shelenova for
providing informational assistance.<P>


