<H1>United Nations Economic Development Organization recommends.</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal CurrentsSupplement- United Nations Economic Development
Organization recommends.</TITLE>

Early in 1995, a local Baikalsk newspaper (<I>Baikalskiy Celluloznik</I>,
January 5) published information about the invitation of UNIDO (United
Nations Economic Development Organization) experts to develop one more
program for conversion of the Plant.  The experts' tasks were to
provide independent, expert advice on modifications to the process
employed at the Baikalsk Pulp and Paper Plant.  In September, 1995 a
meeting to discuss the results of UNIDO's study  took place in
Baikalsk.  Excerpts from the UNIDO Final Document follow:<P>

"The Baikalsk Plant doesn't have a serious impact on Lake Baikal. From
the beginning of it's work in the 60s until 1990, the Baikalsk Plant
waste discharges are probably the best in the world.  Since then, only
a few enterprises which produce Kraft have been able to match the
quality of the Baikalsk discharges."<P>

"There are no appropriate alternatives to closing the Plant, so we can
avoid  the expenses connected with social issues. "The best protection
for the Lake will be if the existing Plant is modernized."<P>

"The standards for discharge at Baikalsk are the strictest in the
entire world. It is practically impossible to meet them."<P>

"The Plant has very good production capacity and good domestic and foreign market.<P>

"The technological processes at this plant, in comparison with similar
plants elsewhere, are relatively clean."<P>

"It is possible to achieve zero water and air emissions from this type
of industry, but it will require big investments. <P>

"At present, the Plant purifies waste
waters and produces energy.  It is possible to monitor it's air
emissions and water discharges.  It will be more difficult to monitor
the situation if somebody establishes small enterprises."<P>

"The only advantage of the Plant closure will be the elimination of air
emissions, which rae above established limits now, but not dangerous,
according to scientific research."<P>

"The closure of the plant will bring unemployment.  Recultivation of
the surrounding areaafter  dismantling the Plant will require
$229,000,000 US, and total expenses, including social and economic
costs, will be about $600,000,000 US.  It is difficult to find money
for those purposes." <P>

"Also, it is difficult to decide who will be responsible for the
storage of lignine. <P>

The will be no way to treat municipal wastes if the Plant is
closed."<P>

"In order to seriously consider the establishment of timber, wood
products, furniture, etc., serious feasibility studies and a real
business plan are needed."<P>

"There are no advantages to the idea of moving industrial facilities to
Selenginsk." <P>

"Discharges will be the same as at the Baikalsk Plant.  The bleaching
process in Selenginsk will cost more, since it will require additional
technological capacities, and capital investments will be much higher
than if the Baikalsk Plant is remodeled."<P>

"Due to the fact that, at present, no harm to Baikal is done by the
Baikalsk Plant, we recommend modernization, which will  reduce energy
consumption and minimize discharges into the lake, reduce air emissions
and solid waste discharges."<P>

"Complete modernization can be accomplished within the five year
period."<P>

[<I>See also</I> <A HREF="mccubbin.html">Neil McCubbin, formerly of UNIDO team,
comments.</A>]
<HR>


