<TITLE>Baikal Currents- Neil McCubbin, formerly of UNIDO team, comments.</TITLE>

<H1>Neil McCubbin, formerly of UNIDO team, comments.</H1>

<H3>Published by request of Neil McCubbin. Unedited.</H3>

I was very interested to receive your special supplement to your <A HREF="fall95.html">"Baikal
Currents"</A> newsletter which addressed the UNIDO study of the Baikalsk town and
industry in 1995.  As one of the members of the UNIDO team, I would like to
correct some misconceptions in the <A HREF="supp95un.html">document</A>, which I hope will be helpful in
resolving this issue in a logical way.<p>

Please note that I am writing this because I am interested in Baikal. My
assignment with UNIDO is over, and I have no professional involvement.<p>

<H2>Summary</H2>

The starting point of any discussion must be the situation as it exists to-day,
with an operating pulp mill on the shores of Lake Baikal.  Many hard words have
been said in the past, but re-hashing them leads only to hard feelings, not
solutions.<p>

Most people involved recognize that Lake Baikal deserves the highest level of
environmental protection, for scientific reasons (it is a very special body of
water) and also because is has a special place in the hearts of Russians.<p>

The UNIDO team was made up of seven independent experts from outside Russia,
some of whom have extensive experience in pulp and paper, while others have a
background in sociology etc. that gives them a very broad view of the world. 
All have experience in working in a variety of  economic, technical and
climatic conditions.  Only two could conceivably have a financial interest in
the modernization of the mill in the sense that their employers are are
engineers who get involved in building mills.  Their company, PI, is prabably
too small to become involved in Baikalsk.  I consider their inclusion in the
group quite reasonable, due to their engineering knowledge and the need for a
balanced analysis.  To the others, there is no conceivable financial advantage
in the outcome of the Baikalsk dispute.  I have been involved in developing
environmental regulations in Canada and the US, and have been widely criticized
by the industry for being too demanding.<p>

We all accepted the assignment because it is professionally interesting.  The
fees UNIDO pays are far below world market rates.<p>

The mandate was to consider all aspects, and we were given no instructions or
subjected to pressure to recommend a particular solution by UNIDO.  Naturally,
the mill staff wanted to keep the mill running, some local environmentalists
wished to close it, and we heard a number of positions expressed by the people
involved.<p>

The key issue is "What is best for Baikal?"  The team concluded that the Lake
and region are best with a modern, environmentally clean operating mill, which
would take care of the residual sludge lagoons and reduce air emissions
substantially.  We could not see any realistic possibility of developing
alternative industries in the town in any reasonable time frame.  It would
require at least tern years to develop industry and/or tourism to support the
population.  Other developments would not necessarily be environmentally
friendly. Around the world, the large modern industries are becoming cleaner,
while small industry and commence is much harder to control.  Tourism, in
particular, can be a serious environmental problem.<p>

If the mill is shut down, we have serious concerns that the money to clean up
the site would not be available, and that uncontrollable industry would take
over, with undesirable environmental consequences. In principle, the government
is responsible, but in view of much more serious concerns elsewhere, we believe
that if the mill is shut down, it would simply rot, and ultimately the lignin
lagoons would leak to the lake due to lack of maintenance.<p>

The greatest environmental risk would be that the mill continue, with
modernization paralyzed by continuing dispute, till the mill cannot maintain
its environmental protection measures.<P>

<H2>Comments by NGO's on UNIDO Report</H2>

Some points require clarification or correction.

<H3>UNIDO team</H3>

Refer to above, and note that the Finnish and Austrian suppliers of pulping
equipment who were at the Baikalsk meetings in September, were NOT involved in
the team.  I believe they were invited to the mill to explain the environmental
advantages of the technology the mill.  The UNIDO team had no contact with them
prior to reaching conclusions and writing the report.<p>

<H3>Emission Regulations.</H3>

We did not say they should be adapted to mill capacity.  We said they should be
based on mass flow of pollutants, NOT concentration.  If limits are based on
concentration, them the mill is encouraged to use plenty water to dilute
discharges.  We discussed limits in terms of kg/ton pulp since this is the
practical and widely accepted way of comparing mills and environmental
protection technology.  The mill limits should be converted to units of kg/day
that are low enough to protect the lake and to force the best available
pollution prevention technology.  Some of the current limits are far lower than
science can support, and only serve to force additional energy consumption for
no benefit.<p>

NGO's questioned "If mill is so good, why modernize".  The answer is to correct
equipment of declining efficiency and to make the mill best in the world with
respect to water pollution.  It was best for many years, but technical advances
have put a few mills ahead of it.  Also, the technology we recommended is a
major step towards zero effluent.<p>

We do not regard a reduction in mill employment as positive step.  It is a fact
of life that technological advances increase efficiency. They also increase
prosperity ,and open up other employment opportunities. We are well aware of
the significance of incinerating dioxin containing sludge.  The process can be
controlled satisfactorily.  The fact is the sludge exists, and a positive
solution is desirable.  The tendency to criticize all incineration because some
incinerators do not work well defies common sense.<p>

When criticizing the unreasonably low limit on methyl mercaptan discharges, we
are well aware of the Siberian conditions.  The mills we referred to with
respect to the limit of 0.05 kg/ton produce anywhere from 200 to 3000 tons per
day pulp.  Baikalsk has about half the capacity of the average mill in North
America or Scandinavia or Brazil.<p>

We are very well aware of the unique quality of Baikal water.  We examined
considerable data from Russian and foreign investigators, and considered the
reliability of the data carefully.  I have worked in Canada for many years,
where the climate is similar to Siberia.<p>

When we pointed out that Irkutsk had an effect on the lake, we were referring
to airborne pollutants.  I assume the comments in the newsletter were due to a
mistranslating somewhere.<p>

I am not sure it is true to say that developed countires wish to encourage
primary processing of raw materials in developing countries to protect their
own environments.  However, this is a very complex issue, and I agree that
there are may things to criticize in the policy of the developed countries.<p>

There is a worldwide problem in that developed countries have more stringent
environmental controls, but this is not relevant to Baikal, since the mill
regulations are much more stringent than in any Western country.  I suggest
that the solution to the Baikalsk problem can be found best by logical
discussion, and not by unsupported emotional statements.<p>

Neil McCubbin<BR>
Quebec, Canada<BR>
FAX    514 242 3294<BR>
E-mail mccubbin@hexonx.com

