<H1>For Life In Baley</H1>

<TITLE>Baikal Currents Supplement- For Life In Baley</TITLE>

Baley  is a town in the Chita region with a population of 23 thousand,located on
the Unda river, 350 kilometers east of Chita, approximately 1000 kilometers from Baikal.<P>

This town, despite being small and very remote, is well known as one of the centers of the Russian gold mining industry.<P>

Gold was discovered in Baley  during the "gold rush" at the end of the 19th century.  In 1928, quartz veins rich in gold were discovered.  In
August, 1929,  an enterprise called BaleyZoloto (Gold of Baley) was established
and intensive gold mining began.<P>

By 1933, 33 per cent of the entire gold mining of Eastern Siberia was
concentrated in Baley. <P>

But Baley is also known (not so broadly, though) as a center for mining monocite,
a mineral which contains uranium and thorium 232. Thus, the natural level of
background radiation in Baley is rather high: 60-70 microroentgen per hour (in
Chita it is 14-16 microroentgen per hour). <P>

The entire area of Zabaikal'e is known for a very peculiar natural environmental
condition: high levels of radon and  radioactive emissions, which are good to
keep in mind whenever talking about development in this area.<P>

As complex a situation as this is, it has been further  complicated by the
careless and irresponsible development during the Soviet era: after the ore was
processed, sand tailing dumps  were not properly taken care of, and no
rehabilitation measures took place.  Instead, this fine, nice-looking golden sand
was used by the developer (now shut down, it was a subdivision of what is now
Minatom:  Ministry of Nuclear Affairs)  for the construction of apartment
buildings and  kindergartens.  Indeed, a prudent developer never wastes any
materials! And this action caused a disaster.<P>

For years people have been exposed to high levels of radioactivity and didn't
even suspect it.  The Chita Branch of Federal Medical Sanitary Inspection tried
to draw attention to this fact in the 80s, but at the time, this area was
"classified" and monitoring of the site was the domain of the Third Department
(connected to the Defense Ministry) of  the Ministry of Health. Subsequently, the
results of the monitoring were never made public.  Only in 1992 was the local
sanitary inspection allowed to perform an Environmental Impact Statement. The
radiological EIS confirmed that the situation in Baley, Krasnokamensk, and
Oktyabrskiy was disastrous. (The remaining dumps have still not  complied with
all existing regulations). <P>

<H2>Extracts from the report of 1992  geochemical expedition</H2>

 There are 11
local abnormalities within the total area of 11 square kilometers, with a high
background radiation at 50 bekkerel per cubic meter (this is 6 to 33 times normal
levels). <P>

71 buildings were inspected, 27 of them apartment buildings.  Radon concentration
is 2 to 37 times above the permissible level, at  200 bekkerel per cubic meter.
Thus, the annual dose of radiation is over 2 ber per year, or 4 times higher than
accepted norms.<P>

<H2>Extracts from "The Report on the Health of the Population of the Chita
region"</H2>

Nov. 14, 1994 by the Eastern Siberian Science Center of the
Russian Academy of Medicine:<P>

A preliminary medical-ecological survey conducted in 1993 by the Siberian Branch
of the Medical Scientific Academy revealed that the level of oncological disease
(predominantly lung cancer) in Baley outrates all other places in the Chita
region.  It is 3-4 times higher than in other areas.  Down's syndrome is
diagnosed here 3-5 times more often than in European areas.  A survey of
children's health revealed a devastating situation:  <P>

95.4% of children suffer minor physical abnormalities, <P>

81% have changes in immunnograms (three times higher than normal)  Concentrations
of sodium in hair is 8 to 25 times higher than normal<P>

Concentrations of manganese is 3 to 48 times higher than normal.<P>

In atmospheric air in Baley, proportions of lead, manganese, arsenic and  mercury
are 50 times higher than allowed by sanitary norms.  19 percent of women in Baley
and Krasnokamensk (a town with an industrial uranium mine, south of Baley) end
their pregnancy with miscarriages.<P>

54.8 % of children have speech problems and psychological activities connected
with the development of speech are reduced.<P>

Compensatory abilities of the nervous system are very limited.<P>

The level of congenital abnormalities in children of Baley and Krasnokamensk
(9.83 per 1000) is 5.2 times higher than in Irkutsk, and 3-8 times higher than in
Kazakhstan or St. Petersburg.<P>

4.7% of children were diagnosed with oncological disease.<P>

Rather rare problems, such as congenital cataracts, are registered extremely
often in Baley.<P>

73.3 % of the children have symptoms of immune deficiency.<P>

<H2>From  interviews with  the  citizens of Baley:</H2>

"If I learn that I got cancer, I'll find a gun and go and shoot all our
government officials. I don't care, since I will die anyway..."  <P>

"Shall we write a  letter to the United Nations in order to be heard?"<P>

"Probably, all of us who live in contaminated houses shall gather together, go to
the closest train station and block the railroad. Maybe then somebody will pay
attention to our situation?"<><P>

<H2>Chronology of official documents and events on Baley.</H2>

The radiological situation in Baley was studied by a Federal Environmental Impact
Statement on October 15, 1992.<P>

The Chita Regional Administration developed a program for the Normalization of
the Radioactive Situation in Baley, Krasnokamensk and Oktyabrskiy for 1993-19925.
The estimated cost was over 8 billion rubles (1992 prices).<P>

Federal Agencies approved the program as a whole on July 26, 1993,  and
recommended that Minatom include measures to rehabilitate the areas contaminated
as a result of nuclear industry, allocating 2,487 billion rubles from the federal
budget.<P>

This decision was confirmed by the Russian Government on July 6, 1994 with The
Emergency Measure on Handling Radioactive Wastes for 1994. In addition, an
agreement allocating 785 million rubles to he Chita region was signed. (Not one
kopeck has been received from federal funds for this program so far).<P>

Also, the Chita region, parts of which the EIS declared to be disaster areas,
became a part of the Federal Program "RADON", which was established in 1994-95 to
reduce levels of radiation among the population.  This program (which is still
not adopted by the government) also suggests allocating  money from the regional
budgets. This means that it will not be implemented, since the Chita Regional
Treasury is empty.<P>

In 1993, 8 million rubles were provided for Baley to take care of its problems.
According to the estimates of the local administration it will annually require
4,500,000,000 rubles (1993 prices).<P>

Meanwhile, the situation in Baley and the surrounding area becomes more and more
devastating. <P>

<H2>For Rich or For Poor, For Better or For Worse......?</H2>

A Canadian gold company, Armada Gold, holds 56% of the shares of Baley Gold and
49% of Baley Tailings. According to information provided by the company itself on
the World Wide Web, the gold deposit at Baley is an open pittable resource of
approximately  65 million tons at a grade of 3.3 gm/ton or 6.9 million ounces.
The tailings have an average of 0.8 gm of gold per ton, and contain about 1.1
million ounces. <P>

Feasibility studies have been completed and they propose resuming operations at
Baley in the summer of 1996. <P>

<H2>Goal of the <A HREF="bcci.html">Baikal Center</A>  Program</H2>

In response to a request from the town administration and the NGO "For Life In
Baley" and in cooperation with the Chita Branch of The Baikal Fund, we are
initiating a two-fold program:<P>

1. To find an approach which will allow some positive changes for Baley;<P>

2. To empower local people to make these changes.<P>

The final objectives of the program are:<P>

1. To develop documents for consideration by the Government of the Russian
Federation for recognition of Baley as an ecological disaster zone (which 	<P>

means that some emergency funds will be allocated from the federal budget);<P>

2. To introduce a legal initiative as a measure of social justice for Baley
citizens 	<P>

and to provide compensatory measures;<P>

3. To publish a booklet with stories of Baley inhabitants and Baley as a study
case; <P>

4. To initiate a civil case on behalf of families in Baley.<P>

Also, while working on this program, we are  looking for charitable organizations
which will be able and willing to provide assistance to the Baley Children's
Hospital, which is in a state of collapse.  For more information and a list of
emergency help needed please  contact us at  e-mail: <baikalwatch@igc.apc.org> or
<chita@glas.apc.org>, or <irkutsk@glas.apc.org><P>

<HR>

Financial support for this program was provided by <B>United States Agency for
International Development</B> through the <B>Save the Children Foundation</B>.<P>

This issue  was prepared by Jonathan Burstein, I. Dyatlovskaya-Birnbaum.<P>

Special thanks to Lev Khodyrev, Valentina Dudareva, Tatiana Strizhova, Michael
Grachev, Sergey Shapkhaev, Arkady Kalikhman, Vera Shelenova for providing
informational assistance.<P>

WebMaster is Ken Yarborough at Earth Island Institute.


