<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The  Borneo Project: A Community-based Mapping Workshop,
Baram Region, Sararak</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFBC0" TEXT="800000">


<H2>A Community-based Mapping Workshop,
Baram Region, Sararak</H2>
1995
<P></P>


<P>In mid-1995 The Borneo Project conducted a mapping workshop in the Baram region of Sarawak, East Malaysia.  The intent of the workshop was to provide the indigenous representatives in the area with practical skills they would need to be able to produce maps of their land and resources.  Maps can be an important source of documentation for indigenous resource knowledge, land use, and planning.  And, in light of the continuing destruction of the forests for timber production and other land conversion schemes, maps can be a critical form of documentation for legal defense of native customary lands.</P>

<IMG SRC="mapping.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT alt="Map of Borneo" VSPACE=5 HSPACE=5>

<P>
	The workshop was held at the longhouse village of Sungai Keluan (Berkeley's sister community), but participants came from all over the Baram region.  Participants, men and women, ranged in age from 18 to 70.  We emphasized the importance of participation of as many different people in the community as possible.  And while some had received more education than others (especially the younger folks), others had a profound knowledge of the local landscape, including local names and boundaries, which was critical to the mapping efforts.  </P>
<P>
	The approach taken in conducting the workshop was twofold: first, we emphasized the fact that they are the experts on their land and resources, and therefore it is up to them to determine what would be mapped; second, we taught mapping concepts and techniques, and provided materials needed to gather data and produce maps. </P>
<P>
	In order to determine and prioritize the mapping needs of the participants, we facilitated a number of group discussions which encouraged participants to think about the issues they needed to address and the resources to be mapped.  Next we conducted a sketch-mapping exercise in which members from the various communities used tape, string, paper and any other materials they chose to layout a large-scale map of their lands; these tactile maps were then transferred onto paper maps.  The results were astounding.  After hours of enthusiastic and animated discussions, the groups had produced high quality, albeit not highly accurate, maps of their respective territories, most seeing their land on a map for the first time.
	The formal training component of the workshop can be divided into two distinct phases: (1) "classroom" instruction of map-related concepts and techniques; (2) practical exercises in data collection, plotting of field data, and drafting of final maps. </P>
<P>
	The teaching of the conceptual material was perhaps the most challenging part of the workshop.  Concepts such as scale, compass direction and geographic coordinates are complex, especially for people with a limited education.  However, with repetition and some creative improvisation, we were able to convey these concept to a majority of the participants.  This was an important component of preparing them for making meaningful and accurate maps. </P>
<P>
	After several days of instruction in the corrugated steel-roofed community pavilion we were all ready to go into the field.  Splitting into teams, we surveyed trails, streams, and boundaries using compass (direction) and tape (distance), meticulously recording data points and significant features on the landscape.  In addition, to the traditional compass and tape, we used to 2 global positioning system (GPS) units (donated by Magellan Systems Corp.) to gather precise geographic coordinates for selected points.  While introducing this technology complicated the process of instruction, the power of this tool has the potential to greatly enhance mapping efforts in the region. Phase II of the mapping project will involve a follow-up training in the more advanced applications of GPS.</P>
<P>
	In the final few days of the workshop we turned to the task producing maps from the data we had collected.  After determining an appropriate scale, each team plotted the survey data they'd collected onto graph paper.  The survey lines were then rectified according to GPS points, which provided a network of "control points" of geographic coordinates, providing a link to maps of Sarawak or the world as a whole.  Finally, this "raw" data was to be traced onto a final map, to which was added a legend, title, scale, source, and other pertinent information.  Unfortunately, time constraints prevented us from plotting all the points collected and producing a final map.  But we were gratified to find out that within a week of our departure, the participants continued the work and produced a high-quality map of their forest preserve area. </P>
<P>
	The enthusiasm over the mapping workshop was palpable among the participants.  Village elders stressing the importance of recorded information about their land renewed the struggle to defend their way of life.  The younger generations feeling empowered expressed optimism about controlling their own future.  And we out-of-place Westerners preparing for departure felt that we had learned as much if not more from these peaceful, good-natured people living their day-to-day existence in the beautiful, at times harsh, Borneo interior.</P>
<HR>

