<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Borneo Project: Lahmeyer International is Planning Bakun Hydropower Project in Sarawak,
Malaysia</TITLE></HEAD>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFBC0" TEXT="800000">

<P>
Press Release, Lahmeyer International Frankfurt am Main Germany  October 17,
1995 
</P>

<H2>Lahmeyer International is Planning Bakun Hydropower Project in Sarawak,
Malaysia 
</H2>

<P>Bakun, the most important hydroelectric power plant in Southeast Asia with
an installed generating capacity of 2400 megawatts and a financial cost of more
than six billion DM, is to be constructed over a period of seven years and
finished by the year 2003. Lahmeyer International has been contracted to plan
the hydropower facility and to draw up the contract documents for the
construction and tendering and will support the project development groups
during their contract negotiations.  
</P>

<HR> 

<H2>Seminar on Bakun Dam: Feasibility, Impact and Alternatives
</H2>

<P>
 2nd &amp; 3rd December 1995    </P>

<P> Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia 
</P>

<P>(Organised jointly by Institute For Community Education and Selangor Chinese
Assembly Hall-Youth, in collaboration with the Coalition of 40 Malaysian NGOs)  
                  </P>

<CENTER>SEMINAR RESOLUTION 
</CENTER>

<P>The Non-Governmental Organisations (NGOs) and participants present at the
Bakun Dam Seminar on the dam's feasibility, impact and alternatives held on the
2nd and 3rd of December 1995 call upon the Government to address the following
issues:</P>

<P>1) Viability
</P>

<P>
Serious questions have been raised concerning the Bakun Hydroelectric Project's
(HEP) viability in terms of economic, ecological, technical, social and cultural
considerations.  Specifically, the Bakun HEP is not economically viable; and the
current dam design has not adequately addressed the dangers of flooding and
reservoir-induced seismicity.  We urge the Government to seriously consider
viable alternatives to the existing Bakun HEP proposal. Views and suggestions
from the public and concerned NGOs must be seriously considered.
</P>

<P>
2) Access to Information 
</P>

<P>We urge the government to make publicly available all 17 feasibility studies
and reports conducted on the Bakun HEP. All the appendices, interim and final
reports of the relevant Environment Impact Assessments must also be made
accessible to the general public. We urge the Government to declare publicly its
resettlement plan for the affected communities. 
</P>

<P>3) Public Accountability 
</P>

<P>We urge the government to respect due process of environment impact
assessments (EIA) by making all EIA reports publicly available prior to their
approval. We urge the Government to conduct integrated studies into the Bakun
HEP as one single project, to consider its social consequences, economic costs,
and ecological impact. 
</P>

<P>4) The Needs of the Indigenous Communities 
</P>

<P>We are concerned that the Government's Resettlement Plans have not been made
public. It is our understanding that there is a plan to resettle the affected
communities in the infertile Belaga area in which they cannot make a decent
living - this is not acceptable. We further note that the affected communities
themselves have expressed opposition to this resettlement plan.  We urge the
Government to resolve all outstanding issues pertaining to the resettlement and
compensation of the affected communities.  We further urge the Government to
base its development projects on a serious consideration of the needs and
aspirations of the indigenous communities. It is essential that all the people
participate in the decision-making process, and are informed of all alternatives
related to this Bakun HEP. 
</P>

<P>5) Alternatives
</P>

<P>
We understand that there are sufficient energy alternatives that are cheap and
viable to sustain Malaysia's future energy requirements. There should be a
coherent Energy Policy based on energy conservation and renewable resources.  We
urge the Government to explore all other viable energy alternatives to the Bakun
HEP. The Bakun HEP must not resume until all such studies are exhausted.
</P>

<P>
6) Access 
</P>

<P>We urge the Malaysian and Sarawak Government to provide unrestricted access
to Sarawak and the Bakun HEP site to all concerned individuals and NGOs.  In
this regard, we protest that Dr. Weilou Wang was unable to obtain a visa to
attend this seminar and share his expertise with the participants. This was in
spite of him making his applications one month before the seminar.
</P>

<P>
7) Ultimate Responsibility
</P>

<P>We urge the Government to clarify its position in committing public funds to
the construction of the Bakun HEP.  Since Ekran Berhad is believed to bear only
20% of Bakun HEP's total equity, we urge the Government to clarify the parties
financially responsible for the completion, operation and maintenance of the
Bakun HEP.  We further urge the Government to give a public assurance that the
electricity tariffs will not be increased to subsidise the Bakun HEP.  WE URGE
THE GOVERNMENT TO CEASE ALL WORK ON THE PROJECT SITE, AND MUST NOT RESUME, UNTIL
ALL THE ABOVE MATTERS ARE RECTIFIED. 
</P>

<HR> 

<H2>Sarawak Government empowered to approve EIA Report
</H2>

<P>
The Borneo Post (front page)
</P>

<P>December 7, 1995  KUALA LUMPUR. The Sarawak Government is empowered to
evaluate and approve the Environment Impact Assessment (EIA) report for the
Bakun hydro-electricity project, the Dewan Rakyat, was told today.  Following
the passage of the Sarawak Natural Resources and Environment Ordinance 1993, the
state government has such powers, Deputy Minister of Science, Technology and
Environment Datuk Abu Bakar Daud said. 
</P>

<P>The Ordinance was to ensure that development projects which were likely to
have an effect on the environment were subjeced to EIA studies particualrly
projects involving resources under the jurisdiction of the state government. 
The Bakun hydro project was government by the ordinance, Abu Bakar said when
winding up the debate at committee stage on matters pertaining to his minstry in
the Supply Bill for next year. 
</P>

<P>He was responding to the points raised by Dr Maximus Johnity Ongkili
(PBS-Bandau) who wanted to know why the Sarawak Government had been given the
power to approve the EIA report and had expressed the hope that it would not set
precedent for other states. 
</P>

<P>At this point Dr Tan Seng Giaw (DAP-Kepong) rose to say that conferring such
powers to approve EIA reports to state government was not correct in line with
moves to coordinate efforts to safeguard the environment.  Abu Bakar said under
the Federal Constitution land and forests were under the jurisdiction of state
governments.   
</P>

<HR> 

<H2>BAKUN BULLETIN  
</H2>

<P>This bulletin was prepared by Sahabat Alam Malaysia (SAM/Friends of the
Earth, Malaysia). They may reached at 27 Lorong Maktab, 10250 Penang, Malaysia.
Fax No: + 6 04 375  705, Phone No: + 6 04 376 930. 
</P>

<P>1. BAKUN CASE POSTPONED TO 24 JANUARY 1996 
</P>

<P>~ The legal suit brought by Kajing Tubek, Tahu Lujah and Saran Imu against
Ekran Berhad, the Malaysian Government and the Malaysian Director General of
Environmental Quality has been adjourned yet again at the behest of the
defendants. 
</P>

<P>~ The case was originally meant to be heard by the Kuala Lumpur High Court
on 4 August 1995 but was adjourned to 14 December 1995 . However, due to a last
minute application by the Attorney Generals chambers to the High Court, the case
has been adjourned once again--this time, to 24 January 1996 ... we hope it will
then be heard!  
</P>

<P>2. SECOND PART OF BAKUN EIA APPROVED WITHOUT PUBLIC FEEDBACK 
</P>

<P>~According to Ekran's executive chairman, Tan Sri Ting Pek Khiing, the
second part of the environmental impact assessment (EIA) report was approved by
the Sarawak Natural Resources and Environment Board (NREB) on 9 December 1995. 
The second part of the EIA cocncerns the construction of the dam and ancillary
facilities.  Public interest groups such as Sahabat Alam Malaysia have expressed
their outrage at the approval of the second EIA by the NREB:
</P>

<P>
~The practice of making EIAs available to the public after it is approved makes
the EIA meaningless. EIAs have to be made public before they are approved. This
is to enable comments to be made to the relevant approving bodies. Approval
should be given only after the comments are given due and proper consideration.
For a gigantic and controversial project like the Bakun dam it is all the more
reason why the EIA must be displayed and made public before it is approved. An
open and transparent EIA process will strengthen public confidence.</P>

<P>~The first part of the EIA, on Reservoir Preparation was approved by the
NREB in April this year. The approval of the first EIA also generated tremendous
controversy as the authority for approval of the EIA was transfered from the
federal level (the Department of Environment) to the state level (the NREB). 
The transfer of jurisdiction from federal level to the state level was effected
by a retrospective amendment to the Environmental Quality (Prescribed
Activities) (Environmental Impact Assessment) Order 1987, which was published in
the Government Gazette of 21 April 1995.  3. Financing and Construction of the
Bakun dam
</P>

<P>~ Ekran Berhad intends to list its 100 per cent owned Bakun Hydroelectric
Corporation Sdn Bhd on the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) as a means of
financing the RM 15 billion Bakun Hydroelectric Project (BHEP). Ting Pek Khiing,
the executive chairman of Ekran said an application for the proposed listing
would be made to the Securities Commission next year.  
</P>

<P>~ The construction of the Bakun dam will be undertaken by the Bakun
Hydroelectric Corporation Sdn. Bhd. (BHC). While the tender for the construction
of the dam, power plant and transmission lines will be closed on 15 January
1996, the BHC has already awarded a RM 247 million contract to the South Korean
Dong-Ah Construction and Industrial Co. to divert the Balui River.  Dong-Ah
Construction and Industrial Co. built the Songsu bridge over the Han River in
central Seoul which collapsed, killing 32 people in October last year.  
</P>

<HR>

