<TITLE>STRP: Why should you ask for Turtle-Safe shrimp?</TITLE>

<H1>Why should you ask for Turtle-Safe shrimp?</H1>

Responsible Shoppers want to know<BLOCKQUOTE> Can we have our shrimp and save rare, wild sea turtles too?</BLOCKQUOTE>

Sea turtles have lived quietly on Earth for 100 million years. Yet six out of
the seven species of sea turtles are now in danger of extinction. Shrimp
fishing is one of the major reasons. By asking for Turtle-Safe shrimp, you help
create an incentive for shrimp fisherman to protect endangered sea
turtles.<P>

<H2>How do sea turtles get caught in the nets?</H2><P>

As shrimp nets are dragged through the water, they catch everything in their
path - needlessly trapping unwanted fish and sea turtles. Sea turtles ensnared
in shrimp nets are held under until they drown. Thousands of endangered sea
turtles are killed this way every year.<P>

<H2>How can shrimp nets be made Turtle-Safe?</H2><P>

It's easy. By using Turtle Excluder Devices (TEDs), shrimp fishermen help
protect sea turtles without reducing their catch of shrimp. TEDs are grids that
are sewn into shrimp nets and guide sea turtles out an escape hatch. TEDs not
only let sea turtles escape, they also keep  out much of the otherwise wasted
fish, protecting shrimp caught in the nets and saving fishermen the time of
sorting through their catch.<P>

<H2>Aren't sea turtles protected by law?</H2><P>

Yes, and the law requires shrimp fisherman in the U.S. and 14 other countries
that export shrimp to the U.S. to use TEDs. But more than 2,000 sea turtles
washed up in 1994, suggesting that many shrimpers are failing to comply with
the law. Additionally, seafood suppliers continue to import shrimp from
countries where TEDs are not required.<P>

<H2>How does the Turtle-Safe program work?</H2><P>

Members of the nonprofit Earth Island Institute fund educational and marketing
efforts in cooperation with responsible shrimp fishers. Participating fisherman
sign agreements with Earth Island Institute stipulating that they properly
utilize TEDs and agree to monitoring. Their catch is registered as Turtle-Safe.
Earth Island observers monitor compliance from the boats to the marketplace, to
certify that shrimp is Turtle-Safe. The goal is simple: by giving shrimp
fisherman the every reason to comply with laws protecting sea turtles, together
we can help rescue these exotic, gentle creatures from the brink of
extinction.<P>

<H2>Won't you join us?</H2><P>

Help make sure these endangered creatures survive. Three things you can do
right now are listed on the back of this pamphlet. To join us today, call the
number below. And remember, always look for the Turtle-Safe shrimp mark when
buying shrimp.<P>

Only wild shrimp caught in TED-equipped net, or outside sea turtle habitats
are certified Turtle-Safe.<P>

Farm raise shrimp are not certified because their ponds can destroy habitat and
pollute water.<P>

<H2>3 things you can do to save endangered sea turtles</H2><P>

<OL>

<LI><B>Eat only turtle safe shrimp.</B><P>

Shrimp nets that don't allow sea turtles to escape are a major threat to these
endangered creatures. By asking for Turtle Safe shrimp, you help create an
incentive for shrimp fisherman to protect endangered sea turtles.<P>

<LI><B>Spread the word among your friends, and the businesses you patronize. </B><P>

Look for the Turtle-Safe shrimp mark where you dine and shop. If you don't see
it, let grocers and chefs know you'll accept nothing less. The more people
demand Turtle-Safe shrimp, the sooner we ca stop the slaughter of sea
turtles.<P>

<LI><B>Learn more about sea turtles and how you can protect them. </B><P>

</OL>

The campaign to rescue sea turtles is a campaign to protect our ocean
environment. These shy, quiet , mysterious creatures outlasted the dinosaurs.
But will they survive the 20th century? You can make a difference. Join us by
calling (800) 859-SAVE. For more information about sea turtles and how you can
help save them, write us at our address below.<P>

Sea Turtle Restoration Project<BR>
300 Broadway, San Francisco, CA 94133<BR>
(800) 859-SAVE<P>

