<H1>STRP Central American Nesting Beach Program</H1>
<TITLE>STRP: Central American Nesting Beach Program</TITLE>

The goals of the Sea Turtle Restoration Project's Central American Sea Turtle Nesting Beach Program are to:<P>
<UL>
<LI>Address the root causes of the slaughter of sea turtles -uncontrolled commercial exploitation and lack of community control over natural resources- at both the national and local levels;<P>

<LI>Address the needs of local economies by promoting the establishment of locally engineered sustainable development alternatives to uncontrolled exploitation; <P>

<LI>Promote citizen participation in problem solving by developing educational campaigns that build links between activists in the affected countries and their U.S. counterparts; and<P>

<LI>Support emerging organizations in Central America in their call for international pressure to protect endangered sea turtles and our common marine resources.<P>

</UL>
At present we have focused our program primarily on the countries of Nicaragua and Mexico because of their prominent sea turtle nesting beaches. Our programs in these countries will be discussed separately below.<P>


<H2>Nicaragua</H2>

The olive ridley is known to have nested in <I>arribadas</I> exceeding 5,000 females at only a dozen beaches worldwide. Of these, two are located on the southern Pacific coast of Nicaragua, Chococente and Playa La Flor. Chococente is a National Wildlife Reserve, and Playa La Flor is located by the Nicaraguan village of Ostional, near the <A HREF="../gsc/costa.html">Costa Rican</A> border. <P>

IRENA, Nicaragua's natural resources agency reports <I>arribada</I> nesting aggregations of olive ridleys at both sites in the range of 5,000 to 10,000 individuals, but Stephen Cornelius (World Wildlife Fund, pers. comm.) believes the actual size of <I>arribadas</I> may be even higher. Even at the lower estimates, this would place these beaches among the nine largest extant nesting sites for this species. Leatherbacks, Pacific green turtles and hawksbills also nest at these sites.<P>

Local communities have harvested the eggs of turtles arriving in <I>arribadas</I> for thousands of years.  In the past, harvesting did not adversely affect the turtle populations since the number of harvested eggs was relatively small compared to the millions of eggs laid by the turtles. However, in recent years, increased ability to ship the eggs long distances, coupled with other pressures on turtle populations, have led to the continued decline of the populations. One solution has been sustainable egg harvesting programs including monitoring by biologists and establishment of permissible quotas for harvesting. The local communities are then allowed to harvest the permitted number of eggs from turtles arriving early in the year in exchange for patrolling and protecting the beach from poachers during late year arrivals.<P>

In 1981 the Nicaraguan government began operating sustainable egg-harvesting programs at these beaches. However, in the early 1990's a seriously deteriorating economic situation within the country caused major budget cuts which derailed the conservation programs. Sporadically, the beaches were either completely closed to locals by the Army or uncontrolled harvesting was allowed. In 1990 and 1991, the beaches were exploited by egg poachers with practically all of the eggs were being stolen because no funds were available to monitor or patrol the beaches. <P>

In the face of this ecological disaster, STRP initiated a decisive and aggressive program. STRP coordinated the construction of field stations and hired Nicaraguan biologists to conduct studies at these sites. We also funded park rangers at Playa la Flor and organized a sea turtle training program for Nicaraguan biologists, college students and resources managers. Continued research into the socio-economic aspects of human-sea turtle interactions, as well as the biological studies of sea turtles, are being used to develop policies to control the harvesting of eggs so as not to be detrimental to sea turtle populations, while meeting the needs of local communities. Work is continuing on long-term management plans for the areas. In addition, we have coordinated an exchange between Nicaraguan community leaders, biologists and resources managers involved in sustainable egg harvesting projects with their colleagues in Costa Rica who have also established egg harvesting programs.<P>

 The experiments underway at Chococente and Playa La Flor offer real hope for the sea turtles of the eastern Pacific. We will continue to raise resources and involve the international sea turtle community in support of these model programs. <P>

<H2>Mexico</H2>

In 1989 STRP began working with others to embarrass the Mexican government into closing a slaughterhouse where 35,000-75,000 turtles were being killed yearly. STRP traveled to Mexico and returned to the U.S. with a first-hand account of the carnage including graphic video footage. We launched a media and grassroots campaign in the U.S. which generated articles and editorials in major newspapers, magazines and television. Other national and international environmental organizations joined the campaign which generated more than 70,000 letters to the Mexican President. In 1990, Mexico responded to our pressure, declaring a permanent ban on the killing of sea turtles and agreeing to eventually join the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES), doing so in 1991. <P>

In addition to demanding closure of the slaughterhouse we advocated that economic alternatives be found for the local communities which had grown to rely on income from the harvest of these endangered animals. STRP initiated discussions toward transforming the former sea turtle slaughterhouse into a sea turtle natural history museum and won acceptance for this idea from local communities and Mexican environmental organizations. In September 1991, after extensive discussions with members of the Mexican government, President Salinas announced that "the sea turtle museum shall be created on the shores of Oaxaca." <P>

We were encouraged by the 1990 ban; however, our monitoring of Mexico's enforcement revealed serious backsliding in the following years. Accordingly, in 1993 STRP launched a major campaign to compel the Mexican government to enforce its sea turtle protection laws. STRP ran a full page ad in <I>The New York Times</I> to coincide with September 20, 1993 visit of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari to San Francisco, California, with the headline "DOES MEXICAN PRESIDENT CARLOS SALINAS HONOR HIS ENVIRONMENTAL PROMISES?" A protest was conducted outside of the International Industrial Conference, where president Salinas gave a speech on NAFTA, and President Salinas was compelled to revise his speech to address his pledge to protect sea turtles and use turtle excluder devices. He claimed that Mexico was enforcing its sea turtle protection laws and that Mexico was "vigorously enforcing" the use of turtle excluder devices on Mexican shrimp vessels. 
 
President Salinas requested a private meeting with STRP's Director, wherein he reiterated his personal commitment to the protection of sea turtles and agreed to an independent monitoring program for Mexican shrimp vessels. Unfortunately, however, the Mexican government never permitted the promised monitoring program.<P>

In addition to our efforts on the national level we have also been active at the local, community level. A unique program which integrates sea turtle protection with community development in a Nahuatl indigenous community in the towns of Colola- Maruata, Michoacan, Mexico, run by Mexican environmentalists has strived to find alternatives for communities which once commercially harvested sea turtles for their skin and meat In addition to involving the townspeople in the conservation program for sea turtles, local economic alternatives which are operating include: an iguana raising project, dying of textiles with natural dyes produced by a marine snail, a crafts/ceramic co-op and eco-tourism. STRP has been able to financially assist these endeavors through its expedition program.<P>

It has become clear that we will need to maintain our vigilance to protect turtles in Mexico, and we will continue to
<OL>
<LI>monitor enforcement by the Mexican government;
<LI>pressure the Mexican government to de-politicize sea turtle conservation to allow NGOs to participate in developing policies; and
<LI>encourage solutions that meet the needs of local communities. 
</OL>

