<H1>Expedition program</H1>
<TITLE>STRP: Expedition program</TITLE>

Our expedition program brings North Americans to critical sea turtle habitats to participate and provide needed human power in conservation activities. Learning about sea turtle conservation first-hand has proven to be an excellent tool for bringing the plight of the sea turtle to North Americans; our participants come home with an intense desire to help the sea turtles and the communities that surround their nesting beaches. Over the past three years STRP has coordinated several successful expeditions to important sea turtle nesting beaches in Mexico, Costa Rica and Nicaragua. <P>

One of the most important aspects of these expeditions is that they demonstrate to the local communities the international importance and uniqueness of their environment and the economic value of <B>living</B> sea turtles to their communities. In addition, these eco-expeditions can provide long-term support for sea turtle conservation and sustainable development projects. <P>

These expeditions also support the local community and conservation efforts in a more direct manner: a per person fee is paid to the host site which supports the conservation/research program. Local people are hired to assist the expedition group. Other expedition activities, such as sight-seeing excursions, also produce income for people from the local community. Overall, we estimate that over 70% of the money received for these expeditions is spent in the host country. The remainder is used to cover expenses of STRP staff time and to promote the expeditions.<P>

Direct support generated from our expeditions program resulted in funding a $4,000 grant proposal from Ostional, Costa Rica to complete a health clinic and community center and $1,800 to support sea turtle conservation at Mexico's most important nesting beaches for the black sea turtle in Colola, Michoacan<P>

<H2>More about STRP</H2>
<UL>
