<H1>STRP India Campaign</H1>
<TITLE>STRP: India Campaign</TITLE>

The Sea Turtle Restoration Project is launching a new campaign to preserve and protect the Bhitarkanika Reserve in India. This campaign will expand our work geographically (into India) and allow us to diversify ecologically to work towards the protection of a large number of endangered marine and terrestrial habitats and species. Our campaign is aimed at educating and empowering concerned citizens in the West to support a grassroots campaign in India to halt a development scheme that threatens the entire biodiversity of the southeastern India and local people's sustainable use of natural resources in this spectacular and sacred place. Indian environmentalists have specifically asked us to mount such an educational campaign in the West, to support their demands to protect the natural heritage of southeastern India. Furthermore, this campaign will help to build and solidify permanent links with these activists in our common fight to protect global biodiversity. <P>

STRP was approached because the threatened site includes the most important nesting beach in the world for the endangered olive ridley turtle and because of our past success in helping local activists draw international attention to their issues. As with all our campaigns, we see the sea turtle issue not only as a single-species environmental tragedy that needs immediate attention, but as a vehicle for shifting the paradigm of how the human species views its relationship with the natural world. We will continue to provide an analysis that stresses the unequal distribution of wealth and lack of community control of natural resources as the underlying roots of environmental destruction. <P>

The context for our work at Bhitarkanika can be summarized by a quote from Banka Behary Das:<P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
"If nature has any paradise it is here in Bhitarkanika. It is a gift of nature to humanity and should be conserved at any cost." <P>
</BLOCKQUOTE>

Banka Behary Das is is a "freedom fighter" who worked with Gandhi for the independence of India from Britain. He served 3 1/2 years in prison for his non-violent work, and after independence was elected to Parliament. He has now turned his attention to protecting the natural heritage of India and has founded a progressive NGO, Krushak Mahasangh, which has been instrumental in fighting for the protection of mangrove forests and local culture, and against prawn farming.  Mr. Das and his organization have requested our help to protect the Bhitarkanika Reserve.<P>

Bhitarkanika in Orissa, India is the site where more sea turtles nest than any other place in the world. As recently as March 1992, 610,000 pregnant females emerged from the sea to lay eggs during a six day period in the reserve. The mass simultaneous arrival called the <I>arribada</I> has been described as one of the most spectacular events of nature and occurs in great numbers at only four places on the entire planet. <P>

The Reserve is home to a large number of endangered species. White-breasted sea eagles hunt for food along the mangrove-lined shoreline which is filled with openbill and painted storks, and dozens of species of herons and egrets searching for fish and shrimp to feed their young. Six species of kingfishers and the largest population of bareheaded geese in Asia also call this place home. All told, 80,000 wading birds nest in the reserve. Two other endangered sea turtles also live and nest here, including the largest turtle in the world, the giant leatherback, and perhaps the most beautiful, the hawksbill. Endangered pythons and king cobras also live here, as do the endangered salt-water crocodile and an endangered soft-shelled turtle.<P>

The late Prime Minister Indira Gandhi recognized the importance of sea turtles to the people of India and the international importance of this nesting site for a species that migrates thousands of miles through the sovereign waters of many nations and into international seas. While sea turtles and their eggs were not eaten by the local people of Orissa, in the 1970s, outsiders came to exploit the eggs and meat for the markets of Calcutta and beyond. Gandhi had the beaches and forests of the area declared a reserve to protect the biodiversity of the region. <P>

<H2>The Threats</H2>

Now, twenty years later after Gandhi declared the area a reserve, this place is threatened by the construction of a commercial fishing port for 500 mechanized shrimp trawlers, a fish processing plant and a large shrimp farm operation only a few kilometers from the reserve. In addition, a road is planned to be built through the mangrove forest to service the construction of the port. <P>

Why has this location been chosen for the development of a port? One active environmentalist in India, a member of the IUCN Species Survival Commission summed it up in these few words "politics, vote-catching and money." Once again, lack of control of natural resources by the local community is resulting in the sacrifice of a natural treasure for the profit of a few at the expense of many.<P>

Shrimp vessels are notorious for drowning endangered sea turtles. Worldwide, more than 150,000 turtles drown in shrimp nets each year, although technology exists to prevent the capture of turtles.<P>

In the past ten years, there has already been a significant increase in shrimp trawlers in this region of Orissa, India, and with it an increase in turtles drowning in shrimp nets. Three thousand turtles or more wash up on shore each year at Bhitarkanika, and this represents only a small fraction of the turtles that actually die unnecessary and horrible deaths as they struggle to free themselves from the net to surface for air. Even when the turtles are still alive in the nets, fishermen often club the pregnant females to death to get them out of their nets, rather than cut and damage their nets and allow the turtles to escape alive.<P>

Regulations for the reserve require shrimp trawlers to stay five kilometers away from the nesting beach, but the law is almost never enforced. With a large increase in fishing vessels, the situation will only get much worse.<P>

Modern shrimp farming has proven to be a terribly destructive practice throughout the world. Large tracts of mangrove forests, the nursery grounds for most fish and shell-fish (including many pelagic species) are destroyed for the shrimp-growing ponds. Mangrove forests also provide nesting and feeding sites for wading birds, birds of prey, crocodiles and hundreds of additional species fish, reptiles, mammals and birds. Shrimp farming has not proven to be sustainable. After a few very profitable years (for the owners), the ponds become toxic and unusable due to the high input of fertilizers, antibiotics (including the widespread use of human antibiotics in Asia and South America), and waste produced from the extremely high density of shrimp. When a farm is no longer economically productive, the cheapest and most common practice is to abandon it and clearcut another tract of mangroves and move the operation. This type of shrimp farming has destroyed 80-90 percent of the mangrove forests of Ecuador and large areas of Asia and South America, as well as the livelihood of local communities who have long relied on the high productivity of mangrove forests for food, fuel and building materials. Regeneration of mangrove forests, and the biodiversity it supports, from land that was formerly in shrimp production is low, at best.<P>

Road-building through the mangroves to the fishery complex is expected to have the same effects on the region as road-building has had on forests in the U.S. and the Amazon. Increased access brings increases in poaching of wildlife and destruction of cultural and natural resources.<P>

Are there alternatives? Environmentalists in India stress that other ports in the region could easily be enlarged and modified to handle additional vessels and processing plants. Time is needed to develop plans that allow for sustainable use of natural resources which allow community control and benefit. Local communities must have access to information from other locales which have already felt the destructive impacts of increased trawling and shrimp farming on their local resources.<P>

<H2>The Plan of Action</H2>

Activists in India have called for an international campaign to pressure the government of India to reconsider any expansion of fishing, development and shrimp farming in the area that will adversely affect the reserve and the biodiversity of the region. To date, no U.S. organization other than Earth Island Institute has taken an active role in organizing such a campaign. <P>

The Sea Turtle Restoration Project of Earth Island Institute is in an excellent position to play a lead role in organizing a grassroots and high-profile media campaign to build a coalition with non-governmental organizations (NGOs) throughout the world. Earth Island's Sea Turtle Restoration Project and <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">International Marine Mammal Project</A> have had considerable success in mounting such campaigns. Our successful campaigns have lead to major worldwide changes in fishing practices that destroy marine diversity as demonstrated by:
<UL>
<LI>success of protecting <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">dolphins</A> from tuna fishing in the eastern Pacific
<LI>the closing of the notorious sea turtle slaughterhouse in Mexico
<LI>the international banning of driftnets, and 
<LI>the on-going campaign to implement the use of turtle excluder devices (TEDs) in the U.S. and worldwide. <P>
</UL>

In addition, Earth Island has personnel working on fishing issues in Asia, including <A HREF="../gsc/thai.html">Thailand</A> and the Philippines. Earth Island Institute has just formed a <A HREF="../map/map.html">Mangrove Action Project</A> (MAP) with NGOs from Asia and South America. We will work closely with this new project and be able to use their already strong connections in India and throughout Asia. Support has already been distributed to support regional conferences in Asia and South America on the impact of shrimp farming by MAN, and Earth Island personnel have developed extensive contacts with organizations concerned with this issue.<P>
<H2>More about STRP</H2>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="tsafe2news.html">Turtle-Safe shrimp news<P>
<LI><A HREF="tsafe1dry.html">Turtle-Safe(tm) shrimp<P>
<LI><A HREF="turtlesafe.html">Why should you ask for Turtle-Safe shrimp?</A>.<P>
<LI><A HREF="strpca.html">Central American Nesting Beach Program</A>.<P>
<LI><A HREF="strpexpd.html">Expedition program</A>.<P>
<LI><A HREF="strplati.html">Latin American Monitoring</A>.<P>
<LI><A HREF="strpprob.html">Statement of the Problem</A>.<P>
<LI><A HREF="strpted.html">International Implementation of Turtle Excluder Devices</A>.<P>
</UL>

