<H1>STRP Latin American Monitoring</H1>
<TITLE>STRP: Latin American Monitoring</TITLE>

The goals of this program are to:
<OL>
<LI>watchdog compliance with US and Mexican laws and international treaties designed to protect sea turtles and their habitats, and<LI>build and augment the grassroots environmental movement in Latin America for the protection of these global resources.
</OL>
This program targets Latin American countries for the following reasons:<P>
<OL>
<LI>US consumers are the primary users of the fish products derived from these fisheries, and therefore, we must assume some responsibility for ensuring the industry is conducted in an ecologically responsible way.<P>

<LI>The geographic area of concern borders the US as well as several Latin American countries. It is an extremely biologically diverse ecosystem and one in which highly industrial development is expanding and poorly controlled.<P>

<LI>STRP has already begun the process of building strong relationships with environmentalists in Central America.
</OL>		
<H2>Enforcement</H2>

The Latin American Monitoring Program seeks to collect evidence about whether marine protection laws and international treaties are being enforced. Specifically, monitors will determine the extent to which turtle excluder devices are used and whether the Mexican ban on the slaughter of turtles for leather and shells is being enforced.<P>

This program is necessary because industries cannot be expected to self-monitor and few governments expend the resources necessary to provide sufficient monitoring programs. Furthermore, enforcement mechanisms cannot be triggered without hard evidence of violations.<P>

In the United States citizen groups often act as watchdogs to ensure that environmental laws are implemented and enforced. When problems exist, these groups lobby regulators or Congress or they file lawsuits - and they are often successful. In Mexico and elsewhere in Latin America environmental protection is still in its formative stages. An environmental movement exists, but it is hampered by economic realities, the enormity of problems, corrupt government, and fear of reprisals.<P>

Environmental protection cannot be achieved simply by legislating within national boundaries. Recognizing this, and in an attempt to give parity to US industries competing with foreign companies, Congress has passed laws requiring companies exporting to the US to maintain standards of environmental protection comparable to those applied to domestic companies. These laws are: The Pelly Amendment to the Fishermen's Protective Act and Public Law 101-162. For instance PL. 101-162 requires foreign countries exporting shrimp to the US to abide by the same sea turtle kill rates permitted to US fleets.<P>

The acquisition of more hard data about compliance with these laws will provide the facts needed to convince the US to use diplomatic and trade pressures for international environmental protection. Also, our monitoring program will identify violations of national laws of Latin American countries. For instance, Mexico has laws that prohibit the slaughter of sea turtles and that require the use of <A HREF="strpted.html">TEDs</A>. There is widespread concern, and some evidence which we have obtained, that these laws are not being properly enforced. For example, recently a U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service biologist reported to STRP that 11 nesting Kemp's Ridley turtles (only 400 nesting Kemp's turtles remain in the world) were killed when Mexican shrimpers, with no <A HREF="strpted.html">TEDs</A>, were illegally trawling in a protected marine reserve. In another incident, poachers in Baja California were discovered with 20 dead sea turtles. They have gone unpunished. This monitoring program would be very useful in identifying and publicizing problems such as these and assisting Mexican conservation groups in pressing for enforcement of existing laws.<P>

<H2>Building the Environmental Movement</H2>

While we believe citizens in Latin American countries are as concerned with environmental protection as US citizens, an environmental movement on par with those in North America or Europe does not yet exist.<P>

A monitoring program in Latin America would assist in building the grassroots environmental movement in this region. As in other areas where STRP has developed a monitoring presence, the monitoring staff hired by STRP would be indigenous citizens. In many instances it would provide the first compensated environmental activists in these countries. Establishing a monitoring program would also create a foothold for expanded environmental advocacy. STRP's umbrella would add credibility and protection from retaliation.<P>

We believe the STRP model of grassroots organizing combined with high profile media work is an extremely effective strategy for the protection of marine biodiversity. The monitoring program will be a model for local activists to learn and develop strategies for addressing other environmental issues. Training of monitoring staff will include time working in the San Francisco office and may also include STRP staff taking temporary assignments in, and frequent travel to Latin America.<P>

STRP has developed a strong, international reputation in marine biodiversity issues. STRP's ability to provide strong leadership and high profile media attention in legal actions, legislative efforts, and international diplomacy will provide an effective shield for nationals employed in the monitoring program. The degree to which this organization is regarded by its adversaries as a force to be reckoned with is exemplified by high level meetings with Presidents and Ministers in various Latin American nations and effective international legislation.<P>

<H2>Program Activities</H2>

The specific program activities include initial start-up activities involved in establishing monitoring offices, including staff time, travel, opening offices, and hiring and training staff. Once the program is operational, the day-to-day tasks of the monitors would include:<P>
<UL>
<LI>establishing a presence on the loading docks of shrimping vessels to monitor for the use of turtle excluder devices;<P>

<LI>recording both compliance with and violation of national and international regulations, using video and tape recorders to document violations;<P>

<LI>record-keeping and report preparation for filing with STRP's San Francisco office;<P>

<LI>monitoring aboard ship to ensure proper <A HREF="strpted.html">TED</A> use and to collect data on incidental and destructive by-catch;<P>

<LI>conducting seagoing spot inspections of shrimp vessels to ensure proper <A HREF="strpted.html">TEDs</A> use;<P>

<LI>-providing educational materials and workshops on turtle biology, the ease of using and availability of <A HREF="strpted.html">TEDs</A> and sustainable turtle egg harvesting programs; and,<P>

<LI>coordinating and assisting other NGO's (e.g. Grupo 100 in Mexico) on specific issues.<P>
</UL>

STRP believes that this monitoring program will provide an effective method for expanding enforcement of laws and regulations applying to sea turtles. If countries refuse to comply, then the documentation obtained by monitors will assist in building cases for US diplomatic pressure and trade sanctions. Further, the information gathered by the monitors will be used to certify compliance with <A HREF="strpted.html">TED</A> regulations. This information is of great assistance to processors desiring to buy turtle-safe products and for them to gain greater access to growing world turtle-safe markets. The goal is to create self-sustaining, indigenous programs over a period of three years. In some instances turtle-safe companies may be convinced to provide financial support for monitoring efforts.<P>

<H2>Time Schedule</H2>

STRP would like to initiate this program in late 1994 by establishing monitoring offices in Mexico and Costa Rica. By the end of the first year or beginning of the second, we plan to expand the program to include operations in Colombia and Ecuador.<P>


<H2>More about STRP</H2>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="tsafe2news.html">Turtle-Safe shrimp news<P>
<LI><A HREF="tsafe1dry.html">Turtle-Safe(tm) shrimp<P>
<LI><A HREF="turtlesafe.html">Why should you ask for Turtle-Safe shrimp?</A>.<P>
