<H1>Statement of the Problem</H1>
<TITLE>STRP: Statement of the Problem</TITLE>

Sea turtles have been on earth for over 150 million years, and they predate the dinosaurs. Until this century, these giant reptiles were abundant members of the oceans ecosystems. Sea turtles form a unique assemblage of marine bio-diversity and occupy a novel position in the oceans' food web, feeding on an unusual range of prey including jellyfish, sponges, tunicates, algae, sea grasses, and crustaceans. The nesting phase of their life cycle also makes them an important component of beach and coastal ecology. The nesting females and the massive quantity of eggs laid are eaten by a myriad of predators ranging from small crabs to jaguars. Even the bacteria and micro-fauna of beaches are strongly influenced by the nesting turtles. Scientists have hardly begun to speculate on the detrimental impacts that the complete loss of the sea turtle species would have on the delicate balance of ocean and beach ecosystems.<P>

Sea turtles have been an important part of the diet of coastal peoples for thousands of years, and local human consumption has probably had a minimal impact on sea turtle populations. However, today's commercial exploitation for international markets and incidental drownings threaten the sea turtles, local people's subsistence use of turtles and the biological diversity of the oceans. Sea turtles migrate thousands of miles through the waters of many nations as well as international waters, a fact which emphasizes the need for international cooperation in their protection.<P>

Six of the seven species of sea turtles have been declared endangered or threatened by the U.S. Endangered Species Act and several international treaties. Nonetheless, sea turtle populations continue to decline under an onslaught of human-caused threats. At sea, they are subject to incidental capture in the nets of shrimping and other fishing vessels. On land, commercial development along once isolated coasts threatens their nesting beaches. Meanwhile, the uncontrolled pollution of the oceans continues, and everything from oil-tar balls to floating plastic are commonly found blocking the intestines of sea turtles that have washed up dead along our coasts. Fibropapilloma, a formerly rare disease that has become extremely common, is devastating some turtle populations. Direct commercial exploitation of adults and uncontrolled harvesting of eggs also threaten many populations. <P>

Incidental capture of sea turtles in shrimp nets has been identified as the most important human-caused threat to sea turtles in the U.S., suggesting a much larger global problem which has not yet been adequately quantified. More than 85 nations besides the US are engaged in shrimp fishing, and most of them do not require vessels in their waters to use <A HREF="strpted.html">TEDs</A>. We estimate that more than 155,000 turtles may drown each year due to this failure. Progress is being made to control this threat within U.S. waters and beginning efforts are now being made in the Atlantic/Caribbean region. Yet little or no effort is directed at the larger worldwide problem. <P>

Shrimp trawling is not only devastating to turtles but to other parts of the <A HREF="../immp/immp.html">marine environment</A> as well. It is estimated that 10 pounds of fish (excluding an unquantified number of invertebrates) are killed and discarded for every pound of shrimp caught. In the U.S. alone, 10 billion fish are destroyed each year by U.S. shrimp vessels. The worldwide impact of shrimp trawling is staggering and remains unquantified. Its impact on other commercial fisheries and the livelihood of subsistence fisher-folk is known to be devastating throughout the world. <P>

U.S. consumers play a major role in creating the demand for more and more shrimp trawling operations. Shrimp is an expensive luxury item that is imported out of the developing world to feed the affluent of the developed world. The U.S. is the largest consumer nation of shrimp, both caught and farmed. <P>

The ridley species has a nesting strategy unique among all turtles. Described as one of the most spectacular events in the reptile world, the "<I>arribada</I>", which is the nearly simultaneous arrival of thousands of pregnant females -sometimes more than 100,000 turtles at a single locale- makes this species extremely vulnerable to commercial exploitation.  There used to be a dozen <I>arribada</I> sites worldwide, but two-thirds of these sacred sites have been decimated, and now only four remain on the entire planet. Even these last four <I>arribada</I> sites are at risk. <P>

Watching a giant sea turtle lumber out of the sea and lay her eggs as her kind has done for eons, literally since before the time of the dinosaurs, it is easy to sense something magical and mysterious. Scientists do not understand why only the ridley turtles use this mass nesting strategy. One hypothesis is that by "putting all your eggs in one basket", no predator can take them all and some will survive to become the next generation. This strategy has worked for the sea turtles for 150 million years, yet the human predator of the past 100 years has driven this species and five other species of sea turtles to the brink of extinction.<P>

Imagine what it is like to watch tens of thousands of ancient creatures return to the same beach where their kind has for thousands of years and complete this ritual all at once! By the time the <I>arribada</I>, has subsided, literally tens of millions of sea turtle eggs will have been deposited on the sandy beach, providing sustenance and an important link in the web of life for an incredible diversity of wildlife of the region. Possibly even more remarkable are the few nights some 45 days later when literally millions of tiny, baby hatchlings crawl out of the sand and head for the ocean, finding their way by heading toward the reflection of stars and moonlight off the sea. Few of these cookie-sized babies will make it to adulthood decades later, as the majority are eaten by the hundreds of predators who feast on this bountiful food source. But this is the way of nature, and the turtles are a keystone species that supports the abundant web of terrestrial and marine wildlife located throughout the reserve.<P>

