<H1>International Implementation of Turtle Excluder Devices</H1>
<TITLE>STRP: International Implementation of Turtle Excluder Devices</TITLE>

The leading cause of human-induced sea turtle mortality in the United States in recent years has been from the incidental capture and drowning in shrimp trawls, according to a 1990 National Academy of Sciences study. Estimates of U.S. annual mortality ranged from approximately 11,000 to 55,000 before the requirement to use Turtle Excluder Devices (TEDs). TEDs are "trap doors" that are attached to shrimp nets and reduce sea turtle mortality by more than 97 percent while insignificantly affecting shrimp catch. The devices cost $50-400 per net. <P>

Attempts to require the use of TEDs on U.S. shrimp fishing vessels have resulted in significant controversy over the past ten years. TEDs have now been required on shrimp fishing vessels in the United States. The dire predictions by the U.S. shrimp fishing industry that use of these devices would result in the collapse of the U.S. shrimp industry have proven unfounded. To the contrary, TEDs have proven to be effective in reducing turtle mortality, inexpensive and have not significantly reduced the harvest of shrimp.<P>

Sea turtle mortality for the combined fleets of the more than 85 nations which harvest shrimp are not known. Assuming an equal capture rate between the U.S. and international fleet (number of turtles per ton of shrimp), sea turtle mortality worldwide would exceed 155,000 per year. After approximately $10 million and ten years of research and development in the United States, it is necessary to begin transferring information and technology to the more than 85 nations who use shrimp trawls.<P>

The U.S. Department of State's actions to implement the use of TEDs internationally have been relatively ineffective and inefficient. A bi-lateral approach, instead of a multi-lateral approach to negotiations, and US AID funding continues at a snails pace. At the present rate of 3 countries per year, technology transfer could take 30 years to complete. The additional positive benefits of TEDs technology, such as protection of artisanal and important commercial fisheries, are not being promoted abroad. A new innovative approach is necessary, and STRP has developed and begun to implement a multi-faceted program to address the problem, comprising international cooperation, public education and litigation.<P>

<H2>International Cooperation</H2>
STRP and the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) have jointly produced a video tape promoting the use of TEDs, and the U.S. Information Agency has contacted STRP requesting the opportunity to distribute the tape worldwide. Our alliance with UNEP will include co-sponsorship workshops on TEDs, as well as cooperation in producing a U.N. resolution encouraging the use of TEDs.  Government representatives from Pakistan have contacted STRP requesting instruction in the use of TEDs. Earth Island Institute has developed excellent ties with non-governmental organizations (NGOs) around the world and has employees working in Asia and Central America. This places us in an excellent position to work with NGOs to pressure their own governments to take responsible action. Since virtually all TEDs research has been done in the U.S., information is not readily available in many nations. STRP will develop and distribute needed information on TEDs to governments and NGOs. These materials will emphasize the negative impacts of shrimp bycatch on other fisheries, especially local and artisanal fisheries that are important to the local economies of many nations. Modifications of TEDs to reduce fish bycatch may prove to be a determining factor in convincing many developing nations to embrace TED technology.<P>

<H2>Public Education</H2>
Earth Island Institute has developed excellent working relationships with national media in print, television and radio. The Sea Turtle Restoration Project works extensively with Public Media Center (a non-profit media, marketing and communications agency) in helping to develop public participation in policy issues relating to marine conservation. STRP will use these contacts in organizing citizen awareness and participation in encouraging the use of TEDs.<P>

<H2>Litigation</H2>
Public Law 101-162 section 609, enacted by Congress in 1989, requires nations who wish to export shrimp to the United States to "adopt regulations governing the incidental taking of sea turtles comparable to those of the U.S., and that the average rate of incidental taking be comparable to the incidental rate of capture by U.S. vessels." The clear intent of this law is to encourage nations to adopt regulations requiring TEDs on all shrimp trawling vessels fishing in waters shared with five sea turtle species (Kemp's ridley, hawksbill, loggerhead, green, leatherback).<P>

To compel nations to take these actions, the law specifically prohibits the importation of shrimp into the U.S. from nations which have not adopted regulations that reduce incidental sea turtle capture to rates comparable to those of the U.S. Despite section 609's clear mandate to include "... <U>all</U> foreign governments which are engaged in ...commercial fishing operations which...may affect adversely [endangered] species of sea turtles...", the Department of State issued regulations which severely limit the scope of the law, and which greatly reduce its potential to act as a catalyst for international implementation of TEDs. Specifically, the State Department regulations limit coverage to only 14 nations in the wider Caribbean/western Atlantic region. These 14 nations represent less than 17 percent of the 85 countries that import shrimp into the United States and only 9.1 percent, by metric tons, of the total world wild-caught shrimp harvest. Furthermore, the Department of State regulations illegally extended by three additional years the May 1, 1991 deadline for compliance.<P>

After unsuccessful negotiations with the Department of State to employ universal and equal application of PL 101-162, STRP filed suit. Unfortunately, the Department of State has proven it will not vigorously enforce this law without legal oversight and citizen pressure. We will use the lawsuit to generate pressure to streamline TED technology transfer to developing nations, leverage additional expenditures of U.S. funds to help nations implement TEDs compliance and to alert the public of its role in influencing policy.<P>

