<html>







<head>



<title>Guatemala Trip</title>



</head>







<body>







<h1 align=center>Guatemala Biointensive Gardening Project</h1>



<h3 align=center>



<I>Learn biointensive gardening techniques and share this knowledge with local villagers.</I>



</h3>







<img SRC="hola2.gif" align=left>







<p>GSC volunteers in Guatemala will learn biointensive techniques at the New Forests Project's Agroforestry 



Training Center in Nueva Concepcion, near the southern coast of the country.  They will help put together a 



public seminar to demonstrate these new skills to Guatemalans in the area.  Then they will trek to outlying villages,



where they will share their new abilities with rural farmers who are eager to learn more fruitful ways of growing 



food for their families.











<p>The group departs Friday morning, arriving in Guatemala City that evening.   The next day, we travel to 



the project site in Nueva Concepcion in southwestern Guatemala.  Here we attend a 4 day bilingual 



training session on the methods of biointensive agriculture.  Side by side with Guatemalan cohorts we will 



learn such techniques as crop selection, double digging, composting and seedling management.  During 



this time, the group will stay in the dormitory at the Agroforestry Training Center.  On the following day, the 



newly trained volunteers will assist in presenting a public seminar on biointensive agriculture to the local



villagers.







<p>During the next two days the group will enjoy a relaxing mid-project break at beautiful Lake Atitlan, and 



then settle into homestays in various communities near Nueva Concepcion.  Teams of two GSC volunteers 



and one Guatemalan partner will work with women's groups and other village organizations to teach and 



demonstrate the biointensive techniques that were learned in the first half of the trip.  We will help the



Guatemalans create organic gardens, moving towards a more sustainable form of agriculture and away



from deforestation and environmental damage.  On the final day of the project, the group will travel to the



historic town of Antigua, in the outskirts of Guatemala City.  There we will have a chance to do some



sightseeing and shopping before returning to the United States the following day.<p>







<hr>







<h3>Guatemala Project News</h3>







<p>Volunteers on our October program will have the once in a lifetime chance to be part of the birth of an 



exciting and urgently needed new program. Guatemala offers a perfect example of the need for 



biointensive agriculture in developing countries. Poverty and poor land distribution have forced farmers to



destroy lush forests to grow enough food. GSC volunteers will play a crucial role in fighting this trend. By 



revealing biointensive skills to local farmers, participants will not only help remove the causes of deforestation 



but will let the Guatemalan people nourish themselves in a way that is healthier, more productive, and



consistent with their own culture. New Forests Project, our partner in this endeavor, has many years of 



experience in Guatemala. Their staff is familiar with the culture and conditions of rural life, and they predict 



that biointensive agriculture will substantially enrich the people of Guatemala.  







<p>"These farmers are the people that we must reach if we are to reverse the catastrophic deforestation 



occurring around the world today"







<p>Stuart Conway



<br>Director



<br>New Forests Project







<hr>







<h3>Project Dates and Costs:</h3> 



<ul>



<li>1996: October 4 - 20



<li>1997: July 5 - 21, October 10 - 26



<li>$1595 land costs



</ul><p>







