<TITLE>Ocean Alert - Summer/Fall 1996: Sea Lions and Seals are Scapegoats for Fisheries Depletion.</TITLE>

<H1>Pinnipeds are Scapegoats for Fisheries Depletion.</H1>

<I>Pinniped: Aquatic mammals (as a seal or walrus) with all
four limbs modified into flippers.</I><P>

In what is now a worldwide phenomenon, marine mammals are becoming scapegoats
for human environmental destruction. The Ballard Locks in Seattle, Washington
is the site of controversy surrounding interactions between California sea
lions and an endangered population of winter-run steelhead trout. In a complex
ecological management tangle, species are being pitted against species. Fishers
and conservation agencies justify their attacks on sea lions based on the
pinnipeds' consumption of the endangered fish. Others point out that predation
by sea lions is not the reason the endangered fish continue to decline. The
depleted fish populations are clearly in need of protection, but data indicate
that the decline is the result of fisheries mismanagement and habitat
destruction, not surging marine mammal populations. In the Locks, for instance,
past removal of predatory sea lions has had no lasting impact on numbers of
returning fish.<P>

Numbers of steelhead returning to spawning streams through the  Locks have
plummeted from 2,000 a year in the early 1980's to 76 in 1994 and 137 in 1995.
As fish pass through the narrow Locks, they are easy prey for sea lions. For
the past decade, fishers and management agencies have pointed to the sea lions
as the culprits of the steelhead depletion. This strategy mirrors the
widespread trend toward blaming pinnipeds for competing with fish. The reality
is that sea lions killed only six, eleven, and zero steelhead, respectively, in
1994, 1995, and 1996,  but claims against them persist.<P>

In response to pinniped consumption of depleted fish stocks at the Locks and
elsewhere, Congress amended the Marine Mammal Protection Act in 1994 to allow
"lethal taking of individually identifiable pinnipeds which are having a
significant negative impact on the decline or recovery of certain salmonid
fishery stocks." The stocks in question must meet one of the following three
conditions to justify pinniped take: be listed under the Endangered Species
Act, be approaching threatened or endangered species status, or "migrate
through the Ballard Locks at Seattle, Washington." This clause was invoked in
the planned removal of five sea lions from the Ballard Locks this year. Thus
far, three sea lions have been captured and relocated to Sea World, triggering
a lawsuit by a coalition of environmental groups  including EII.<P>

The Ballard Locks-Pinniped Fishery Task Force, a diverse group of fishers,
agency representatives, tribal representatives, independent biologists, and conservation groups, is working to resolve the problem.
According to Task Force member Toni Frohoff, "What is needed is to remedy fish
passage problems at the Locks as well as other factors which are primary causes
of the steelhead decline." Frohoff and many others point out that the real
cause of the steelhead population crisis is a combination of poor Locks design,
habitat degradation, and fisheries mismanagement.<P>

The Ballard Locks was built around 1916 by the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers to
allow ships to get into the Lake Washington watershed by controlling water flow
between the lake and the Puget Sound. The design of the Locks results in injury
to approximately 60% of the smolt passing through, due to barnacle-encrusted
plumbing that de-scales them. This is a major source of steelhead mortality.
The Corps has expressed willingness to redesign the Locks, but no action has
yet been taken. Deforestation along the streams has impinged on spawning
habitat by causing siltation, eliminating shade for the eggs, and removing
felled trees that block the water around the eggs. Fisheries management issues
include illegal fishing and competition with hatchery fish. Until recently,
government agencies released hatchery fish into Lake Washington, resulting in
direct competition with wild steelhead for habitat and genetic mixing of less
robust hatcheries stocks with wild stocks.<P>

The final word is not in on the Ballard Locks sea lions, though the gravity of
the steelhead's situation increases the likelihood that other causes of their
dwindling population will be addressed. Meanwhile, attacks on pinnipeds by
fishers are growing. The Fishermen's Alliance of Monterey Bay, CA, complaining
that sea lions are "stealing" some 80% of their catch, is currently circulating
a petition to further relax protection of the California sea lion. Japanese
fishers are killing Pacific white-sided dolphins, false killer whales, and
bottlenose dolphins because of perceived competition for fish stocks. Canadians
are killing 200,000 harp seals a year because of the collapse of cod stocks off
the Newfoundland coast. Nine of the world's seventeen major fisheries are in
major decline and the rest are approaching their limits. Killing  marine
mammals to ensure more availability of fish for human fishers is a strategy
that obfuscates the real, much more complex issues of fisheries mismanagement
and habitat destruction and victimizes marine mammals.<P>


<A HREF="immp.html"><IMG ALIGN=top SRC="arrowrt.gif">IMMP table of contents</A>.<P>

