<TITLE>IMMP: Sea Lions To Be Slaughtered In Washington State</TITLE>

<H1>Sea Lions To Be Slaughtered In Washington State</H1>

California sea lions may be killed at the Ballard Locks in Seattle, Washington because of a misguided effort to save steelhead trout.
The majority of a task force recently voted to recommend the killing of sea lions. However, almost half of the Task Force members (including wildlife biologists, ecologist, and environmentalists) voted against the proposed kill. This could represent the first slaughter of marine mammals in US waters in over 20 years.<P>


Killing sea lions will not solve the problem. On the contrary, there is evidence that removal of sea lions will not be effective in saving the steelhead because other sea lions will take the place of the slaughtered animals. Other options to save the steelhead are much more likely to work in the short and long term.  Further, they could also save other declining fish populations in Lake Washington.<P>


Further, sea lion predation is neither the primary nor principal cause of the steelhead deadline. According to a 1993 government report (GAO), dams are considered to be the primary factors in the decline of the currently protected salmon runs. Further, Fraker (1994) stated "while marine mammal predation may be important locally, such as at the Chittenden locks, it does not appear to be great enough to explain the general decline". Coho, chinook, and sockeye populations are also crashing in Lake Washington, but sea lions are not considered responsible because they do not even typically eat these species at the locks. Government studies indicate that there are many areas in which sea lion and salmonid populations co-exist successfully: and they have done so for millennia. <p>

The decline of our fish populations is due to problems with people, not marine mammals. If we continue to avoid addressing the real cause of the decline, there is little reason to believe that our streams, oceans: or fishing industries will ever recover and a national treasure, the California Sea Lion, will have been slaughtered in vain.

<H2>What you Can Do:</H2>
<LI><A HREF="slpetition.html">Print and send in this Agreement</A> and -<P>

<LI>Please write to ask that sea lions not be killed and  to choose non-lethal, 
       long term solutions to the problem of declining fisheries:<P>

Ronald H. Brown<BR>
Secretary of Commerce<br>
Herbert C. Hoover Building<br>
14th & Constitution Ave NW<br>
Washington, DC 20230<P>

Rolland Schmitten<br>
National Marine Fisheries Services<br>
1315 East West Highway<br>
Silver Springs, MD 20910<P>


<BR>

