<TITLE>Bluewater Network: The Marine Motor Industry</TITLE>

<H2>The Marine Motor Industry</H2>

The marine motor industry is characterized by over 140 manufacturers around the
globe, most of which are engaged in the design and construction of inboard or
sterndrive motors. Inboard/sterndrive motors pollute magnitudes of order less
than their malignant counterparts, the modern two-stroke outboard or personal
watercraft engines  (PWC) colloquially known as jet skis. There are fourteen
major manufacturers of two-strokes. They are:

<UL>

<LI>Yamaha

<LI>OMC (Johnson, Evinrude)

<LI>Mercury (Mercury, Force)

<LI>Nissan

<LI>Suzuki

<LI>Tohatsu

<LI>Selva, the Italian manufacturer

<LI>A.H. Young Industries, the Korean manufacturer (Swallow, Maxxon)

<LI>Bombardier, Kawasaki, Polaris, Wetjet, Aquajet, and Arctco. These six are
PWC manufacturers.<P>

</UL>

Over the past several years, the EPA has negotiated with the manufacturers to
clean up the emission levels of the motors they produce. The final rulemaking
has been highly favorable to industry. While industry has anticipated a
potential ban on the sale of two-strokes for years, the new regulations only
require 75 percent improved hydrocarbon emissions characteristics for new
motors, phased-in by the year 2006; and a system of averaging, banking, and
trading of emission credits among manufacturers. This will permit certain
manufacturers who choose not to meet the new motor emissions regulations for
their new motors the lawful right to purchase credits from those who exceed the
EPA standards - for example, a PWC manufacturer such as Bombardier may choose
to continue their sales of "dirty" two-strokes and buy their emissions credits
from Honda.<P>

While the manufacturers are heralding the new rules as a vast improvement, SAIL
magazine claims they are breathing a collective sigh of relief that the EPA has
been so lenient. Some industry insiders believe that it is economically and
technically feasible to reduce two-stroke emissions by an absolute, unaveraged
standard of 95% instead of an averaged 75% - as Honda has already done by
shifting designs to four-stroke technology - but this is a solution which the
manufacturers strongly resisted in their negotiations with the EPA. Moreover,
Bluewater believes the industry is capable of shifting its entire production
line to the new technologies well before the year 2006 - without undue economic
hardship. Industry claims that such a rapid shift would reduce profits and
cause business failure, a controversial claim.<P>

In reality, the new regulations will only slow the damages from total
hydrocarbon emissions. For instance, one manufacturer may be able to purchase
emission credits indefinitely at lower cost than that entailed by retooling
their manufacturing operations. Others may find niche markets for the "dirty"
motors such as low-income buyers, who cannot afford a 15% higher cost for the
new, cleaner motors - despite the fact that tremendous fuel savings from
cleaner motors offset the higher purchase costs based on average usage. Other
manufacturers may elect to keep a portion of their PWC product lines as "dirty"
two-strokes due to mild performance advantages to the consumer (higher speeds,
lighter weights). Furthermore, the new averaging, banking, and trading
regulations effectively substitute one form of pollution for another, rather
than creating absolute emission standards, as some believe is required
according to the terms of the Clean Air Act.<P>

Anticipated new two-stroke sales over the next ten years are over ten million
units, representing many billions of gallons of hydrocarbon content. Such sales
growth will add tremendously to the pollution content of the world's waterways
and coastal areas.


